\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark on the roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently, certain science publishers started enforcing the rule of using
 a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in differentials (for instance, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}^{2}x(\tau)/\textrm{d}\tau^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\textrm{d}^{3}x$
\end_inset

) rather than using an italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as was the common practice during the previous two centuries.
 I decided to use the roman symbol 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to denote the exterior differential in the calculus of differential forms,
 but continue to use the italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in other situations when differential forms are not involved.
 My intention is to use a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for rigorously defined objects, such as differential forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

, and to contrast them with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

, which are only heuristic notational tools that help the intuition.
 I write integrals, e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\int\textrm{d}^{3}x$
\end_inset

, with a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 when the integration of a differential form is implied, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}^{3}x$
\end_inset

 is a shorthand notation for the 3-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

.
 However, I write an italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in derivatives, 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dt$
\end_inset

, and in integrals such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)dx$
\end_inset

 where I need a simple one-dimensional integration rather than an integration
 of 1-form over a contour.
 I also write the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metric interval,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-dx^{2}-dy^{2}-dz^{2},\]

\end_inset

with an italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because this notation is essentially a jargon that bears only marginally
 on the calculus of differential forms; for instance, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $ds$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cannot be understood as a 1-form in this notation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When using ordinary derivatives, I write 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}/d\tau^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the italic 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, for the following reasons.
 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}/d\tau^{2}$
\end_inset

 are not essentially different from the partial derivative operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial^{2}/\partial x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Traditionally, one writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial x$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 depends not only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 but also on other variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y,z,...$
\end_inset

 that are held constant while 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y,z,...)$
\end_inset

 is differentiated with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, one writes 
\begin_inset Formula $df/dx$
\end_inset

 to emphasize that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a function of only one variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, or that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an expression that must be reduced, through suitable substitutions,
 to a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 only.
 This notation is widely used to avoid cluttering the equations with explicit
 substitutions.
 For instance, the Euler-Lagrange equation of mechanics is written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x}-\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=0,\]

\end_inset

implying that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial L/\partial\dot{x}$
\end_inset

 must be expressed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 before evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dt$
\end_inset

.
 However, the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

's in the differential operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset

 are merely historically developed notation and are not directly related
 to the exterior differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

.
 I use an italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to emphasize the difference between the rigorously defined operation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in an expression such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\mbox{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 and the heuristic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal quantity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset

.
 Readers who are comfortable with differential forms may ignore this typographic
al subtlety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A related recent trend is to write a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{e}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the base of the natural logarithm and a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the imaginary unit (
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{i}^{2}=-1$
\end_inset

).
 One reason for switching to roman
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{e}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s is to avoid confusion when other quantities are denoted by the letters
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 In this book, my principal intention is to make the notation unambiguous
 for a student who initially does not feel sure in this subject, while not
 excessively cluttering the writing.
 I use a roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the imaginary unit because the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is frequently used as an index, e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 However, I use an italic 
\begin_inset Formula $e=2.718...$
\end_inset

 to avoid confusion with a boldface roman 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 frequently used for frame basis vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
