\begin_layout Subsection
Sample practice problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You should be able to solve these problems if you know the material of Chapter\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:Calculus-in-curved}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Null vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove that two nonzero, non-parallel null vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 cannot be orthogonal.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}=\lambda\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a metric in four-dimensional space with the Lorentzian signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+,-,-,-\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extremum of a functional on curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a functional
\begin_inset Formula \[
F[\gamma]=\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}f(g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}))\textrm{d}\tau,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a given smooth, nonconstant function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent vector to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Derive the Euler-Lagrange equations describing the extremum of the functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $F[\gamma]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Symmetric geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a three-dimensional space.
 Suppose that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\phi(x)dx^{2}+A(y,z)dy^{2}+C(y,z)dz^{2},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A(y,z)>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C(y,z)>0$
\end_inset

 are smooth functions that depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 as indicated.
 Show that lines 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\textrm{const},z=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the coordinate lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) are geodesics.
 Obtain an explicit formula for a Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 admits.
 Is the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 geodesic?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lie transport.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 be a Killing vector for a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and let two vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 be connecting for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and such that the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is orthogonal (but not necessarily orthonormal) at one point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
a)
\series default
 Can one choose the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 connecting for each other everywhere? 
\series bold
b)
\series default
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 the flow line of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 that passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Is the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 orthogonal everywhere along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extrinsic curvature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hypersurface with normal vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is embedded in a curved space with metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The extrinsic curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 of the hypersurface is defined as a bilinear form
\begin_inset Formula \[
K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the induced metric on the hypersurface and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary vectors tangent to the hypersurface.
 
\series bold
a)
\series default
 Starting from the definition and using 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
b)
\series default
 Compute the extrinsic curvature tensor explicitly for the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+y^{2}-z^{2}=-1$
\end_inset

 defined in 3-dimensional Euclidean space with Cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates on the surface.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic notions: Manifolds and vector fields
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Manifolds-and-tangent}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In nongravitational physics, one describes events in four-dimensional Minkowski
 spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 with familiar coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Physical laws are expressed as partial differential equations for various
 fields in spacetime.
 General Relativity replaces Minkowski spacetime by a 
\emph on
curved
\emph default
 spacetime, and partial derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 are replaced by more complicated differential operations.
 The mathematical concept of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and accompanying notions are used to formalize the idea of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the ways of writing differential equations for fields in such spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following subsection\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Formal-definitions-manifolds}

\end_inset

, I will list concise definitions of manifolds, tangent spaces, vector fields,
 etc.
 If you are satisfied by or already familiar with these definitions, you
 may skip the entire Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Manifolds-and-tangent}

\end_inset

 and continue reading from Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Lie-derivative}

\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, you may find it helpful to read the following sections (from
 Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Manifolds-and-coordinates}

\end_inset

 onwards) where I explain those definitions more visually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definitions
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Formal-definitions-manifolds}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section concisely summarizes the definitions and properties of manifolds
 and tangent vectors.
 If you prefer visual explanations to formal definitions, you may ignore
 this section and start reading from Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Manifolds-and-coordinates}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
manifold
\series default
 
\series bold

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!definition}

\end_inset


\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a set of points (which I informally call a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that locally looks like a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 has a small neighborhood around it, which is one-to-one mapped into a subset
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This mapping is called a 
\series bold
chart
\series default
 and is equivalent to specifying a set of scalar functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(p)$
\end_inset

, defined in an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{0})$
\end_inset

 of some point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 and giving the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to points 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 These functions must uniquely identify each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so that for any two points 
\begin_inset Formula $p,p'$
\end_inset

 from the neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{0})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(p)=x^{\mu}(p')$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p'$
\end_inset

.
 Also, the image of the neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{0})$
\end_inset

 under the map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mapsto x^{\mu}(p)\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 must be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Under these conditions, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(p)$
\end_inset

 constitute a 
\series bold
local coordinate system
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{local coordinates}

\end_inset

 defined on an open subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{0})\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, different subdomains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{0})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}(p_{1})$
\end_inset

, etc., may have different local coordinate systems.
 Whenever there is an intersection of two domains of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 where local coordinate systems are defined, we get a 
\series bold
coordinate change
\series default
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 defined in a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold is 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 (
\series bold
differentiable
\series default
) 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{smooth manifold}

\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!smooth}

\end_inset

if all these coordinate change maps are smooth (differentiable) in the ordinary
 sense (as functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particular manifold may be specified either by an explicit embedding into
 a larger space, or by giving a complete set of charts and re-charting maps,
 specifying how the charts are to be glued together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical example of a manifold is the surface of a sphere in 3-dimensional
 space, usually called the 
\series bold
two-dimensional sphere
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
2-sphere
\series default
) 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{2-sphere}

\end_inset

and denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The 2-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is locally like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, but globally is not (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement:-A-2-sphere}

\end_inset

).
 It is useful to visualize a manifold as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 embedded in a larger space, and to think that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers living entirely within the surface.
 So 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cannot see the larger space and must describe the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 exclusively through its intrinsic properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example of a manifold described in a different way, consider the set
 of all 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 unitary complex matrices with unit determinant.
 These matrices form a group denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 (A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
unitary
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{unitary matrix}

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\dagger}A=1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is the Hermitian conjugate, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the transposed and complex conjugate matrix.)
 It is perhaps not immediately clear how to introduce coordinates in this
 set of matrices.
 It can be shown (see Statement
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{par:Exercise:SU2 quaternions}

\end_inset

) that all matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in SU(2)$
\end_inset

 can be described explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a_{0}-\text{i}a_{3} & -\text{i}a_{1}-a_{2}\\
-\text{i}a_{1}+a_{2} & a_{0}+\text{i}a_{3}\end{array}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

 are real numbers satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=0}^{3}a_{j}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent (as a manifold) to a three-dimensional sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A smooth, one-to-one map from one manifold to another is called a 
\series bold
diffeomorphism
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{diffeomorphism}

\end_inset

 Two manifolds are called 
\series bold
diffeomorphic
\series default
 if there exists a diffeomorphism between them.
 Diffeomorphic manifolds are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

topologically equivalent.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For example, a sphere can be diffeomorphically mapped onto the surface
 of a cube, but not onto a torus.
 Another example we have just seen is an explicit diffeomorphism (specified
 using coordinates) between 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will always consider 
\emph on
smooth
\emph default
 finite-dimensional manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, on these manifolds; so we omit the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a point on a manifold, 
\series bold
scalar functions
\series default
 (scalar fields) are functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 is a number, and boldface letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w},...$
\end_inset

 are vectors and vector fields (defined below).
 We use Greek letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,...,\lambda,\mu,...$
\end_inset

 for tensor indices and also for numbers (scalars).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
curve
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{curve on a manifold}

\end_inset

on a manifold is a set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 parametrized by a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, sometimes defined only on a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
derivation
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at a point
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a map from scalar functions to numbers, satisfying the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

derivative-like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 properties 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{D}(f+g) & =\textrm{D}f+\textrm{D}g,\;\textrm{[linearity]}\\
\textrm{D}(fg) & =\textrm{D}(f)g+f\textrm{D}(g),\;\textrm{[Leibnitz rule]}\\
\textrm{D}f & =0\;\textrm{ if }f=\textrm{const around }p.\end{align*}

\end_inset

All the derivations at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 form a vector space called the 
\series bold
tangent space
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent space}

\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Vectors from the tangent space are denoted by boldface letters, e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and their action on functions is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as the derivative of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Using a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,n$
\end_inset

, one can prove that the tangent space is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space.
 An explicit basis in this space is given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinate derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\equiv\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The components of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in this basis can be found as 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}=\mathbf{v}\circ x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, and then the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\sum_{\alpha=1}^{n}v^{\alpha}\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}=\sum_{\alpha=1}^{n}v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The union of all tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
tangent bundle
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent bundle}

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The tangent bundle is itself a manifold with the same charts as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 but with twice the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This is so because every chart will map a patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and tangent vectors map into vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, thus the patch of the tangent bundle will map into a patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vector field
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 chosen at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 such that the image 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 of every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 belongs to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at the same point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
covector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{covector}

\end_inset

is a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 from vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 into numbers.
 The space of covectors to tangent vectors at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
cotangent space
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cotangent space}

\end_inset


\series default
 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(p)\in T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 chosen at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
1-form
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{1-form}

\end_inset

 The pointwise action of a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and is a scalar function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A
\series bold
 tensor field
\series default
 on a manifold is defined similarly: it is a tensor based on the tangent
 space at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
commutator
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{commutator of vectors}

\end_inset

of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 defined by its action on functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f\equiv\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)-\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\mathbf{u}\circ f\right).\]

\end_inset

(It can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 also satisfies the properties of a vector field; see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset

.) One says that the vector fields 
\series bold
commute
\series default
 if their commutator is equal to zero.
 For example, coordinate basis vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 commute because 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}\partial_{y}f=\partial_{y}\partial_{x}f$
\end_inset

