\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This motivates us to consider the idea of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

general kind of curved space,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is, a space which is only 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
 similar to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 but globally very different from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The mathematical object that formalizes this intuitive idea is called a
 
\series bold
manifold
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold}

\end_inset

 A standard, formal definition of a manifold is given in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Formal-definitions-manifolds}

\end_inset

.
 I will now motivate and explain that definition, using a two-dimensional
 surface as a main example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalize the idea that a two-dimensional surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locally looks like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, one says that for each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 there is a small patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 which is mapped bijectively (one-to-one) into some patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be described by coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},x_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 that vary in some finite ranges.
 Therefore, there is a one-to-one map assigning values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 to points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in a small patch (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:A-manifold-visualized2}

\end_inset

).
 This map is called a 
\series bold
local coordinate system
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{local coordinates}

\end_inset

 or a 
\series bold
chart
\series default
.
 We can now formulate a first rough definition: A 
\series bold
manifold
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold}

\end_inset

 is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 such that there is a local coordinate system around every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold can be visualized as a surface that is smooth near each point
 and does not have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corners
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

spikes.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example: 2-sphere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical example of a smooth manifold is the 
\series bold
unit 2-sphere
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{2-sphere}

\end_inset

specified by the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=1,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are the ordinary Cartesian coordinates in a three-dimensional Euclidean
 space.
 The 2-sphere is usually denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To establish that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a manifold, it is sufficient to find a local coordinate system near
 each point.
 This is straightforward; for instance, it is easy to see that the first
 two Cartesian coordinates, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

, can be used as local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},x_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of the north pole 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

, even in the entire northern hemisphere (but not beyond the equator).
 The coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 cannot be used near the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} =\left\{ 0,1,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 because, e.g., a part of the straight line segment 
\begin_inset Formula $\{-1<x<1,\, y=0.99\}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 that maps onto 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes a small circle in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 do not provide a one-to-one map from any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 near the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1,0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be used as a local coordinate system near 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1,0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of a non-manifold is a 2-sphere with a line attached to it.
 No two-dimensional local coordinate system can adequately represent the
 geometry in the neighborhood of the point where the line is attached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example: 2-Torus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example of a two-dimensional manifold is a 2-torus.
 One way to describe the 2-torus is to specify it as the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} \in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the equation (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:2-torus}

\end_inset

