\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}-A\right)^{2}+z^{2}=R^{2},\quad A>R.\label{eq:torus embedding 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Another possibility is to describe the torus as a square with opposite sides
 identified.
 One can introduce local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi,\theta\right\} $
\end_inset

 on the torus and the specify the embedding into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

