\begin_layout Subsection
Manifolds: intrinsic picture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A very important idea is to imagine that there are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers living entirely within the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 These observers cannot see the larger space and describe the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 exclusively through the relationships between the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, without referring to any embedding into a larger space.
 Such a description is called 
\series bold
intrinsic
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{intrinsic description}

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The main fact is that the intrinsic description is sufficient for all purposes
 relevant to the internal geometry of the manifold.
 One may certainly introduce an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a larger space
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
It is shown in differential geometry (Whitney's embedding theorem\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Whit36}

\end_inset

) that any manifold can be embedded in a sufficiently high-dimensional Euclidean
 space.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 --- either as a way to describe a particular manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 more concisely or as a guide for the intuition,--- but the final results
 must be independent of any such embedding.
 In any case, it turns out that the intrinsic description of the geometry
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is more elegant than a description in terms of an embedding into a larger
 space.
 Another argument in favor of the intrinsic description is that according
 to General Relativity, 
\emph on
we
\emph default
 
\emph on
are
\emph default
 observers living in a four-dimensional curved manifold (the spacetime),
 and we do not directly see any higher-dimensional space in which our spacetime
 is embedded as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hypersurface.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Therefore, we need a way to describe the properties of our spacetime in
 terms of 
\emph on
intrinsic
\emph default
 measurements, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
measurements performed entirely within the spacetime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of an intrinsic property is smoothness.
 A function is 
\series bold
smooth
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{smooth function}

\end_inset


\series default
 (of class 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

) if it is infinitely many times differentiable.
 In the embedding picture, one can visualize a smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional hypersurface smoothly embedded into an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean space with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,...,N$
\end_inset

.
 Using a fixed smooth embedding of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

, one could easily define smoothness of functions and curves on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 These definitions may look like this.
 A 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 
\series bold
scalar
\series default
 
\series bold
function
\series default
 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which is a smooth function of the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 
\series bold
curve
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 such that the curve coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{a}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 in the embedding space are smooth functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 However, these definitions depend on the embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This dependence can be avoided and equivalent definitions can be given
 
\emph on
intrinsically
\emph default
, using local charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 that map patches of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into patches of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Here is how one can define a smooth scalar function.
 Within one chart, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 becomes a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, defined on a patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be defined as smoothness of each restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to patches of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In brief, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 if it is smooth in every chart.
 Similarly, a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is smooth if its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to each chart is smooth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we define smoothness of functions through their restrictions to charts,
 we need to consider what happens within an intersection of two different
 charts.
 Could it happen that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth according to one chart but not smooth according to the other
 chart? Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}_{1},\mathcal{U}_{2}\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 be two different chart domains and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}:\mathcal{U}_{1}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}:\mathcal{U}_{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding local coordinate maps.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are one-to-one maps, we may define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\phi_{2}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 (This map is defined in a small patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which is the image of the intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}_{2}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

.) We may call this map a 
\series bold
coordinate change
\series default
 
\series bold
map
\series default
.
 If 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 coordinate change map (for every pair of intersecting charts) is a smooth
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in the usual sense, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
defined by smooth functions in the standard coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then all charts will agree about the smoothness or otherwise of a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, one adds to the definition of a smooth manifold the requirement
 that every coordinate change map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is smooth, for every pair of intersecting charts.
 In this way, smoothness of the manifold itself is adequately described
 by the requirement that the coordinate change maps be smooth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there exists a smooth one-to-one map between two entire manifolds, these
 manifolds are called 
\series bold
diffeomorphic
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!diffeomorphic}

\end_inset

 For example, the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x^{2}+y^{2}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 because there is a one-to-one map between points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 on the surface and the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Thus, just one chart (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 as the coordinates) is sufficient to map this manifold into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, a 2-sphere is not diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 (Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement:-A-2-sphere}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors are used in ordinary physics to specify 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitudes,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 such as velocities and forces.
 Therefore, it is important to develop the concept of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitude
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a curved space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Embedding picture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To aid the intuition, let us visualize a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as a surface embedded in a larger space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 An immediate example of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitude
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from considering the velocity of a moving point.
 Hence, let us imagine a point that moves along a 
\series bold
curve
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 within a manifold, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that the velocity of the moving point can be viewed as a vector
 
\emph on
in the larger space 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This velocity vector always remains tangent to the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to this picture, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitudes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 defined within a manifold are called 
\series bold
tangent vectors
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent vector}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, there is a tangent plane to the surface.
 This tangent plane is a vector subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 that contains all the tangent vectors at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Considered as a two-dimensional vector space, it is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
tangent space
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent space}

\end_inset

 to the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Tangent-spaces}

\end_inset

).
 If the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is an (
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

)-dimensional hypersurface embedded into an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 then each tangent plane is a vector space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, consider a hypersurface defined by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{x})=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 has the following components, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
n_{j}(\mathbf{x}_{0})=\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial x^{j}}\right|_{\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}_{0}}.\]

\end_inset

Any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the hypersurface at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the tangent plane at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 specified by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}\cdot\left(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}_{0}\right)\equiv\sum_{j=1}^{n}(x^{j}-x_{0}^{j})n_{j}(\mathbf{x}_{0})=0.\]

\end_inset

The tangent space is made of vectors with components 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{j}-x_{0}^{j}$
\end_inset

 satisfying this equation.
 This is a two-dimensional vector space that depends on the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
it is a different space for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

