\begin_layout Caption
Tangent spaces at points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 of a manifold, visualized as vector subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cap:Tangent-spaces}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to realize that tangent spaces at different points are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 naturally related to each other, even though every tangent space is two-dimensi
onal and looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, there is no natural way to add a tangent vector at a point
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 to a tangent vector at another point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

, or to subtract these vectors.
 This should be especially clear from Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Tangent-spaces}

\end_inset

, which shows different tangent planes.
 There is no obvious way to map vectors from one tangent plane into vectors
 from the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will see such a map later when we define an additional structure on the
 manifold called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connection.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 That structure literally provides a connection (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a one-to-one map) between
 tangent spaces that are infinitesimally close (and thus, in principle,
 between any two tangent spaces).
 However, there are infinitely many possible 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connections
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on a manifold.
 In order to select a single 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connection, one needs to introduce additional considerations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a Euclidean space is given, there is a way to construct a geometrically
 preferred connection.
 One imagines that the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and the tangent planes are solid surfaces, and that one can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roll
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the first tangent plane without sliding and without turning around the
 surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 along a certain path in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 until the location of the other plane is reached.
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mechanically
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 motivated procedure yields a one-to-one map from one tangent plane into
 another one.
 The mapping between tangent planes depends on the path along which we 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roll
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 them, but is unambiguous for 
\emph on
infinitesimally
\emph default
 
\emph on
close
\emph default
 points.
 (It is only the mapping between infinitesimally close tangent spaces that
 is necessary to determine a connection.) The resulting connection is called
 the 
\series bold
Levi-Civita connection
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Levi-Civita connection}

\end_inset

; it is defined in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Levi-Civita-connection}

\end_inset

 without referring to the mechanical construction just described.
 Of course, this connection depends on the embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a Euclidean space.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Intrinsic picture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we considered tangent vectors using the embedding picture, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
by imagining
 that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 manifold is a hypersurface embedded into a larger space.
 However, it is much more useful to describe tangent vectors 
\emph on
intrinsically
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
without such an embedding.
 We could try to define a tangent vector as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma/d\tau$
\end_inset

 of some curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 going through 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 However, we cannot directly differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 without an embedding because the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau+\delta)-\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is undefined: we cannot 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

subtract
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 one point from another.
 To circumvent this problem without introducing coordinates, we focus not
 on points but on
\emph on
 scalar-valued functions
\emph default
 of points.
 (Generally, shifting the attention from an abstract set to
\emph on
 
\emph default
functions
\emph on
 
\emph default
defined
\emph on
 
\emph default
on
\emph on
 
\emph default
the
\emph on
 
\emph default
set
\emph on
 
\emph default
is a powerful idea that has proven useful in many areas of mathematics.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a scalar function defined on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 (A 
\series bold
scalar
\series default
 function means a function with a numeric value, as opposed to a matrix-valued
 or a vector-valued function.) Suppose that a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 goes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau=0)=p_{0}$
\end_inset

, and consider the 
\series bold
directional derivative
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{directional derivative}

\end_inset

of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
along
\series default
 
\series bold
the
\series default
 
\series bold
curve
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This directional derivative is defined as the derivative of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\gamma(\tau))$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f(p_{0})\equiv\left.\frac{d}{d\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}f(\gamma(\tau)).\]

\end_inset

This derivative is interpreted as the instantaneous rate of change of the
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, as one moves along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make the discussion specific, consider the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are arrays of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{1},...,x^{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

, a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{j}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

 of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x^{1},...,x^{n})$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is expressed by the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f(p_{0})=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\left.\frac{d\gamma^{k}}{d\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial x^{k}}\right|_{\left\{ x^{j}\right\} =p_{0}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our present purposes, it is important to view the directional derivative
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 as an object that knows how to evaluate a derivative of any given function,
 i.e., as a 
\emph on
map
\emph default
 from functions to numbers.
 The directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 depends not only on the direction of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, but also on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

speed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at which the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 are traversed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 changes.
 For instance, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

 will be multiplied by 2 if we keep the shape of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 unchanged but replace the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

 depends on the behavior of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in an infinitesimal neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 but does not depend on the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at other points; there are many curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 that yield the same derivative operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 carries the information only about the magnitude and the direction of the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intantaneous velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 along the curve at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This is precisely the information we expect to be represented by a tangent
 vector at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we are motivated to view the 
\emph on
map
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
itself
\emph default
 as the tangent vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a visual motivation for considering directional derivatives.
 We would like to define the tangent vector as an object that carries informatio
n about the velocity of a moving point.
 The point is 
\emph on
moving
\emph default
 if some quantities are 
\emph on
changing
\emph default
 along its path.
 A scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can represents a local quantity, or some property at a point (such as intensity
 of a physical field or a temperature).
 Then it is natural to consider the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 along the path of a moving particle.
 This directional derivative, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

, depends both on the motion of the particle and on the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 So the part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

 that is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the differential operator itself, is the object that carries information
 about the velocity of the motion.
 Hence, it is natural to identify the tangent vector as the differential
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now define the space of the tangent vectors at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the 
\series bold
tangent
\series default
 
\series bold
space
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p_{0}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, as the vector space consisting of all the possible directional derivatives
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This will be an 
\emph on
intrinsic
\emph default
 definition of the tangent space because this definition does not make use
 of any embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a larger space.
 This definition also does not rely on a choice of a local coordinate system
 because only the 
\emph on
curve
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 --- a set of points in the manifold --- that is used to construct the direction
al derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is perhaps difficult for the reader to visualize the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space of all possible directional derivatives.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In order to help the intuition and to describe this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space of derivatives
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 more explicitly, let us temporarily introduce a local coordinate system
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 around the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is represented in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 by functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, we can express the directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

 of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f(p_{0})=\sum_{\alpha}\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right|_{p_{0}}\left.\frac{d\gamma^{\alpha}}{d\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}=\left[\sum_{\alpha}\left.\frac{d\gamma^{\alpha}}{d\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right|_{p_{0}}\right]f.\]

\end_inset

It is clear from this formula that the derivative operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is represented by the differential operator
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}_{\gamma}\equiv\sum_{\alpha}\left.\frac{d\gamma^{\alpha}}{d\tau}\right|_{\tau=0}\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right|_{p_{0}}\]

\end_inset

acting on functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the partial derivative with respect to one coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we see that all the possible directional derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 are described by the set of coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ d\gamma^{\alpha}/d\tau\right\} $
\end_inset

 multiplying a fixed set of differential operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma^{\alpha}/d\tau$
\end_inset

 depend on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, while the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 do not.
 Therefore, it is natural to regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 as the basis in the vector space of directional derivatives and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma^{\alpha}/d\tau$
\end_inset

 as the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 in that basis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way, we have expressed directional derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 as differential operators in a local coordinate system.
 An arbitrary directional derivative can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\alpha}u^{\alpha}\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are some coefficients.
 Now it is clear that all directional derivatives at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 form a vector space spanned by the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This vector space is 
\emph on
the same
\emph default
 as the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p_{0}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 defined above using the embedding picture.
 This is so because the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p_{0}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in the embedding picture consists of all the possible vectors tangent to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, which is the same as the set of velocity vectors of all possible curves
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the set of all possible values of the components 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma^{\alpha}/d\tau$
\end_inset

.
 So we may 
\emph on
identify
\emph default
 the space of tangent vectors to curves at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 with the space of directional derivatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 These are two equivalent descriptions of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p_{0}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A tangent vector can be understood both as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction within the manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and, at the same time, as a differential operator acting on scalar functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The natural basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the tangent space is called the 
\series bold
coordinate basis
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{coordinate basis}

\end_inset

 corresponding to a chosen coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will denote tangent vectors by boldface letters such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 rather than by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, since the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 plays only an auxiliary role.
 The action of a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 on a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 will be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

 rather than by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f$
\end_inset

.
 In local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

, one can express the value of a directional derivative (tangent vector)
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 applied to a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}\circ f=\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\left.\frac{\partial f}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right|_{p_{0}},\label{eq:vector on func}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Hence, it is convenient to visualize the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as the derivative operator
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\equiv\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}.\]

\end_inset

 The derivative of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 along a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}_{\gamma}f(p_{0})\equiv\left.\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right|_{p_{0}}\circ f,\]

\end_inset

where the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right|_{p_{0}}$
\end_inset

 means the tangent vector to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark on notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbol 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used in general to denote the application of an operation to its argument(s).
 For instance, a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is by definition a derivative operation, which can be applied to a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and yields another function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 In this notation, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $X\circ Y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Below, I also occasionally use the symbol 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to denote the application of a 1-form to a vector and of multilinear forms
 to sets of vectors.
 For instance, a bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 applied to two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 yields a number denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $B\circ\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tangent vectors to curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 where this does not cause confusion.
 I will not use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 any more, and I will call tangent vectors simply 
\series bold
vectors
\series default
 unless a vector is explicitly constructed as tangent to a curve or a surface
 within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Coordinate basis vectors such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial y$
\end_inset

 are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 for brevity; in that case, the subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 an index but a local coordinate, and this will be made clear in the text.
 I will call attention to cases when the traditional index notation and
 the Einstein summation convention, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}\partial_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, are used.
 These cases will not be common in the text.
 Usually, summation over indices will be written out explicitly.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is given, the components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in any local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be found by substituting the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinate functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{n}$
\end_inset

 into Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vector on func}

\end_inset

).
 Thus, the components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 can be found as
\begin_inset Formula \[
v^{\alpha}=\mathbf{v}\circ x^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset

This is a convenient way to compute the components of a vector in a coordinate
 system, if the vector is already known through another coordinate system
 or expressed in another way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a two-dimensional manifold with local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is specified as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma(\tau)=\left\{ x_{0}(\tau),y_{0}(\tau)\right\} =\left\{ \cos\tau,2\sin\tau\right\} \]

\end_inset

 in these coordinates.
 Let us compute the tangent vector to the curve, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(\tau)\equiv\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts on functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\circ f\equiv\frac{d}{d\tau}f(x_{0}(\tau),y_{0}(\tau)).\]

\end_inset

The tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 are a basis in the tangent space at any point.
 The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{x},\partial_{y}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are found by using the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the above equation.
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
v^{x} & =\mathbf{v}\circ x=\frac{d}{d\tau}x_{0}(\tau)=-\sin\tau,\\
v^{y} & =\mathbf{v}\circ y=\frac{d}{d\tau}y_{0}(\tau)=2\cos\tau.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=-\left(\sin\tau\right)\partial_{x}+2\left(\cos\tau\right)\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 By inspection, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 directly through 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=-\frac{1}{2}y\partial_{x}+2x\partial_{y}.\]

\end_inset

Using this formula, we can define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as a vector 
\emph on
field
\emph default
 everywhere (not only on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 However, there are infinitely many different vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 that coincide with 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

; the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 shown above is just one such field that was, by a coincidence, easy to
 write down in the present case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us also compute the components of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in a different coordinate system.
 For example, consider a new local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a,b\right\} $
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
a=x+y,\quad b=e^{x-y}.\]

\end_inset

The inverse functions are
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=\frac{1}{2}\left(a+\ln b\right),\quad y=\frac{1}{2}\left(a-\ln b\right).\]

\end_inset

 The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are found as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
v^{a} & =\mathbf{v}\circ a=\left(-\frac{1}{2}y\partial_{x}+2x\partial_{y}\right)\left(x+y\right)=-\frac{1}{2}y+2x,\\
v^{b} & =\mathbf{v}\circ b=\left(-\frac{1}{2}y\partial_{x}+2x\partial_{y}\right)e^{x-y}=\left(-\frac{1}{2}y-2x\right)e^{x-y}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, we can express the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the new coordinate system as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\left(\frac{3}{4}a+\frac{5}{4}\ln b\right)\partial_{a}+\left(-\frac{5}{4}a-\frac{3}{4}\ln b\right)b\partial_{b}.\]

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

