\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent vectors as short curve segments
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive picture of an ordinary vector is that of a piece of a straight
 line with an arrow at one end.
 In a curved space, there are in general no naturally defined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

straight lines,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but a sufficiently short line segment can be considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost straight.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 So one can visualize a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 heuristically as a short line segment going from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to a neighbor point 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now explore this heuristic picture, since it provides an important
 intuitive link between the ordinary geometric notions in flat space and
 the corresponding notions in the curved space calculus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To build a correspondence between tangent vectors and line segments, consider
 a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and goes through 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\gamma(\tau_{0})$
\end_inset

, and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $p'=\gamma(\tau_{0}+\sigma)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is heuristically a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 number.
 (In other words, we will take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 at the end).
 Now we would like to define a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to the short segment of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 between the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A tangent vector is, by definition, a derivative along a curve (the derivative
 is applied to scalar functions).
 So it is natural to consider the derivative of an arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ f\equiv\lim_{\delta\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{f(\gamma(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau))-f(\gamma(\tau_{0}))}{\delta\tau}.\]

\end_inset

While finding the exact value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ f$
\end_inset

 requires taking the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we will compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ f$
\end_inset

 sufficiently precisely if we use the finite value 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau=\sigma$
\end_inset

, provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently small.
 Then we obtain the approximate expression
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ f\approx f(p')-f(p).\]

\end_inset

The error of this approximation is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

