\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})=p'$
\end_inset

.
 We can compute the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and then the formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\left(\tau_{1}-\tau_{0}\right)\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau_{0})\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}.\]

\end_inset

The tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 represents the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

arrow between the points
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 in the sense of the formula 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f(p')-f(p)\approx\mathbf{v}\circ f,\label{eq:tangent vector for finite separation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which is approximately valid for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 up to second-order corrections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Tangent space as space of derivations
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Every-derivation-is}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will see that the properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

) are a minimal necessary set of properties describing 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 the possible directional derivatives.
 Therefore, one may forget that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 was defined using some curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

, drop the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, call any map 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 from functions to numbers satisfying the above properties a 
\series bold
derivation
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{derivation}

\end_inset

 and define the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p_{0}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as the set of all possible derivations.
 This somewhat abstract definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is more elegant from the purely mathematical point of view but entirely
 equivalent to the earlier definitions, because every derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

) is a directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 along some curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the only way to differentiate a function is to take a derivativ
e along a curve in some direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove these statements, let us perform explicit calculations in a local
 coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 is a derivation satisfying Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function, then we can apply the chain rule (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:chain rule}

\end_inset

) and compute
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}\circ f(p)=\sum_{\alpha}\frac{\partial f}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\textrm{D}\circ x^{\alpha}(p),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}\circ x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the application of the derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 to the scalar coordinate function 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{D}\circ f(p)=\left[\sum_{\alpha}\left(\textrm{D}\circ x^{\alpha}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right]f(p)\equiv\sum_{\alpha}u^{\alpha}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}\equiv\textrm{D}\circ x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 It is always possible to find a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 with the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma^{\alpha}/d\tau=u^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus any derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{D}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to a tangent vector in the previous sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector fields and flows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vector field
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field}

\end_inset

on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by choosing a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Most of the time, we will only need a vector field defined in a neighborhood
 of some point, rather than on the entire manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to visualize a vector field is to imagine that the manifold
 is filled by nonintersecting curves going through all its points (or at
 least through every point in some neighborhood); see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Vector-field}

\end_inset

.
 Such a collection of curves is called 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{congruence}

\end_inset

a 
\series bold
congruence
\series default
 of curves or a 
\series bold
flow
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{flow}

\end_inset

 of a vector field.
 If a congruence of curves is given, derivatives along curves at various
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will determine tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 at all points and thus define a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 This vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
tangent
\series default
 to the flow or the 
\series bold
generator
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{generator}

\end_inset

 of the flow.
 The curves in the congruence are also called the 
\series bold
flow lines
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!flow lines of}

\end_inset

 or 
\series bold
orbits
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!orbits of}

\end_inset

 of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In our notation, a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is an orbit of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau)=\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{\gamma(\tau)}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 along the curve.
\end_layout

