\begin_layout Caption
A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 tangent to a congruence of curves, which are the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 For each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 belongs to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cap:Vector-field}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Orbits of a nonzero, smooth vector field always exist and are unique because
 they are solutions of ordinary differential equations.
 To see this, consider a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is specified by its components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 (the components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 can be found as 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}=\mathbf{v}\circ x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

).
 A curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinate functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau)=\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{\gamma(\tau)}$
\end_inset

 translates into a system of differential equations,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)}{d\tau}=\left.v^{\alpha}\right|_{p=\gamma(\tau)}.\]

\end_inset

We may choose the initial condition as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(0)=x_{(0)}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{(0)}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are the local coordinates of an initial point of the curve.
 Since the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is smooth, such a system of equations always has a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 by the well-known theorem of differential calculus.
 This solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 represents the required curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 in the local coordinate system.
 Of course, this system of equations may be complicated and so it is not
 always possible to obtain an 
\emph on
explicit
\emph default
 formula for the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 In most cases, an approximate solution can be found numerically.
 Since solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\alpha}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 exist and are unique starting from any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the orbits of a nonzero, smooth vector field always form a congruence
 that (at least locally) fills space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, consider the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 going through each point of some neighborhood.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 be the parameter along each of the orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 This defines 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as a scalar function on the manifold.
 We can compute the scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Along every orbit, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\circ\tau=\frac{d}{d\tau}\tau=1,\]

\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ\tau=1$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are local coordinates around a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, we can consider a congruence of curves of varying 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}$
\end_inset

 and constant 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

, ...
 The tangent vector field to this congruence is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This congruence consists of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved coordinate axes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the other coordinate basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{2}$
\end_inset

, etc., can be seen as tangent vectors to a congruence of curves made by
 other coordinate axes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Diffeomorphism flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flow of a vector field can be visualized as a collection of diffeomorphisms,
 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
of smooth maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 that move points in the manifold.
 For each value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, there is a diffeomorphism, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(\tau\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
 This diffeomorphism, by definition, moves each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 which is at parameter distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 that starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A diffeomorphism flow is given explicitly by the equations
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\{ x,y,z\right\} \mapsto\left\{ x+\tau y,y,z-\tau x\right\} \]

\end_inset

in a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Compute the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 that generates this flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=y\partial_{x}-x\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Tangent bundle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all the tangent spaces (one tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

) is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and called the 
\series bold
tangent bundle
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent bundle}

\end_inset

of the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The tangent bundle is itself a manifold with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This manifold is perhaps not easy to visualize as a whole, but we will
 not need to do anything complicated with the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as a manifold.
 Let us only verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a smooth manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold and, as such, can be covered by a set of charts.
 Consider one such chart that maps a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Tangent vectors at points 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 are mapped into tangent vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

, which are simply vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is a portion of the flat Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the part of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 consisting of tangent planes to points 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one mapped into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}=\mathbb{R}^{2n}$
\end_inset

, we have established that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 can be covered by patches, and one can find charts that map these patches
 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2n}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to realize that the tangent bundle, as a whole manifold,
 is not necessarily equivalent (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
diffeomorphic) to the direct product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, even though every small patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to a patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is the same as that for the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 not being diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, even though small patches of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are diffeomorphic to patches of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, the patches may be glued together in a nontrivial way such that
 the global geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is different from that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A detailed consideration would lead us too far into differential topology,
 so I will give only a qualitative example.
 Suppose a diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{M}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 exists, such that every vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $p\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, is mapped one-to-one onto the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 via an invertible linear transformation.
 Then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 one may apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p\times\left\{ 1,0,0,...,0\right\} \in\mathcal{M}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and obtain a nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}(p)\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 However, such a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 sometimes cannot exist; a typical example is the 2-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It is known that there exists no everywhere nonvanishing and smooth tangent
 vector field on a 2-sphere.
 This property is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

impossibility of combing a sphere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{combing a sphere}

\end_inset

 (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset

).
 So it is impossible to choose even a single nonzero vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 that smoothly varies throughout the sphere.
 Thus, a diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:S^{2}\times\mathbb{R}^{2}\rightarrow TS^{2}$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
 A tangent bundle which is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
trivial
\series default
.
 It follows that the 2-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial tangent bundle.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tensor fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
covector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{covector}

\end_inset

is a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 from vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 into numbers.
 I assume that you know this standard construction from linear algebra,
 and I will only summarize the concepts we will need.
 In the index notation, covectors are denoted by letters with a subscript
 index, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 In our notation, a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 applied to a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 gives a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (read 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

); sometimes we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for the same thing.
 (In the index notation, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Covectors themselves naturally form a vector space called the 
\series bold
dual space
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{dual space}

\end_inset

 The dual space to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and consists of covectors acting on tangent vectors at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is also called the 
\series bold
cotangent
\series default
 
\series bold
space
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cotangent space}

\end_inset


\series default
 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{dual space}

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
covector field
\series default
, also called a 
\series bold
1-form
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{1-form}

\end_inset

 is a choice of a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\omega\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 from the dual space (cotangent space) 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be seen as a linear map from vector fields to functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, by acting pointwise on a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and producing a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega:\mathbf{v}\mapsto f;\quad\left.\omega\right|_{p}\circ\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}\equiv f(p).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of a 1-form is the mapping of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 into the derivative of a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, that is, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\mapsto\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, this map is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and hence, by definition, it is a 1-form.
 This 1-form is called the 
\series bold
gradient
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{gradient}

\end_inset

of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for a fixed function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we have defined the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 by its action on a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v}\equiv\mathbf{v}\circ f.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us recall that tangent vectors can be understood as an approximate represent
ation of short curve segments (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

).
 If a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 represents a short curve segment between points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 then the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 yields approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p')-f(p)$
\end_inset

, according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:tangent vector for finite separation}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a two-dimensional manifold with a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The gradient of the coordinate function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, this 1-form acts on vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\textrm{d}x\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}\circ x$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 then obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\circ x=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this notation, we obtain the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\textrm{d}x\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\left(\textrm{d}x\right)\circ\partial_{x}=1,\]

\end_inset

 which may look unusual or even confusing at first glance.
 However, it is only the notation that is unusual; the results are always
 consistent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider another vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=y^{2}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=x^{2}y^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and produces the function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\circ f=y^{2}\frac{\partial}{\partial x}f(x,y)=2xy^{5}.\]

\end_inset

 The 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 can be computed using standard rules of calculus as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}f=2xy^{3}\textrm{d}x+3x^{2}y^{2}\textrm{d}y.\]

\end_inset

However, note that now 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 are well-defined objects (1-forms) rather than heuristic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimals.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 on the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v}\equiv\mathbf{v}\circ f=2xy^{5}.\]

\end_inset

Let us see how this result can be obtained using the explicit expressions
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v} & =\left(2xy^{3}\textrm{d}x+3x^{2}y^{2}\textrm{d}y\right)\circ y^{2}\partial_{x}\\
 & =\left(2xy^{5}\right)\textrm{d}x\circ\partial_{x}+\left(3x^{2}y^{4}\right)\textrm{d}y\circ\partial_{x}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\circ\partial_{x}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\circ\partial_{y}=0$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v}=2xy^{5}$
\end_inset

 as before.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

