\begin_layout Subsection
Commutator of vector fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a (first-order) differential operator acting on functions
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}:f\mapsto\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

, one may consider the 
\series bold
commutator
\series default
 of two such operators,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f\equiv\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)-\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\mathbf{u}\circ f\right).\label{eq:def commutator}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It turns out (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset

) that the result is 
\emph on
again a
\emph default
 
\emph on
derivation
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a first-order differential operator acting on functions, even though
 it may appear at first glance that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f$
\end_inset

 involves second-order derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 For this reason, the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to some vector field acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 This vector field is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
commutator
\series default
 of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 It follows from the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:def commutator}

\end_inset

) and Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Leibnitz rule}

\end_inset

) that the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 satisfies the defining properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)--(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

) of a derivation.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 is itself a vector field.

\series bold
 (b)
\series default
 The components 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 of the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 in terms of the components 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}=\sum_{\alpha}u^{\alpha}\mathbf{e}_{\alpha},\quad\mathbf{v}=\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\mathbf{e}_{\alpha},\quad\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\equiv\sum_{\alpha}c^{\alpha}\mathbf{e}_{\alpha},\]

\end_inset

are given by the expression
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\right)^{\beta}\equiv c^{\beta}=u^{\alpha}\frac{\partial v^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}-v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial u^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}.\label{eq:commutator in components}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\series bold
 (c)
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\equiv\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are the coordinate basis vector fields defined through a local coordinate
 system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{\alpha},\mathbf{e}_{\beta}\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof of Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Proof-of-Statement-connecting}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a) 
\series default
The properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

) are obvious; the nontrivial one is the Leibnitz rule\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Leibnitz rule}

\end_inset

).
 To verify the Leibnitz rule, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ(fg)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are smooth functions: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ(fg) & =\mathbf{u}\circ\left(g\mathbf{v}\circ f+f\mathbf{v}\circ g\right)-\mathbf{v}\circ\left(g\mathbf{u}\circ f+f\mathbf{u}\circ g\right)\\
=g\mathbf{u}\circ & \left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)+f\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\mathbf{v}\circ g\right)-g\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\mathbf{u}\circ f\right)-f\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\mathbf{u}\circ g\right)\\
 & +\left(\mathbf{u}\circ g\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)+\left(\mathbf{u}\circ f\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ g\right)\\
 & -\left(\mathbf{v}\circ g\right)\left(\mathbf{u}\circ f\right)-\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\left(\mathbf{u}\circ g\right)\\
= & \left(\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f\right)g+f\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ g.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(b)
\series default
 A straightforward calculation using the representation of the basis fields
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 as differential operators yields
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right] & =\sum_{\alpha,\beta}\left(u^{\alpha}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right)\left(v^{\beta}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\right)-\sum_{\alpha,\beta}\left(v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right)\left(u^{\beta}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha,\beta}u^{\alpha}v^{\beta}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}+\sum_{\alpha,\beta}\left(u^{\alpha}\frac{\partial v^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\\
 & \quad-\sum_{\alpha,\beta}v^{\alpha}u^{\beta}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}-\sum_{\alpha,\beta}\left(v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial u^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha,\beta}\left(u^{\alpha}\frac{\partial v^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}-v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial u^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\equiv\sum_{\beta}c^{\beta}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 is indeed a first-order differential operator, and also gives an explicit
 formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(c)
\series default
 For a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x^{1},...,x^{n})$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}f=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\beta}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}f\]

\end_inset

according to a well-known theorem of calculus.
 Therefore the basis vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 commute with each other.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Discussion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:connecting}

\end_inset

 presents two ways of proving the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a first-order differential operation, in parts (a) and (b).
 The first proof (a) is performed purely algebraically, using the abstract
 definition of tangent vectors as (unspecified) operations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ(...)$
\end_inset

 with certain properties.
 The other proof (b) uses a specific representation of tangent vectors as
 differential operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the proofs have certain advantages and disadvantages.
 The proof (a) is very general because it uses only some properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ(...)$
\end_inset

.
 So this proof applies not only to directional derivatives but to 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 operation with the properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Leibnitz rule}

\end_inset

), such as the Lie derivative and the covariant derivative that we will
 use later.
 The proof (a) applies equally well to derivatives and to finite difference
 operators, to operators in infinite-dimensional spaces, and so on.
 The proof (a) is also more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

elegant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because it is index-free, does not involve unnecessary structures (such
 as a local coordinate system and a basis), and does not depend on the explicit
 representation of vectors in coordinates.
 This is the kind of proof a mathematician would be looking for.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the proof (b) is conceptually easier to understand (especiall
y for beginners) because it consists of a specific computation in a familiar
 and elementary context, namely, manipulations with partial derivatives
 of functions.
 Also, the result of the proof (b) is a directly usable formula for the
 components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

, while the proof (a) merely shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined vector.
 In the text that follows, I will usually not need explicit formulas for
 components of vectors, and therefore index-free calculations will be preferable.
 However, in every case one can translate the final results into components
 in a local coordinate system.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

