\begin_layout Section
Lie derivative
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Lie-derivative}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts as a directional derivative on scalar functions.
 The 
\series bold
Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset


\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie derivative}

\end_inset

with respect to a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is an important differential operation that can be applied not only to
 scalars but also to all tensor fields.
 We now deduce the formulas for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 in an 
\series bold
axiomatic
\series default
 
\series bold
way
\series default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
by assuming some desirable properties of this operation.
 Later we will give a geometric interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 to act as the usual directional derivative on scalar functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}f=\mathbf{v}\circ f.\label{eq:Lie on scalar}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Additionally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 should have the following properties, fully analogous to Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Leibnitz rule}

\end_inset

), but applicable to arbitrary tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A+B) & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A)+\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(B),\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A\otimes B) & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A)\otimes B+A\otimes\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(B),\label{eq:tensor product}\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A\circ B) & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(A)\circ B+A\circ\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(B),\label{eq:contraction}\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes B$
\end_inset

 is the tensor product and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\circ B$
\end_inset

 here denotes any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pairing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pairings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this sense).
 As we will see, these properties uniquely define the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 on any tensor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Commutator as Lie derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a scalar and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are vectors, we expect to have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{u}\circ f)=\left[\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{u})\right]\circ f+\mathbf{u}\circ\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(f).\]

\end_inset

Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie on scalar}

\end_inset

), this is rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\circ(\mathbf{u}\circ f)=\left[\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{u})\right]\circ f+\mathbf{u}\circ(\mathbf{v}\circ f).\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{u})\right]\circ f=\mathbf{v}\circ(\mathbf{u}\circ f)-\mathbf{u}\circ(\mathbf{v}\circ f)=\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right]\circ f.\]

\end_inset

In other words, the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the commutator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}=\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right]=-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

In the index notation, we have, according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:commutator in components}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}\right)^{\alpha}=\sum v^{\beta}\frac{\partial u}{\partial x^{\beta}}^{\alpha}-u^{\beta}\frac{\partial v^{\alpha}}{\partial x^{\beta}}.\label{eq:Lie derivative in components}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to realize that the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 depends on the 
\emph on
derivatives
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (not only on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Lie-derivative-of-lambdav}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Lie-derivative-of-lambdav}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 involves derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are vector fields and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}=\lambda\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}-\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

 To derive this expression, we use the antisymmetry of the commutator and
 the Leibnitz rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u} & =\left[\lambda\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right]=-\left[\mathbf{u},\lambda\mathbf{v}\right]=-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\mathbf{v}\right)\\
 & =-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\right)\mathbf{v}-\lambda\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\mathbf{v}\right)\\
 & =-\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\mathbf{v}+\lambda\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lie derivative of tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us continue to investigate the properties of the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 According to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:contraction}

\end_inset

), we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\circ\mathbf{u})=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega)\circ\mathbf{u}+\omega\circ\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function, so Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie on scalar}

\end_inset

) gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\circ\mathbf{u})=\mathbf{v}\circ(\omega\circ\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

Hence, the Lie derivative of a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

 that acts on an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega)\circ\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{v}\circ(\omega\circ\mathbf{u})-\omega\circ\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right].\]

\end_inset

In the index notation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega)\right]_{\mu}=v^{\alpha}\partial_{\alpha}\omega_{\mu}+\omega_{\alpha}\partial_{\mu}v^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of the Lie derivative on an arbitrary tensor can be derived similarly
, using the properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie on scalar}

\end_inset

)--(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:contraction}

\end_inset

).
 For example, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form with vector values, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
 (The index notation for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 would be 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.) Then the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{w}}A$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{w}}A\right](\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\left[\mathbf{w},A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\right]-A(\left[\mathbf{w},\mathbf{u}\right],\mathbf{v})-A(\mathbf{u},\left[\mathbf{w},\mathbf{v}\right]).\]

\end_inset

 In the index notation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A\right)_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}=v^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}A_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}+A_{\alpha\mu}^{\lambda}\partial_{\beta}v^{\mu}+A_{\mu\beta}^{\lambda}\partial_{\alpha}v^{\mu}-A_{\alpha\beta}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}v^{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative with respect to a coordinate basis vector of a given
 coordinate system has special properties with respect to that coordinate
 system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Lie-derivative-constant-coefficients}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:Lie-derivative-constant-coefficients}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be local coordinates in a manifold, and consider the standard coordinate
 bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\mu}\right\} \equiv\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \textrm{d}x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the tangent and the cotangent spaces respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) The Lie derivatives with respect to a coordinate basis vector of another
 basis vector or of a basis 1-form are zero,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\left(\partial_{\nu}\right)=0,\quad\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\left(\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\right)=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) Let us represent an arbitrary tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m,n\right)$
\end_inset

 in the coordinate basis by an array of components.
 For example, a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is represented by an array 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
T=\sum_{\alpha,\beta,\gamma}T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\beta}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\gamma}.\]

\end_inset

If it is known that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\partial/\partial x^{1}}T=0$
\end_inset

, it means that the component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}$
\end_inset

 are independent of the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) The coordinate basis vectors commute since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\left(\partial_{\nu}\right)f=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\nu}}f-\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\nu}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}f=0\]

\end_inset

for a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative of a 1-form is defined through the action of the 1-form
 on an arbitrary vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\right)\circ\mathbf{v}=\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\left(\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\circ\mathbf{v}\right)-\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\circ\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\mathbf{v}\right).\]

\end_inset

By definition of the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\circ\mathbf{v}\equiv\mathbf{v}\circ x^{\nu},\quad\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\circ\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\mathbf{v}\right)\equiv\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\mathbf{v}\right)\circ x^{\nu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is understood as a scalar function representing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-th coordinate of a point.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{\mu}}\textrm{d}x^{\nu}\right)\circ\mathbf{v} & =\partial_{\mu}\left(\mathbf{v}\circ x^{\nu}\right)-\left[\partial_{\mu},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ x^{\nu}\\
 & =\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\partial_{\mu}\circ x^{\nu}\right)=\mathbf{v}\circ\delta_{\mu}^{\nu}=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) It is sufficient to show the proof on the given example involving a
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Leibnitz rule, we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{1}}T=\sum_{\alpha,\beta,\gamma}\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{1}}T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}\right)\partial_{\alpha}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\beta}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\gamma}\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha,\beta,\gamma}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{1}}T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}\right)\partial_{\alpha}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\beta}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\gamma},\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{1}}\partial_{\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{1}}\textrm{d}x^{\beta}=0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Since the set of basic tensors of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\alpha}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\beta}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent, it follows that every derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{1}T^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma}$
\end_inset

 vanishes.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
