\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie derivative!interpretation}

\end_inset

To illustrate the geometric significance of the Lie derivative, we first
 note that the Lie derivative of a connecting vector field is zero.
 A connecting vector, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Connecting-vector}

\end_inset

, is transported from the initial point by the flow of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We can imagine that the entire neighborhood of points around the initial
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is transported along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to another nearby point 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

; this neighborhood is deformed in a certain way by the transport.
 The character of this deformation is determined by the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the neighborhood of the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and along the way to 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Tangent vectors at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be visualized as directions towards points near 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So all tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},...\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are also transported to particular tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}',\mathbf{b}',...\in T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-tangent-space-flow}

\end_inset

).
 Thus the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 determines a map between tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, as long as the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 lie on a single orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

