\begin_layout Standard
We have already seen (Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Connecting-vectors}

\end_inset

) that a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 obtained by transporting an initial vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 along the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

.
 (The transport from an initial point defines the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 along a single orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, so we need to use many orbits and many initial values to define the vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.) In general, for two vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 So we might say (heuristically) that the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 measures the extent to which a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 fails to be a connecting field for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make these considerations somewhat more precise, let us temporarily denote
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\tau}:T_{p}\mathcal{M}\rightarrow T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 the map that transports tangent vectors along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 from point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to point 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the parameter distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 (In other words, we introduce a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 parameterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)=p'$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 everywhere along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.) In this notation, the vectors in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-tangent-space-flow}

\end_inset

 satisfy
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}'=\varphi_{\tau}\left(\mathbf{a}\right),\quad\mathbf{b}'=\varphi_{\tau}\left(\mathbf{b}\right).\]

\end_inset

Now we would like to compute the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is some vector field.
 Let us compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

; let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is very small and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a vector pointing from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 We might try to write the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p'}-\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p}}{\tau},\quad???\]

\end_inset

but this expression is meaningless since we cannot subtract vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 at different points: these vectors belong to different tangent spaces.
 However, we can transport 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p'}\in T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 back to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 using the inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\tau}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 So we write the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}=\lim_{\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{\varphi_{\tau}^{-1}\left(\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p'}\right)-\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p}}{\tau}.\label{eq:Lie derivative formula phi}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The geometric interpretation of this expression is clear: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is the extent to which the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 fails to be transported along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Although in this section I do not actually 
\emph on
prove
\emph default
 that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative formula phi}

\end_inset

) is equivalent to the previous definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, a proof can be straightforwardly filled in or found in differential geometry
 textbooks, albeit perhaps in a more formal or abstract language.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar considerations apply to the Lie derivative of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with respect to a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Any tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be defined as a multilinear function of tangent vectors and covectors,
 while vectors and covectors are defined through the points in an infinitesimal
 neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, any tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is ultimately an object defined through combinations of points near 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 When these points are transported by the flow of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the corresponding transport 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\tau}(A)$
\end_inset

 of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is also well-defined.
 Then the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 is defined by a formula analogous to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative formula phi}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from expressions derived above that the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 contains not only derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 but also derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 So the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 depends not only on the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 but also on the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in an entire neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 is not a true directional derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A true directional derivative along a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a derivative that depends only on the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\equiv\mathbf{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, must be independent of the 
\emph on
derivatives
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Such a true directional derivative cannot be defined without introducing
 some additional structures on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This is so because the tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $A(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(p')$
\end_inset

 at neighboring points belong to different tensor spaces, and thus there
 is no definition for a quantity such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A(p')-A(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, there is no possibility to integrate vectors or tensors over
 a domain.
 We might say, in figurative language, that the tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

are disconnected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and a directional derivative cannot be computed without a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between these spaces.
 (The structure called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will be introduced in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Connection}

\end_inset

 below.) When we evaluate the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, the information about how to connect the tangent spaces comes from the
 flow of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to relate directions around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to directions around 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this procedure uses information about the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the entire neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, not just at one point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

