\begin_layout Subsection
Volume as antisymmetric tensor
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Volume-as-antisymmetric}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The familiar notion of volume can be given a natural interpretation in terms
 of antisymmetric multilinear functions of vectors, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
antisymmetric tensors.
 This interpretation is a great help in calculations because antisymmetric
 tensors have rich properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the two-dimensional Euclidean plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In two dimensions, the 
\emph on
area
\emph default
 plays the role of volume, so let us consider the area of a parallelogram
 spanned by two vectors 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 According to standard formula of elementary geometry, the area of the parallelo
gram is
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=\left|\mathbf{u}\right|\left|\mathbf{v}\right|\sin\alpha,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the vectors, which is a number between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 determined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\cos\alpha\equiv\frac{\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}}{\left|\mathbf{u}\right|\left|\mathbf{v}\right|}.\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{u}\right|\equiv\sqrt{\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the standard Euclidean scalar product.
 Thus the area of a parallelogram spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative number defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\equiv\sqrt{\left|\mathbf{u}\right|^{2}\left|\mathbf{v}\right|^{2}-\left(\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}\right)^{2}}.\]

\end_inset

 This number appears to be a complicated nonlinear function of the vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 It is more convenient to work with the 
\series bold
oriented area
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{oriented area}

\end_inset

 which is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}=+A$
\end_inset

 if the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right\} $
\end_inset

 has positive orientation and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}=-A$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 (We can fix the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive orientation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to be that of the coordinate axes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the plane, taken in this order.) The decisive advantage of the oriented
 area 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 over the conventional (unsigned) area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 turns out to be an 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
 
\emph on
bilinear
\emph default
 
\emph on
function
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In mathematics, a number-valued bilinear function of two vectors is usually
 called a 
\series bold
bilinear form
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{bilinear form}

\end_inset

 while an 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
 bilinear form is called a 
\series bold
2-form
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{2-form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The oriented area 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is by definition antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

, since the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right\} $
\end_inset

 has opposite orientation to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is an bilinear form can be demonstrated quite straightforwardly.
 When one of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by a positive number, the area of a parallelogram is multiplied
 by the same number.
 If one of the vectors is multiplied by a negative number, the orientation
 of the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is reversed and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 changes sign.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(0,\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.
 So it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\lambda\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\lambda\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary real number (positive, zero, or negative).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=-\tilde{A}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

, the same property holds for the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Further, one can show by an elementary geometric construction (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Area-of-the-parallelogram}

\end_inset

) that the area does not change when a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is added to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u}+\lambda\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

In two dimensions, two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are a basis if 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 is linear in each argument: we can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u}_{1}+\mathbf{u}_{2},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 by decomposing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}=\lambda_{1}\mathbf{u}+\mu_{1}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{2}=\lambda_{2}\mathbf{u}+\mu_{2}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and then it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u}_{1}+\mathbf{u}_{2},\mathbf{v})=\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{v})+\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u}_{2},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

The same property holds for the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is an antisymmetric bilinear form that we may call the 
\series bold
area 2-form
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

