\begin_layout Standard
To make the above discussion less abstract, let us express all quantities
 in Cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 have components 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u_{1},u_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ v_{1},v_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

; the unoriented area is
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\sqrt{\left(u_{1}^{2}+u_{2}^{2}\right)\left(v_{1}^{2}+v_{2}^{2}\right)-\left(u_{1}v_{1}+u_{2}v_{2}\right)^{2}}.\]

\end_inset

After some algebraic simplification, this becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\sqrt{\left(u_{1}v_{2}-u_{2}v_{1}\right)^{2}}=\left|u_{1}v_{2}-u_{2}v_{1}\right|.\label{eq:unoriented area}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is the absolute value of a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=u_{1}v_{2}-u_{2}v_{1}=\left|\begin{array}{cc}
u_{1} & v_{1}\\
u_{2} & v_{2}\end{array}\right|.\]

\end_inset

The sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 is chosen such that the area of the unit square spanned by the unit basis
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 (in this order) is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 We note that the oriented area 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}$
\end_inset

 is more closely related to linear algebra than the unoriented area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar argument (with a suitable generalization of Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Area-of-the-parallelogram}

\end_inset

 to three dimensions) shows that the oriented 3-volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{V}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c)}$
\end_inset

 of a parallelepiped spanned by three vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 in a three-dimensional Euclidean space is a totally antisymmetric trilinear
 form (3-form).
 The same conclusion holds in any dimensions.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional oriented volume of a parallelepiped spanned by vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 in Euclidean space is given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{V}(\mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n})=\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{1}^{1} & \cdots & a_{n}^{1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{1}^{n} & \cdots & a_{n}^{n}\end{array}\right|,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}^{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th component of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

