\begin_layout Standard
The last formula suggests a close connection between antisymmetric forms
 and the calculus of determinants.
 Indeed, such a close connection exists.
 For instance, one can show that the oriented volume of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepiped transformed by a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 will change by a numerical factor, which depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 but does not depend on the parallelepiped.
 This numerical factor is equal to the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Determinants}

\end_inset

, we use this property as a convenient 
\emph on
definition
\emph default
 of the determinant of a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A somewhat more complicated concept is the area of a parallelogram spanned
 by two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a higher-dimensional Euclidean space, for example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The ordinary (unoriented) area 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v)}$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:unoriented area}

\end_inset

).
 In three (or more) dimensions, one cannot define an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oriented
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 area 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, it turns out that one can define a 
\emph on
vector-valued
\emph default
 antisymmetric, bilinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 whose absolute value is equal to the area 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
 This function is the familiar vector product of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{A}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\mathbf{u}\times\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

 Indeed, it is well known that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{u}\times\mathbf{v}\right|=\left|\mathbf{u}\right|\left|\mathbf{v}\right|\sin\alpha=A(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

Thus, one could say that in three dimensions the area has an orientation
 
\emph on
vector
\emph default
.
 Thus, it is natural to regard the fundamental area as vector-valued; the
 ordinary area is then computed as the absolute value of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

area vector.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same idea can be generalized to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepipeds embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space (where 
\begin_inset Formula $N>n$
\end_inset

).
 This time, it turns out that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orientation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume is not a vector but an antisymmetric tensor; so the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oriented
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume is naturally tensor-valued.
 The ordinary volume is a suitable 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of that tensor.
 More explanations can be found in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Oriented volume and n-vectors}

\end_inset

.
 One may even change the point of view and regard the 
\emph on
oriented
\emph default
 volume as a basic quantity --- which is a certain totally antisymmetric
 tensor --- and the ordinary volume as a quantity 
\emph on
defined
\emph default
 as the absolute value of the oriented volume.
