\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation for differential forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In standard courses of multivariate calculus, one studies integrals such
 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iiint_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e^{-x^{2}-y^{2}-z^{2}}dxdydz=\pi^{3/2}.\]

\end_inset

 Expressions such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dxdydz$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurring under the sign of multiple integration are usually explained
 as a purely symbolic notation.
 It is perhaps not obvious to a student of calculus that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dxdydz$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 above can be interpreted, quite rigorously, as an 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
 product of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dy$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dz$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rather than an ordinary, symmetric product.
 In fact, the antisymmetric interpretation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dxdydz$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is necessary if one wishes to obtain a consistent calculus where objects
 such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dxdy$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are well-defined and transform correctly under a change of variables.
 Differential forms can be understood as the rigorous mathematical objects
 that make precise sense out of expressions such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dxdydz$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In this section we explore these motivational ideas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us begin by considering an example familiar from mechanics.
 Suppose a particle moves in three-dimensional space along a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(\tau)\equiv\left\{ X(\tau),Y(\tau),Z(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

 and experiences a space-dependent external force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\equiv\left\{ F_{1},F_{2},F_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The work done by the force can be computed as the 
\series bold
line integral
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{line integral}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
W=\int_{\mathbf{x}(\tau)}\left(F_{1}dx+F_{2}dy+F_{3}dz\right).\label{eq:line integral W}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression is computed as the ordinary integral
\begin_inset Formula \[
W=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(F_{1}\dot{X}+F_{2}\dot{Y}+F_{3}\dot{Z}\right)d\tau.\]

\end_inset

 However, this form of the expression requires a parameterization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, while the work 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is actually independent of the choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along the curve: it depends only on the force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 and on the layout of the given curve in space.
 So it is more natural to work with the line integral\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:line integral W}

\end_inset

).
 We can interpret the integrand in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:line integral W}

\end_inset

) directly as a 1-form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega\equiv F_{1}\textrm{d}x+F_{2}\textrm{d}y+F_{3}\textrm{d}z.\]

\end_inset

Note that the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{x}}d\tau$
\end_inset

 is an approximate representation of a short curve segment (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

) between the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(\tau+d\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(F_{1}\dot{X}+F_{2}\dot{Y}+F_{3}\dot{Z}\right)d\tau=\omega\circ\dot{\mathbf{x}}d\tau\]

\end_inset

is interpreted as the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 evaluated on the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{x}}d\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This expression represents a small amount of work done along a short curve
 segment.
 So the line integral\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:line integral W}

\end_inset

) is rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
W=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\omega\circ\dot{\mathbf{x}}\right)d\tau\equiv\int_{\gamma}\omega,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 denotes the path along which the particle is moving in space (regardless
 of the choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One does not write any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s after the integral sign in the last expression because all the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s are hidden in the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 I write the roman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 1-forms to emphasize the fact that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a separate, rigorously defined object, while 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stands for a heuristic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal change of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, one defines the integral of a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 over a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 One splits the curve into a large number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of short segments.
 Each segment is almost straight and thus can be approximately represented
 by a tangent vector (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

).
 Thus we represent the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 segments by 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Each segment contributes to the integral a small amount computed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v}_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 The integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\omega$
\end_inset

 is then defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\gamma}\omega=\lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=1}^{N}\omega(\mathbf{v}_{j}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The line integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\omega$
\end_inset

 can be reduced to an ordinary integral by choosing a parameterization 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 for the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and writing
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{\gamma}\omega=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\omega(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})d\tau.\label{eq:integral of 1-form over a curve}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is easy to see that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\omega$
\end_inset

 actually does not depend on the choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 (A redefinition 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\tau}=f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 will introduce a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

, while a compensating factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f'$
\end_inset

 will come from 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tilde{\tau}$
\end_inset

.) The reason is that the line integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined purely geometrically through splitting of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 into small segments.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\omega$
\end_inset

 is a geometrically defined quantity that is independent of the coordinate
 representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and of the choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculus of 1-forms is designed to be compatible with the change of
 variables under the integral.
 For instance, consider an ordinary integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)dx$
\end_inset

.
 After a change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x=X(\phi)$
\end_inset

, the integral becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int f(x)dx=\int f(X(\phi))\frac{dX}{d\phi}d\phi.\]

\end_inset

This corresponds precisely to the chain rule for the differential operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)\textrm{d}x=f(x)\textrm{d}X(\phi)=f(x)X'(\phi)\textrm{d}\phi.\]

\end_inset

So it is consistent to interpret the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)dx$
\end_inset

 within an ordinary integral as a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider two-dimensional integrals (
\series bold
surface integrals
\series default
).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{surface integral}

\end_inset

 An integral over a surface with local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 is computed as a repeated ordinary integral,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\iint F(x,y)dxdy=\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}dx\int_{y_{1}}^{y_{2}}dy\, F(x,y).\label{eq:surface integral as a repeated integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we would like to interpret the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y)dxdy$
\end_inset

 as an analog and a generalization of the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 seen in the previous example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the previous example, we can divide the surface of integration into
 a large number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of small rectangles with sides 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y$
\end_inset

.
 The sides of each rectangle are approximately represented by a pair of
 tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

.
 A rectangle number 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 located at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j},y_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 gives a small contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x_{j},y_{j})\delta x\delta y$
\end_inset

 to the integral.
 It is clear that the number 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x_{j},y_{j})\delta x\delta y$
\end_inset

 can be understood as the evaluation of a bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 acting on tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(x_{j},y_{j})\delta x\delta y\equiv\omega\left(\mathbf{u}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{j}\right).\]

\end_inset

The bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
2-form
\series default
 since it has 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 vector arguments.
 Then the surface integral is defined as the limit
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iint Fdxdy=\lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=1}^{N}\omega\left(\mathbf{u}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{j}\right).\]

\end_inset

 The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be temporarily written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=F\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now explore its properties under the change of variables in the
 integral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first perform a simple change of variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} \rightarrow\left\{ x,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

, where we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Y(x,\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a fixed function.
 To transform the integral, it is convenient to use the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:surface integral as a repeated integral}

\end_inset

).
 Since the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is held fixed within the integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}dx\int_{y_{1}}^{y_{2}}dy\, F(x,y)=\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}dx\int_{\Phi_{1}(x)}^{\Phi_{2}(x)}d\phi\, F(x,Y)\frac{\partial Y(x,\phi)}{\partial\phi}.\]

\end_inset

Hence, if we wish to interpret the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $F\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 consistently as a bilinear form, we must adopt the rule
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}Y(x,\phi)=\frac{\partial Y(x,\phi)}{\partial\phi}\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}\phi.\]

\end_inset

However, according to the calculus of 1-forms, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}Y(x,\phi)=\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}\textrm{d}x+\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\phi}\textrm{d}\phi\]

\end_inset

and (assuming that the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 is bilinear)
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}Y(x,\phi)=\textrm{d}x\,\left(\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}\textrm{d}x+\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\phi}\textrm{d}\phi\right).\]

\end_inset

Therefore, this calculus is consistent with the properties of two-dimensional
 integration only if we assume that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}x=0.\]

\end_inset

Now it is clear that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be a rather special kind of product of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

.
 This product is called the 
\series bold
exterior product 
\series default
(also 
\series bold
wedge product
\series default
) and is denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

; so one writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\,\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The property
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}x=0\]

\end_inset

together with bilinearity means that the exterior product is 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
.
 To see this, consider
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\left(x+y\right)\wedge\textrm{d}\left(x+y\right)=0\;\Rightarrow\;\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y+\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}x=0.\]

\end_inset

Let us now check the consistency of a more general change of variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} \rightarrow\left\{ \phi,\psi\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=X(\phi,\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Y(\phi,\psi)$
\end_inset

.
 Calculations are straightforward because the only new rule is the antisymmetry
 of the exterior product.
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y & =\textrm{d}X(\phi,\psi)\wedge\textrm{d}Y(\phi,\psi)\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial X}{\partial\phi}\textrm{d}\phi+\frac{\partial X}{\partial\psi}\textrm{d}\psi\right)\wedge\left(\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\phi}\textrm{d}\phi+\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\psi}\textrm{d}\psi\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial X}{\partial\phi}\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\psi}-\frac{\partial X}{\partial\psi}\frac{\partial Y}{\partial\phi}\right)\textrm{d}\phi\wedge\textrm{d}\psi,\label{eq:two-dimensional Jacobian}\end{align}

\end_inset

where we used the antisymmetry properties 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\phi\wedge\textrm{d}\phi=\textrm{d}\psi\wedge\textrm{d}\psi=0,\quad\textrm{d}\phi\wedge\textrm{d}\psi+\textrm{d}\psi\wedge\textrm{d}\phi=0,\]

\end_inset

to get the last line.
 Now we may recognize Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:two-dimensional Jacobian}

\end_inset

) as the standard formula for the change of variables, involving the two-dimensi
onal Jacobian of the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} \rightarrow\left\{ \phi,\psi\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In this way, we can see that the unusual rule of the exterior product is
 a natural consequence of the known properties of multiple integration.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
However, note that we obtained the Jacobian itself rather than its absolute
 value, which one has in formulas involving the area of domain.
 This is consistent because integrals of 2-forms are defined on 
\emph on
oriented
\emph default
 surfaces and are not merely integrals of the ordinary, unsigned area.
 Reversing the orientation of the surface will reverse the sign of the integral.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric formulation of the surface integral is therefore the integral
 of a 2-form over a surface, written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is a surface (or part of a surface) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same formulation applies to integrals over surfaces embedded in a higher-dim
ensional space.
 Consider another example familiar from physics: the flux of a magnetic
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 through a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is computed as a surface integral 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi=\int_{\mathcal{A}}\mathbf{B}\cdot d\mathbf{S},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 is understood as a vector-valued 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal surface element.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The flux integral is usually written in components, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\equiv\left\{ B_{x},B_{y},B_{z}\right\} $
\end_inset

, as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{A}}\left(B_{x}dydz+B_{y}dxdz+B_{z}dxdy\right).\]

\end_inset

However, this notation needs to be supplemented by a complicated prescription
 for the orientation of the surface elements.
 Integrals of this kind become more transparent in the notation of 2-forms.
 One introduces the 2-form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\beta}\equiv B_{x}\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z+B_{y}\textrm{d}z\wedge\textrm{d}x+B_{z}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\]

\end_inset

and expresses the flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi=\int_{\mathcal{A}}\boldsymbol{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

The (somewhat complicated) rules for changing variables in such integrals,
 as well as the orientation prescriptions, are automatically reproduced
 by the calculus of differential forms.
 The rules of this calculus are simple: one just needs to use the chain
 rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 and the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, one can treat a three-dimensional integral, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iiint F(x,y,z)dxdydz,\]

\end_inset

as an integral of the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y,z)\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

 over a three-dimensional manifold (or part of a manifold).
 The same rules will provide the correct formulas under any changes of variables
 in the integral.
 Collectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms (
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,...$
\end_inset

) are called 
\series bold
differential forms
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{differential forms}

\end_inset

since they represent expressions involving the differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this motivation, we proceed to summarize the main definitions and
 properties of differential forms.
 We begin by studying totally antisymmetric tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Antisymmetric tensors
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Antisymmetric tensors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{$n$-form}

\end_inset

An 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series bold
-form
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a totally antisymmetric map from sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vector fields to numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n})\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, which is linear in each of its vector arguments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form is a totally antisymmetric tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,n\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalent notations 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},...\mathbf{v}_{n})\equiv\omega\circ(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n})$
\end_inset

 will be used for convenience or clarity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When considering vector fields on manifolds, one deals with vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 defined in each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 So it is natural to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n};p)$
\end_inset

 defined in each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form fields.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 These 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form fields
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
differential forms
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{differential forms}

\end_inset

or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, just as we sometimes call vector fields simply vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

, tangent vectors are represented by components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms are represented by multi-indexed arrays of components, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha\beta...\gamma}$
\end_inset

, such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n})=\omega_{\alpha\beta...\gamma}v_{1}^{\alpha}v_{2}^{\beta}...v_{n}^{\gamma}.\]

\end_inset

The array of components 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha\beta...\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is totally antisymmetric in all indices.
 We use the index-free notation in which 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms are represented explicitly through basis 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
 To express the antisymmetry of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form, one writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 denotes the special antisymmetric product to be introduced now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{exterior product}

\end_inset

The 
\series bold
exterior product
\series default
 (also called the 
\series bold
wedge product
\series default
)
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{wedge product}

\end_inset

 of two forms, say an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

, is an 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+n)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

, defined by a total antisymmetrization of products of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
(\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2})\circ(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{m+n}) & \equiv\frac{1}{m!n!}\sum_{\sigma}(-1)^{\left|\sigma\right|}\nonumber \\
\times\omega_{1}\left(\mathbf{v}_{\sigma(1)},...,\mathbf{v}_{\sigma(m)}\right) & \omega_{2}\left(\mathbf{v}_{\sigma(m+1)},...,\mathbf{v}_{\sigma(m+n)}\right),\label{eq:definition of exterior product of n-forms}\end{align}

\end_inset

where the sum goes over all the permutations 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,...,m+n\right\} $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sigma\right|=0,1$
\end_inset

 is a function showing whether the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is even or odd.
 Note that the factors 
\begin_inset Formula $m!n!$
\end_inset

 in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:definition of exterior product of n-forms}

\end_inset

) will cancel due to the total antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form then
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\theta\wedge\omega\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}\right) & =\theta(\mathbf{x})\omega(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})+\theta(\mathbf{y})\omega(\mathbf{z},\mathbf{x})\\
 & \quad+\theta(\mathbf{z})\omega(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 are 1-forms then
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\eta\wedge\theta)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =\eta(\mathbf{x})\theta(\mathbf{y})-\eta(\mathbf{y})\theta(\mathbf{x})=\det\left|\begin{array}{cc}
\eta(\mathbf{x}) & \eta(\mathbf{y})\\
\theta(\mathbf{x}) & \theta(\mathbf{y})\end{array}\right|,\\
\left(\eta\wedge\theta\wedge\omega\right) & \circ\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}\right)=\det\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
\eta(\mathbf{x}) & \eta(\mathbf{y}) & \eta(\mathbf{z})\\
\theta(\mathbf{x}) & \theta(\mathbf{y}) & \theta(\mathbf{z})\\
\omega(\mathbf{x}) & \omega(\mathbf{y}) & \omega(\mathbf{z})\end{array}\right|.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\wedge\theta$
\end_inset

 in a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\eta\wedge\theta)_{\alpha\beta}=\eta_{\alpha}\theta_{\beta}-\theta_{\alpha}\eta_{\beta},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are the components of the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=y\textrm{d}x-2\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=x\textrm{d}y+y\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

.
 The exterior product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is computed as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\eta\wedge\theta & =\left(y\textrm{d}x-2\textrm{d}z\right)\wedge\left(x\textrm{d}y+y\textrm{d}z\right)\\
 & =xy\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y+y^{2}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}z+2x\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z\end{align*}

\end_inset

(we used 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z=-\textrm{d}z\wedge\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

).
 Let us now compute how the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\wedge\theta$
\end_inset

 acts on a pair of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=5\partial_{x}-y\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\partial_{x}+3z\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}y\circ\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}z\circ\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

, which simplifies the calculations:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right) & =\left(\textrm{d}x\circ\mathbf{u}\right)\left(\textrm{d}y\circ\mathbf{v}\right)=15z,\\
\left(\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}z\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right) & =-\left(\textrm{d}z\circ\mathbf{u}\right)\left(\textrm{d}x\circ\mathbf{v}\right)=y,\\
\left(\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right) & =-\left(\textrm{d}z\circ\mathbf{u}\right)\left(\textrm{d}y\circ\mathbf{v}\right)=3yz.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Finally, we compute
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right)\circ(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=xy\cdot15z+y^{2}\cdot y+2x\cdot3yz=21xyz+y^{3}.\]

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A useful property is that the exterior product of linearly dependent 1-forms
 vanishes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:exterior-product-linearly-independent}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-:exterior-product-linearly-independent}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}$
\end_inset

 are some 1-forms, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge...\wedge\omega_{k}\neq0$
\end_inset

 iff the set of the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \omega_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:exterior-product-linearly-independent}

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \omega_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent then we can express e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 through other 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j}$
\end_inset

, and the exterior product vanishes due to antisymmetry (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j}\wedge\omega_{j}=0$
\end_inset

).
 If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \omega_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly independent then it is either already a basis or can be completed
 to a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \omega_{1},...,\omega_{k},...,\omega_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space of 1-forms.
 So the exterior product is (by definition) an alternating linear combination
 of tensor products of basis 1-forms,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega_{1}\wedge...\wedge\omega_{k}=\sum_{\sigma}\left(-1\right)^{\left|\sigma\right|}\omega_{\sigma(1)}\otimes...\otimes\omega_{\sigma(k)},\]

\end_inset

where the sum is over all permutations 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,...,k\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Since the set of all basis tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \omega_{j_{1}}\otimes...\otimes\omega_{j_{k}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is by definition linearly independent, the linear combination cannot vanish.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Oriented volume and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Oriented volume and n-vectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Volume-as-antisymmetric}

\end_inset

, we have introduced the notion of oriented area and oriented volume.
 Now we develop a more general picture in which certain antisymmetric tensors
 represent 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volumes embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space, where dimensions are arbitrary and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By analogy with the exterior product of forms, one can define the exterior
 product of vectors.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{exterior product!of vectors}

\end_inset

 For instance, the exterior product of two vectors is the antisymmetric
 tensor defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}\equiv\mathbf{x}\otimes\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{y}\otimes\mathbf{x};\quad(\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y})^{\alpha\beta}=x^{\alpha}y^{\beta}-x^{\beta}y^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset

One can consider the vector space of linear combinations of such exterior
 products; this is the space of antisymmetric tensors of rank (2,0).
 Similarly, the exterior product of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors is an antisymmetric tensor of rank (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,0).
 Such totally antisymmetric tensors are sometimes called 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
vectors
\series default
 or 
\series bold
multivectors
\series default
;
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{multivectors}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{$n$-vectors}

\end_inset

for instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
bivector
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{bivector}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this construction, one can reinterpret an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form as a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors into numbers.
 For example, a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 acts on a bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega(\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y})=\omega(\mathbf{x}\otimes\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{y}\otimes\mathbf{x})=\omega(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-\omega(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})=2\omega(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

Notice the appearance of an extra factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, this extra factor will be 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 since we will need to sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 possible permutations of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some textbooks use extra factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 when defining the exterior product of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 1-forms; for instance, one could define 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\frac{1}{2}\left(\eta(\mathbf{x})\theta(\mathbf{y})-\eta(\mathbf{y})\theta(\mathbf{x})\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then extra factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 will appear in some equations but disappear from some other equations.
 These factors play no essential role, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
they are 
\series bold
cosmetic
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cosmetic factors}

\end_inset

(they merely make some equations better looking).
 Of course, one must keep track of the extra factors when one uses formulas
 from different books.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{oriented $n$-volume}

\end_inset

An 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 can serve as a representation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume of a parallelepiped spanned by a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 given vectors 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset


\series default
 in an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space (where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq n$
\end_inset

).
 Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset

 shows that the (oriented) volumes of two such parallelepipeds spanned by
 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{b}_{1},...,\mathbf{b}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are equal iff the two corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}$
\end_inset

, are equal.
 This is proved by geometric arguments similar to those in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Volume-as-antisymmetric}

\end_inset

, and by using an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional generalization of Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Area-of-the-parallelogram}

\end_inset

.
 Note that an analogon of Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:exterior-product-linearly-independent}

\end_inset

 holds also for vectors: an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vector is nonzero iff the set of its constituent vectors is linearly independen
t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
(a)
\series default
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to every other 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vector.
 
\series bold
(b)
\series default
 The ratio of the oriented volumes of two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepipeds spanned by the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{b}_{1},...,\mathbf{b}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are related by the same proportionality factor as the two corresponding
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ordinary (scalar) volume of the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be calculated as a suitably defined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\series bold
norm
\series default
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right)=\sqrt{\left|\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}\right|^{2}}.\]

\end_inset

 The norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}\right|$
\end_inset

 is defined in the usual manner through the scalar product on the space
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors, which is in turn defined through the scalar product in the vector
 space.
 For instance, the area of a parallelogram spanned by two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

 is calculated as follows.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oriented area
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the parallelogram is represented by the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the standard Cartesian basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

, one can decompose this bivector into basis bivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<j\leq N$
\end_inset

, with some coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}=\sum_{1\leq i<j\leq N}A_{ij}\mathbf{e}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j}.\]

\end_inset

The scalar product is then defined in the space of bivectors by postulating
 that the bivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 constitute an orthonormal basis.
 The scalar product of two arbitrary bivectors is then computed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\sum_{i,j}A_{ij}\mathbf{e}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j}\right)\cdot\left(\sum_{i,j}A_{ij}\mathbf{e}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j}\right)=\sum_{i,j}A_{ij}B_{ij}\]

\end_inset

(all the sums are taken over 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<j\leq N$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, the ordinary (scalar) area of the parallelogram is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Area}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)=\sqrt{\sum_{1\leq i<j\leq N}\left|A_{ij}\right|^{2}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Determinants
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Determinants}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A standard definition of the determinant of a square 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is a formula involving the matrix elements: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det\left(A_{ij}\right)\equiv\sum_{\sigma}\left(-1\right)^{\left|\sigma\right|}A_{1\sigma(1)}...A_{n\sigma(n)},\]

\end_inset

where the sum is performed over all transpositions 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a one-to-one map from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,...,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 to the same set.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sigma\right|$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
even
\series default
 transposition (equivalent to an even number of pair interchanges) and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is an odd transposition.
 This formula is explicit but complicated.
 The geometric meaning and the properties of the determinant are much more
 apparent if one adopts a different (but equivalent) definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the 
\series bold
determinant
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 of a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as the volume of the image of the unit cube under the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we select an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and transform it using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

, obtaining the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{T}\mathbf{e}_{1},...,\hat{T}\mathbf{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the oriented volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepiped spanned by these 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A little work using the concept of multivectors shows that the the initial
 set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 does not actually need to be an orthonormal basis; this is desirable, since
 we can then define the determinant of a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 without the necessity to have a scalar product in the vector space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-determinants}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-determinants}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 arbitrary vectors; denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 the oriented volume of the parallelepiped spanned by these vectors.
 Consider also the parallelepiped spanned by the transformed vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the transformed volume is proportional to the original volume with
 the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}(\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{n})=\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)\cdot\det\hat{T}.\]

\end_inset

This factor is independent of the choice of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A similar relationship holds for the corresponding multivectors, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{1}\wedge\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{2}\wedge...\wedge\hat{T}\mathbf{v}_{n}=\left(\mathbf{v}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{v}_{2}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)\det\hat{T}.\]

\end_inset

(Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-determinants}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-determinants}

\end_inset

, we can reformulate the definition of the determinant as follows: The determina
nt of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the factor that multiplies the volume of an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepiped after the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this definition, it is easy to derive the fundamental property of
 determinants: the determinant of a product of two transformations is equal
 to the product of the two determinants,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det(\hat{A}\hat{B})=(\det\hat{A})(\det\hat{B}).\]

\end_inset

This property is a simple consequence of the fact that the volume of every
 parallelepiped transformed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, let us prove an important relationship involving volume in Euclidean
 space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-volume-of-parallelepiped}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-volume-of-parallelepiped}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The volume of a parallelepiped spanned by vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)=\sqrt{\det g_{ij}},\quad g_{ij}\equiv\mathbf{v}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the scalar product of two vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-volume-of-parallelepiped}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in this space.
 The volume of a parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is, by definition, equal to 1.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis, there exists a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 that brings 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 into the given set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 By Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-determinants}

\end_inset

, the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}$
\end_inset

, so it remains to compute that determinant.
 Let us introduce the components of the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}_{j}\equiv\hat{T}\mathbf{e}_{j}=\sum_{k}T_{jk}\mathbf{e}_{k}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{k}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{l}=\delta_{kl}$
\end_inset

, we can express the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{ij}=\mathbf{v}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{j}=\left(\sum_{k}T_{ik}\mathbf{e}_{k}\right)\cdot\left(\sum_{l}T_{jl}\mathbf{e}_{l}\right)=\sum_{k}T_{ik}T_{jk}.\]

\end_inset

It follows that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the product of two matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is found as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det g_{ij}=\left(\det T_{ij}\right)\left(\det T_{ji}\right)=\left(\det T_{ij}\right)^{2},\]

\end_inset

where we used the fact that the determinant of the transposed matrix is
 the same as the determinant of the original matrix.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)=\det T_{ij}=\sqrt{\det g_{ij}},\]

\end_inset

which is the desired formula.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider 
\series bold
differential forms
\series default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms defined in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 An example of a differential form written in local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=x^{2}\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z-3y^{3}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\]

\end_inset

(in this example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For scalar functions (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0-forms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v}\equiv\mathbf{v}\circ f.\]

\end_inset

 So the notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 itself can be understood as the differential operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 acting on the function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f(x)=f'(x)\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

, which is a familiar rule of calculus (the chain rule).
 For this reason, the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms is convenient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 can be generalized to a linear operator acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms and producing 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-forms; this operator is then called the 
\series bold
exterior differential
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{exterior differential}

\end_inset

 So the exterior differential of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n+1\right)$
\end_inset

-form written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exterior differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 can be defined either explicitly (see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:exterior differential - explicit}

\end_inset

) below), or through the properties it satisfies.
 These properties are the following.
 For any forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 and scalar functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we have the Leibnitz-like rule
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{d}\left(f\omega_{1}\right) & =\textrm{d}f\wedge\omega_{1}+f\textrm{d}\omega_{1},\\
\textrm{d}(\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2}) & =(\textrm{d}\omega_{1})\wedge\omega_{2}+(-1)^{n_{1}}\omega_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}\omega_{2},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

-form.
 Heuristically, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sign changes when one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pulls 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 through an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second fundamental property of the exterior differential is 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 This property can be understood heuristically as follows: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is symmetric with respect to the exchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

; each 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 adds a vector argument into the form, but the result must be a totally
 antisymmetric form.
 So we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d d}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the simplicity of these rules, calculations with differential forms
 are straightforward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=x^{2}\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}=xy\textrm{d}x+2\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

.
 The exterior differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\omega_{1}=\textrm{d}\left(x^{2}\textrm{d}y\right)=2x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y+x^{2}\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}y\right)=2x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y,\]

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}y\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{d}\omega_{2} & =\textrm{d}(xy)\wedge\textrm{d}x+xy\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}x\right)+2\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}y\right)\\
 & =y\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}x+x\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}x\\
 & =-x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y,\end{align*}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}x=-\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 due to antisymmetry.
 Consider now the differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\left(\textrm{d}\omega_{2}\right)=\textrm{d}\left(-x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\right)=-\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y=0.\]

\end_inset

Another example calculation is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\left(xy\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}z\right)=\textrm{d}\left(xy\right)\wedge\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}z=-x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z.\]

\end_inset

In this way, arbitrary differentials can be computed.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


