\begin_layout Standard
A rather cumbersome but explicit formula can be derived for the differential
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 of an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n+1}) & \equiv\sum_{s=1}^{n+1}(-1)^{s-1}\mathbf{v}_{s}\circ\omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{s},...,\mathbf{v}_{n+1})\nonumber \\
+\sum_{1\leq r<s\leq n+1}(-1 & )^{r+s-1}\omega([\mathbf{v}_{r},\mathbf{v}_{s}],\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{r},...,\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{s},...,\mathbf{v}_{n+1}),\label{eq:exterior differential - explicit}\end{align}

\end_inset

where the hat over a vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{s}$
\end_inset

, indicates the 
\emph on
absence
\emph default
 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{s}$
\end_inset

 among the listed arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 As an example of using this formula, consider a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 is the 2-form defined by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv\mathbf{x}\circ\left(\omega(\mathbf{y})\right)-\mathbf{y}\circ\left(\omega(\mathbf{x})\right)-\omega(\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]).\label{eq:dw 12}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that this formula actually defines a bilinear
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 that does not contain derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Statement-dw is a bilinear form}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{Statement-dw is a bilinear form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

) defines a bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 despite the apparent presence of derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{Statement-dw is a bilinear form}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-dw is a bilinear form}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

) defines an antisymmetric function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 So it is sufficient to show that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\lambda\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\lambda(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\]

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function of a point.
 Once this is proved, it will follow that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 does not contain derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 or
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining part of the proof is thus a straightforward calculation:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\lambda\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =\lambda\mathbf{x}\circ\omega(\mathbf{y})-\mathbf{y}\circ\left(\lambda\omega(\mathbf{x})\right)-\omega(\left[\lambda\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right])\\
 & =\lambda\left(\mathbf{x}\circ\omega(\mathbf{y})-\mathbf{y}\circ\omega(\mathbf{x})-\omega(\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right])\right)\\
 & \quad-\left(\mathbf{y}\circ\lambda\right)\omega(\mathbf{x})+\omega\left(\left(\mathbf{y}\circ\lambda\right)\mathbf{x}\right)\\
 & =\lambda(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here we used Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Lie-derivative-of-lambdav}

\end_inset

 to express 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\lambda\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a useful relationship between the Lie derivative and the exterior
 differential.
 For convenience of notation, one introduces the 
\series bold
insertion
\series default
 operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 (also called the 
\series bold
interior product
\series default
) that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inserts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms as the first argument,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n-1}\right)\equiv\omega\left(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n-1}\right).\]

\end_inset

The insertion operator produces 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-forms out of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative operation can be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

.
 To see how, let us first compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

 for some 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

 acts on an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\omega\circ\mathbf{u}\right)-\omega\circ\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}\right)=\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\omega(\mathbf{u})\right)-\omega([\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}]).\]

\end_inset

Let us compare this with the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

; by inspection, we notice that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right)+\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\omega(\mathbf{v})\right).\]

\end_inset

Using the insertion operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, we can rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)\right)\circ\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right).\]

\end_inset

Finally, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function, so
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\equiv\left(\textrm{d}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\right)\circ\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\circ\mathbf{u}=\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)+\textrm{d}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\right)\circ\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

Omitting the arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the 
\series bold
Cartan homotopy formula
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Cartan homotopy formula}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega=\textrm{d}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)+\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right),\]

\end_inset

written also more concisely as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}=\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}+\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}.\label{eq:Cartan homotopy formula}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This important formula holds not only for 1-forms, but also for arbitrary
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the exterior differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 brings 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms into 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n+1\right)$
\end_inset

-forms, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 does not change the number of arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cartan homotopy formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms can be derived directly from the explicit definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:exterior differential - explicit}

\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 and the Leibnitz property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, for instance by computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 and showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega-\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

.
 See also e.g.\InsetSpace ~
the book\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Stra84}

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset

4.5.
 I omit this straightforward verification; unconvinced readers are encouraged
 to try an explicit calculation for a 2-form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following properties also hold for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega'$
\end_inset

, and vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\left(\omega\wedge\omega'\right) & =\left(\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\omega\right)\wedge\omega'+\left(-1\right)^{n}\omega\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\omega',\\
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\right)\omega & =\left(\textrm{d}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\right)\omega,\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\omega\wedge\omega'\right) & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)\wedge\omega'+\omega\wedge\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega',\\
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\right)\omega & =\iota_{\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}\right]}\omega+\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\omega.\end{align*}

\end_inset

These properties can be verified by straightforward computations which I
 omit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Canonical decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Literature: This material is covered in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BaSt90}

\end_inset

, volume 2, chapter 22, Appendix; see also 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Lang02}

\end_inset

, chapter 5.
 
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section I review some classical results obtained in the theory of
 differential forms.
 The main statements are the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a suitable choice of local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a suitable domain of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A given 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in one of two ways: either as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k},\]

\end_inset

or as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k}+\textrm{d}x_{2k+1}.\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(The Darboux theorem) A given 
\emph on
closed
\emph default
 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(The Poincar lemma) Any closed 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is locally exact: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}\theta$
\end_inset

 in some domain (but perhaps not in the entire manifold).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Canonical decomposition of closed 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-forms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional smooth manifold.
 In a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

, an arbitrary 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^{n}\Omega_{ij}(x_{1},...,x_{n})\textrm{d}x_{i}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{j},\label{eq:Omega decomposition general}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}=-\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-dependent matrix.
 However, the coordinate system may be chosen so that a particular 2-form
 is written in a simpler way.
 For example, a closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{A}=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+x_{3}\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{3}\]

\end_inset

can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{A}=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}\left(x_{2}+\frac{1}{2}x_{3}^{2}\right)=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}y_{2},\quad y_{2}\equiv x_{2}+\frac{1}{2}x_{3}^{2}.\]

\end_inset

In this example, a particular choice of the new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},y_{2},x_{3},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 reduces the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 to a simpler expression involving just two of the coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to know how many different coordinates are needed to represent
 a given 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 in the simplest possible way.
 Of course, it is also useful to be able to 
\emph on
determine
\emph default
 the new coordinates explicitly if a closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is specified in a given coordinate system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Darboux theorem
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Darboux theorem}

\end_inset

 (proved below) says that for any closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 a suitable local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be found such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
within a certain domain) expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+\textrm{d}x_{3}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{4}+...+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k},\label{eq:omega decomposition}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n/2$
\end_inset

 is some number.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is advantageous to find such 
\series bold
canonical
\series default
 local coordinates because then calculations with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 are much easier.
 The required number 
\begin_inset Formula $2k\leq n$
\end_inset

 of different coordinates in the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomposition}

\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
rank
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{rank of 2-form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is given in a certain coordinate system, can one determine the rank of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 without knowing the canonical coordinates (but knowing that they exist)?
 In the example with the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 above, it is easy to guess the correct canonical coordinates.
 Consider another example, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{B}=\textrm{d}y_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}y_{2}+y_{1}\textrm{d}y_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}y_{3}.\]

\end_inset

In this case, it is not obvious how to find suitable canonical coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomposition}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the rank of a given closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, the following trick can be used.
 One considers exterior powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, denoted
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega^{\wedge k}=\underbrace{\Omega\wedge...\wedge\Omega}_{k\:\text{times}}.\]

\end_inset

Note that for a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\wedge\Omega$
\end_inset

 does not necessarily vanish.
 A sufficiently high power of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 will, of course, vanish.
 So there will be some number 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n/2$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega^{\wedge k}\neq0,\quad\Omega^{\wedge(k+1)}=0.\label{eq:Omega power cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset

From the Darboux theorem we know that the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomposition}

\end_inset

) is possible in some coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In these coordinates, we can compute 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega^{\wedge k}=k!\,\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}\neq0,\]

\end_inset

since by assumption all 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are independent coordinates in a local coordinate system.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\wedge(k+1)}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the largest integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\wedge k}\neq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\wedge(k+1)}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=0$
\end_inset

, we say that its rank is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, we can immediately see that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

 specified above has rank 2 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}\wedge\boldsymbol{B}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we should expect to find suitable coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Determining these coordinates in practice may be far from easy; a possible
 method of finding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is given in the proof of the Darboux theorem below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rank of a 2-form may be different at different points of the manifold.
 Presently, we assume that we will be dealing only with such 2-forms whose
 rank remains constant 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
throughout some neighborhood of some point.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximal rank of a 2-form on an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (for even 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) or 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 (for odd 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 For a 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be 
\series bold
nondegenerate 
\series default
if the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is invertible (has nonzero determinant).
 This condition can be expressed in the following way: for any nonzero vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 there exists at least one vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\neq0$
\end_inset

; in other words, the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a nonvanishing 1-form.
 Equivalently: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 for some vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:maximal-rank-nondegenerate}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:maximal-rank-nondegenerate}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of maximal rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is such that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega$
\end_inset

 vanishes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\left(\Omega^{\wedge k}\right)=k\left(\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\Omega\right)\wedge\Omega^{\wedge\left(k-1\right)}=0.\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\wedge k}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{\wedge k}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the volume form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}$
\end_inset

 with a nonzero coefficient.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\left(\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}\right)=0.\]

\end_inset

Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{j}\partial/\partial x_{j}$
\end_inset

, it is straightforward to see that all the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 must vanish.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the Darboux theorem is true, it is easy to see that a nondegenerat
e 2-form always has maximal rank.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 does not have maximal rank, the canonical decomposition of a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is free of some of the coordinates, say of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\equiv\partial/\partial x_{n}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is degenerate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An algebraic version of the Darboux theorem is the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Darboux-finite-dim}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:Darboux-finite-dim}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An arbitrary antisymmetric bilinear form (2-form) 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B=\theta_{1}\wedge\theta_{2}+...+\theta_{2k-1}\wedge\theta_{2k},\label{eq:B theta decomp}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 are some suitable 1-forms.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \theta_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of these 1-forms is linearly independent.
 The smallest required number (
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

) of these 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms is the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, which is equal to the rank of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{ij}$
\end_inset

 in any basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice of a cnonical basis for an antisymmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a standard task of finite-dimensional linear algebra.
 We consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B=0$
\end_inset

, the rank is zero and the statement is proved.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{1}}B$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 Thus there exists another vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric, the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be parallel to each other, thus they can be completed to a basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can choose the other basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that they are orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
B(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{j})=B(\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{j})=0,\quad j=3,...,n.\]

\end_inset

This choice is always possible because we may add to each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=3,...,n$
\end_inset

 a suitable linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j}=\mathbf{e}_{j}-B(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{j})\mathbf{e}_{2}+B(\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{j})\mathbf{e}_{1},\]

\end_inset

so that now 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{e}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j})=B(\mathbf{e}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j})=0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $j=3,...,n$
\end_inset

.
 For brevity, let us denote the resulting basis again by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The result of this construction is that the two subspaces spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{3},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are orthogonal to each other with respect to the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After choosing the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in this way, we compute the dual basis 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \theta_{1},...,\theta_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and represent the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
B=\theta_{1}\wedge\theta_{2}+B^{(1)},\]

\end_inset

where the new 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, it is sufficient to consider the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 within the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-2\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{3},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can now apply the same construction to 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 in a smaller number of dimensions; either 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{(1)}=0$
\end_inset

, or we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{4}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{(1)}=\theta_{3}\wedge\theta_{4}+B^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, etc.
 The construction eventually stops because at every step the dimensionality
 of the space is reduced by two.
 At that point, we will obtain a decomposition of the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:B theta decomp}

\end_inset

), where all 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 are (by construction) a linearly independent set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is represented by the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\begin{array}{cccccccc}
0 & 1\\
-1 & 0 &  & 0 &  &  & 0\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 & 0 &  & 0 & 1\\
 &  &  & -1 & 0\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
 & 0 &  &  &  &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  &  &  & 0\end{array}\right),\]

\end_inset

in which the lower right 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-2k\right)\times\left(n-2k\right)$
\end_inset

 block is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is straightforward to verify that the rank of the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 according to the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Omega power cond}

\end_inset

) of the rank.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{\wedge k}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero due to the linear independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \theta_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
B^{\wedge k}=k!\,\theta_{1}\wedge...\wedge\theta_{2k},\]

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{\wedge\left(k+1\right)}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference between the algebraic and the differential-geometric versions
 of the Darboux theorem is the following.
 According to the algebraic theorem just proved, one may reduce any 2-form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to a canonical decomposition at any one point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This decomposition will involve a certain choice of the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\left.\theta_{j}\right|_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 at each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 However, this procedure will generally generate different sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\left.\theta_{j}\right|_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 in tangent spaces at different points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so there will be no local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in which the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 are equal to the coordinate 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{j}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Using the algebraic version of the Darboux theorem, one could obtain the
 decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomposition}

\end_inset

) at any one point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 but not at neighboring points.
 The differential-geometric Darboux theorem says that one can actually choose
 a local coordinate system in which the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 has a canonical decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomposition}

\end_inset

) at every point within some domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The Darboux theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A closed 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of local rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 in a 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}\]

\end_inset

in a suitable local coordinate system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theorem is proved in three steps.
 The first step is to show that there exists a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 depends 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 on the first 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^{2k}\Omega_{ij}(x_{1},...,x_{2k})\textrm{d}x_{i}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{j}.\]

\end_inset

Then it is sufficient to consider the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 on a 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-dimensional submanifold where the remaining coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{2k+1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 have fixed values.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step can be proved as follows.
 If a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k<n$
\end_inset

 then, by Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Darboux-finite-dim}

\end_inset

, at every point there exists a decomposition of the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:B theta decomp}

\end_inset

).
 It follows that in the tangent space at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, there will exist a nonempty subspace of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is smooth, this subspace will also vary smoothly between points.
 So at least one smooth vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\neq0$
\end_inset

 can be chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 at every point within some domain.
 A local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\partial/\partial x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 means that the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 may contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 but no 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Further, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 and thus (by the Cartan homotopy formula)
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=\left(\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}+\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\right)\Omega=0.\]

\end_inset

 The property 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 means that the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}(x_{1},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 in the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Omega decomposition general}

\end_inset

) do not actually depend on the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Lie-derivative-constant-coefficients}

\end_inset

).
 Thus, it is sufficient to study the restriction of the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional submanifold of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The same construction can be applied to the reduced 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 If the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

, anther coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 can be found such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 does not indolve 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 do not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we will reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-2\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, etc.
 Each time, the dimension of the manifold is reduced by one, until we obtain
 a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 on a 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a 2-form of maximal rank.
 A 2-form of maximal rank is nondegenerate (Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:maximal-rank-nondegenerate}

\end_inset

).
 Thus it is sufficient to prove the Darboux theorem only for nondegenerate
 2-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step is to prove that there exists a local coordinate system
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that a given closed, nondegenerate 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 has 
\emph on
constant
\emph default
 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^{2n}\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}\textrm{d}x_{i}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{j},\quad\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}=-\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}=\textrm{const}.\]

\end_inset

This involves a differential-geometric argument detailed below.
 The third step is to reduce the nondegenerate, antisymmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $2n\times2n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 to the canonical form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\begin{array}{ccccc}
0 & 1\\
-1 & 0 &  & 0\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 & 0 &  & 0 & 1\\
 &  &  & -1 & 0\end{array}\right).\]

\end_inset

 The reduction is performed through a change of basis.
 According to Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Darboux-finite-dim}

\end_inset

, a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{2n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be chosen such that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 assumes the canonical form shown above (there is no zero block since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 has maximal rank).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to perform the second step.
 We fix a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\Omega\right|_{p}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^{2n}\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}\textrm{d}x_{i}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{j},\]

\end_inset

and define a new 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 at all other points by the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega_{0}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^{2n}\Omega_{ij}^{(0)}\textrm{d}x_{i}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{j}.\]

\end_inset

By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant coefficients
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the given coordinate system.
 Now we would like to find a change of coordinates in a neighborhood of
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 has constant coefficients in the new coordinates.
 This is equivalent to finding a diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\Omega)=\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of finding 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 directly, we will find a one-parametric 
\emph on
flow
\emph default
 of diffeomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}=\textrm{id}$
\end_inset

 (the identity map) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f$
\end_inset

 is the map we need.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to find a map 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 that transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 into a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

between
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The first trick is to write such an interpolation explicitly, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
we define
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega_{t}\equiv\Omega+t\left(\Omega_{0}-\Omega\right).\]

\end_inset

The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}-\Omega$
\end_inset

 is closed and thus, by the Poincar lemma, there exists a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega_{0}-\Omega=\textrm{d}\theta\]

\end_inset

(perhaps, the above will hold only in a smaller star-shaped neighborhood
 of the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

).
 The second trick is to describe the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 through a tangent vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{t}$
\end_inset

 will be obtained by the duality map from the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, using the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metric.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Converting a 1-form into a vector field is possible only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate at every point and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We postpone the proof of the nondegeneracy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

, and presently we assume that we have a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{t}$
\end_inset

 satisfying
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\Omega_{t}=\theta,\quad t\in\left[0,1\right].\]

\end_inset

We now define the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 as the flow generated by the (time-dependent!) vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 into a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-dependent 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(t)$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the differential equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dt}\Omega(t)=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\Omega(t).\]

\end_inset

It is then straightforward to verify that the interpolation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 satisfies this equation:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\Omega_{t} & =\Omega_{0}-\Omega=\textrm{d}\theta,\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\Omega_{t} & =\left(\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}+\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\textrm{d}\right)\Omega_{t}=\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\Omega_{t}=\textrm{d}\theta.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}=\Omega(t)$
\end_inset

 and is indeed the result of the transformation of the initial 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 by the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 is the one that transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to demonstrate that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 has maximal rank for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and at every point within some domain.
 We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 interpolates between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, while the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 coincide at the chosen point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}=\Omega$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 remains nondegenerate for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

; the present task is to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 has maximal rank everywhere in some open domain around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 has maximal rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}^{\wedge n}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}^{\wedge n}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the volume form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2n}$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega_{t}^{\wedge n}=f_{t}(x)\,\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2n},\]

\end_inset

where the coefficient, temporarily denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

, is a function of the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 is maximal if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Since the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 is smooth, the domain where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}\neq0$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-dependent open set containing the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The intersection of all such domains for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is again a nonempty open set (possibly smaller than the set where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 has maximal rank).
 Thus, we have found an open domain containing the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate at every 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Canonical decomposition of 1-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concepts of rank and canonical coordinates can be defined also for 1-forms.
 Heuristically, the rank of a 1-form is the smallest number of independent
 coordinates required to express this 1-form.
 This time, we do not limit ourselves to considering only closed 1-forms;
 but let us briefly examine the case of a closed 1-form.
 By the Poincar lemma, a closed 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is locally represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 using some function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 will be nonconstant if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be used as one of the coordinates in a local coordinate system; so
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be expressed using just one coordinate.
 We conclude that a closed, nonzero 1-form has rank 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below we will prove that any 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be expressed (using suitable local coordinates) in one of two canonical
 ways: either
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\omega=x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k}\label{eq:omega decomp 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

(then we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

), or
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\omega=x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k}+\textrm{d}x_{2k+1}\label{eq:omega decomp 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

(then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k+1$
\end_inset

).
 We may call the coordinates used for such decompositions 
\series bold
canonical coordinates
\series default
 of a given 1-form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Knowing that this statement is true, how could we determine the rank of
 a given 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, for example,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=\textrm{d}x+xy\textrm{d}z,\]

\end_inset

without knowing the canonical coordinates? We use the following trick.
 Consider the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 and compute its exterior powers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,..$
\end_inset

.
 Write the following sequence of the differential forms,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\omega,\:\textrm{d}\omega,\:\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega,\:\textrm{d}\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega,\:\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega,\:...\label{eq:omega sequence cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th element of this sequence (
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,...$
\end_inset

) is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form.
 Eventually some element of this sequence will be zero, and then all the
 subsequent elements will also be zero.
 By substituting the decompositions\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 1}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 2}

\end_inset

) into the sequence\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega sequence cond}

\end_inset

), one finds that the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is equal to the number of initial nonzero elements in the sequence.
 The rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is zero if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

; the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is one if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

; the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is two if 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

; etc.
 In this way it is straightforward to compute the rank of a 1-form given
 in some local coordinates.
 For example, the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}x+xy\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

 is 3 (at points where 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\neq0$
\end_inset

) because 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=x\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z\neq0,\quad\textrm{d}\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Carathodory theorem is a form of Frobenius theorem.
 It states that the set of null curves of a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is surface-forming iff the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 1 or 2, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 (
\series bold
Null curves
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 are curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=0$
\end_inset

.) This is proved by an explicit construction in local coordinates, showing
 that a 1-form of rank 3 or higher has non-surface-forming null curves.
 (A 
\series bold
non-surface-forming
\series default
 set of curves is a set such that curves from the set can reach any point
 in a neighborhood of an initial point.
 See\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BaSt90}

\end_inset

, chapter 22.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of the canonical decomposition theorem for 1-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical decomposition theorem for 1-forms states that for any 1-form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, one can choose a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is locally represented in one of the two ways, (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 1}

\end_inset

) or (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 2}

\end_inset

), as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has a locally constant rank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We prove this theorem by reducing it to the Darboux theorem.
 First, we determine the rank of a given 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 by using the sequence\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega sequence cond}

\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has an odd rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k+1$
\end_inset

, the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 (according to the definition of rank for closed 2-forms) because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}\neq0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k+1)}=0$
\end_inset

.
 According to the Darboux theorem, we can then choose local coordinages
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

Applying the Poincar lemma to the closed 1-form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega-x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k},\]

\end_inset

we show that there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=\textrm{d}f+x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

Since the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k+1$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
0\neq\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}=\textrm{d}f\wedge k!\,\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

Hence, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be used as a local coordinate that is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Denote this function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2k+1}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 2}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second case, the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has an even rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 again has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

, and so we could again arrive at Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 2}

\end_inset

), but we would like to eliminate the last term in that equation.
 So we need to work a little harder.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to find a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k-1$
\end_inset

.
 If such 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is found, then by the previously proved case it will follow that
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\omega=x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-3}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k-2}+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1},\]

\end_inset

so we will obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\omega & =\frac{1}{f}\left(x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-3}\textrm{d}x_{2k-2}+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =y_{1}\textrm{d}y_{2}+...+y_{2k-3}\textrm{d}y_{2k-2}+y_{2k-1}\textrm{d}y_{2k},\label{eq:omega desired}\end{align}

\end_inset

where we simply relabeled the coordinates as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{1}\equiv\frac{1}{f}x_{1},\: y_{2}\equiv x_{2},...,\: y_{2k-1}\equiv\frac{1}{f},\: y_{2k}\equiv x_{2k-1}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

By assumption, the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 and thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}\neq0,\quad\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}=0.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}\neq0$
\end_inset

, it will follow from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega desired}

\end_inset

) that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{1},...,y_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are independent local coordinates, and thus a decomposition of the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega decomp 1}

\end_inset

) will be found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k-1$
\end_inset

.
 It is sufficient to find some function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\left(\textrm{d}(f\omega)\right)^{\wedge k}=\left(\textrm{d}f\wedge\omega+f\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}\\
 & =kf^{k-1}\textrm{d}f\wedge\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}+f^{k}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the differential equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\textrm{d}\ln f\right)\wedge\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}=-\frac{1}{k}\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}.\label{eq:equation for f}\end{equation}

\end_inset

To solve this equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (or rather, to show that a solution exists), we need to use some additional
 information about 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 We know that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, by the Darboux theorem we may choose local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

Applying the Poincar lemma to the closed 1-form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega-x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k},\]

\end_inset

we show that there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=\textrm{d}h+x_{1}\textrm{d}x_{2}+...+x_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k+1)}=\left(k+1\right)!\,\textrm{d}h\wedge\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k},\]

\end_inset

so the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can depend only on the subset of coordinates consisting of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Hence the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 depends also only on these coordinates.
 Let us write
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega=\sum_{j=1}^{2k}a_{j}\textrm{d}x_{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients that depend only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Since both parts of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:equation for f}

\end_inset

) depend only on these coordinates, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function only of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now return to the task of determining a suitable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 First we express the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2k-1\right)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}$
\end_inset

 needed for Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:equation for f}

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}\\
 & =\left(k-1\right)!\left(a_{1}\textrm{d}x_{1}+a_{2}\textrm{d}x_{2}\right)\wedge\textrm{d}x_{3}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k}+...\\
 & +\left(k-1\right)!\left(a_{2k-1}\textrm{d}x_{2k-1}+a_{2k}\textrm{d}x_{2k}\right)\wedge\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\wedge\textrm{d}x_{2k-2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The unknown 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\ln f$
\end_inset

 can then be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\ln f\equiv\sum_{j=1}^{2k}l_{j}\textrm{d}x_{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j}$
\end_inset

 are unknown coefficients depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Using this explicit representation, we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\textrm{d}\ln f\right)\wedge\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}=\left(k-1\right)! & \left(a_{1}l_{2}-a_{2}l_{1}+...\right.\\
\left.+a_{2k-1}l_{2k}-a_{2k}l_{2k-1}\right) & \textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\textrm{d}x_{2k}\end{align*}

\end_inset

 and hence is proportional to the 
\begin_inset Formula $2k$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge k}=k!\,\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\]

\end_inset

 It is convenient to introduce an auxiliary vector field
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\equiv-a_{2}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{1}}+a_{1}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{2}}-...-a_{2k}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{2k-1}}+a_{2k-1}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{2k}}\]

\end_inset

and write
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\textrm{d}\ln f\right)\wedge\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}=\left(k-1\right)!\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\ln f\right)\textrm{d}x_{1}\wedge...\textrm{d}x_{2k}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since both sides of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:equation for f}

\end_inset

) are proportional to the volume form, the equation is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\ln f=\mathbf{v}\circ\ln f=-1.\]

\end_inset

Note that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be also defined without coordinates by the requirement
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left[\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}\right]=0.\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a vector field that annihilates the nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2k-1\right)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\left(\textrm{d}\omega\right)^{\wedge(k-1)}$
\end_inset

.
 (In general, a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form vanishes on an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-k\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional hypersurface, so a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2k-1\right)$
\end_inset

-form vanishes on a 1-dimensional subspace.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a basis vector in that subspace.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found that only restriction on the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is that its logarithmic derivative in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 must equal 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Now it is clear that a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exists (at least locally).
 A particular solution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be determined by integration along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 from arbitrary initial conditions.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Poincar lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Poincar
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Poincar\'e lemma}

\end_inset

 lemma states that a closed 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is locally exact: there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}\theta$
\end_inset

 in a star-shaped neighborhood of some point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
star-shaped neighborhood
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{star-shaped neighborhood}

\end_inset

of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if there exists a diffeomorphism flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 that contracts the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 into the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous set of diffeomorphisms, defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}=\textrm{id}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 maps the entire neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 into the single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is a star-shaped neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a suitable flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 is given.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{t}$
\end_inset

 be the tangent vector field of the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an exact 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form defined in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 The flow 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 into a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-dependent 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{t}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dt}\omega_{t}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\omega_{t}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega_{t}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 commutes with diffeomorphisms.
 Using the Cartan homotopy formula, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dt}\omega_{t}=\left(\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}+\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\textrm{d}\right)\omega=\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\omega.\]

\end_inset

Now we integrate this relationship over 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\omega=\omega_{1}-\omega_{0}=\int_{0}^{1}\left(\frac{d}{dt}\omega_{t}\right)dt=\textrm{d}\int_{0}^{1}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\omega\right)dt.\]

\end_inset

Defining 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\theta\equiv-\int_{0}^{1}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{t}}\omega\right)dt,\]

\end_inset

we find the required relationship, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integration of forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A differential 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms can be 
\series bold
integrated
\series default
 over a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

: namely, 1-forms can be integrated over curves, 2-forms over surfaces,
 etc.
 The integral of a given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 over a given manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is denoted by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega.\]

\end_inset

Note that the differential 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not written after the integral sign because the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 already contains the correct number of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined by the following procedure.
 One starts by splitting the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 into a large number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of small 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional paralellepipeds.
 If all the parallelepipeds are sufficiently small, one can approximate
 the sides of parallelepipeds by tangent vectors (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

).
 Thus, to each parallelepiped numbered 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

) there corresponds a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{v}_{1}^{(j)},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}^{(j)}\}$
\end_inset

.
 The parallelepiped numbered 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 contributes a small amount to the integral; this amount is equal to some
 number (the value of the function being integrated) times the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volume of the parallelepiped.
 It is natural to regard the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-volume of a parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form evaluated on the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Volume-as-antisymmetric}

\end_inset

).
 So the contribution of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th parallelepiped to the integral can be naturally described as an application
 of some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{v}_{1}^{(j)},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}^{(j)}\}$
\end_inset

.
 In the integral we are evaluating, this 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form is the given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, to define the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega$
\end_inset

 we evaluate the contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ(\mathbf{v}_{1}^{(j)},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}^{(j)})$
\end_inset

 of each parallelepiped 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and then compute the sum of the contributions over all the parallelepipeds.
 Thus, the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined as the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 of that sum,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{A}}\omega\equiv\lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=1}^{N}\omega\circ(\mathbf{v}_{1}^{(j)},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}^{(j)}).\]

\end_inset

 This limit is quite similar to the limit involved in the ordinary definition
 of the Riemann integral.
 So integrals of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms are equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold integrals in the usual sense.
 However, an important caveat is that integrals of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms are always performed over 
\emph on
oriented
\emph default
 manifolds.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms are antisymmetric, an integral will change sign when the orientation
 of the manifold is reversed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fundamental relationship between integration and the exterior differential
 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{A}}\textrm{d}\omega=\int_{\partial\mathcal{A}}\omega,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold (or part of a manifold), 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is its 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1$
\end_inset

)-dimensional boundary, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-form.
 This theorem is a generalization of the Stokes and the Gauss laws, as well
 as the fundamental theorem of calculus 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}f'(x)dx=f(b)-f(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is a standard result, we refer the reader to textbooks (such
 as\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Arno97}

\end_inset

) for more detailed explanations of this theorem.
\end_layout

