\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation: metric on surfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will introduce the concept of a metric by starting from the picture of
 a manifold as a surface embedded in a Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be represented by an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural Pythagorean notion of distance in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, namely the 
\series bold
Euclidean metric
\series default
,
\series bold

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Euclidean metric}

\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric!Euclidean}

\end_inset


\series default
 defines the distance between two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Distance}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)=\sqrt{\left(b_{1}-a_{1}\right)^{2}+...+\left(b_{n}-a_{n}\right)^{2}},\label{eq:Euclidean distance}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

 are standard coordinates (components) of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now consider a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 embedded into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to compute the distance between two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, as measured along some path 
\emph on
within the surface
\emph default
.
 However, if the surface has a curved shape then one does not have a simple
 and general formula analogous to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Euclidean distance}

\end_inset

) for distances measured 
\emph on
within
\emph default
 
\emph on
the
\emph default
 
\emph on
surface
\emph default
.
 Nevertheless, if two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 on the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are very close to each other, we may consider a short, almost straight
 curve segment within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 connecting these points.
 The length of this curve segment can be accurately estimated using the
 Euclidean formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Euclidean distance}

\end_inset

).
 Then the length of any curve within the surface can be determined by splitting
 the curve into sufficiently small segments.
 More precisely, one can integrate the 
\emph on
infinitesimal
\emph default
 lengths of infinitesimal segments along the curve.
\end_layout

