\begin_layout Standard
Let us explore this idea in more detail.
 To be specific, let us consider a two-dimensional manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 as a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $z=F(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in standard coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

, as shown in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:A-metric}

\end_inset

.
 We are interested in computing the length of a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The curve is specified by three functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x(\tau),y(\tau),z(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Consider a very short curve segment between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}+\delta\tau$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau$
\end_inset

 is very small.
 This segment is an almost straight line between the nearby points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{0},y_{0},z_{0}\right\} \equiv\left\{ x(\tau_{0}),y(\tau_{0}),z(\tau_{0})\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},y_{1},z_{1}\right\} \equiv\left\{ x(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau),y(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau),z(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 So we may compute the length 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 of the segment approximately as the Euclidean distance between these points,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta L\approx\sqrt{\left(x_{1}-x_{0}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{1}-y_{0}\right)^{2}+\left(z_{1}-z_{0}\right)^{2}}.\]

\end_inset

Further, we may approximate 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{1}-x_{0}=x(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau)-x(\tau_{0})\approx\delta\tau\frac{dx}{d\tau}(\tau_{0}),\quad\textrm{etc.},\]

\end_inset

and hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta L\approx\delta\tau\sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{d\tau}(\tau_{0})\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{dy}{d\tau}(\tau_{0})\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{dz}{d\tau}(\tau_{0})\right)^{2}}.\]

\end_inset

In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, this expression becomes precise since the error is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So the length of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be found as an integral over the infinitesimal curve segments,
\begin_inset Formula \[
L\left[\gamma\right]=\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau_{1}}d\tau\sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{d\tau}(\tau)\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{dy}{d\tau}(\tau)\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{dz}{d\tau}(\tau)\right)^{2}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have used all three coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 to describe the curve.
 However, the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be used as local coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and so we would like to be able to compute lengths of curves without using
 the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we would like to use only an intrinsic description of the
 manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the structure representing the information necessary for computing lengths
 in the intrinsic description.
 Let us now see what that information is in our example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $z=F(x,y)$
\end_inset

, we may express
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dz(\tau)}{d\tau}=\frac{\partial F(x,y)}{\partial x}\frac{dx(\tau)}{d\tau}+\frac{\partial F(x,y)}{\partial y}\frac{dy(\tau)}{d\tau},\]

\end_inset

where it is implied that the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are evaluated on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the length 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 of an infinitesimal curve segment can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\delta L & =\delta\tau\sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{d\tau}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{dy}{d\tau}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{\partial F}{\partial x}\frac{dx}{d\tau}+\frac{\partial F}{\partial y}\frac{dy}{d\tau}\right)^{2}}\nonumber \\
 & =\delta\tau\sqrt{A\left(\frac{dx}{d\tau}\right)^{2}+2B\frac{dx}{d\tau}\frac{dy}{d\tau}+C\left(\frac{dy}{d\tau}\right)^{2}},\label{eq:delta L quadratic element}\end{align}

\end_inset

where we introduced auxiliary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 expressed directly through 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(x,y)\equiv1+\left(\frac{\partial F}{\partial x}\right)^{2},\quad B\equiv\frac{\partial F}{\partial x}\frac{\partial F}{\partial y},\quad C\equiv1+\left(\frac{\partial F}{\partial y}\right)^{2}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we note that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta L quadratic element}

\end_inset

) looks like a quadratic form applied to the two-dimensional vector 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\equiv\left\{ \frac{dx}{d\tau},\frac{dy}{d\tau}\right\} \in T_{\gamma(\tau)}\mathcal{M}.\]

\end_inset

Recalling the correspondence between tangent vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and short curve segments (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

), we can verify that the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\mathbf{v}\equiv\left(\delta\tau\right)\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=\left(\delta\tau\right)\left[\frac{dx}{d\tau}\partial_{x}+\frac{dy}{d\tau}\partial_{y}\right]\in T_{\gamma(\tau_{0})}\mathcal{M}\]

\end_inset

 is the vector representing the short curve segment between 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta L=\delta\tau\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}=\sqrt{g(\delta\mathbf{v},\delta\mathbf{v})},\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the following bilinear form,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g\equiv A\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}x+B(\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}y+\textrm{d}y\otimes\textrm{d}x)+C\textrm{d}y\otimes\textrm{d}y.\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 (the length of a short curve segment) can be expressed through the bilinear
 form 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 alone, without using any other information (such as the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y)$
\end_inset

 or the embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

).
 The length of the curve between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\gamma]=\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau_{1}}d\tau\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that the only information necessary to compute lengths along
 curves within a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 defined in every tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
metric
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric}

\end_inset


\series default
 on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our example, once we computed the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 (which, in a local coordinate system, is equivalent to determining the
 three functions 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

), we may stop using the embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 because it is sufficient to use the local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This simplifies the calculations since one needs to work with fewer coordinates
, and also allows one to concentrate on the intrinsic properties of the
 manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Below we will not use the embedding picture to the metric; instead, we
 will work directly with the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, assuming that somehow 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is given.
 It will be unimportant whether or not the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 comes from an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in a larger Euclidean space.
 An embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be regarded as merely an auxiliary construction that helps visualize
 the concept of metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, it is sometimes useful to specify the metric on a manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by selecting a particular embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into a Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and declaring that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is the natural metric induced by this embedding, through the construction
 of infinitesimal curve segments outlined above.
 The metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is then called the 
\series bold
induced
\series default
 
\series bold
metric
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{induced metric}

\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the given embedding.
 In most cases, it is easier to specify a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 through components in in a local coordinate system.
 In the example above, this would mean that we specify the local coordinates
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y\right\} $
\end_inset

 and declare that the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 of the metric are some given functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this motivation, let us now turn to the formal definition of a metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
metric
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric}

\end_inset

on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a nondegenerate, symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 defined in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
nondenegerate
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric!nondenegeracy of}

\end_inset

if for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\neq0$
\end_inset

 there exists a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

; in other words, no vector can be orthogonal to 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 other vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nondegeneracy condition prohibits 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uninteresting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metrics, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $g=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is also important to note that the nondegeneracy condition permits a
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to be specified uniquely if its scalar products 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 with every other vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are known.
 (If there were two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\neq\mathbf{x}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, then the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}'\neq0$
\end_inset

 would be orthogonal to every vector, but this is excluded by the assumption
 of nondegeneracy of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known from standard linear algebra that symmetric bilinear forms have
 
\series bold
signature
\series default
, which is a set of signs independent of the choice of a basis.
 In GR we shall usually consider four-dimensional metrics with the signature
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\,-\right)$
\end_inset

 as appropriate for a locally Lorentzian physical theory, but many results
 will be the same for arbitrary dimension and signatures of the metric.
 Manifolds with a metric with signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(++...+\right)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
Riemannian
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!Riemannian}

\end_inset

and 
\series bold
pseudo-Riemannian
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!pseudo-Riemannian}

\end_inset

if the metric is not sign-definite.
 The familiar metric with a Lorentzian signature is the 
\series bold
Minkowski metric
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}=\textrm{diag}(1,-1,-1,-1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Self-test question: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 admits 
\series bold
null
\series default
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null vector}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

; for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\left\{ 1,1,0,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a null vector.
 Does this mean that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is degenerate? 
\emph on
Answer:
\emph default
 No.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In GR, the metric describes physically measured lengths and time intervals.
 We focus on the mathematical properties of the metric for now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first example, consider a flat Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\equiv\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 with standard coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be specified by the following index-free expression,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}) & =\left(\mathbf{u}\circ t\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ t\right)-\left(\mathbf{u}\circ x\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ x\right)\\
 & \:-\left(\mathbf{u}\circ y\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ y\right)-\left(\mathbf{u}\circ z\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\circ z\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this expression, the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 are interpreted as scalar functions on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and the vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are interpreted as derivative operations applied to these scalar functions.
 We can then directly compute
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\frac{\partial}{\partial t},\frac{\partial}{\partial t})=1,\quad g(\frac{\partial}{\partial t},\frac{\partial}{\partial x})=0,\quad g(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial}{\partial x},\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial}{\partial x})=0,\]

\end_inset

etc.
 This metric can be also written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}t-\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}x-\textrm{d}y\otimes\textrm{d}y-\textrm{d}z\otimes\textrm{d}z,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}t,\textrm{d}x,\textrm{d}y,\textrm{d}z$
\end_inset

 are the 1-forms defined through the coordinate functions 
\begin_inset Formula $t,x,y,z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark on notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the physics literature, one usually finds the Minkowski metric written
 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-dx^{2}-dy^{2}-dz^{2}.\]

\end_inset

Strictly speaking, this notation is inconsistent; for instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $dt^{2}$
\end_inset

 stands for the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset

, and yet 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cannot be interpreted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}s\otimes\textrm{d}s$
\end_inset

 with any 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}s$
\end_inset

.
 Expressions of this kind are understood as being no more than a traditional
 (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jargon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) notation for the metric, in which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is simply a symbol for the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Also, physicists write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dt\, dx"$
\end_inset

 when they need the symmetric tensor product 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\left(\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}x+\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 I will frequently use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physicists's
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metric notation for brevity.
 To call attention to the traditional character of this notation, I will
 denote the metric by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 instead of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and I
\emph on
 
\emph default
will write 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dt\, dx$
\end_inset

 instead of the rigorous but cumbersome notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\left(\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}x+\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}t\right)$
\end_inset

 that does not yield any computational advantage.
 In those cases, I write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with an italic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because there is no connection to the exterior differential 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More complicated metrics may involve nontrivial coefficients at the coordinate
 1-forms and/or non-diagonal terms, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=f_{1}(t,x,y,z)dt^{2}+f_{2}(t,x,y,z)dt\, dx+...\]

\end_inset

Here are some further examples of metrics describing spacetimes important
 in physics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
Schwarzschild spacetime
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Schwarzschild spacetime}

\end_inset

in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,r,\theta,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

 is described by the metric
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dt^{2}-\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}dr^{2}-r^{2}\left(d\theta^{2}+(\sin^{2}\theta)d\phi^{2}\right).\label{eq:Schwarzschild}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This spacetime is generated by a nonrotating black hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
de Sitter spacetime
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{de Sitter spacetime}

\end_inset

in spatially flat coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 has the metric
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g=dt^{2}-e^{2Ht}(dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dz^{2}).\label{eq:de Sitter}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This spacetime is used to describe (approximately) the universe that is
 undergoing an accelerated expansion (
\series bold
cosmological inflation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cosmological inflation}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In GR, a physical spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a four-dimensional manifold with a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

; the metric should have the Lorentzian signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\,-\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A simple-minded view of a curved spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} \equiv\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

, and a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is specified through the components 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 However, this picture is insufficiently general; for instance, spacetimes
 containing black holes do not have this simple structure.
 In some cases, it turns out that the full manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is not covered by the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in which a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 was originally specified.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=t\partial_{t}+x\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=t\partial_{x}-x\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g=dt^{2}-dx^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Give an example of a vector orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in this metric.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Orthonormal frames
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Orthonormal-frames}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is a very brief introduction to the notion of orthonormal frames.
 This subject is more extensively developed in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tetrads}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, one can choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a label enumerating the basis vectors.
 We thus obtain a set of vector fields.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
If it turns out that an orthonormal frame cannot be chosen smoothly throughout
 the entire manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, we assume that the vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are smooth within some suitable patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Such a basis of vector fields is called an 
\series bold
orthonormal frame
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{orthonormal frame}

\end_inset

(in four dimensions, a 
\series bold
tetrad
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tetrad}

\end_inset

or a 
\series bold
vierbein
\series default
).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vierbein}

\end_inset

 Orthonormality means that
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})=\eta_{ab},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix having diagonal elements equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, depending on the signature of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, in GR one uses metrics with Lorentzian signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\,-\right)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix
\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta_{ab}=\textrm{diag}(1,-1,-1,-1)=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1\\
 & -1\\
 &  & -1\\
 &  &  & -1\end{array}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{dual basis}

\end_inset

The dual basis consists of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 that can be expressed as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ\mathbf{u}\equiv\eta_{aa}g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

The 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are a basis in the cotangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, as a rank (0,2) tensor, can be recovered from the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g=\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b};\quad g^{-1}=\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\mathbf{e}_{a}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{b}.\label{eq:g through estar}\end{equation}

\end_inset

A derivation of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g through estar}

\end_inset

) can be found in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tetrads}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Correspondence of vectors and covectors
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Correspondence-of-vectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 determines a one-to-one map between vectors and covectors (and thus between
 vector fields and 1-forms).
 I denote this map by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form corresponding to a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 as follows, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})\circ\mathbf{x}\equiv g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

Then the dual basis 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\eta_{aa}\hat{g}\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the correspondence between vectors and 1-forms is one-to-one, there
 exists the inverse map (from 1-forms to vectors), denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This map converts a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 into the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\hat{g}^{-1}\omega$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u})\equiv g(\hat{g}^{-1}\omega,\mathbf{u})\equiv\omega\circ\mathbf{u}\]

\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the scalar product is also defined on 1-forms and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}(\omega_{1},\omega_{2})\equiv g(\hat{g}^{-1}\omega_{1},\hat{g}^{-1}\omega_{2}).\]

\end_inset

Note that the dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is orthonormal with respect to the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

