\begin_layout Subsection
The Levi-Civita tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ordinary vector algebra in three-dimensional space makes use of the 
\series bold
Levi-Civita symbol
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Levi-Civita symbol}

\end_inset

 which is defined as the totally antisymmetric array of numbers,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\varepsilon_{123}=1,\quad\varepsilon_{ijk}=-\varepsilon_{ikj}=-\varepsilon_{jik},\quad i,j,k=1,2,3.\]

\end_inset

In curved space, the role of this symbol is played by a totally antisymmetric
 tensor field, called the Levi-Civita tensor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a four-dimensional manifold (to be specific and to avoid unnecessary
 complications in the notation).
 In four dimensions, the 
\series bold
Levi-Civita tensor
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Levi-Civita tensor}

\end_inset

 has rank four and is defined as the 4-form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis of 1-forms (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Orthonormal-frames}

\end_inset

).
 We now review the motivation for this definition and the properties of
 the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a three-dimensional Euclidean space, the Levi-Civita symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 is closely related to volume.
 It is known that one can calculate the (oriented) volume of a parallelepiped
 spanned by three vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

 by using the following explicit formula,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right)=\mathbf{a}\cdot\left(\mathbf{b}\times\mathbf{c}\right)=\sum_{i,j,k}\varepsilon_{ijk}a^{i}b^{j}c^{k},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{i},b^{j},c^{k}$
\end_inset

 are the Euclidean components of the three vectors (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
components in an orthogona
l basis).
 We have seen in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Oriented volume and n-vectors}

\end_inset

 that the oriented volume of such a parallelepiped is equal to the value
 of a 3-form evaluated on the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the array of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the array of components of the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 in the orthogonal basis.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right)=\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\circ\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us generalize this construction to a curved, four-dimensional manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 In a tangent space at a fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, we look for a totally antisymmetric form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\mathbf{v}_{3},\mathbf{v}_{4})$
\end_inset

 is equal to the oriented 4-volume of the parallelepiped spanned by the
 tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 orientation then the 4-volume of the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is equal to 1.
 Thus, we are looking for a 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3})=1.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ\mathbf{e}_{b}=\delta_{b}^{a}$
\end_inset

, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is one such 4-form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 through a particular basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, so we need to investigate whether and to what extent 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 depends on the choice of the basis.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 changes sign when the orientation of the basis is reversed.
 It turns out that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 does not actually depend on the choice of the basis, as long as the orientation
 of the basis is fixed (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-epsilon-independent-of-basis}

\end_inset

 below).
 In particular, the orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 may be defined only locally, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
different frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 need to be used in different parts of the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is defined uniquely and 
\emph on
globally
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
throughout the entire manifold, as long as the manifold is globally
 orientable.
 A manifold is 
\series bold
globally orientable
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{manifold!globally orientable}

\end_inset

 if a choice of orthonormal frame can be made in every chart such that the
 orientation of the orthonormal frames is the same in every overlapping
 region between two charts.
 A Mbius strip is an example of a manifold that is not globally orientable.
 It seems that in General Relativity one never needs to consider nonorientable
 manifolds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-epsilon-independent-of-basis}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-epsilon-independent-of-basis}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levi-Civita tensor 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}\]

\end_inset

is invariant under changes of orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, except that it changes sign when the orientation of the basis is reversed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 that brings the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 into another basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}=\hat{T}\mathbf{e}_{a},\quad\tilde{\boldsymbol{\theta}}^{a}=\hat{T}^{-1}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}.\]

\end_inset

By definition of the determinant (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Determinants}

\end_inset

), the oriented volume of the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if the new basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is orthonormal and has the same orientation as the old orthonormal basis,
 the oriented volume of the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is also equal to 1.
 Hence, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{T}=1$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}\equiv\tilde{\boldsymbol{\theta}}^{0}\wedge\tilde{\boldsymbol{\theta}}^{1}\wedge\tilde{\boldsymbol{\theta}}^{2}\wedge\tilde{\boldsymbol{\theta}}^{3}=(\det\hat{T}^{-1})\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}=\boldsymbol{\varepsilon},\]

\end_inset

by the same logic as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\wedge\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\wedge\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\wedge\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{4}=(\det\hat{T})\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{4}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore the new 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}$
\end_inset

 defined through the new basis is equal to the old 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levi-Civita tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, but it 
\emph on
does
\emph default
 depend on the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now determine the explicit formula for the Levi-Civita tensor
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 All 4-forms in four-dimensional space are proportional to each other, so
 the Levi-Civita tensor can be written 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
s determined by different metrics will be proportional to each other.
 So a formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the metric can be given by a single scalar function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of 1-forms to write the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

, but actually we can use any other basis: since all 4-forms are proportional
 to each other, we only need to include a correct scalar factor.
 So let us use the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \textrm{d}x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Using this basis, the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\end_layout

\end_inset

in a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=f\textrm{d}x^{0}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{2}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{3},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is some unknown scalar function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to determine the unknown coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 To do that, we can use a suitable modification of Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-volume-of-parallelepiped}

\end_inset

.
 By definition, the matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 are equal to scalar products 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\partial_{\mu},\partial_{\nu})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} \equiv\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a coordinate basis.
 Thus one can show that the 4-volume of the parallelepiped spanned by the
 tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\sqrt{\left|\det g_{\mu\nu}\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 The factor 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reflects the fact that the volume is oriented and may be negative if the
 coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 has a negative orientation.
 The absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\det g_{\mu\nu}\right|$
\end_inset

 is needed to compensate for the signature of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, which might make the determinant negative.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\equiv\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\partial_{0},\partial_{1},\partial_{2},\partial_{3})=\textrm{Vol}(\partial_{0},\partial_{1},\partial_{2},\partial_{3})=\pm\sqrt{\left|\det g_{\mu\nu}\right|}.\]

\end_inset

It is convenient to assume that the coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 has positive orientation.
 Hence the final formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 in local coordinates is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\sqrt{\left|\det g_{\mu\nu}\right|}\textrm{d}x^{0}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{1}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{2}\wedge\textrm{d}x^{3}.\]

\end_inset

In this way, the functional dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 on the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is made explicit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is so because 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is a 5-form, and there are no nonzero 5-forms in four-dimensional space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main use of the Levi-Civita tensor in GR is to compute 4-dimensional
 volume in curved space.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
There are other, more advanced applications of the Levi-Civita tensor, such
 as the Hodge star operation, which I will consider below.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the tangent vectors are an approximate representation of short curve
 segments (Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Short-curve-segments}

\end_inset

), the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 yields a good approximation to the 4-dimensional volume for very small
 volumes.
 Therefore, one can compute the 4-dimensional volume of a spacetime domain
 by integrating the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 over that domain, and one can also integrate scalar functions times 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 over a domain.
 The integration is defined purely geometrically, regardless of the choice
 of the coordinate system, once the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is fixed.
 For this reason (independence of coordinates), physicists know the Levi-Civita
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 by the name 
\series bold
covariant volume element
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{volume element}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is simply called the 
\series bold
volume 4-form
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{volume 4-form}

\end_inset

 since the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 evaluates the volume in each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that the construction of the Levi-Civita tensor can be straightforw
ardly generalized to an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold with a given metric and orientation.
 Through this generalization one obtains an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-form, which is frequently denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Vol}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as I have done above.
 Below I will also sometimes denote the Levi-Civita tensor by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Vol}$
\end_inset

, particularly when it is used only for integration over a manifold.
 I will use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 when I need to use its specific properties as a 4-form, e.g.\InsetSpace ~
when I need to
 evaluate it on some tangent vectors or differentiate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Affine connection
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Connection}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formulate the laws of physics, we need to write differential equations
 for some vector and tensor fields on the spacetime manifold.
 These differential equations involve derivatives of these vector or tensor
 fields in various directions.
 Thus we need to have a directional derivative operation that acts on arbitrary
 tensors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One could think at first that the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is to be used as a directional derivative operation.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is not a true directional derivative because it depends on the behavior
 of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the neighborhood of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and not only on the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 A true directional derivative of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in a direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 must depend 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 on the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 at the given point.
 Defining such a true directional derivative requires some information about
 how to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 neighbor tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

near-by
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 If such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between the neighbor tangent spaces were defined, tensors at different
 points could be subtracted.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.A\right|_{p'}-\left.A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 would be defined as a tensor in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and the derivative of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 along a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv\gamma(\tau_{0})$
\end_inset

 could be defined as the limit 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{\delta\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{A(\gamma(\tau_{0}+\delta\tau))-A(\gamma(\tau_{0}))}{\delta\tau}.\]

\end_inset

 Such a true directional derivative operation 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 be defined.
 It is usually denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 (pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nabla
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

del
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and called a 
\series bold
covariant derivative
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{covariant derivative}

\end_inset

 an 
\series bold
affine connection
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{affine connection}

\end_inset

 or simply a 
\series bold
connection
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{connection}

\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the direction of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}A\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor and does not depend on derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that a connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is not unique because there are infinitely many ways to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the neighbor tangent spaces, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
there are infinitely many possible maps
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p'}\mathcal{M}\rightarrow T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connection map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be described by a transformation-valued 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(\mathbf{u}):T_{p'}\mathcal{M}\rightarrow T_{p}\mathcal{M},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent vector at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the direction of point 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, there are as many connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 as maps 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 In a local coordinate system, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is represented by a quantity with three indices, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, but it is not a tensor in a single tangent space at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: by definition, it is a map connecting 
\emph on
different
\emph default
 tangent spaces.
 (The map 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is related to the non-tensorial Christoffel symbol; see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:The-coordinate-derivative}

\end_inset

 below.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In General Relativity, one formulates the laws of physics using a particular
 choice of the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 (called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Levi-Civita connection,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Levi-Civita-connection}

\end_inset

 below).
 This connection has several physically motivated and technically convenient
 properties with regard to the given metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on the spacetime manifold.
 So the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 directly involves the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and cannot be defined unless a metric is given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A visual motivation for the Levi-Civita connection, using the idea of embedding
 a curved manifold in a flat space, is given in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Covariant-derivative-through-projection}

\end_inset

 (Appendix\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:Elements-of-Special}

\end_inset

).
 Presently, I approach the definition of the Levi-Civita connection in a
 somewhat more abstract way: I first formulate the desirable properties
 of connections in general and then impose suitable conditions to deduce
 the Levi-Civita connection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are studying the general properties of tensors, we will avoid working
 in a local coordinate system; instead, we will perform calculations in
 a coordinate-free manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General properties of connections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to define a derivative operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 which maps scalars to scalars, vectors to vectors, etc., and depends only
 on the direction of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 should not contain any derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{(\lambda\mathbf{v})}A=\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}A,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary scalar function.
 If we had such an operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, we could define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gradient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 which maps scalars to 1-forms, vectors to (1,1)-tensors, and generally
 tensors of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m,n\right)$
\end_inset

 to tensors of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m,n+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 will have its own index; e.g.\InsetSpace ~
the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gradient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor of rank (0,3) denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}A_{\alpha\beta}\equiv A_{\alpha\beta;\mu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors are always boldface in our index-free convention, so there should
 be no confusion between expressions such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\nu}a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The former is the index representation of the rank-two tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\cdot}\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, while the latter is the covariant derivative of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in the given direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The index representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}a_{\;;\alpha}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the direction of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 may be equivalently rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}f=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}f=(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, according to the convenience of the moment.
 The index representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}f_{,\alpha}=v^{\alpha}f_{;\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 should also act on scalar functions as the usual directional derivative,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}f=\mathbf{v}\circ f.\]

\end_inset

In addition, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 should have the properties analogous to Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:tensor product}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:contraction}

\end_inset

), except that the contraction 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 now means 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 a contraction of tensors (e.g., application of a 1-form to a vector) and
 not the derivative operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the Lie derivative, the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is not expected to satisfy the property 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\neq(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})\circ f+\mathbf{v}\circ\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}f\right).\]

\end_inset

 If we assumed that this contraction property holds, we would be forced
 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\equiv\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordinate derivative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connection
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:The-coordinate-derivative}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above properties of the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 do not yet uniquely specify that operation.
 There are infinitely many possible affine connections.
 A simple way to define a connection is to fix a local coordinate system
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\lambda}\equiv\partial_{\lambda}\equiv\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\lambda}};\quad\left(\partial_{\mathbf{v}}A\right)^{\alpha\beta\gamma...}\equiv v^{\lambda}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\lambda}}A^{\alpha\beta\gamma...}\equiv v^{\lambda}A^{\alpha\beta\gamma...}{}_{,\lambda}\]

\end_inset

for any tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the component 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\alpha\beta\gamma...}{}_{;\lambda}$
\end_inset

 of the covariant derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is calculated as the partial derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 of the component 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\alpha\beta\gamma...}$
\end_inset

 of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the fixed coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 It is customary to use the semicolon in the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\alpha\beta\gamma}{}_{;\lambda}$
\end_inset

 before the extra index introduced by the covariant derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index-free notation, we denote the derivative with respect to the
 coordinates in a fixed coordinate system by 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is defined through the components in the fixed coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{\alpha}=u^{\lambda}v_{\;,\lambda}^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset

 In the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is just the usual derivative, so it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 satisfies all the properties of a connection.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined affine connection which we call the 
\series bold
coordinate derivative
\series default
 connection 
\series bold
determined by the coordinate system
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We stress that the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is tied to a 
\emph on
particular
\emph default
 coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In a different coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 do not have the same simple form 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\lambda}\partial v^{\alpha}/\partial y^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for 
\emph on
each
\emph default
 coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 we have a different coordinate connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 does not indicate explicitly the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 through which 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 So it is important to identify that coordinate system every time one uses
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 We will rarely make use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, but when we do, we will make it clear which coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is implied in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us also investigate how an arbitrary connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is related to the coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla-\partial$
\end_inset

 acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 linearly (without involving derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\mathbf{v}\right)-\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\mathbf{v}\right)=\lambda\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right).\]

\end_inset

Hence, for a fixed vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}-\partial_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation.
 Equivalently, we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla-\partial$
\end_inset

 is a transformation-valued 1-form and write
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla-\partial\equiv\Gamma;\quad\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}-\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\right)\mathbf{v}=\Gamma\left(\mathbf{u}\right)\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
Christoffel tensor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Christoffel tensor}

\end_inset

of the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 with respect to the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate derivative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, various choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 will give different connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the Christoffel tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 parametrizes all the possible covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that two different connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 are given (not necessarily coordinate derivative connections in any coordinate
 system).
 Using the defining properties of a connection, show that the difference
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and can thus be described as a linear transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compatibility with the metric
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formulate the laws of physics, we need to write differential equations
 for tensors on the spacetime manifold, and thus we need to use a directional
 derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 One possible choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 in a fixed coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 But the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\equiv\partial$
\end_inset

 is inconvenient not only because it depends on a fixed coordinate system
 (while the laws of physics are expected to be independent of coordinates),
 but also because it is in general 
\emph on
incompatible with the metric
\emph default
 in the following sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locally constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the direction of some other vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is natural to expect that the length of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is also constant in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, this property does not necessarily hold, since we will generally
 have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}) & =(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g)\circ(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})+g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})+g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})\\
 & =(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g)\circ(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\neq0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

This inconvenience will be avoided only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g=0$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 The property 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla g=0$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
compatibility with the metric
\series default
 (or 
\series bold
metricity
\series default
 of the connection).
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metricity}

\end_inset

An equivalent way to write this property is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}\circ g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})+g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w}).\label{eq:compatibility with the metric}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 behaves as a constant under a covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

, and only 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 are differentiated when one computes 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Torsion and torsion-freeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usual partial derivatives of 
\emph on
scalar
\emph default
 functions with respect to coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 (in 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 local coordinate system) commute,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial_{\mu}\partial_{\nu}f=\partial_{\nu}\partial_{\mu}f.\]

\end_inset

We may ask whether the same property holds for covariant derivatives,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}f=\nabla_{\nu}\nabla_{\mu}f.\label{eq:derivatives commute}\end{equation}

\end_inset

At the moment this property is written using the index notation.
 To reformulate the property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivatives commute}

\end_inset

) in a geometric way (without introducing coordinates explicitly), we contract
 Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivatives commute}

\end_inset

) with two arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\mu}v^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and rewrite the result using covariant derivatives,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
u^{\mu}v^{\nu}\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}f & =u^{\mu}\nabla_{\mu}\left(u^{\nu}\nabla_{\nu}f\right)-\left(u^{\mu}\nabla_{\mu}u^{\nu}\right)\left(\nabla_{\nu}f\right)\\
 & =\mathbf{u}\circ(\mathbf{v}\circ f)-\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)\circ f.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Thus, the property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivatives commute}

\end_inset

) is equivalent to
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u})\circ f=\mathbf{u}\circ(\mathbf{v}\circ f)-\mathbf{v}\circ(\mathbf{u}\circ f)=\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ f.\]

\end_inset

It is not necessarily true that an arbitrary connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 satisfies this property.
 To describe the extent of the deviation from this property, one defines
 the 
\series bold
torsion
\series default
 
\series bold
tensor
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{torsion tensor}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}-\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right],\label{eq:torsion def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is a vector-valued 2-form (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-torsion}

\end_inset

 below).
 The property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivatives commute}

\end_inset

) is then equivalent to the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

; this is called the 
\series bold
torsion-free
\series default
ness
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{torsion-free}

\end_inset

 of the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if a connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is torsion-free, we have the relation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\equiv\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]=\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}.\label{eq:Lie through nabla}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This relation is similar to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative in components}

\end_inset

), except that now covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 are used.
 Note that the coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 (defined with respect to a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

) is always a torsion-free connection because coordinate derivatives commute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-torsion}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-torsion}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 as defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:torsion def}

\end_inset

) does not actually involve derivatives of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, for an arbitrary scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=fT(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{u},f\mathbf{v})=fT(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-torsion}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For arbitrary scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $f,\phi$
\end_inset

 and vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(f\mathbf{u}) & =\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}f\right)\mathbf{u}+f\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u}=\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\mathbf{u}+f\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{u},\\
\nabla_{f\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v} & =f\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v},\\
\left[f\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ\phi & =f\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\mathbf{v}\circ\phi\right)-\mathbf{v}\circ\left((f\mathbf{u})\circ\phi\right)\\
 & =f\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]\circ\phi-\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\phi\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

and it follows that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
T(f\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\circ\phi & =fT(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\circ\phi-\left(\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\mathbf{u}\right)\circ\phi+\left(\mathbf{v}\circ f\right)\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\phi\right)\\
 & =fT(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The analogous property for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 will follow from the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that all possible connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 are parameterized as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla=\partial+\Gamma$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is a rank 3 tensor (the Christoffel tensor) with respect to a fixed coordinate
 system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate derivative.
 We can now compute the torsion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is torsion-free, it follows immediately from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:torsion def}

\end_inset

) that
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{v}-\Gamma(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

To visualize this property, we may interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 as a vector-valued bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\equiv\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and then the property 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Gamma(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\Gamma(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

 Thus a torsion-free connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is characterized by a 
\series bold
symmetric
\series default
 Christoffel tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given affine connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

, does there always exist a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is equal to the coordinate derivative?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Hint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the torsion of the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Answer:
\emph default
 No.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Levi-Civita connection
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Levi-Civita-connection}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 which is torsion-free and compatible with the metric is called the 
\series bold
Levi-Civita connection
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Levi-Civita connection}

\end_inset

or the 
\series bold
metric connection
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric connection}

\end_inset

In General Relativity, this is the connection used to formulate differential
 equations for physical quantities.
 The properties of metricity and torsion-freeness are imposed for several
 reasons, including mathematical simplicity.
 Ultimately, these properties are 
\emph on
physical
\emph default
 
\emph on
assumptions
\emph default
, that is, hypotheses verified by experiments.
 See Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:A-Choice-of-connection}

\end_inset

 in Appendix\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:Elements-of-Special}

\end_inset

 for more discussion and motivation.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Other, more complicated theories of gravity may use non-metric connections,
 e.g.\InsetSpace ~
the Einstein-Cartan theory 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein-Cartan theory}

\end_inset

admits a connection with nonzero torsion.
 Well...
 do we actually say anything about the EC theory? No.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now derive an explicit formula for the Levi-Civita connection, starting
 from the properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:compatibility with the metric}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivatives commute}

\end_inset

).
 It will follow that such a connection is unique.
 Later we shall see how to describe other connections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
First examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before presenting a general derivation, let us make the discussion less
 abstract by considering examples.
 First we verify that the Levi-Civita connection in the Euclidean space
 is just the ordinary, familiar directional derivative.
 Consider the three-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the metric 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dz^{2},\]

\end_inset

and let us evaluate some covariant derivatives.
 We will be using only the assumed properties of the Levi-Civita connection
 and see where this will lead us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we need to compute the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The way to compute it is to evaluate scalar products of this vector with
 other vectors.
 For instance, using the compatibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 with the metric, and the properties 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x})=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\partial_{x},\partial_{y})=0$
\end_inset

 etc., we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x},\partial_{x}) & =\frac{1}{2}g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x},\partial_{x})+\frac{1}{2}g(\partial_{x},\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x})\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\partial_{x}}g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x})=\frac{1}{2}\partial_{x}\left(1\right)=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using the torsion-freeness and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial_{x},\partial_{y}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, we also find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x},\partial_{y}) & =\nabla_{\partial_{x}}g(\partial_{x},\partial_{y})-g(\partial_{x},\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y})\\
 & =0-g(\partial_{x},[\partial_{x},\partial_{y}]+\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{x})\\
 & =-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\partial_{y}}g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x})=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this way, it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 has zero scalar products with every basis vector; thus it is itself zero,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We have already seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{x})=0$
\end_inset

, and further we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{y})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\partial_{x}}g(\partial_{y},\partial_{y})=0.\]

\end_inset

The computation of the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{z})$
\end_inset

 is a bit longer.
 First, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{z}) & =g(\left[\partial_{x},\partial_{y}\right]+\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{x},\partial_{z})=-g(\partial_{x},\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{z})\\
 & =-g(\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{z},\partial_{x}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The trick is to notice that we now have a similar structure with the coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 cyclically transposed.
 Repeating the transposition twice more, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{z})=-g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{z}),\]

\end_inset

so it vanishes.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{z}=0$
\end_inset

, etc.
 In other words, in flat space the covariant derivative of every basis vector
 in any direction equals zero.
 Now, we consider an arbitrary vector field 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=A\partial_{x}+B\partial_{y}+C\partial_{z},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

.
 We compute
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\mathbf{v}=\left(\partial_{x}A\right)\partial_{x}+\left(\partial_{x}B\right)\partial_{y}+\left(\partial_{x}C\right)\partial_{z},\]

\end_inset

since the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}$
\end_inset

 of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

 vanish.
 In other words, the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}$
\end_inset

 simply differentiates the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A,B,C\right)$
\end_inset

 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This is the behavior familiar from standard vector analysis.
 Thus, the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}$
\end_inset

 in flat space coincides with the familiar directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a less trivial example, let us consider a two-dimensional space with
 a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 and the metric
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=dx^{2}+f(x)dy^{2},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 is some (known) function that depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Let us compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 using the same approach as above.
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{x}) & =g(\left[\partial_{x},\partial_{y}\right]+\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{x},\partial_{x})=\frac{1}{2}\partial_{y}g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x})=0;\\
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y},\partial_{y}) & =\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\partial_{x}}g(\partial_{y},\partial_{y})=\frac{1}{2}f'(x).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this way, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 is completely determined through its scalar products with basis vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{f'(x)}{f(x)}\partial_{y}.\]

\end_inset

Similarly, one may evaluate other covariant derivatives, such as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{y},\partial_{y}) & =0,\\
g(\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{y},\partial_{x}) & =-g(\partial_{y},\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{x})=-g(\partial_{y},\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{y})=-\frac{1}{2}f'(x).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\partial_{y}}\partial_{y}=-\frac{1}{2}f'(x)\partial_{x}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Derivation of the Levi-Civita connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the examples above, we have computed covariant derivatives of some vectors
 by using only the defining properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:compatibility with the metric}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie through nabla}

\end_inset

) of the Levi-Civita connection.
 We now derive a general formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 using the same approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 are given, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 will be unambiguously determined if we compute its scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

 with an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.
 So we start with the scalar product expression 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

 and rewrite it using the assumed properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:compatibility with the metric}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie through nabla}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{y},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{z})\\
 & =\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{y},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}])-g(\mathbf{y},\nabla_{\mathbf{z}}\mathbf{x})\\
 & =\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{y},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}])-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{z}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have related 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

 to the same structure with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 cyclically transposed.
 So now we repeat the same procedure twice more, replacing the term with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{z}}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 by a term with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

, and finally by a term with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{y},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}])-\mathbf{z}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & +g(\mathbf{x},[\mathbf{z},\mathbf{y}])+\mathbf{y}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{z},[\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x}])-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the final formula for the Levi-Civita connection is
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Levi-Civita connection!Koszul formula}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =\frac{1}{2}\big(\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})+\mathbf{y}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})-\mathbf{z}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\nonumber \\
 & -g(\mathbf{x},[\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}])-g(\mathbf{y},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}])+g(\mathbf{z},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])\big).\label{eq:LC connection ans}\end{align}

\end_inset

 This is known as the 
\series bold
Koszul formula
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Koszul formula}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:Christoffel-derivation}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-:Christoffel-derivation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The familiar formula for the covariant derivative in the index notation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\nabla_{\mu}u^{\nu} & =\partial_{\mu}u^{\nu}+\Gamma_{\alpha\mu}^{\nu}u^{\alpha},\nonumber \\
\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda} & \equiv\frac{1}{2}g^{\lambda\mu}\left(\partial_{\alpha}g_{\mu\beta}+\partial_{\beta}g_{\mu\alpha}-\partial_{\mu}g_{\alpha\beta}\right),\label{eq:Christoffel components}\end{align}

\end_inset

can be derived from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Details: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Christoffel tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 describes the difference between the covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 and the coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 in a particular coordinate system.
 Let us select a coordinate system and substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\partial_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}=\partial_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}=\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\mu$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 values of the indices) into Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

).
 We note that the commutators of these vectors vanish and so
\begin_inset Formula \[
2g(\nabla_{\partial_{\alpha}}\partial_{\beta},\partial_{\mu})=\partial_{\alpha}g_{\beta\mu}+\partial_{\beta}g_{\mu\alpha}-\partial_{\mu}g_{\alpha\beta}.\]

\end_inset

Now we can decompose an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\lambda}u^{\lambda}\partial_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and compute 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\alpha}u^{\nu}=g^{\mu\nu}g(\nabla_{\partial_{\alpha}}\mathbf{u},\partial_{\nu})=\partial_{\alpha}u^{\nu}+\Gamma_{\alpha\mu}^{\nu}u^{\mu}.\]

\end_inset

 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is defined through the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and thus implicitly depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 involves not only first derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, but also first derivatives of the metric.
 This is easy to see by inspection of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

), where the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 clearly stands under differentiation in the first three terms.
 It is instructive to verify this statement more directly, without using
 Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

).
 Let us change the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as follows, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda}g,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function.
 (This transformation of the metric is called a 
\series bold
conformal transformation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conformal transformation}

\end_inset

because it preserves angles between vectors.) Now we can use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

) to determine the new connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

 using the 
\emph on
new
\emph default
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

, rather than the old metric.
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =\left(\mathbf{x}\circ\lambda\right)\tilde{g}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})+\left(\mathbf{y}\circ\lambda\right)\tilde{g}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})-\left(\mathbf{z}\circ\lambda\right)\tilde{g}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\nonumber \\
 & +\tilde{g}(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}).\label{eq:nabla after conformal}\end{align}

\end_inset

This expression contains first derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\circ\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the Levi-Civita connection indeed involves first derivatives
 of the metric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:The-coordinate-derivative}

\end_inset

, all the possible connections (covariant derivatives) 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 can be described by choosing a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 (in which the coordinate derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

) and a transformation-valued 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}=\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}+\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Torsion-freeness implies the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{v}=\Gamma(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is not otherwise constrained.
 Of all the possible torsion-free connections, the Levi-Civita connection
 is described by a particular unique choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 determined by the metricity requirement.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the (2,0) tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse metric defined on 1-forms, or alternatively the map from
 vectors to 1-forms to vectors.
 We now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(g^{-1})=0$
\end_inset

 for the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple (but less explicit) calculation is as follows.
 Consider the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

 from vectors to 1-forms and the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 from 1-forms to vectors.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{g}\hat{g}^{-1}=\hat{1},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map from 1-forms to 1-forms.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\hat{g}\hat{g}^{-1})=\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\hat{g}^{-1}=\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\hat{1}=0,\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\hat{g}^{-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a more detailed calculation along the same lines.
 For an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega\circ\mathbf{v}=g(\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{\omega},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

Now we apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 to both sides,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\omega\circ\mathbf{v})=\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{\omega},\mathbf{v})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{\omega}),\mathbf{v})+g(\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{\omega},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 satisfies Leibnitz's rule with respect to tensor products and contractions,
 we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\omega\circ\mathbf{v}) & =(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\omega)\circ\mathbf{v}+\omega\circ(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})\\
 & =g(\hat{g}^{-1}(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\omega),\mathbf{v})+g(\hat{g}^{-1}\omega,\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The result 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\hat{g}^{-1}=0$
\end_inset

 follows.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Killing vectors
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Killing-vectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 can be applied to arbitrary tensors, and in particular to the metric tensor
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Let us compute the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g$
\end_inset

 with respect to a given vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form acting on two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 by first letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 act on the entire expression 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 and then subtracting the Lie derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right) & \equiv\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\left(g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\right)-g(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{a},\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{b})\\
 & =\mathbf{v}\circ g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a}\right],\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{a},\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}\right]).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists a more convenient formula for the Lie derivative of the metric.
 This formula uses the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-the-Killing-equation}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-the-Killing-equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lie derivative of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form that can be computed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{k}).\label{eq:Lie derivative of metric formula}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary vector field.
 By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g$
\end_inset

, we have for arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 the expression
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{b})\nonumber \\
 & =(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})+g(\left[\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a}\right],\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},[\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b}]).\label{eq:Lk ab}\end{align}

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the metricity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a}\right]=\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{a}-\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b}\right]$
\end_inset

, we obtain Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative of metric formula}

\end_inset

).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g=0$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Killing vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Killing vector}

\end_inset

for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The Killing vector describes a special set of directions in space, such
 that the metric 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remains constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in these directions.
 It is only due to the presence of a certain symmetry that a metric could
 have even a single Killing vector field.
 (By contrast, the Levi-Civita connection gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g=0$
\end_inset

 for any vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, but this is due to a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 rather than a special property of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that the Lie derivative is defined independently of the metric.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Example-:Killing-vector1}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Example-:Killing-vector1}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-dimensional space with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{1},...,x^{3}\right)\equiv\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 and the metric
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\sum_{\alpha,\beta=1}^{N}A_{\alpha\beta}(x,z)\textrm{d}x^{\alpha}\otimes\textrm{d}x^{\beta},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\beta}(x,z)$
\end_inset

 are some complicated functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (but not of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

).
 Then it is intuitively clear that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The mathematical formulation of this property is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 is the Killing vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can verify this property explicitly.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 depends only on the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, but not on derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the calculations, let us choose the vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a}\right]=0,\quad\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}\right]=0\]

\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of the components 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, these conditions mean that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\frac{\partial a^{\mu}}{\partial y}\right|_{p}=0,\quad\left.\frac{\partial b^{\mu}}{\partial y}\right|_{p}=0\]

\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 It is always possible to adjust the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 at any single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, without changing the values of the vectors at that point.
 Then we find, at the same point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g\right)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =\mathbf{v}\circ g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a}\right],\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{a},\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}\right])\\
 & =\partial_{y}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\partial_{y}\left[\sum_{\alpha,\beta}A_{\alpha\beta}(x,z)a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\right]_{p}=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The same calculation goes through at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Example-:Killing-vector2}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Example-:Killing-vector2}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the Schwarzschild metric
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dt^{2}-\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}\negmedspace dr^{2}-r^{2}\left(d\theta^{2}+(\sin^{2}\theta)d\phi^{2}\right).\]

\end_inset

This metric has the Killing vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 One describes the corresponding symmetries of the spacetime by saying that
 the geometry is stationary (independent of time) and azimuthally symmetric
 (independent of the azimuthal angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{azimuthally symmetric spacetime}

\end_inset

 Note that these vectors commute, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial_{t},\partial_{\phi}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, meaning that the symmetries are independent of each other.
 Of course, any linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 (with constant coefficients) is also a Killing vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Produce an explicit example showing that in general 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}g\neq0$
\end_inset

 for a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative of metric formula}

\end_inset

), the Killing vector property 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=0$
\end_inset

 can be rewritten in a more convenient way, as a differential equation for
 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This equation is called the 
\series bold
Killing equation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Killing equation}

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{k})=0,\label{eq:Killing nabla cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and is understood as an identity that should hold for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index notation, the Killing equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mu}k_{\nu}+\nabla_{\nu}k_{\mu}=0\label{eq:Killing index cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and involves the 
\emph on
covariant
\emph default
 components of the Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an arbitrary vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, we may consider the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{x})}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{x})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{x})}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
distortion tensor
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{distorsion tensor}

\end_inset

 corresponding to the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, the distortion tensor is written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[B_{(\mathbf{x})}\right]_{\mu\nu}=\nabla_{\mu}\mathbf{x}_{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

The Killing equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

) can be easily restated in terms of the distorsion tensor
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B_{(\mathbf{k})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b})\label{eq:Bk 2 def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector iff its distorsion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{k})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=-B_{(\mathbf{k})}(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{k})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector.
 The following problem derives an explicit representation of this 2-form.
\end_layout

