\begin_layout Subsection
Divergence of a vector field
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Divergence-of-a}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The divergence of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is a number characterizing the change in the volume of space carried by
 the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be definite, let us consider a 
\emph on
four
\emph default
-dimensional manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 be a given vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and consider the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as curves parameterized by a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 We may select a region 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at an initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

, and let the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 transform this region to a different region 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-dependent region of space is called 
\series bold
comoving
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{comoving volume}

\end_inset

with the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is more convenient to consider an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 volume, or a 
\series bold
volume element
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{volume element}

\end_inset

 A 4-volume element of the comoving volume can be thought of as a parallelepiped
 spanned by the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathbf{u}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 and by three vectors connecting the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to nearby points on the congruence corresponding to the same value of the
 curve parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we need to choose three 
\emph on
connecting vectors
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we would like to compute the rate of change of the volume element
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\equiv\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the Levi-Civita symbol.
 The result will be the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 along the flow, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere timelike and normalized by the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=1$
\end_inset

, we may interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proper time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measured by observers along the orbits.
 Then the connecting vectors will correspond to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

comoving
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spatial directions measured at a fixed time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 in the reference frame of an observer.
 So the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V$
\end_inset

 will be interpreted as the local rate of change of the comoving 3-volume
 of space.
 (The 3-volume is completed to a 4-volume by the unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.) However, for the present calculation we do not need to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is timelike.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{a}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{b}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}=0,\]

\end_inset

 the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})=\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\circ(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}).\]

\end_inset

The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is a totally antisymmetric tensor (4-form), and so it must be proportional
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 itself.
 Hence we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=f\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is some scalar function.
 This function depends on the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
divergence
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{divergence of vector fields}

\end_inset

or the 
\series bold
expansion
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-divergence-formula}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-divergence-formula}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 and an orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})=\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

, by the formulas
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u} & =\sum_{a}\eta_{aa}g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{u})\\
 & =\sum_{a}\eta_{aa}g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{u}\right]).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the index notation, the divergence can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=\nabla_{\mu}u^{\mu}\equiv u^{\mu}{}_{;\mu}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-divergence-formula}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the orthonormal basis of 1-forms dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can then compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}\right)\\
 & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}+...,\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we omitted similar terms involving 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 We now consider the first term above.
 The 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a linear combination of the basis 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{a}.\]

\end_inset

 Due to antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 within 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}$
\end_inset

, only the term proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}$
\end_inset

 survives, so
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}=\left(\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{0}\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\circ\mathbf{e}_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, we can simplify 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{0}$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{0} & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\circ\mathbf{e}_{0}\right)-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\circ\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{0}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\circ\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{u}-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{0}\right)\\
 & =\eta_{00}g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{u}-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{0})=\eta_{00}g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{u}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the property 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\left[\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{u}\right])=g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{u}),\]

\end_inset

which is due to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{0})=\textrm{const},\quad g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{0})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{0})=0.\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}=\eta_{00}g(\mathbf{e}_{0},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{u})\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}.\]

\end_inset

Analogous simplifications are performed for other terms, and so we obtain
 the first required formula.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{a})=0\]

\end_inset

due to the normalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{u})=g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{u}\right]).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 in the index notation can be now derived by expressing the orthonormal
 basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 through the coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{a}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are the components of the orthonormal frame, so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{a}=e_{a}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}.\]

\end_inset

 Then in the index notation we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{u})=g_{\lambda\mu}e_{a}^{\mu}e_{a}^{\nu}u^{\lambda}{}_{;\nu}.\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=\sum_{a}\eta_{aa}g_{\lambda\mu}e_{a}^{\mu}e_{a}^{\nu}u^{\lambda}{}_{;\nu}.\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g through estar}

\end_inset

) gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{a}\eta_{aa}e_{a}^{\mu}e_{a}^{\nu}=g^{\mu\nu}.\]

\end_inset

Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=g_{\lambda\mu}g^{\mu\nu}u^{\lambda}{}_{;\nu}=u^{\mu}{}_{;\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

, our final result is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V=\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})=\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)V.\]

\end_inset

Thus the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
relative
\emph default
 rate of change of the volume carried by the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The divergence of a vector field can be also expressed in terms of the Hodge
 star operation.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hodge duality}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

