Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $*\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, so it is sufficient to show that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=\textrm{d}*\hat{g}\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
*\hat{g}\mathbf{u}=\iota_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}.\]

\end_inset

Using the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=0$
\end_inset

 and the Cartan homotopy formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan homotopy formula}

\end_inset

), we compute 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}*\hat{g}\mathbf{u}=\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}-\iota_{\mathbf{u}}\textrm{d}\right)\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\equiv\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}.\]

