\begin_layout Section
Calculations in index-free notation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Calculations-in-index-free}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index-free notation has its advantages and disadvantages, in comparison
 with the index notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Index-free notation emphasizes geometric operations, such as the commutator
 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]$
\end_inset

 or scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

, that would otherwise remain hidden under a mass of indices.
 For instance, the Bianchi identities are clearly seen to be consequences
 of the Jacobi identity and the assumptions about the Levi-Civita connection.
 Also, the geometric relations between tensors are shown explicitly, rather
 than encoded in the positions of indices.
 Thus, calculations in index-free notation help develop geometric intuition
 rather than merely an agility with manipulating indices.
 In the index notation, the same calculations appear to consist of a certain
 lucky manipulations of indices (the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

juggling of indices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 It remains unclear how to guess the correct sequence of index manipulations
 that would be needed for a particular calculation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Index-free notation is in many cases more concise than the index notation,
 since one does not need to write indices next to each letter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the index-free approach, every object is defined through geometric operations
, so it is impossible to introduce a non-tensorial quantity.
 For instance, the non-tensorial Christoffel symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 in its usual form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Christoffel components}

\end_inset

) is simply 
\emph on
undefined
\emph default
; instead one might define a Christoffel 
\emph on
tensor
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, which is a transformation-valued 1-form representing the difference between
 two given affine connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{v}\equiv\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

 Within the index notation, one frequently uses non-tensor quantities and
 calculates their components in a convenient coordinate system, and then
 one needs to check that the results are tensors.
 Operations with non-tensor quantities obscure the logic of a derivation
 and may lead to hard-to-spot errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Index-free notation appears more abstract, whereas expressions in the index
 notation can be easily interpreted as just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

arrays of numbers.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Index-free notation is unwieldy if complicated contractions or symmetrizations
 are applied to tensors of high rank.
 For instance, an expression such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu;\rho}^{[\rho}B_{\alpha}^{\beta]\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is difficult to manipulate in the index-free notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{index-free approach}

\end_inset

On the whole, it appears that the index-free notation is more suitable for
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

abstract
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 calculations, such as definitions of new quantities or derivations of general
 properties of tensors.
 In calculations involving complicated tensor contractions and symmetrizations,
 the index notation is better.
 For specific calculations, e.g.\InsetSpace ~
when components of a certain tensor are known
 in particular coordinates, the index notation is unavoidable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps, the index notation should be studied first, because a certain familiari
ty with the index notation seems to be helpful for learning more abstract
 material.
 However, I feel that learning to think in the index-free notation is also
 helpful, if only for the fact that the entire mathematical literature has
 been using exclusively index-free notation for several decades.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Abstract index notation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Abstract-index-notation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is somewhat cumbersome to use the index-free notation when dealing with
 tensors of higher rank.
 For example, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a transformation-valued one-form such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation in the tangent space, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla A$
\end_inset

 is a transformation-valued bilinear form that acts as
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\nabla A)(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}\equiv\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}A\right](\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}.\]

\end_inset

 Note that we have some difficulty in making it clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla A)(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is a derivative in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and that only 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is to be differentiated but not 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

.
 We could write
\begin_inset Formula \[
``(\nabla A)(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}"\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left[A(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}\right]-A(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}-A(\mathbf{v})\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w},\]

\end_inset

but manipulating such expressions is a rather cumbersome affair.
 In such cases, it is more convenient to write everything in the index notation,
 e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
``(\nabla A)(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}"\equiv u^{\mu}v^{\lambda}w^{\alpha}\nabla_{\mu}A_{\alpha\lambda}^{\beta}\equiv u^{\mu}v^{\lambda}w^{\alpha}A_{\alpha\lambda;\mu}^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

This notation clearly shows that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 supplies the direction for the derivative, and the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 are contracted with the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, but only 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is differentiated.
 However, when using the index notation we do not actually need to talk
 about components of the vectors in a basis; in fact, we have not really
 chosen any explicit basis so far.
 In most cases, the indices are actually used only as labels indicating
 that vectors and tensors are contracted with each other in a particular
 order.
 This is the idea of the 
\series bold
abstract index notation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{abstract index notation}

\end_inset

introduced by R.
 Penrose as a re-interpretation of the familiar component notation.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Penrose wrote in\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Penr68}

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
What I shall present here is an entirely frame-independent algebra which
 allows one to calculate with indexed quantities exactly as before (but
 now with a clear conscience!)...
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clear conscience
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 referred to is the absence of a cordinate system.
 However, this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conscience
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not really 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if one still uses non-tensor quantities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 or performs calculations in specially chosen coordinate systems.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The abstract index notation can be summarized as follows: An index, such
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, does not take values 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,2,...$
\end_inset

, but is merely a label indicating that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector while 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form.
 Repeated indices, e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}u_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, do not mean summation but instead indicate that a certain vector is being
 contracted with a certain 1-form.
 No particular basis or coordinate system is chosen or implied, and one
 is careful to perform only well-defined geometric operations on all quantities.
 (Geometric operations are the tensor product, the contraction of tensors,
 the Lie derivative, and the covariant derivative.
 The ordinary coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is disallowed.) The results of such calculations may be interpreted either
 as coordinate-free expressions or as component expressions 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid in any coordinate system.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Strictly speaking, the abstract index notation disallows non-tensorial
 quantities such as the Christoffel symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, operations with individual components of tensors such as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha4\beta4}$
\end_inset

, or an implicit choice of a coordinate system (e.g.\InsetSpace ~
calculations in locally
 inertial coordinates).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach taken in this book is coordinate-free and the notation is almost
 everywhere index-free.
 However, we 
\emph on
do
\emph default
 use the abstract index notation when it is significantly more convenient.
 For instance, it is straightforward to express complicated tensor contractions
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu;\rho}^{\rho}B_{\alpha}^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 in the index notation, but cumbersome without indices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I would like to emphasize that the index notation such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}A_{\alpha\lambda}^{\beta}\equiv A_{\alpha\lambda;\mu}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 does not imply that the covariant derivative is applied to each component
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 separately.
 Rather, this notation refers to the components of the higher-rank tensor
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla A)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the component 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{1}A_{12}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is not equal to an operator ``
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 acting on the component 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{12}^{1}$
\end_inset

 of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Rather, the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{1}A_{12}^{1}$
\end_inset

 stands for the component 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla A){}_{112}^{1}$
\end_inset

 of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla A$
\end_inset

.
 If (for example) 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\lambda}^{\beta}=-A_{\lambda\alpha}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 then the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 property 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\lambda;\mu}^{\beta}=-A_{\lambda\alpha;\mu}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is not automatically satisfied (as it would be if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\lambda;\mu}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 were a component-wise derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\lambda}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

).
 This property must be derived as a consequence of the properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is not a collection of fixed tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{0},\nabla_{1},\nabla_{2},\nabla_{3}$
\end_inset

; rather, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 represents different operations when applied to different tensors.
 Therefore, an abstract index expression such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha\lambda;\mu}^{\beta}$
\end_inset


\emph on
 
\emph default
must be interpreted and used with care.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{index notation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Converting expressions into index-free notation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Converting-expressions-into}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we develop the methods for converting indexed expressions
 into an index-free form.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{index-free notation!converting into}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correspondence between the index notation and the index-free notation
 is established using the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\equiv\partial/\partial x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, by assuming 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 values of all the indices.
 For example, consider a covector (1-form) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 It is represented in the index notation by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\alpha}A_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 means the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha,\beta\right)$
\end_inset

-component of the rank (0,2) tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the component 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\alpha}A_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the number defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\beta;\alpha}\equiv\nabla_{\alpha}A_{\beta}\equiv\left(\nabla\mathbf{A}\right)_{\alpha\beta}=(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}}\mathbf{A})\circ\mathbf{e}_{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

An equation written in the index notation, such as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{\beta;\alpha}+g_{\alpha\beta}-2A_{\alpha;\beta}=0,\label{eq:A identity}\end{equation}

\end_inset

is converted to the index-free notation by first rewriting it as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\alpha}A_{\beta}+g_{\alpha\beta}-2\nabla_{\beta}A_{\alpha},\]

\end_inset

where we introduced the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 explicitly, and then by fixing 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 and inserting basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

, thus obtaining
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}}\mathbf{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{\beta}+g\left(\mathbf{e}_{\alpha},\mathbf{e}_{\beta}\right)-2\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{\beta}}\mathbf{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{\alpha}=0.\]

\end_inset

However, we expect that such tensor relations can be expressed 
\emph on
in a geometric way
\emph default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
as statements about arbitrary vectors, without using a particular basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this can be done with a little work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic rule of converting indexed expressions to the index-free notation
 is to contract each free index with an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 
\emph on
vector
\emph default
.
 The resulting expression will then depend on a certain number of arbitrary
 vectors but will be independent of the choice of basis.
 Consider Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:A identity}

\end_inset

) as an example.
 Since Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:A identity}

\end_inset

) has two free indices (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

), let us contract it with arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 having index representations 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\beta}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}A_{\beta;\alpha}+a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}g_{\alpha\beta}-2a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}A_{\alpha;\beta}=0.\]

\end_inset

Then we rewrite covariant derivatives explicitly through the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\nabla_{\alpha}A_{\beta}+a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}g_{\alpha\beta}-2a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\nabla_{\beta}A_{\alpha}=0.\]

\end_inset

Finally, this equation is rewritten in the index-free notation as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{b}+g\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)-2\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{a}=0.\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{A})$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form acting on vectors.
 For the purpose of facilitating further calculations with the above expression,
 it might be useful to rewrite the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{A})\circ\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{A})\circ\mathbf{b} & =\mathbf{a}\circ(\mathbf{A}\circ\mathbf{b})-\mathbf{A}\circ(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b})\\
 & =\mathbf{a}\circ(\mathbf{A}\circ\mathbf{b})-\mathbf{A}\circ(\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]+\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{a})\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in some other form.
 In any case, we now have an equation involving 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and the known 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

, and we are not using any basis vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A somewhat more complicated example is an indexed expression involving repeated
 covariant derivatives, such as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v^{\lambda}{}_{;\beta\alpha}-v^{\lambda}{}_{;\alpha\beta}=\nabla_{\alpha}\nabla_{\beta}v^{\lambda}-\nabla_{\beta}\nabla_{\alpha}v^{\lambda}=0.\label{eq:ab ex 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Contracting Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ab ex 0}

\end_inset

) with arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\nabla_{\alpha}\nabla_{\beta}v^{\lambda}-a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\nabla_{\beta}\nabla_{\alpha}v^{\lambda}=0.\label{eq:ab ex 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We would like to rewrite this expression in the index-free notation.
 But now we encounter a difficulty: Nested covariant derivatives, such as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, contain also derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, which are not present in the expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ab ex 1}

\end_inset

).
 Therefore we first rewrite
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}\nabla_{\alpha}\nabla_{\beta}v^{\lambda} & =a^{\alpha}\nabla_{\alpha}\left(b^{\beta}\nabla_{\beta}v^{\lambda}\right)-\left(a^{\alpha}\nabla_{\alpha}b^{\beta}\right)\left(\nabla_{\beta}v^{\lambda}\right)\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b})}\mathbf{v},\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly for the other term in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ab ex 1}

\end_inset

), and then finally Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ab ex 0}

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}} & \nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b})}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{(\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{a})}\mathbf{v}\\
 & =\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right]\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{v}=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the last line, the first commutator is simply a shorthand notation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right]\mathbf{v}\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v},\]

\end_inset

while the second commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\equiv\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is the commutator of vector fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewrite the following indexed expressions in an index-free manner:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}h_{;\alpha\beta} & =C_{\alpha\beta}v^{\beta}g^{\alpha\lambda}f_{,\lambda};\\
u_{\alpha;\beta}-u_{\beta;\alpha} & =v_{\alpha}w_{\beta}-v_{\beta}w_{\alpha};\\
v^{\alpha}u_{\beta;\alpha}-u^{\alpha}v_{\beta;\alpha} & =w^{\alpha}w_{\alpha;\beta};\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha},v^{\alpha},w^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are indexed representations of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are scalar functions; and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv C_{\alpha\beta}x^{\alpha}y^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Answers: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}h-\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}}h=C(\mathbf{v},\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}f)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{u}=\left(\hat{g}\mathbf{v}\right)\wedge\left(\hat{g}\mathbf{w}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}\right])=g(\mathbf{w},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{w})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if we used coordinate basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 instead of arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial_{\mu},\partial_{\nu}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 and the term with the commutator would vanish.
 Thus we would have obtained a simpler formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\partial_{\mu}}\nabla_{\partial_{\nu}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{\partial_{\nu}}}\nabla_{\partial_{\mu}}\mathbf{v}=0,\]

\end_inset

which looks quite similar to the indexed expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ab ex 0}

\end_inset

).
 The simplification is due to the fact that the commutator term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 drops out.
 But the same simplification can be achieved without choosing the coordinate
 basis vectors.
 It suffices to assume that the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 commute.
 Since our expression is actually independent of the 
\emph on
derivatives
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, we can always choose commuting vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of any one point.
 This choice will be possible in every case when we convert an indexed expressio
n into an index-free form, since any number of simultaneously commuting
 vector fields can be chosen at a point (see, for example, Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-exist-connecting-basis}

\end_inset

).
 We will frequently use this method of simplification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Index-free computations of trace
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Index-free-trace}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traces of tensors 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 be computed in the index-free notation, although in many cases calculations
 are easier in the index notation.
 Nevertheless, it is possible to develop a sufficiently powerful formalism,
 so that the index notation is 
\emph on
in principle
\emph default
 never needed.
 In this section I explain the index-free approach to calculating the trace.
 Since the readers will certainly be more familiar with the index notation
 for traces, I provide a comparison between indexed and index-free approaches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I begin by reviewing the index-free definition of the trace of a linear
 transformation.
 A transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is expressed in a tensor form as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T=\mathbf{a}_{1}\otimes\boldsymbol{\omega}_{1}+\mathbf{a}_{2}\otimes\boldsymbol{\omega}_{2}+...,\label{eq:T 2 decomp}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are some vectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are some covectors; by definition, any (1,1)-tensor can be decomposed in
 this way.
 Then the 
\series bold
trace
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{trace}

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{Tr }T=\boldsymbol{\omega}_{1}\circ\mathbf{a}_{1}+\boldsymbol{\omega}_{2}\circ\mathbf{a}_{2}+...\label{eq:T 2 trace decomp}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this definition is not convenient in more complicated cases.
 For example, a tensor expressed in the index notation as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 may be interpreted as a transformation-valued 1-form, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow T(\mathbf{a})\mathbf{x},\quad\left(T(\mathbf{a})\mathbf{x}\right)^{\lambda}\equiv T_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}a^{\alpha}x^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

Suppose we would like to compute the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, expressed in the index notation as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:T 2 trace decomp}

\end_inset

), we first need to decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of tensor products, as in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:T 2 decomp}

\end_inset

).
 This computation is cumbersome because a large number of tensor product
 terms will be needed in a decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, such explicit decompositions usually require a choice of basis.
 For example, the identity operator can be decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{1}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\mathbf{e}_{j}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the corresponding dual basis.
 (The above relation is called a 
\series bold
decomposition of identity
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{decomposition of identity}

\end_inset

) Calculations with such decompositions rapidly become unwieldy for higher-rank
 tensors, and so we will proceed by another route.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be specific, let us first show how one can compute the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in a basis-free manner.
 We first 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower the index
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta\lambda}\equiv T_{\alpha\beta}^{\mu}g_{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

, which is in the index-free notation a trilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})\equiv g(T(\mathbf{a})\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}).\]

\end_inset

Then we need to specify two of three arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 which are to be contracted.
 For instance, the covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}\equiv T_{\alpha\lambda}^{\alpha}\equiv T_{\alpha\beta\lambda}g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 looks like the contraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

 with respect to the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 To make this relationship explicit, we use the following notation, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}(\mathbf{c})=\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c}).\label{eq:Trace example}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This notation is somewhat verbose but explicit and unambiguous.The vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 does not enter the final object 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}(\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is merely an auxiliary part of notation.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in the right-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Trace example}

\end_inset

) may be called a 
\series bold
mute
\series default
 
\series bold
vector
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{mute vectors}

\end_inset

, similarly to the mute index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 used in summation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus I propose the following index-free notation for the 
\series bold
trace
\series default
 of a multilinear tensor-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the arguments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...)$
\end_inset

 is first written as a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...)$
\end_inset

, and then the trace is found by substituting the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which is a (2,0)-tensor, instead of the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c},...)\equiv\left.T(\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...)\right|_{\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b}=g^{-1}}.\]

\end_inset

Note that the use of the same vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in both arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 reflects the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric (2,0) tensor.
 This notation often helps simplify terms that vanish due to antisymmetry.
 An alternative notation, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Tr}_{\left\langle \mathbf{a}\mathbf{b}\right\rangle }T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

, would be more cumbersome to use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index notation for the trace above is 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\alpha\beta}T_{\alpha\beta\gamma...}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way, the trace operation is understood as a simple substitution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b}=g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 into a multilinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 An explicit notation for this substitution,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c},...)\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{b}=g^{-1}}T(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...)\label{eq:trace notation a b g}\end{equation}

\end_inset

could be useful when one needs to specify explicitly that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is being used.
 For instance, one could then introduce several metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, ..., and compute traces with respect to these metrics.
 However, we will be working most of the time with one metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and so the verbose and explicit notation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:trace notation a b g}

\end_inset

) will not be necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the trace notation, we may now rewrite an arbitrary indexed expression
 in an index-free form.
 When an indexed expression contains a sum over a pair of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dummy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indices, we can first lower both indices (inserting an extra 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

) and then replace the 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 by a pair of mute vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us rewrite the following equation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}u^{\gamma}w_{\gamma;\alpha\beta}=C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta},\]

\end_inset

 in the index-free notation.
 Using the techniques from Sec.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Converting-expressions-into}

\end_inset

, we rewrite the left-hand side as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w}-\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w}).\]

\end_inset

 Turning now to the right-hand side, we note that it is only necessary to
 express the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}$
\end_inset

, since all other contractions are ordinary.
 The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\mu\beta}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a transformation-valued function of two vectors,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{z}\rightarrow C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z},\quad\left[C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}\right]^{\lambda}\equiv C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\mu\beta}z^{\alpha}x^{\mu}y^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

(In an actual calculation, such as that in the practice problem 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Practice-problem:trace-of-C}

\end_inset

 below, we may be given an explicit, index-free formula for the transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.) The trace 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}$
\end_inset

 is first converted into a contraction with 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}=g^{\lambda\mu}C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}.\]

\end_inset

The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a function of four vectors, expressed through the original tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\mu\beta}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}a^{\lambda}z^{\alpha}x^{\mu}y^{\beta} & =g_{\kappa\lambda}a^{\kappa}C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\mu\beta}z^{\alpha}x^{\mu}y^{\beta}\\
 & \equiv g(\mathbf{a},C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z})\equiv C(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we rewrite
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}=g^{\lambda\mu}C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

 Finally, we introduce two mute vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 whose tensor product 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\lambda}b^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 will replace 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

 in the contraction 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\lambda\mu}C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 The result of the replacement is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g^{\lambda\mu}C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta} & \rightarrow a^{\lambda}b^{\mu}C_{\lambda\alpha\mu\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}=C(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{u})\\
 & =g(\mathbf{a},C(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{u})\mathbf{u}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The trace of this expression with respect to the mute vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},C(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u})\mathbf{u})=C^{\lambda}{}_{\alpha\lambda\beta}u^{\alpha}u^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

In this way, we are able to rewrite the initial indexed expression in an
 index-free manner.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One sometimes needs a repeated trace over several sets of indices.
 In these cases I use the notation
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula \[
\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},....,\mathbf{b},\mathbf{b},...)\equiv\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{b}}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},....,\mathbf{b},\mathbf{b},...).\]

\end_inset


\series default
The repeated trace can be computed in any order: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{b}}=\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{b}}\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that each mute vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},...$
\end_inset

 appears exactly twice in the expression under the trace.
 This is similar to the Einstein summation convention where each repeated
 index can appear only twice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the trace such as that in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Trace example}

\end_inset

) in an actual calculation, we need to have a concrete expression for the
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in terms of other known vectors or tensors, and a procedure to implement
 the trace operation via an index-free calculation.
 I now describe such a procedure and then give examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we need to compute the trace of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 One possibility to perform this calculation in the index-free notation
 is to use an explicit decomposition of the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 through tensor products of orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{-1}=\mathbf{e}_{0}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{0}-\mathbf{e}_{1}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{1}-\mathbf{e}_{2}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{2}-\mathbf{e}_{3}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{3},\label{eq:metric decomp 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which corresponds to the index notation
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{\alpha\beta}=e_{0}^{\alpha}e_{0}^{\beta}-e_{1}^{\alpha}e_{1}^{\beta}-e_{2}^{\alpha}e_{2}^{\beta}-e_{3}^{\alpha}e_{3}^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)$
\end_inset

 is a bilinear form in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

, we can compute the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z},...)$
\end_inset

 by substituting the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 1}

\end_inset

) of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 instead of the arguments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z},...)=T(\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{z},...)-\sum_{j=1}^{3}T(\mathbf{e}_{j},\mathbf{e}_{j},\mathbf{z},...).\label{eq:trace decomp 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Of course, the trace does not depend on the choice of the basis.
 For instance, we may also use a decomposition of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{-1}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\mathbf{u}_{j}\otimes\mathbf{v}_{j},\label{eq:metric decomp 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are some suitable vectors that are not necessarily linearly independent
 or orthogonal (and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq4$
\end_inset

).
 If we use the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 2}

\end_inset

), we will have to write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z},...)=\sum_{j=1}^{n}T(\mathbf{u}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{j},\mathbf{z},...).\]

\end_inset

However, it is somewhat inconvenient to have to choose particular vectors
 for a decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 1}

\end_inset

) or (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 2}

\end_inset

), especially since the result does not depend on the choice of these vectors.
 In many cases, a trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z},...)$
\end_inset

 can be computed without selecting an explicit decomposition of the metric,
 especially when the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is given by an index-free expression involving fixed vectors, the metric
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and covariant derivatives.
 The following statement lists the basic building blocks for index-free
 trace calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:trace-properties}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:trace-properties}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trace operation has the following properties:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{trace!index-free computation}

\end_inset

 
\newline
Linearity and distributivity:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}\left(A+B\right) & =\textrm{Tr }A+\textrm{Tr }B,\\
\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{b}}(...) & =\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{b}}\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}(...),\\
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}A(...)\otimes B(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},...) & =A(...)\otimes\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}B(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},...),\\
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},...) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},...).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary tensors, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{1},\hat{P}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are linear transformations, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
(1,1)-tensors, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},...,\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 are vectors.
\newline
Symmetry properties:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\hat{P}_{1}\hat{P}_{2}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}) & =\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\hat{P}_{2}\hat{P}_{1}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}),\\
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\hat{P}_{1}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}) & =\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\hat{P}_{1}^{T}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{T}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
adjoint
\series default
 
\series bold
transformation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{adjoint transformation}

\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

: The transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{T}$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 by yielding a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{T}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\hat{P}^{T}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv g(\mathbf{x},\hat{P}\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 (The adjoint transformation is represented in an 
\emph on
orthonormal
\emph default
 basis by the transposed matrix, hence the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{T}$
\end_inset

.) 
\newline
Relations involving the metric:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a}) & =\textrm{div}\mathbf{x};\\
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}) & =4,\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 4 is the dimension of spacetime.
 
\newline
The substitution properties:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{x},\]

\end_inset

or more generally,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)=A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)\]

\end_inset

for an arbitrary tensor-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{x},...)$
\end_inset

 linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
\newline
Relations involving the Levi-Citiva tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\mathbf{x}',\mathbf{y}')\\
 & \quad=-2g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}')g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y}')+2g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}')g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x}');\\
 & \textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\mathbf{a}_{3}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\mathbf{a}_{3},\mathbf{x})\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{a}_{2},\mathbf{a}_{3},\mathbf{x}')=-6g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}').\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Hints:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These properties are straightforward to derive using a tensor decomposition
 of the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in an orthonormal basis.
 As a last resort, one could rewrite all expressions in the index notation,
 but this is not necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Partial proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first derive the two substitution properties.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{x},$
\end_inset

 we decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{j}x_{j}\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 in an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 1}

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{a}=\sum_{j}g(\mathbf{e}_{j},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{e}_{j}=\sum_{j}x_{j}\mathbf{e}_{j}=\mathbf{x}.\]

\end_inset

For an arbitrary tensor-valued multilinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $A(...)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y},...)=A(g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y},...)$
\end_inset

.
 Since we already derived the desired property for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $A(...)$
\end_inset

 is linear in its arguments, it follows that the the same trace property
 holds also for 
\begin_inset Formula $A(...)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now derive the symmetry properties.
 Due to the substitution property, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\hat{P}_{1}\hat{P}_{2}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})=\mbox{Tr}_{\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}}g(\hat{P}_{1}\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a})g(\hat{P}_{2}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

The last expression is obviously symmetric with respect to exchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The second symmetry property follows directly from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us compute the trace of the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}\mathbf{x}\equiv\mathbf{x}-2\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a given unit vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we define the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv g(\hat{P}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

; then we compute its trace with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr }\hat{P} & \equiv\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}P(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{x}}\left[g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})-2g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})\right]\\
 & =4-2g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=2.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Practice-problem:trace-of-C}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 in four-dimensional space, compute the trace
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},C(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u})\mathbf{u}),\]

\end_inset

where the transformation-valued 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}\equiv g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\mathbf{x}-g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})\mathbf{y}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Answer: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $3g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Solution:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})\mathbf{a})-g(\mathbf{a},g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u}),\mathbf{u}) & =\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u})g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{u})\\
 & =\left(4-1\right)g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=3g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u}).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Derivatives of mute vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tensor under the trace 
\emph on
may
\emph default
 contain derivatives of mute vectors,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{mute vectors}

\end_inset

 as long as these derivatives can be moved out of the expression or when
 the derivatives ultimately cancel out.
 In other words, the expression under the trace should be a 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 
\emph on
function
\emph default
 of the mute vectors, not really involving their derivatives.
 Otherwise, the trace expression is 
\emph on
undefined
\emph default
 (meaningless).
 For instance, the expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a}])$
\end_inset

 are, strictly speaking, meaningless because the result of a calculation
 according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 2}

\end_inset

) depends on the derivatives of the basis vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 However, such meaningless expressions can occur neither by transforming
 well-defined index-free expressions nor through rewriting well-defined
 indexed expressions with traces.
 Only well-defined trace expressions can be obtained in practice.
 For instance, the following expressions containing derivatives of mute
 vectors are well-defined,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{y}) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{y})=\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{y});\\
\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x}-\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x}\right) & \equiv\square\mathbf{x}\equiv g^{\mu\nu}\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}\mathbf{x}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 The last line is the D'Alembert operator acting on a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The trace is well-defined because the expression under the trace is actually
 independent of the derivatives of the mute vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computations with expressions of this kind can be simplified using the following
 trick.
 It is always possible to choose basis vector fields so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{j}}\mathbf{e}_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

 at 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 point in spacetime.
 Hence, when computing a 
\emph on
well-defined
\emph default
 trace expression containing derivatives, one could simply assume that all
 the mute vectors are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant vectors,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that their (covariant) derivatives in any direction are all
 equal to zero.
 This assumption is also consistent with the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\cdot}g=0$
\end_inset

 and a decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric decomp 1}

\end_inset

) of the metric through a basis that enters the trace via Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:trace decomp 1}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this book I will use the simplifying convention that covariant derivatives
 of mute vectors are always equal to zero.
 For instance, the D'Alembert operator can then be written more intuitively
 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square\mathbf{x}=\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary of calculation rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formalism of coordinate-free, index-free calculations is sufficiently
 powerful to handle all situations involving vector fields and 1-forms,
 the metric, and covariant derivatives.
 (However, the index-free notation becomes cumbersome when one needs to
 manipulate tensors of higher rank.) In comparison with the index notation,
 this formalism is more transparent, emphasizes the geometric content of
 a calculation, and frequently helps to guess the necessary sequence of
 manipulations that lead to a desired result.
 I summarize the rules of index-free, coordinate-free calculations for convenien
ce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vector fields are denoted by boldface letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 etc., while scalar functions are denoted by ordinary letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,f$
\end_inset

, etc.
 It is sometimes convenient to use Greek letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\lambda,\mu$
\end_inset

 for scalar functions.
 In blackboard calculations, vectors may be underlined or even simply left
 unmarked if it does not create confusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic operations of tensor calculus are tensor product, tensor contraction,
 and the various derivative operations.
 Explicit tensor products are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\otimes\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and seem to be seldom needed.
 Tensor contraction is written as an application of a function to a vector,
 for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a metric, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 creates a correspondence between vectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms; this correspondence and its inverse are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three basic derivative operations: the Lie derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (the application of a vector field to a scalar field is a particular case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\lambda$
\end_inset

 ); the exterior differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-forms are understood as scalar functions); and the Levi-Civita covariant
 derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the direction given by a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 are tensors of the same rank as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-form if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In calculations, it is usually more convenient to use 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 with vectors but 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operations 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 are linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\series bold
local
\series default
 (depend only on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 at a point but not on its derivatives):
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right)=\lambda\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right),\quad\nabla_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right)=\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right).\]

\end_inset

However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is not local in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right)\neq\lambda\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\left(...\right).\]

\end_inset

The precise expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}A$
\end_inset

 depends on the rank of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The Leibnitz rule with respect to tensor products holds for the derivative
 operations, with the exception of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 which needs an extra sign:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right) & =\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\eta\right)\wedge\theta+\eta\wedge\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\theta,\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right) & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\eta\right)\wedge\theta+\eta\wedge\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\theta,\\
\textrm{d}\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right) & =\left(\textrm{d}\eta\right)\wedge\theta+\left(-1\right)^{\left|\eta\right|}\eta\wedge\textrm{d}\theta,\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|$
\end_inset

 in the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1\right)^{\left|\eta\right|}$
\end_inset

 means the rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

.
 Also
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\left(\eta\wedge\theta\right)=\left(\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\eta\right)\wedge\theta+\left(-1\right)^{\left|\eta\right|}\eta\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\theta.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some further rules for calculations are the following (here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 are vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the metric tensor).
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\circ\lambda & \equiv\mathbf{a}\circ\left(\mathbf{b}\circ\lambda\right)-\mathbf{b}\circ\left(\mathbf{a}\circ\lambda\right),\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b} & =\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]=\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{a}=-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{a},\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\lambda & =\mathbf{a}\circ\lambda\equiv\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\circ\mathbf{a}\equiv\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\textrm{d}\lambda=\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\lambda,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\lambda & =\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\lambda,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g & =0,\\
\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}\right)\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =\mathbf{a}\circ\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}\circ\mathbf{b}\right)-\mathbf{b}\circ\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}\circ\mathbf{a}\right)-\boldsymbol{\theta}\circ[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}],\\
\left(\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\omega\right)\circ(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...) & \equiv\omega\circ\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...\right);\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}\omega & =\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\omega+\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\textrm{d}\omega,\\
\textrm{dd}\omega & \equiv0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\equiv$
\end_inset

 refers to properties that hold directly by definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When an expression involves arbitrary vectors and is a local function of
 these vectors, it is often convenient to choose these vectors so that their
 (
\emph on
first
\emph default
) derivatives vanish.
 (Second derivatives cannot be constrained to vanish simultaneously with
 the first derivatives.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g=0$
\end_inset

 and the Leibnitz rule is the identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\hat{g}^{-1}\omega=\hat{g}^{-1}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\omega\]

\end_inset

for a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

 on scalars leads to useful simplifications in some calculations with the
 metric.
 For instance,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{a}\circ g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c});\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}) & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})+g(\mathbf{b},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{c}),\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}) & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{a}}g\right)\circ(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})+g([\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}],\mathbf{c})+g(\mathbf{b},[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c}]).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Depending on the particular calculation, one of these equivalent forms may
 be used to proceed.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rules for index-free calculations with traces are listed in Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:trace-properties}

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, one may use the simplifying convention that all (
\emph on
first
\emph default
) covariant derivatives of mute vectors vanish.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is another example of an index-free calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-variation-of-divergence-conformal}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-variation-of-divergence-conformal}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda}g$
\end_inset

 be two metrics related by a conformal transformation.
 For a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, we can then compute two different divergences 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\textrm{div}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 These divergences are related by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\textrm{div}}\mathbf{u}=\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}+N\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the manifold.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
(Details 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-variation-of-divergence-conformal}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-variation-of-divergence-conformal}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-variation-of-divergence-conformal}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest proof is through the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as the coefficient in the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)\boldsymbol{\varepsilon},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the Levi-Civita tensor corresponding to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The Levi-Civita tensor is defined as the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-form with the property 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{N})=1,\]

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 When the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\lambda}$
\end_inset

, each vector in the orthonormal basis is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the Levi-Civita tensor is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{N\lambda}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}=e^{N\lambda}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}.\]

\end_inset

Then we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}} & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}e^{N\lambda}\right)\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}+e^{N\lambda}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\left(N\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}+\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}\\
 & =\left(\tilde{\textrm{div}}\mathbf{u}\right)\tilde{\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us perform another, slightly longer computation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\textrm{div}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 using the formula involving the trace.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 the Levi-Civita connection for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse metric is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}^{-1}=e^{-2\lambda}g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We will use the formula for the divergence through the trace, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\textrm{div}}\mathbf{u}=\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}\otimes\mathbf{a}=\tilde{g}^{-1}}\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a})=e^{-2\lambda}\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a}).\]

\end_inset

Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:nabla after conformal}

\end_inset

), we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
e^{-2\lambda}\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a}) & =\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\\
+\textrm{Tr}_{\mathbf{a}}\left[\left(\mathbf{a}\circ\lambda\right)g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a})\right. & \left.+\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})-\left(\mathbf{a}\circ\lambda\right)g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a})\right]\\
=\textrm{div}\mathbf{u} & +N\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Curvature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A motivation for introducing the concept of curvature is to describe in
 detail the deviation of the geometry of a manifold near each point from
 the flat geometry.
 A direct description of this deviation can be given using the concept of
 parallel transport (see also Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Parallel-transport-of}

\end_inset

).
 In Appendix\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:Elements-of-Special}

\end_inset

 a formula is derived for the parallel transport of a vector along an infinitesi
mally small closed curve, and thus the connection to the curvature tensor
 is made explicit (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:-Expressing-Riemann}

\end_inset

).
 In this approach, the curvature tensor is the object describing the transformat
ion of vectors under parallel transport along infinitesimally small closed
 curves.
 However, calculations in this approach require using a local coordinate
 system because otherwise the parallel transport operation cannot be described
 explicitly.
 Presently, I introduce the curvature tensor by a different formula that
 can be directly used in index-free and coordinate-free calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Curvature of a connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
curvature
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{curvature}

\end_inset


\series bold
of a connection
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is a transformation-valued 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

) is known as the Ricci identity; it is convenient to regard it as the definitio
n of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}=\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{u}},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\right]\mathbf{w}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\mathbf{w}.\label{eq:R2 def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

At first glance, it may appear that the right-hand side of the expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

) contains derivatives of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this is not so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-is-form}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Riemann-is-form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

) does not depend on the derivatives of the vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is indeed a transformation-valued 2-form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-is-form}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that no derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 remain in 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

; to that end, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\lambda\mathbf{w}=\lambda R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary scalar function.
 This is obtained by a direct computation:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\lambda\mathbf{w} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}+\left(\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda\right)\mathbf{w}\right)\\
 & =\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}+\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}\\
 & +(\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda\right))\mathbf{w}+(\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda)\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w};\\
\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\lambda\mathbf{w} & =\lambda\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\mathbf{w}+([\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]\circ\lambda)\mathbf{w};\end{align*}

\end_inset

now it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\lambda\mathbf{w}-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\lambda\mathbf{w}=\lambda R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}+\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\lambda\mathbf{w}.\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 is a linear function also of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
does not involve derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

) by computing 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\lambda\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

.
 We use Calculation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Lie-derivative-of-lambdav}

\end_inset

 to express 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\lambda\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

, and obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\lambda\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}\right)=\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}+\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w};\\
\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\lambda\mathbf{v}]}\mathbf{w} & =\nabla_{\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\mathbf{v}+\lambda\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]}\mathbf{w}=\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\lambda\right)\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}+\lambda\nabla_{\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]}\mathbf{w};\\
R(\mathbf{u},\lambda\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w} & =\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}-\lambda\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}-\lambda\nabla_{\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]}\mathbf{w}=\lambda R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The analogous property for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 follows from the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index notation for the curvature tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta\mu}{}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

, can be defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}\right)^{\nu}\equiv x^{\alpha}y^{\beta}z^{\mu}R_{\alpha\beta\mu}{}^{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

We can also define a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 of rank (0,4) by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lowering the index,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})\equiv g(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})\equiv R_{\alpha\beta\mu\nu}a^{\alpha}b^{\beta}c^{\mu}d^{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

Either of these equivalent tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, when evaluated using the Levi-Civita connection, is called the 
\series bold
Riemann tensor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Riemann tensor}

\end_inset

of the manifold.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
We are using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-+-\right)$
\end_inset

 sign convention, according to the classification in Misner-Thorne-Wheeler\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{MTW73}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bianchi identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section I review and derive the standard properties of the Riemann
 tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The antisymmetry property,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})=-R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}),\label{eq:R antisymmetry 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset

follows immediately from the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

).
 Additionally, the curvature tensor corresponding to the Levi-Civita connection
 has the following symmetry properties:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}) & =-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d},\mathbf{c}),\label{eq:R antisymmetry}\\
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}) & +R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{d})+R(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d})=0.\label{eq:Bianchi 1}\\
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}) & =R(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}).\label{eq:transposition R}\end{align}

\end_inset

 The property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
first Bianchi identity
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Bianchi identity!first}

\end_inset

These properties hold 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 for the Levi-Civita connection; we always work with that connection here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remarks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, one simply says 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Riemann tensor of the manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of the more precise but cumbersome phrase 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Riemann tensor of the Levi-Civita connection corresponding to the given
 metric on the manifold.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The Riemann tensor is a function of the metric that involves second derivatives
 of the metric (see Calculation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Riemann-conformal}

\end_inset

 below).
 It is easier to remember the symmetries\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R antisymmetry 0}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:transposition R}

\end_inset

) of the Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 if one thinks of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c})g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d})-g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{d})g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

.
 This expression (as will be shown below) is actually equal the Riemann
 tensor of a unit sphere in Euclidean space, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the induced metric on the sphere.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the symmetry properties, the Riemann tensor has 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{12}n^{2}(n^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

 independent scalar components for an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold.
 This fact, which does not seem to have direct applications in General Relativit
y, nevertheless enjoys a mention (usually without a clear derivation) in
 many GR textbooks.
 Here I follow the venerable tradition.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show in a series of statements that: the property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) is a consequence of torsion-freeness and the compatibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 with the metric; the property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

) is a consequence of torsion-freeness and the Jacobi identity for commutators
 of vectors; and Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:transposition R}

\end_inset

) is a purely algebraic consequence of Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R antisymmetry}

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-1}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Riemann-1}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann tensor has the property 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary vectors.
 The identity\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) then follows due to linearity of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\cdot,\cdot,\cdot,\cdot)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Idea of proof: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transform the torsion-freeness condition 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}-\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\right)\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\]

\end_inset

using the metricity condition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:compatibility with the metric}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-1}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=2g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})+2g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}]g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=2g([\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}]\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

Further, we rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 and find 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=2g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}) & =g(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\\
 & =g([\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}]\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})-g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left([\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}]-\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\right)g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 The identity 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})+R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d},\mathbf{c})=0$
\end_inset

 follows by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{c}+\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Simplifying assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation in the preceding proof can be made shorter by assuming that
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 commute, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, and that the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 in directions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 vanish.
 This can be assumed without loss of generality because 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 does not depend on derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, but only on values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 at a point, and thus these derivatives (such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

) can be set to zero.
 (We can always find any finite number of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},...$
\end_inset

 in the neighborhood of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}(p),\mathbf{b}(p),\mathbf{c}(p),...$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are prescribed and all first derivatives, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

; but second derivatives, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, will in general not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is the abbreviated calculation.
 Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x}=\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{x}=\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right]g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\\
 & =2g(\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right]\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=2R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Below we will often use the assumption of vanishing first derivatives to
 simplify calculations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-2}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Riemann-2}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

) follows by rewriting the Jacobi identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{a},\left[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right]\right]+\left[\mathbf{b},\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a}\right]\right]+\left[\mathbf{c},\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\right]=0\]

\end_inset

 using covariant derivatives and the torsion-free condition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie through nabla}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-2}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{a},\left[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right]\right] & =\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\left[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right]-\nabla_{[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}]}\mathbf{a}\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{c}-\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{b}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}]}\mathbf{a},\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly for the other terms.
 Then we write the Jacobi identity and rearrange the resulting expression:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{a},\left[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right]\right]+\left[\mathbf{b},\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a}\right]\right]+\left[\mathbf{c},\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\right] & =\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{c}-\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{b}+\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{a}\\
-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{c}+\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}-\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{a} & -\nabla_{[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}]}\mathbf{a}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a}]}\mathbf{b}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{c}\\
=R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{c}+R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})\mathbf{a}+R(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph

\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-3}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Riemann-3}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any tensor of rank (0,4) satisfying the transposition properties\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

) will also satisfy Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:transposition R}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-3}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For brevity, we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{abcd}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 within this calculation.
 First, we use the transposition properties to move the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $c,d$
\end_inset

 to the left:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\underline{abcd}+\underline{bcad}+\underline{cabd}=\\
 & =\underline{abcd}+\underline{bcad}+(-\underline{cadb})\\
 & =\underline{abcd}+\underline{bcad}+(\underline{adcb}+\underline{dcab}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

which means that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{abcd}-\underline{cdab}=-(\underline{bcad}-\underline{adbc}).\]

\end_inset

This last property can be now used repeatedly on different indices:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
-(\underline{bcad}-\underline{adbc}) & =+(\underline{cabd}-\underline{bdac}),\\
+(\underline{cabd}-\underline{bdac}) & =-(\underline{abcd}-\underline{cdab}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{abcd}-\underline{cdab}=-(\underline{abcd}-\underline{cdab})=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann tensor also satisfies the 
\series bold
second Bianchi identity
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Bianchi identity!second}

\end_inset

written in index notation as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\kappa}R_{\lambda\mu\nu\rho}+\nabla_{\lambda}R_{\mu\kappa\nu\rho}+\nabla_{\mu}R_{\kappa\lambda\nu\rho}=0.\label{eq:Bianchi 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is somewhat cumbersome to write this identity using the index-free notation
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 because only 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is to be differentiated and not the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

, which is not easy to indicate without using indices.
 The property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 2}

\end_inset

) has important consequences for GR.
