\begin_layout Standard
Let us now derive the Bianchi identity for the transformation-valued tensor
 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

).
 We need to convert the index expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 2}

\end_inset

) into an index-free form.
 So we introduce arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and consider the expression
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
c^{\kappa}a^{\lambda}b^{\mu}v^{\nu}\nabla_{\kappa}R_{\lambda\mu\nu\rho} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\big(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}\big)-R(\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}\\
 & -R(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

(The subtractions are needed to make sure that only 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is differentiated.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-4}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Riemann-4}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The identity\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 2}

\end_inset

) holds, due to the vanishing of the sum of the twelve terms obtained via
 cyclic permutations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 in the above formula.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Riemann-4}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start the derivation by writing the 
\series bold
Jacobi identity
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Jacobi identity}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\left[A,B\right],C\right]+\left[\left[B,C\right],A\right]+\left[\left[C,A\right],B\right]=0.\]

\end_inset

This is a purely algebraic relation that holds for arbitrary operations
 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 in any context (as long as the composition of operations is associative).
 We now apply the Jacobi identity to the operations 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, and also use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, to derive the following identities,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right],\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\right]\mathbf{v}+\left[\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{b}},\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\right],\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\right]\mathbf{v}+\left[\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{c}},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\right],\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right]\mathbf{v} & =0,\\
\nabla_{\left[\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right],\mathbf{c}\right]}\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\left[\left[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right],\mathbf{a}\right]}\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\left[\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{a}\right],\mathbf{b}\right]}\mathbf{v} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The Bianchi identity will follow if we subtract the first of these relations
 from the second and express various terms through 
\begin_inset Formula $R()$
\end_inset

 using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

).
 For instance,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
-\left[\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{a}},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\right],\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\right]\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\left[\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right],\mathbf{c}\right]}\mathbf{v} & =-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}\\
-\nabla_{[\mathbf{a,}\mathbf{b}]}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v} & +\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}]}\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\left[\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right],\mathbf{c}\right]}\mathbf{v}\\
=\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\big(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}\big)-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v} & -R([\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}],\mathbf{c})\mathbf{v}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Adding up the cyclic permutations of the last expression in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

 and using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie through nabla}

\end_inset

) and the obvious property 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{v}=-R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a})\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we find all the terms required for the Bianchi identity.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ricci tensor and scalar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Ricci tensor
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Ricci tensor}

\end_inset

is the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 defined as the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

The Ricci tensor is a symmetric bilinear form due to the property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:transposition R}

\end_inset

).
 In the index notation, this contraction of the Riemann tensor is written
 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}=R_{\mu\alpha\nu\beta}g^{\alpha\beta}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Ricci scalar
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Ricci scalar}

\end_inset

is the trace of the Ricci tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
R\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv g^{\mu\nu}R_{\mu\nu}.\]

\end_inset

 It is sometimes more convenient to use the index notation for calculations
 with the Riemann and Ricci tensors.
 The following examples illustrate the typical calculations.
 We will use both the index and the index-free notations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Einstein equation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein equation}

\end_inset

relates the Ricci tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 to the energy-momentum tensor of matter, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R=-8\pi GT_{\mu\nu},\label{eq:Einstein}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is Newton's constant.
 According to this equation, curvature of the spacetime is related to the
 energy density, velocity, and pressure of matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-T-conserved}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-T-conserved}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from the Einstein equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Einstein}

\end_inset

) and the second Bianchi identity that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is always
\series bold
 covariantly conserved
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{energy-momentum tensor!covariant conservation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{\mu}T_{\mu\nu}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-T-conserved}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contracting Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 2}

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\kappa\nu}g^{\mu\rho}$
\end_inset

, we can easily show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{\mu}(R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R)=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a four-dimensional spacetime with a known metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following relationship for a symmetric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, similar to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Einstein}

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\mu\nu}+ag_{\mu\nu}A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}=S_{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a given constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is a given symmetric tensor, and the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}\equiv A_{\mu\nu}g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to obtain an explicit expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index-free notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric bilinear form satisfying
\begin_inset Formula \[
A+ag\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=S,\]

\end_inset

or more explicitly
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+ag(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=S(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

The unknown tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 would be readily found from this equation if we knew its trace.
 So let us compute the trace of both parts with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)$
\end_inset

; since the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is 4, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+4a\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}S(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\frac{1}{1+4a}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}S(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}),\]

\end_inset

and therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=S-\frac{a}{1+4a}g.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index notation, the calculation looks as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
S_{\mu\nu}g^{\mu\nu} & =\left(A_{\mu\nu}+ag_{\mu\nu}A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}\right)g^{\mu\nu}=A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}+ag_{\mu\nu}g^{\mu\nu}A_{\alpha}^{\alpha}\\
 & =\left(1+4a\right)A_{\alpha}^{\alpha},\end{align*}

\end_inset

therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\mu\nu}=S_{\mu\nu}-\frac{a}{1+4a}g_{\mu\nu}S_{\lambda}^{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset

 Note that there may be 
\emph on
no solutions
\emph default
, or at any rate no unique expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $a=-\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Einstein-Cartan theory 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein-Cartan theory}

\end_inset

(which is a modification of GR), the torsion 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{torsion}

\end_inset

tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is related to the spin density tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 of matter by the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}+\delta_{\mu}^{\lambda}T_{\nu\rho}^{\rho}-\delta_{\nu}^{\lambda}T_{\mu\rho}^{\rho}=8\pi GS_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset

 Consider a more general relationship,
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}+a\left(\delta_{\mu}^{\lambda}A_{\nu\rho}^{\rho}-\delta_{\nu}^{\lambda}A_{\mu\rho}^{\rho}\right)=S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a given constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a given tensor (both 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are antisymmetric in the lower indices).
 Obtain an explicit expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Hint: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute a suitable trace of the left-hand side of the given equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Answer: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq-\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, the solution is
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}=S_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}-\frac{a}{1+3a}\left(\delta_{\mu}^{\lambda}S_{\nu\rho}^{\rho}-\delta_{\nu}^{\lambda}S_{\mu\rho}^{\rho}\right).\]

\end_inset

 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

