\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the new affine tangent vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{n}}=\phi\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is an unknown function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:nabla after conformal}

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

 that, for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\tilde{g}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\phi\mathbf{n}}\left(\phi\mathbf{n}\right),\mathbf{x}) & =2\phi^{2}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda\right)\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})+\tilde{g}(\nabla_{\phi\mathbf{n}}(\phi\mathbf{n}),\mathbf{x})\\
 & =\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})\phi^{2}\left(2\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda+\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\ln\phi\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

This will vanish if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=e^{-2\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The new affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


