\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
proper length
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{proper length}

\end_inset

of a curve segment 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L[\gamma]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}d\tau.\label{eq:Length functional}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The proper length is 
\emph on
extremized
\emph default
 (but not necessarily maximized or minimized) if the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\gamma]$
\end_inset

 does not change in first order in the perturbation when the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is infinitesimally perturbed while the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 remain fixed.
 We now apply the standard considerations of the variational calculus to
 this condition and derive the corresponding differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A perturbation of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 can be described as the flow of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 which, we imagine, is directed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transversely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and leaves the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

) in place.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 a parameter along the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, starting from the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 transforms the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 into a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\tau;\sigma)$
\end_inset

 when we let the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 carry the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 for a parameter distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 the vector field obtained by taking tangent vectors to various curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 transported the initial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 by various distances 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 along the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{v}=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The proper length of a perturbed curve can now be seen as a function of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\tilde{\gamma};\sigma]=\int_{\tilde{\gamma}}\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}d\tau,\]

\end_inset

where the integration is performed along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}(\tau;\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the variational principle, the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will extremize the proper length if 
\begin_inset Formula $dL/d\sigma=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0$
\end_inset

.
 The operation 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d\sigma$
\end_inset

 corresponds to applying (under the integral sign) a derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}$
\end_inset

 along the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\sigma}L[\tilde{\gamma};\sigma]=\int_{\tilde{\gamma}}\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}d\tau=\int_{\tilde{\gamma}}\frac{g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}d\tau.\]

\end_inset

Here we have used the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{v}=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The last expression above does not contain derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and is evaluated on the initial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\frac{d}{d\sigma}L[\tilde{\gamma};\sigma]\right|_{\sigma=0}=\int_{\gamma}\frac{g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}d\tau.\label{eq:geodesic pre deriv}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 extremizes the proper length if the above integral vanishes for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic pre deriv}

\end_inset

) contains an undesirable derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 To eliminate that derivative, we now perform the usual trick consisting
 of integration by parts.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 acts as a total derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{d\tau}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}=0$
\end_inset

 at both endpoints of the curve, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\gamma}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{t},\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}})d\tau=0.\]

\end_inset

Subtracting this from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic pre deriv}

\end_inset

), we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\frac{d}{d\sigma}L[\tilde{\gamma};\sigma]\right|_{\sigma=0}=-\int_{\gamma}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}})d\tau.\]

\end_inset

This can vanish for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 only if 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}\right|_{\gamma(\tau)}=\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\frac{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}{\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}}=0.\]

\end_inset

 This is almost the geodesic equation, except for the normalization of the
 tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

.
 We now need to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is not null.
 Then a redefinition of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\rightarrow f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be used to set 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=\mbox{const}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Since an arbitrary change of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'=f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 does not change the proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\gamma]$
\end_inset

, we may choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to normalize the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, where the constant may be either 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 or zero, depending on the causal character of the curve.
 At the moment, we only consider segments of the curve that have the same
 causal character, and also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

 (the case of null curves will be considered below).
 Similarly, the perturbed curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 can be normalized in the same way, so that the flow of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 does not perturb the normalization and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.
 We can then drop the constant factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})-g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

an integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 removes the total derivative term 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})\equiv\frac{d}{d\tau}g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

 because by assumption the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at the endpoints.
 The remaining term yields the condition
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})d\tau=0.\]

\end_inset

 Since this condition should be satisfied for any vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\end_inset

we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

, which is precisely the geodesic equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Geodesic equation}

\end_inset

).
 Note that the resulting geodesic equation is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 invariant under arbitrary changes of parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\rightarrow f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 because we have already assumed a fixed normalization of the tangent vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a brief time in the above calculation, we needed to use expressions
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which require that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 be a vector field defined also away from the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 This minor inconvenience is easily remedied by supposing that the curve
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is one of the orbits of 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent vector to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can have arbitrary values away from the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 Since the final result (the geodesic equation) contains only the derivative
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are irrelevant.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

