\begin_layout Paragraph
Null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the derivation above, we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\neq0$
\end_inset

; let us now consider the case of 
\series bold
null curves
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null curve}

\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=0$
\end_inset

 along the curve.
 Such null geodesics 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 be obtained by extremizing the functional\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Length functional}

\end_inset

), because a variation (even an infinitesimal one) of a null curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 will make some portions of the curve spacelike and other portions timelike,
 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}$
\end_inset

 will not remain well-defined.
 To avoid this difficulty, one can simply postulate Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Geodesic equation}

\end_inset

) for null geodesics.
 Alternatively, a different variational principle can be used to derive
 the geodesic equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Geodesic equation}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the variational problem with the functional
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L[\gamma(\tau);N(\tau)]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\frac{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}{N(\tau)}d\tau,\label{eq:functional for null}\end{equation}

\end_inset

depending on an additional unknown function 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the functional does not contain derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, this variable plays the role of a Lagrange multiplier.
 The variation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

 yields the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=0$
\end_inset

, while the variation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 yields the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
N\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=-\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}N\right)\mathbf{v}+\frac{1}{2}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}N.\]

\end_inset

Using the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

 and choosing a function 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that is constant along the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, one recovers the geodesic equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Geodesic equation}

\end_inset

).
 When the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is chosen arbitrarily, one obtains the same geodesic curve in a non-affine
 parameterization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variational principle of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:functional for null}

\end_inset

) can be generalized to the case of timelike or spacelike geodesics in the
 following way.
 One writes the functional
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\gamma(\tau);N(\tau)]\equiv\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left[\frac{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}{N}+KN\right]d\tau,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a Lagrange multiplier.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a function only of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}N=0$
\end_inset

 for a transverse perturbation field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 (orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 connect points at equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.) Variation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\tau)$
\end_inset

 yields the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=KN^{2}$
\end_inset

, while variation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 yields the non-affine geodesic equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\frac{\dot{\gamma}}{N}=0.\]

\end_inset

 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 can be chosen freely to control the causal character of the curve.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is never in the denominator, while 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 can be chosen freely, the value 
\begin_inset Formula $K=0$
\end_inset

 is perfectly admissible.
 In this way, geodesics of every kind are described through a single variational
 principle.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Motion under external forces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In classical physics, equations of motion for particles and fields are derived
 from an 
\series bold
action principle
\series default
:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{action principle}

\end_inset

 The correct trajectories must extremize a certain functional called the
 
\series bold
action functional
\series default
.
 As an example, we now derive the equations of motion for a charged massive
 particle in the presence of an external electromagnetic field in curved
 spacetime.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
I called the electromagnetic field 
\series bold
external 
\series default
to emphasize that this field is assumed to be given and fixed, rather than
 determined dynamically.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motion of a massive particle corresponds to a timelike worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 in spacetime.
 The electromagnetic field is described by a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

, and the gravitational field by the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that these fields are fixed, and the question is to determine
 the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 of the particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action functional for the particle is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\gamma;\boldsymbol{A},g]=-m\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\sqrt{g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})}d\tau+q\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\boldsymbol{A}\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)d\tau,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the rest mass and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the electric charge of the particle.
 The first term in the action is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times the proper time along the trajectory, while the second term is simply
 the integral of the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 along the worldline, which may be written more concisely as 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 (see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:integral of 1-form over a curve}

\end_inset

) and the preceding explanations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion for the particle are derived by extremizing the
 functional 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with respect to the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Although the actual computation is fairly short, I will go through it slowly
 and show every step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Derivation of geodesic equation}

\end_inset

, we introduce a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 which is transverse to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 perturbs the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 by shifting it to the side.
 Then we construct the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 by shifting the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 by different parameter distances 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The variation of the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is found by applying the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}$
\end_inset

 under the integral,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{d\sigma}S[\gamma;\boldsymbol{A},g]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\left(-m\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}+q\boldsymbol{A}\circ\mathbf{v}\right)d\tau.\label{eq:variation S A g}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The terms under the integral are simplified using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 and the Leibnitz property of the Lie derivative.
 The first term yields
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})} & =\frac{\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}g\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right)}{2\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}\lyxbuildrel1\above=\frac{g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}\\
 & \lyxbuildrel2\above=-g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}})+\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}\end{align*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel1\above=$
\end_inset

 is via Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative of metric formula}

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel2\above=$
\end_inset

 is to separate a total derivative).
 The integral of the total derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(...)$
\end_inset

 vanishes since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the first integral term in the right-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:variation S A g}

\end_inset

) is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \[
m\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}})d\tau.\]

\end_inset

The second term in the right-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:variation S A g}

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\left(\boldsymbol{A}\circ\mathbf{v}\right)=\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{v},\]

\end_inset

and then the line integral can be transformed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\circ\mathbf{v}\,\textrm{d}\tau & \lyxbuildrel1\above=\int_{\gamma}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{t}}\boldsymbol{A}\lyxbuildrel2\above=\int_{\gamma}\left(\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{t}}\boldsymbol{A}+\iota_{\mathbf{t}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\\
 & \lyxbuildrel3\above=\int_{\gamma}\iota_{\mathbf{t}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}\lyxbuildrel4\above=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v}\right)d\tau\\
 & =-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left\{ \iota_{\mathbf{t}}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\right\} d\tau\end{align*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel1\above=$
\end_inset

 is by definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:integral of 1-form over a curve}

\end_inset

) of integrals of 1-forms over curves, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel2\above=$
\end_inset

 is by the Cartan homotopy formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan homotopy formula}

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel3\above=$
\end_inset

 is due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\gamma}\textrm{d}f=0$
\end_inset

 for a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that vanishes at the endpoints of the curve, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel4\above=$
\end_inset

 is by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{t}}$
\end_inset

).
 Putting the two terms together and evaluating the derivatives on the initial
 curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left.\frac{d}{d\sigma}S[\gamma;\boldsymbol{A},g]\right|_{\sigma=0} & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}mg(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}})d\tau\\
 & \quad-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}q\left\{ \iota_{\mathbf{t}}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}\right)\right\} d\tau.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The integrand above is linear in the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, and thus can be expressed as an auxiliary 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}$
\end_inset

 applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left.\frac{d}{d\sigma}S[\gamma;\boldsymbol{A},g]\right|_{\sigma=0} & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{t}}\boldsymbol{V}\right)d\tau=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(\boldsymbol{V}\circ\mathbf{t}\right)d\tau,\\
\boldsymbol{V} & \equiv m\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}-q\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 The action 
\begin_inset Formula $S[\gamma;\boldsymbol{A},g]$
\end_inset

 is extremized if the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dS/d\sigma=0$
\end_inset

.
 This can happen for an arbitrary field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 only if the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}$
\end_inset

 vanishes for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{V}=m\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})}}-q\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}=0.\]

\end_inset

 This is the equation of motion for a charged particle in an external electromag
netic field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may rewrite this equation in a more familiar form by choosing the parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

 and noting that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 is the electromagnetic field tensor (2-form), usually denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
m\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=q\hat{g}^{-1}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\boldsymbol{F}.\]

\end_inset

This can be recognized as a covariant form of Newton's law.
 The left-hand side is the proper acceleration times mass, and the right-hand
 side is the Lorentz force.
 In the index notation, this is written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
mv^{\alpha}v^{\mu}{}_{;\alpha}=qg^{\mu\nu}F_{\lambda\nu}v^{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset

Note that the electromagnetic force appears in the right-hand side, while
 the gravitational force is not explicitly introduced (but is implicitly
 present because of the covariant derivative in the left-hand side).
 In GR, the effects of gravitation are described not by forces but by the
 modification of the equations of motion due to the presence of covariant
 derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deviation of geodesics
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Deviation-of-geodesics}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a geodesic congruence with an affine tangent vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and an affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the proper time, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let us investigate how neighboring geodesics deviate from each other with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 It is natural to measure the deviation between neighbor geodesics using
 a connecting vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, since it would connect points corresponding to the same value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 In the reference frame of an observer whose time coordinate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the neighbor geodesic thus has the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\delta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very small.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Then the observer moving along a geodesic worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=\left.\mathbf{v}\right|_{p=\gamma(\tau)}$
\end_inset

, measures the 4-acceleration of the neighbor observer as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}=\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\mathbf{c}.\]

\end_inset

Let us compute this quantity using the properties
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c}\right]=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}-\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v}=0,\quad\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0,\quad\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\equiv\mathbf{v}(p).\]

\end_inset

We find, evaluating all the quantities at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v}=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c})\mathbf{v}+\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}\\
 & =R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c})\mathbf{v}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is called the equation of 
\series bold
geodesic deviation
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{geodesic deviation}

\end_inset

 In components, this equation can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
a^{\mu}=R_{\lambda\nu\rho}{}^{\mu}v^{\lambda}c^{\nu}v^{\rho}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation of geodesic deviation shows that the Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has a direct physical manifestation: Inertial geodesics will accelerate
 with respect to each other (exhibiting a gravitational 
\series bold
tidal effect
\series default
)
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tidal effect}

\end_inset

 iff the Riemann tensor is nonzero.
 Furthermore, the entire Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\lambda\mu\nu\rho}$
\end_inset

 can be recovered if the vector-valued quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c})\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is known for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

; this is derived in the following statement.
 Thus, all the components of the Riemann tensor at a point can be (in principle)
 measured using only (a finite number of) geodesic deviation experiments
 within an infinitesimal neighborhood of that point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-measure-Riemann}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-measure-Riemann}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann tensor at a point can be determined from a finite number of
 measurements of relative acceleration of 
\emph on
massive
\emph default
 particles in 
\emph on
their 
\emph default
proper reference frame.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through its special values of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for some future-directed, timelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and some spacelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-measure-Riemann}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Example: hypersurface of constant curvature 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 be the usual rectangular coordinates in a 
\emph on
flat
\emph default
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 with metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and let us consider the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}x_{\mu}\equiv g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=A^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a given constant.
 This hypersurface will be a sphere if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean metric, or a hyperboloid if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is pseudo-Euclidean, but for now we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has a Euclidean signature and 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 We shall show that this hypersurface is an (
\begin_inset Formula $m-1$
\end_inset

)-dimensional space of constant curvature; this will elucidate the concept
 of constant curvature.
 This result holds regardless of the signature of the metric and the sign
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}$
\end_inset

, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent bundle and induced metric
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Tangent-bundle-and}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\mu}(x)\equiv\frac{1}{A}x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is, by construction, everywhere normal to the hypersurface and normalized
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 (The normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

 holds 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 on the hypersurface, but this is sufficient for our calculations.) Vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 tangent to the hypersurface satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})=0$
\end_inset

; let us call such vectors simply 
\series bold
tangent
\series default
.
 The equivalent condition for tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{t}\circ(g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})-A^{2})=\mathbf{t}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=0\]

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 on the hypersurface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The commutator of tangent vector fields is again tangent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint:
\emph default
 Tangent vectors to a hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\circ f=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 This follows directly from the definition of the commutator: The vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]$
\end_inset

 is defined intrinsically through curves lying within the hypersurface and
 derivatives of functions along these curves.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a derivative along some curve within the hypersurface, and thus must
 be a tangent vector field.
 Here is also an explicit calculation.
 Suppose that the hypersurface is specified by an equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

; then a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is tangent if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\circ f=0$
\end_inset

.
 By definition of the commutator we have (for tangent 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]\circ f=\mathbf{x}\circ(\mathbf{y}\circ f)-\mathbf{y}\circ(\mathbf{x}\circ f)=0.\]

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us construct a self-adjoint
\series bold
 projector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{projector}

\end_inset

onto the tangent bundle of the hypersurface, that is, a self-adjoint linear
 transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere tangent for any field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that the (transformation-valued) tensor field 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 must be defined as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}-\mathbf{n}\, g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{n})\label{eq:P def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{u},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The condition of 
\series bold
self-adjoint
\series default
ness,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{projector!self-adjointness}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=g(\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y}),\label{eq:self-adjointness}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 can be motivated by the consideration that the projection of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 onto the tangent space must preserve the scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 with vectors that are already tangent, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=g(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})\quad\textrm{for all }\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}.\]

\end_inset

 This latter requirement expresses the usual geometric picture of projecting
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

straight down to the surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is modified by subtracting a multiple of the normal vector, which preserves
 scalar product.
 By exchanging 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=g(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=g(P\mathbf{y},P\mathbf{x})=g(\mathbf{y},P\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

which is the condition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:self-adjointness}

\end_inset

).
 Conversely, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:self-adjointness}

\end_inset

) with the property 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=g(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
induced metric
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{induced metric}

\end_inset

on the hypersurface is simply the same metric as in the larger space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 but restricted to tangent vectors.
 For convenience of notation, we call the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for 
\emph on
tangent
\emph default
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the hypersurface has the structure of a (pseudo-) Riemannian manifold.
 Let us now compute the curvature tensor of this manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Induced connection
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Induced-connection}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the hypersurface has a metric (the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

), we may define the corresponding Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 (also called the 
\series bold
induced connection
\series default
).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{induced connection}

\end_inset

 This connection is defined 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 for vector fields tangent to the hypersurface.
 We note that there is a natural flat connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, which is acts by the partial derivatives with respect to the Cartesian
 coordinates, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{\alpha}\equiv u^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}v^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset

We shall now see how to express the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 on the hypersurface through the existing connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 in the larger space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first motivation for deriving the induced connection is the following
 heuristic consideration.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 are tangent vector fields, we can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, but the result is not necessarily a tangent vector field.
 To make it tangent, we can project 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 onto the tangent bundle using the projection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
we define
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}\equiv P\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}.\label{eq:induced nabla P}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The result is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

induced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 that has values in the tangent bundle of the hypersurface.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is not immediately obvious that this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

projected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is indeed the Levi-Civita connection that would be defined intrinsically
 on the hypersurface, without using the already existing connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 in a larger space.
 Therefore we give a second, more rigorous motivation: The Levi-Civita connectio
n on the hypersurface is defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

) if we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, the induced metric, instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h=g$
\end_inset

 and the Levi-Civita connection for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, we obtain for arbitrary tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})=g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}).\label{eq:induced nabla def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla def}

\end_inset

) defines the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 only through its scalar product with an arbitrary tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily tangent, but Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla def}

\end_inset

) shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 must have equal scalar products with any tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 (and, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 must be tangent).
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 must be the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 onto the tangent bundle, as shown in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla P}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})\equiv0$
\end_inset

 for any tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\partial_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})=g(\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})+g(\mathbf{n},\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t})\]

\end_inset

on the hypersurface.
 Then we can rewrite the induced connection\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla P}

\end_inset

) using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:P def}

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}=\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}-\mathbf{n}g\left(\mathbf{n},\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}\right)=\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}+\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{t},\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{n})\equiv\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}+\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{t},\label{eq:induced nabla}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is the following transformation-valued 1-form,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{t}\equiv\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{t},\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{n})=\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}u^{\alpha}t^{\beta};\quad\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}\equiv n^{\lambda}\partial_{\alpha}n_{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
connection 1-form
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{connection 1-form}

\end_inset

or the 
\series bold
Christoffel symbol
\series default
.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\mu}=\frac{1}{A}x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\partial_{\alpha}n^{\beta}=\frac{1}{A}\delta_{\alpha}^{\beta},\quad\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{n}=\frac{1}{A}\mathbf{u},\quad\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{t}=\frac{1}{A}\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{t}).\label{eq:induced Gamma}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The induced connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is in the Levi-Civita connection on the hypersurface, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
for arbitrary tangent
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}h(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-h(\mathbf{y},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{z}) & =0,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}-\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{x}-\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right] & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}h(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & \equiv\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z});\\
h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z});\end{align*}

\end_inset

then we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{y},\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{z})=0$
\end_inset

 (the flat connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the flat metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

).
 Torsion-freeness follows by projecting onto the tangent bundle:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}-\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{x}=P(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}-\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{x})=P\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]=\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right],\]

\end_inset

the last equality holds since 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]$
\end_inset

 is tangent.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Self-test question:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above calculation, the connection 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is obviously a tensor since it is defined in an invariant, geometric way
 by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced Gamma}

\end_inset

).
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 plays the role of the Christoffel symbol because Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla}

\end_inset

) is written in the component notation as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\alpha}v^{\lambda}=\partial_{\alpha}v^{\lambda}+\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}v^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 It is explained in most GR textbooks that the Christoffel symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is not a tensor.
 Is there a contradiction?
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Christoffel symbol!tensor or non-tensor}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Hint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index-free approach, 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 quantity is a tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Our
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is defined using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordinate-based
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 which depends on a particular, 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 coordinate system in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, which is in the present case the natural Cartesian coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If we pass to a different coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

, say to the spherical coordinate system, the components of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 will have to be transformed according to the usual tensor law.
 The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 will not be the same in the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 One could say that the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 itself is no longer 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 in a different coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and its components also need to be transformed.
 The standard GR textbooks, on the other hand, define the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 by a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
, non-covariant formula in an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 coordinate system.
 This procedure does not define a tensor.
 So then it is no surprise that the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 do not transform as components of a tensor.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A transformation-valued tensor field 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is defined in the tangent bundle of the hypersurface by its action on tangent
 vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 in the following way,
\begin_inset Formula \[
S\mathbf{t}=h(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v}-\frac{1}{17}\mathbf{t},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the induced metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a given tangent vector field which is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla S$
\end_inset

, which should be a transformation-valued 1-form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 For arbitrary tangent vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}S)\mathbf{t} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(S\mathbf{t})-S\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(h(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v}-\frac{1}{17}\mathbf{t}\right)-h(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v}+\frac{1}{17}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}\\
 & =h(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v}+h(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\\
 & =g(\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v}+g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\left(\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}-\frac{1}{A}\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Riemann tensor within the hypersurface
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Induced-Riemann}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, let us compute the Riemann tensor of the hypersurface.
 By definition, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}=\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{x}},\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\right]\mathbf{z}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]}\mathbf{z},\]

\end_inset

and we write out the terms using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced nabla}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{z} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\left(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{z}+\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{z}+\Gamma(\mathbf{x})\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{z}+\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}+\Gamma(\mathbf{x})\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z};\nonumber \\
\nabla_{[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]}\mathbf{z} & =\partial_{[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]}\mathbf{z}+\Gamma([\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])\mathbf{z};\nonumber \\
\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{x}},\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\right]\mathbf{z} & -\nabla_{[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]}\mathbf{z}=\underline{\left[\partial_{\mathbf{x}},\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\right]\mathbf{z}-\partial_{[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]}\mathbf{z}}+\left[\Gamma(\mathbf{x}),\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\right]\mathbf{z}\nonumber \\
+ & \,\underline{\Gamma(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}-\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{x}-[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])\mathbf{z}}+(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}-(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{z}\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\Gamma(\mathbf{x}),\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\right]\mathbf{z}+(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}-(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{z}.\label{eq:Gauss-Codazzi pre}\end{align}

\end_inset

In the last line we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is a flat and torsion-free connection, in order to cancel the underlined
 terms.
 (Note the similarity of the last formula to the standard expression for
 the Riemann tensor in the component notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{....}=\partial_{.}\Gamma_{..}^{.}-\partial_{.}\Gamma_{..}^{.}+\Gamma_{..}^{.}\Gamma_{..}^{.}-\Gamma_{..}^{.}\Gamma_{..}^{.}$
\end_inset

; see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann through Gamma}

\end_inset

) in Appendix\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:Elements-of-Special}

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we substitute Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:induced Gamma}

\end_inset

) into Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi pre}

\end_inset

) and find (for tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\Gamma(\mathbf{x})\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z} & =\frac{1}{A}\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{x},\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z})=\frac{1}{A}\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n}(...))=0,\nonumber \\
(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z} & =\frac{1}{A}(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})=\frac{1}{A^{2}}\mathbf{x}g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}),\nonumber \\
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z} & =\frac{1}{A^{2}}\left(\mathbf{x}g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-\mathbf{y}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})\right),\nonumber \\
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t}) & =\frac{1}{A^{2}}\left(g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{t})g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{A^{2}}\left(h(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{t})h(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-h(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})h(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})\right),\label{eq:Riemann constant curvature}\end{align}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=h(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, the above Riemann tensor is
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}=\frac{1}{A^{2}}\left(h_{\alpha\delta}h_{\beta\gamma}-h_{\alpha\gamma}h_{\beta\delta}\right).\]

\end_inset

A manifold with a Riemann tensor of form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann constant curvature}

\end_inset

) is called a space of 
\series bold
constant curvature
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{space of constant curvature}

\end_inset

Note also that the second Bianchi identity forces 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 for a Riemann tensor of the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann constant curvature}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our result is that the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mu}x^{\mu}=A^{2}$
\end_inset

 has constant curvature.
 The actual magnitude of the curvature is 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-2}$
\end_inset

 if the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is Euclidean and 
\begin_inset Formula $-A^{-2}$
\end_inset

 if it is pseudo-Euclidean with signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--...\right)$
\end_inset

, because in the latter case the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

timelike
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is negative-definite.
 (The cases 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mu}x^{\mu}=-A^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=-1$
\end_inset

 can be treated in a very similar way and the result is essentially the
 same, with appropriate sign changes.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following two arguments help to visualize the concept of constant curvature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first argument appeals to the intuitive understanding that a sphere
 is a perfectly symmetrically curved surface that has a constant curvature
 at all points.
 The above calculation of the Riemann tensor obviously holds for a sphere
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}=R^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the usual Euclidean space.
 It makes intuitive sense to say that a sphere of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has a constant curvature equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/R$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, any space with a Riemann tensor\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann constant curvature}

\end_inset

) is a space of constant curvature, and the value of the curvature is equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second argument is somewhat more abstract.
 The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta\lambda\mu}=R_{\lambda\mu\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a symmetric bilinear form in the space of 2-forms, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\omega^{(1)},\omega^{(2)})=R^{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}\omega_{\alpha\beta}^{(1)}\omega_{\gamma\delta}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, or as a linear transformation in the space of 2-forms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha\beta}\rightarrow R_{\alpha\beta}{}^{\lambda\mu}\omega_{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\alpha\beta}=-\omega_{\beta\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary 2-form.
 The space of 2-forms is six-dimensional, and the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\omega^{(1)},\omega^{(2)})$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a symmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Due to this symmetry, the corresponding transformation is diagonalizable.
 Consider the six eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}(p)$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{6}(p)$
\end_inset

 of that transformation as functions of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 on the manifold.
 These six scalar functions characterize (in some way) the magnitude of
 the curvature of the manifold at various points.
 Without a detailed analysis of the significance of the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding eigenvectors, we may heuristically expect that, for
 a manifold of 
\emph on
constant
\emph default
 curvature, all the six eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 should be equal to each other and remain constant throughout the manifold.
 Thus the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta}{}^{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

 must be proportional to the identity map in the space of 2-forms,
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\alpha\beta}{}^{\lambda\mu}=\left(\delta_{\alpha}^{\mu}\delta_{\beta}^{\lambda}-\delta_{\alpha}^{\lambda}\delta_{\beta}^{\mu}\right)K,\quad K=\textrm{const}.\]

\end_inset

(The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 must be constant also by the second Bianchi identity, once we assume that
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta}{}^{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

 has the form given above.) Then the comparison with the sphere shows that
 the numeric value of the curvature is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a surface embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, specified by an equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a given scalar function and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Obtain the normal vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and the flat metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and the Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution: 
\emph default
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 normal to the hypersurface is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}=\frac{1}{N}\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}f),\quad N\equiv\sqrt{g^{-1}(\textrm{d}f,\textrm{d}f)}.\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})=N^{-1}\partial_{\mathbf{x}}f$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In components:
\begin_inset Formula \[
n^{\alpha}=\frac{g^{\alpha\beta}\partial_{\beta}f}{N},\quad N\equiv\sqrt{g^{\alpha\beta}\left(\partial_{\alpha}f\right)\left(\partial_{\beta}f\right)}.\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The projection onto the tangent bundle is
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

 The induced connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 projected onto the tangent bundle,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}=P\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}=\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{n},\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y})=\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}+\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{y},\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}),\]

\end_inset

which can be also written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}=\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}+\Gamma(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{y},\quad\Gamma(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{y}\equiv\mathbf{n}g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

The connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is the Levi-Civita connection on the hypersurface.
 The curvature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z} & =\left[\Gamma(\mathbf{x}),\Gamma(\mathbf{y})\right]\mathbf{z}+(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{y})\mathbf{z}-(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\Gamma)(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{z}\\
 & =g(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}-g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n};\\
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t}) & =g(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})-g(\partial_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})g(\partial_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the index notation, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
R_{\kappa\lambda\mu\nu} & =\left((\partial_{\lambda}n^{\alpha})(\partial_{\kappa}n^{\beta})-(\partial_{\kappa}n^{\alpha})(\partial_{\lambda}n^{\beta})\right)g_{\alpha\mu}g_{\beta\nu}\\
 & =\left(\partial_{\lambda}n_{\mu}\right)\left(\partial_{\kappa}n_{\nu}\right)-\left(\partial_{\kappa}n_{\mu}\right)\left(\partial_{\lambda}n_{\nu}\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is flat.
 It is clear that, in general, the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

 is not a space of constant curvature.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Geometry of null surfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this chapter, we consider a four-dimensional spacetime with a
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 having the signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\,-\right)$
\end_inset

, and the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 Most results can be straightforwardly generalized to higher dimensions,
 but it is important that the metric has indefinite signature of the kind
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--...\right)$
\end_inset

 and, as a consequence, that there exist null directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Null vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
timelike
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})>0$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
null
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null vector}

\end_inset

and 
\series bold
spacelike
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})<0$
\end_inset

.
 A geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
lightray
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 (Lightrays are worldlines of light or other radiation carried by massless
 particles.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Null vectors have somewhat peculiar properties which we now review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:-Properties-of-null-vectors}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Exercise:-Properties-of-null-vectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
a)
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is null and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is either parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, or spacelike.
 In other words: the orthogonal complement to a null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and two spacelike vectors.
 (The 
\series bold
orthogonal complement 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{orthogonal complement}

\end_inset

of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is the subspace consisting of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.)
\newline

\series bold
b) 
\series default
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is null and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is some vector such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{n})\neq0$
\end_inset

 then there exists a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\mathbf{n}+\beta\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 that is timelike, and another that is spacelike.
 
