\begin_layout Subsection
Orthogonal complement spaces
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Orthogonal-complements}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:-Properties-of-null-vectors}

\end_inset

 shows that the orthogonal complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 to a null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a three-dimensional subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and two other spacelike vectors.
 For calculations, it is convenient to have a projection operator onto this
 subspace.
 We shall now investigate the properties of such projections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with an easier case: the projection onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 null.
 Recall that a self-adjoint projector 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{projector}

\end_inset

is an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 (any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is projected onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the projection remains projected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), and the bilinear form corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=g(\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 (self-adjointness; see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tangent-bundle-and}

\end_inset

 for a motivation).
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{projector!self-adjointness of}

\end_inset

For a unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, there is a unique self-adjoint projector onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, given by the standard formula 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}).\label{eq:normal projector}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 (See also Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:P def}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:self-adjointness}

\end_inset

) in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tangent-bundle-and}

\end_inset

.) It is easy to compute the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Index-free-trace}

\end_inset

 for details),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y});\\
\textrm{Tr }P & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=4-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=4-1=3.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For calculations in a subspace, it is convenient to define a 
\series bold
partial metric
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{partial metric}

\end_inset

which coincides with the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 for vectors in the subspace but is zero on vectors orthogonal to the subspace.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is defined in the entire space but 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

can only see the subspace.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The advantage of introducing the partial metric is that one can work with
 vectors from the full space, substituting vectors from the subspace only
 at the end of calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a self-adjoint projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 onto the subspace, the partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 satisfying the above requirements can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=g(P\mathbf{a},P\mathbf{b})=g(P\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

(The last equality is due to 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

 and self-adjointness.) For a standard projector\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normal projector}

\end_inset

) to the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

, the partial metric is
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we turn to the case when the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is null.
 Then the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normal projector}

\end_inset

) fails since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{u},\mathbf{n})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 needs to subtract from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 some vector whose scalar product with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 So let us try 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{l}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 is a vector such as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

; however, this operator 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is not self-adjoint, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{T}\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x})\neq P\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, and we need to symmetrize it.
 So finally we define the map 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{projector!for null directions}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{l}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x}),\label{eq:null projector}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is now self-adjoint and that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

 yields the condition
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=g(\mathbf{l},P\mathbf{x})=g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{l}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x}))=g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

which can be satisfied for all 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset


\series default
 only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 itself is null, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the self-adjoint projector\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:null projector}

\end_inset

) is, 
\emph on
by necessity
\emph default
, also a projector onto the orthogonal complement of another null vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
 The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is therefore the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}\right)^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 of vectors orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

, which is not the entire 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 but a 
\emph on
two-dimensional
\emph default
 subspace within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is equal to 2:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr }P=4-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=4-1-1=2.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For null vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, there exists no self-adjoint projector 
\emph on
onto
\emph default
 the full subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 were such a projector, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{n}=\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By assumption the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 must be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and then the condition of self-adjointness yields a contradiction:
\begin_inset Formula \[
0\neq g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{v})=g(P\mathbf{n},\mathbf{v})=g(\mathbf{n},P\mathbf{v})=0.\]

\end_inset

In other words, we cannot project 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 while keeping the scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orthogonal complement subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 has a naturally induced metric, which is just the restriction of the full
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the induced metric is 
\emph on
degenerate
\emph default
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to every vector in the subspace.
 It is awkward to work with a degenerate metric; for instance, tensors specified
 only through their scalar products with vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 become ambiguous (defined up to multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

).
 To avoid this inconvenience, we may further restrict the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 to a two-dimensional subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}\right)^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 which is the image of a projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 The induced metric is nondegenerate on the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}\right)^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this subspace is not uniquely selected since it depends on the
 choice of a second null vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
 Despite these difficulties, we will obtain unambiguous results that are
 independent of the freedom in the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now compare the projectors for the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, where the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 are respectively timelike, null, and spacelike:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
P_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{x} & =\mathbf{x}-g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{v},\quad g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1,\quad\textrm{Tr }P_{\mathbf{v}}=3;\\
P_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{x} & =\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{l}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x}),\quad g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=1,\quad\textrm{Tr }P_{\mathbf{n}}=2;\\
P_{\mathbf{s}}\mathbf{x} & =x+g(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{s},\quad g(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{s})=-1,\quad\textrm{Tr }P_{\mathbf{s}}=3.\end{align*}

\end_inset

We find that the timelike and the spacelike cases are quite similar but
 differ from the null case.
 The partial metrics are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
h_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b});\label{eq:hv partial timelike metric}\\
h_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{b});\label{eq:hn partial null metric}\\
h_{\mathbf{s}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{b}).\nonumber \end{align}

\end_inset

We can also write the 
\series bold
partial inverse metrics
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{partial inverse metric}

\end_inset

which are (2,0)-tensors obtained from the above partial metrics by using
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

, according to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h^{-1}(\omega_{1},\omega_{2})\equiv h(\hat{g}\omega_{1},\hat{g}\omega_{2}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary 1-forms.
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
h_{\mathbf{v}}^{-1} & =g^{-1}-\mathbf{v}\otimes\mathbf{v},\\
h_{\mathbf{n}}^{-1} & =g^{-1}-\mathbf{n}\otimes\mathbf{l}-\mathbf{l}\otimes\mathbf{n},\\
h_{\mathbf{s}}^{-1} & =g^{-1}+\mathbf{s}\otimes\mathbf{s}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the partial metrics are not invertible, so we do not talk of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inverse partial metrics.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to investigate the signature the partial metrics on the
 subspaces where they are nondegenerate (the 
\series bold
partial signature
\series default
).
 The easiest way to deduce the signature is to choose a suitable basis containin
g the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

.
 For the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 we choose an orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v},\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{3}$
\end_inset

 are all spacelike.
 Then we find 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{s}_{j},\mathbf{s}_{k})=-\delta_{jk}$
\end_inset

, so the partial signature of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(---\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

, we choose a basis containing the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{l},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are spacelike and orthogonal to each other and to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we find 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{n}}(...,\mathbf{l})=h_{\mathbf{n}}(...,\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{s}_{j},\mathbf{s}_{k})=-\delta_{jk}$
\end_inset

, and therefore the partial signature of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{s}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(--\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{s}}$
\end_inset

 we choose an orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{s},\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a timelike vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{3}$
\end_inset

 are spacelike.
 Thus the partial signature of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{s}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Divergence of a null vector field
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Divergence-of-a-null}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!divergence of}

\end_inset

We have seen that there are 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 spacelike connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 within the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can visualize how the 2-volume (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
area), 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

, of the parallelogram spanned by these two vectors propagates along the
 null direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 From elementary geometric considerations, this area can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})=\left|g(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{1})g(\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{2})-g(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})g(\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{1})\right|^{1/2}.\]

\end_inset

 The change of the area along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is described by the directional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easier to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 if we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 is equal to the 4-volume spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and two unit vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we may choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to be spacelike and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 to be timelike, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y})=1=-g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 The 2-volume 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 is then interpreted as the area measured in the reference frame of an observer
 moving along the timelike direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 (Of course, the area 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 is observer-independent since it is defined regardless of the choice of
 the auxiliary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.) The 4-volume spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is expressed through the Levi-Civita symbol as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})=\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\label{eq:Area through s s x y}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is totally antisymmetric, the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a linear function of the totally antisymmetric (4,0)-tens
or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\wedge\mathbf{c}\wedge\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is the exterior (antisymmetric) product of vectors.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{exterior product of vectors}

\end_inset

 Thus, the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Area through s s x y}

\end_inset

) can be replaced by their linear combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}'$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{x}'\wedge\mathbf{y}'$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out to be convenient for the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}A$
\end_inset

 to choose the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}',\mathbf{y}'$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}'=\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}'=\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 is the null vector orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed the choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}'=\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}'=\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is possible, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{l}\wedge\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Write the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}'=\mathbf{l},\mathbf{y}'=\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 as linear combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 with unknown coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{l}=a_{1}\mathbf{x}+b_{1}\mathbf{y},\quad\mathbf{n}=a_{2}\mathbf{x}+b_{2}\mathbf{y}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=0$
\end_inset

, the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 give
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{1}^{2}=b_{1}^{2},\quad a_{2}^{2}=b_{2}^{2},\]

\end_inset

so we could choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=b_{1},a_{2}=-b_{2}$
\end_inset

 (the signs must differ, or else 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 will come out parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

).
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $1=g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=-2a_{1}a_{2}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{l}\wedge\mathbf{n}=-2a_{1}a_{2}\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the area is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}).\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are connecting vectors, the derivative of the area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 along the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is most conveniently computed by using the Lie derivative,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{dA}{d\tau} & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}A=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})\\
 & =(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})+\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

We need to retain the last term above because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not necessarily 
\emph default
a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us compute the scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{l}\equiv\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l}\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\mathbf{n},\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l}\right]) & =g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{l})-g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{l}}\mathbf{n})\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{l}}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 regardless of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
 (This is to be expected since 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}A(\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2})$
\end_inset

 are defined independently of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.) Finally, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{dA}{d\tau}=(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})A.\label{eq:dAdt divn}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is thus interpreted as the relative rate of change in the area spanned
 by the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 as this area is being transported by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Null surfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Null surfaces (3-dimensional hypersurfaces orthogonal to a null vector field)
 play a major role in relativity.
 Before considering null surfaces, we shall spend some time studying 3-dimension
al hypersurfaces is general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Three-dimensional hypersurfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A convenient way to define a 3-dimensional hypersurface is through an equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary function.
 In this way the hypersurface can be visualized as the locus of constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the hypersurface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 if the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 remains constant in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}\circ f=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\circ f$
\end_inset

 is a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, there exists a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{x}\circ f\equiv(\textrm{d}f)\circ\mathbf{x}=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}),\quad\mathbf{n}=\hat{g}^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}f\right),\label{eq:def of n}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the map from 1-forms into vectors.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
contravariant gradient
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{contravariant gradient}

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and is the normal vector to the hypersurface because it is orthogonal to
 every tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})=\mathbf{t}\circ f=0.\]

\end_inset

 Note that the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined not only on the hypersurface but in the entire space; away
 from the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=0$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is the normal vector to hypersurfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=f_{0}$
\end_inset

 for other values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below we shall almost always work with 3-dimensional hypersurfaces in 4-dimensio
nal spacetimes, and for brevity we shall call them simply 
\series bold
surfaces
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integrable vector fields
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Integrable-vector-fields}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not every vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 admits a family of hypersurfaces for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the normal vector at each point.
 This property is called 
\series bold
hypersurface orthogonality
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!hypersurface orthogonal}

\end_inset

A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal if there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to every vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 tangent to the surfaces of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})=0\;\textrm{ for any }\mathbf{t}\textrm{ such that }\mathbf{t}\circ f=0.\label{eq:hypersurface orthogonal cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general condition for hypersurface orthogonality is given by the 
\series bold
Frobenius theorem
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Frobenius theorem}

\end_inset

(see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Frobenius-theorem}

\end_inset

).
 We shall now motivate and derive a weaker condition called 
\series bold
integrability
\series default
, which is sufficient for many purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the language of classical mechanics, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
contravariant gradient
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{contravariant gradient}

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 In the language of forms, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is dual to the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}f)$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}\circ f\equiv g(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, and it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the normal vector for surfaces of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
integrable
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!integrable}

\end_inset

if there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analogous property for 1-forms is called 
\series bold
exact
\series default
ness.
 A 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
exact
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{1-form!exact}

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 for some scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then we may say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

integral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, and that a vector field is integrable when it is dual to an exact 1-form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Qualitatively, the orbits of an integrable vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are good coordinate lines.
 An immediate example of an integrable vector field is a coordinate basis
 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}\equiv\partial/\partial x^{j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the surface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{j}$
\end_inset

 and is dual to the exact 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}x^{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us produce some explicit examples of non-integrable vector fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In flat space with polar coordinates, an example of a non-integrable field
 would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\phi$
\end_inset

.
 In Cartesian coordinates, this would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=y\partial/\partial x-x\partial/\partial y$
\end_inset

 which is non-integrable because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}=y\textrm{d}x-x\textrm{d}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})=2\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}x\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is not a potential field since its orbits are closed circles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
closed
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{1-form!closed}

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{dd}=0$
\end_inset

, every exact form is closed, and 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
 (but not necessarily globally!) every closed form is exact.
 So a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is (locally) integrable if it is dual to a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 which is closed, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})=0.\]

\end_inset

 Let us now motivate this well-known condition by more intuitive considerations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are trying to find a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function could be found by integrating the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

work done by the force field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 from some initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The work corresponding to an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}\delta$
\end_inset

 in the direction of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{l})\delta=\left(\hat{g}\mathbf{v}\right)\circ\mathbf{l}\delta,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form corresponding to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 [Recall that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})\circ\mathbf{a}\equiv g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

.] So our candidate function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would be defined by integrating this 1-form along a path leading from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(p)=\int_{p_{0}}^{p}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

If the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is well-defined then we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f=\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as required.
 However, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is well-defined only if the value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 is independent of the path of integration, which is the case only if the
 integral along any closed loop 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 vanishes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint_{L}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
 By the integration theorem (a generalization of Stokes's law),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\oint_{L}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}=\int_{A}\textrm{d}(\hat{g}\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a surface enclosed by the loop 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the two-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 must be everywhere equal to zero (this follows by considering infinitesimal
 loops around each point).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now obtain a more convenient form of this condition.
 The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 acts on arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{v})\circ(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =\mathbf{a}\circ\hat{g}\mathbf{v}(\mathbf{b})-\mathbf{b}\circ\hat{g}\mathbf{v}(\mathbf{a})-\hat{g}\mathbf{v}([\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}])\\
 & =\mathbf{a}\circ g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b})-\mathbf{b}\circ g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})-g(\mathbf{v},[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}])\\
 & \equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b})-\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})-g(\mathbf{v},[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}])\\
 & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The condition we are looking for is therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})=0.\label{eq:dgv ab}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Written in the index notation using the covariant components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, this condition becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\alpha}v_{\beta}-\nabla_{\beta}v_{\alpha}=0.\]

\end_inset

This condition is reminiscent of the curl (rotation), 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, in three-dimensional vector analysis, where a vector field is a gradient
 if its curl vanishes.
 By analogy, the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
rotation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!rotation of}

\end_inset

of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to express the integrability condition is to define the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

-dependent bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B_{(\mathbf{v})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}),\label{eq:Bv def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and to require that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 bilinear form, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=B_{(\mathbf{v})}(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that in general, the rotation 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is twice the antisymmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already seen the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bk 2 def}

\end_inset

) when we introduced Killing vectors.
 For a Killing vector
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Killing vector}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, the form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
anti
\emph default
symmetric and thus equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

; for an integrable vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}=0$
\end_inset

 for an 
\emph on
integrable
\emph default
 Killing vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

; this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant everywhere.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The existence of such a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a very special property of the spacetime, indicating a high degree of
 symmetry.
 The orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are geometrically preferred coordinate lines.
 For instance, any vectors transported by the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are parallelly transported.
 If a timelike Killing vector is hypersurface orthogonal, which is a weaker
 property than integrability, the spacetime is called 
\series bold
static
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{static spacetime}

\end_inset

because in that case there is a natural 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

 and thus orthogonal to surfaces of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 A spacetime is called 
\series bold
stationary
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{stationary spacetime}

\end_inset

if it admits a timelike (but not necessarily hypersurface-orthogonal) Killing
 vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An integrable vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 which is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, is always geodesic, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Derivation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(See also the proof of the statement in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Null-functions-generate}

\end_inset

 where forms are not used.) We use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dgv ab}

\end_inset

) to apply the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega\equiv\textrm{d}(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega)\circ\mathbf{a} & \equiv(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\\
 & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

For an integrable field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that it does not follow from 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, but only that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a normalized geodesic field is not necessarily integrable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
acceleration
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!acceleration of}

\end_inset

of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

; if the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is timelike and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as the acceleration of an observer moving along a worldline
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the tangent geodesic line.
 We show that the acceleration of an integrable vector field is again integrable.
 (In this case, one recovers a limited version of the Newtonian picture,
 where the acceleration is determined as the gradient of a ``gravitational
 potential,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Newtonian-limit}

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is integrable, so 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{v})}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and for an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}) & =B_{(\mathbf{v})}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})=B_{(\mathbf{v})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v})\\
 & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

So the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 dual to the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a gradient of the scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

; this is the definition of integrability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Frobenius theorem
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Frobenius-theorem}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Frobenius theorem gives a sufficient and necessary condition for a vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to be hypersurface orthogonal.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!hypersurface orthogonal}

\end_inset

The condition is written in the language of differential forms as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0,\quad\textrm{where}\quad\omega\equiv\hat{g}\mathbf{v},\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form dual to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us motivate the formulation of the Frobenius theorem before we begin
 to prove it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hypersurface orthogonal vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere parallel to the contravariant gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}f)$
\end_inset

 of some function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 describing a family of hypersurfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 The condition of being parallel is most concisely expressed in the language
 of differential forms: Two 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So we are prompted to reformulate the condition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:hypersurface orthogonal cond}

\end_inset

) in the following way.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 the 1-form dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

; then the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal if there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}f=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is inconvenient to involve an unknown function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}f=0$
\end_inset

.
 We can try to eliminate the unknown 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 from this condition by computing
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}f)=\textrm{d}\omega\wedge\textrm{d}f=0,\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 just as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is.
 Heuristically we may say that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to an unknown 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

, so the exterior product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 must vanish, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have eliminated the unknown 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 and obtained a condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, that conveniently involves only the given 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 (equivalently, the given vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

).
 Now we shall begin the proof of the Frobenius theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
parallel
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{$n$-form!parallel to 1-form}

\end_inset

to a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\neq0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\wedge\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 The following lemma states a useful property of parallel forms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\neq0$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\theta\wedge\psi$
\end_inset

.
 (For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 this will be a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\psi\theta$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to think that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and to obtain the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 To obtain the components of a form, we can use a basis of vectors.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\neq0$
\end_inset

, we can choose a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{0},\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},...\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\circ\mathbf{v}_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\circ\mathbf{v}_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{s_{j}}\neq\mathbf{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\theta\wedge\omega\right)\circ(\mathbf{v}_{0},\mathbf{v}_{s_{1}},\mathbf{v}_{s_{2}},...) & =\theta(\mathbf{v}_{0})=\omega\circ(\mathbf{v}_{s_{1}},\mathbf{v}_{s_{2}},...)\\
 & =\omega\circ(\mathbf{v}_{s_{1}},\mathbf{v}_{s_{2}},...)=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is zero on any sets of basis vectors that does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v}_{0},\mathbf{v}_{s_{1}},\mathbf{v}_{s_{2}},...)$
\end_inset

 may be nonzero.
 So we define the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi\equiv\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{0}}\omega;\quad\psi(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},...)\equiv\omega(\mathbf{v}_{0},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},...).\]

\end_inset

 It is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\theta\wedge\psi$
\end_inset

 on any set of basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\theta\wedge\psi$
\end_inset

 on any vectors.
 Note that the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is defined up to a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, because a choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{0}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 will yield 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\circ(\mathbf{v}_{0}^{\prime}-\mathbf{v}_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi^{\prime}=\psi+\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{0}^{\prime}-\mathbf{v}_{0}}\omega=\psi+\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{0}^{\prime}-\mathbf{v}_{0}}(\theta\wedge\psi)=\psi-\theta\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{v}_{0}^{\prime}-\mathbf{v}_{0}}\psi.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An immediate corollary is: If two forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1},\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both parallel to the same 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Lemma 1, it follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\theta\wedge\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 for some 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 are both 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallel to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 some unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is one direction of the Frobenius theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to prove the converse statement, namely that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 then there exists a surface which is everywhere orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can try to construct such a surface by choosing some vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and following the orbits of all such 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 It is sufficient to choose a basis of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{1},\mathbf{t}_{2},\mathbf{t}_{3}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the orbits of these vector fields will not necessarily form a
 single surface.
 For instance, we may follow an orbit of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and then a line of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and we shall not necessarily arrive at the same point as when we are following
 first 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For infinitesimal distances, the discrepancy is in the direction of the
 commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{t}_{1},\mathbf{t}_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This direction must be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 if all the orbits are to lie within a single surface.
 Therefore, surfaces orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 will exist if for any two vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{1},\mathbf{t}_{2}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{t}_{1},\mathbf{t}_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 is again orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now see that this is indeed the case if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
This explanation needs to be made more clear and illustrated by a figure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{t})=0$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 involves the application of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 to the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]$
\end_inset

, according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

).
 This motivates us to formulate and prove the following statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 are everywhere orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, then the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right]$
\end_inset

 is also orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{x})=\omega(\mathbf{y})=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Lemma 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=\theta\wedge\omega$
\end_inset

 for some 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=(\theta\wedge\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\theta(\mathbf{x})\omega(\mathbf{y})-\theta(\mathbf{y})\omega(\mathbf{x})=0.\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

) we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\mathbf{x}\circ\omega(\mathbf{y})-\mathbf{y}\circ\omega(\mathbf{x})-\omega([\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])=-\omega([\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}]).\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega([\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from Lemma\InsetSpace ~
2 that vector fields orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 will have surface-forming orbits if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 This concludes the proof of the Frobenius theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is another useful property of hypersurface-orthogonal geodesic fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hypersurface-orthogonal, normalized, spacelike or timelike, geodesic field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is always integrable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a normalized and geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, so Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dgv ab}

\end_inset

) gives
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega)\circ\mathbf{x}\equiv(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0.\label{eq:iv dw}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We say that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
transverse
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{transverse tensor}

\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The proof can now proceed in one of two ways.
 If we consider the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega)$
\end_inset

 which vanishes since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\iota_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\wedge d\omega)=\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega\right)d\omega-\omega\wedge\left(\iota_{\mathbf{v}}d\omega\right)=\omega(\mathbf{v})d\omega.\]

\end_inset

Since the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is by assumption not null, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})\equiv g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

, and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is integrable.
 Another, more constructive way to prove the statement is the following.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface-orthogonal, there exists a family of surfaces whose normal
 vectors are everywhere parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 This family of surfaces can be described by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, and the vector field normal to the surfaces is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Since this field is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\lambda\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

 or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\lambda\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Then Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:iv dw}

\end_inset

) gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}\lambda(\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\nu-\textrm{d}\nu(\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\lambda\equiv(\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda)\textrm{d}\nu-\frac{1}{\lambda}\omega(\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\lambda.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\neq0$
\end_inset

, we can express
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\lambda=\frac{\left(\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda\right)\lambda}{\omega(\mathbf{v})}\textrm{d}\nu,\]

\end_inset

and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\textrm{d}\nu=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to see where the argument fails for 
\emph on
null
\emph default
 fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

: We cannot divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{v})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we can still find 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\lambda\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

, but the transversality 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 yields only 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
 This condition can be satisfied by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 whose gradients are orthogonal to the null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\lambda,\omega)=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, the gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\lambda$
\end_inset

 does not need to be parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, and thus we might have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\textrm{d}\nu\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 An explicit example can be easily found in Minkowski spacetime: Choose
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=t-x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=y$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\lambda$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Then the vector field dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv\lambda\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=y(\partial_{t}+\partial_{x})$
\end_inset

, and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is geodesic, null, and hypersurface orthogonal (to surfaces of constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $x-t$
\end_inset

), but non-integrable since it has nonvanishing rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}y\wedge(\textrm{d}t-\textrm{d}x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hypersurface-orthogonal field (even normalized and even timelike) does
 not necessarily have an integrable acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint:
\emph default
 It is not necessarily true that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\textrm{d}\omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 even if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{v}}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Explicit counterexamples are the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=(x+y)\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=x(\textrm{d}t-\textrm{d}x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\cosh x\,\textrm{d}t+\sinh x\,\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 in the Minkowski spacetime.
 These 1-forms are dual to hypersurface-orthogonal fields since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, but they do not have integrable acceleration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A geodesic vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface-orthogonal 
\emph on
everywhere
\emph default
 if there exists a 
\emph on
single
\emph default
 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal.
 The same statement holds also for Killing fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 instead of geodesic vector fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\hat{g}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 be the 1-form dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We can show that the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge d\omega=0$
\end_inset

 continues to hold as we move away from the initial surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 It would suffice to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\wedge d\omega)=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge d\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega=\omega\wedge\theta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is some 1-form.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\omega=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(\hat{g}\mathbf{v})=\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0\]

\end_inset

 everywhere, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\wedge d\omega)=\omega\wedge\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(d\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 A calculation shows that therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}(\omega\wedge d\omega)=\omega\wedge\omega\wedge...=0$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, here is a geometric argument.
 // -- this is incorrect: can't compute derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\theta$
\end_inset

 which is only correct on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

! A full calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}d\omega$
\end_inset

 is rather long, it seems...
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is constant along the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and so the affine tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be rescaled, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{v}}=\lambda\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\neq0$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\tilde{\mathbf{v}})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is normalized, geodesic, and orthogonal to the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, it is sufficient to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal everywhere.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\hat{g}\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 be the 1-form dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

; then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, and we need to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 remains zero away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This would mean that the Lie-propagated 3-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

 remains zero along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 when applied to a Lie-propagated basis of connecting vectors to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

; that property is equivalent to having 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 We compute 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\omega\right)\circ\mathbf{x} & =\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\left(\omega\circ\mathbf{x}\right)-\omega\circ\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\mathbf{x}=\\
 & =\nabla_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\mathbf{x})-g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},[\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\mathbf{x}])=g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\tilde{\mathbf{v}})\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\tilde{\mathbf{v}})=0,\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{v}},\tilde{\mathbf{v}})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

 on any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\textrm{d}\omega=\textrm{d}\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\omega=0,\]

\end_inset

and then we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega)=\left(\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\omega\right)\wedge\textrm{d}\omega+\omega\wedge\mathcal{L}_{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}}\textrm{d}\omega=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, here is a geometric argument.
 We can construct a family of 3-surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 which are surfaces of constant affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 measured along orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

, where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We can choose a basis of connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{c}_{j},\tilde{\mathbf{v}}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and thus orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 These connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

 will remain orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (see Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1 in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Lightcones-are-null}

\end_inset

, where we need to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore, the 3-surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 are everywhere orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 and thus also to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider the case of a Killing field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv\hat{g}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
 It is sufficient to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=0$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\omega=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\hat{g}\mathbf{k}=\hat{g}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}=0.\]

\end_inset

We again recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}$
\end_inset

, thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega\right)=\omega\wedge\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\textrm{d}\omega=\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\omega=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, we have the following relationships between integrability, hypersurf
ace orthogonality, and metric properties of a vector field.
 The condition for hypersurface orthogonality, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

, is weaker than the condition for integrability, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\omega=0$
\end_inset

.
 An integrable field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}f)$
\end_inset

 is always hypersurface orthogonal (to the hypersurfaces of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

).
 An integrable field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 which is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, is always geodesic.
 A hypersurface orthogonal, normalized, geodesic field is integrable unless
 it is null (a geodesic field can always be rescaled to make it normalized).
 The acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 of an integrable field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is again integrable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Null surfaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
null surface
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null surface}

\end_inset

is a 3-surface whose normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere null and nonzero, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now study the geometry of null surfaces since they have certain
 special and useful properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One unusual fact is that the normal vector is at the same time 
\emph on
tangent
\emph default
 to the null surface since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 The tangent space to a null surface is thus spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and two other basis vectors.
 The latter two vectors must be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and thus both must be spacelike.
 In fact, all the tangent vectors that are not parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are spacelike (see the Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:-Properties-of-null-vectors}

\end_inset

).
 Thus, a null surface is spanned by the null direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and two spacelike directions orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the tangent space contains its normal vector, the induced metric in
 the tangent space is 
\emph on
degenerate
\emph default
 since the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to every vector in the tangent space.
 This leads to an ambiguity of the induced Levi-Civita connection on the
 null surface: The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

), which is the only constraint on the Levi-Civita connection, does not
 define the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 uniquely through its scalar product with an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are many possible Levi-Civita connections on a null surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another peculiarity is that there is no unique projector onto the tangent
 space (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Orthogonal-complements}

\end_inset

).
 A satisfactory projector\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:null projector}

\end_inset

) can be found only after choosing another null vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 normalized by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=1$
\end_inset

, and then the image of the projection is a two-dimensional subspace within
 the tangent space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Self-test question: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do we need separate considerations for surfaces whose tangent space is spanned
 by (a) a null vector, a timelike vector, and a spacelike vector, (b) two
 null vectors and a spacelike vector, (c) three null vectors?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Answer:
\emph default
 No.
 Each of the described surfaces is in fact 
\series bold
timelike
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{timelike surface}

\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
orthogonal to a timelike vector.
 Their tangent spaces are also spanned by one timelike and two spacelike
 vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of null surfaces
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Examples-of-null}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest example of a null surface is the null cone of lightrays emitted
 from a point.
 Let us describe this surface explicitly in a flat Minkowski spacetime.
 The lightcone emitted at the origin is specified by the equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t-r\equiv t-\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}=0.\label{eq:Minkowski lightcone}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 normal to this surface is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}=\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\frac{x}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial x}+\frac{y}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial y}+\frac{z}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial z}.\]

\end_inset

It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 The tangent space to the lightcone at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 is spanned by the null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and the two spacelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\theta$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\phi} & \equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\left(y\frac{\partial}{\partial x}-x\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right),\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta} & =\frac{z}{r}\left(x\frac{\partial}{\partial x}+y\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)-\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial z}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example of a null surface is the horizon of a nonrotating, spherically
 symmetric black hole (Schwarzschild spacetime).
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Schwarzschild spacetime}

\end_inset

The metric is given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Schwarzschild}

\end_inset

).
 It is well known that the black hole horizon is the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $r-2m=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, it is not easy to analyze vectors at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m$
\end_inset

 since the Schwarzschild coordinates are singular there.
 To show that the horizon surface is null, we note that its tangent space
 is spanned by the two spacelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\theta$
\end_inset

, and also by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 which is null at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m$
\end_inset

 (but not at other values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

 is null, it is also the normal vector to the surface and hence the surface
 is null.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lightcones are null surfaces
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Lightcones-are-null}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can consider the surface formed by 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 the null geodesics emitted from a given initial spacetime point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 in all directions.
 This surface is called the 
\series bold
lightcone
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{lightcone}

\end_inset

emitted at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lightcone emitted at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is always a null surface, in an arbitrary curved spacetime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin the proof by a preliminary calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, and geodesic, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

 is constant along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{n}=\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}\circ g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{c})=g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{c})=g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{n})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tangent space to a lightcone at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is spanned by one null vector and two spacelike vectors that are both orthogona
l to the null vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first note that in the immediate vicinity of the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 the lightcone can be viewed, in suitable local coordinates, as a portion
 of the Minkowski lightcone\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Minkowski lightcone}

\end_inset

).
 Thus the tangent space in the vicinity of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is indeed spanned by one null vector and two spacelike vectors orthogonal
 to it.
 We now need to extend this property away from the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By assumption, the lightcone surface is built 
\emph on
entirely
\emph default
 from the congruence of lightrays emitted at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Translating this assumption into the mathematical language, we say that
 every point on the surface lies on some lightray from the congruence, and
 thus the surface can be parametrically described by a function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma(\tau;s_{1},s_{2}):\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}\rightarrow M\]

\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau;s_{1},s_{2})$
\end_inset

 is a lightray for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that there is a two-dimensional sphere of initial directions for
 emitting the lightrays, hence two parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.) In particular
\series bold
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\partial\gamma/\partial\tau$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the tangent vector field which is null, and the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}\equiv\partial\tau/\partial s_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{2}\equiv\partial\tau/\partial s_{2}$
\end_inset

 are everywhere linearly independent, connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 (see the Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \pageref{par:Exercise:-Connecting-vectors.}

\end_inset

).
 Thus we have the properties
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n}) & =0,\quad\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0,\\
\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{1}\right] & =\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{2}\right]=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 By construction, the connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are always tangent to the surface, and so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 are always a basis in the tangent space to the surface.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere null by assumption, so it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{2}$
\end_inset

 remain spacelike throughout the surface, at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Minkowski description of the lightcone holds for an infinitesimal vicinity
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, and thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{1})=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it follows from Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1 that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{1})=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 everywhere along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Vectors orthogonal to a null vector and not parallel to it must be spacelike
 (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:-Properties-of-null-vectors}

\end_inset

).
 Since each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 on the surface can be reached by 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 remain spacelike and orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Corollary:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The null tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is also the normal vector to the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Lemma\InsetSpace ~
2, the tangent space at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and two spacelike connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2}$
\end_inset

 that remain orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to every vector in the entire 3-dimensional tangent space,
 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is the normal vector to the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have proved that a lightcone is a null surface.
 A lightcone is by construction a surface built from lines (the individual
 lightrays).
 These lines are called the 
\series bold
null generators
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null generator}

\end_inset

of the surface.
 Now we shall use the formalism of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

null functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to prove the converse statement: Any null surface is always built from
 null generators (even though not every null surface is a lightcone emitted
 from one point).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Null functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A null surface can be defined through an equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=0$
\end_inset

, and then the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
null function
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null function}

\end_inset

More generally, a null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 on the spacetime is any function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

 is a null covector, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\nu,\textrm{d}\nu)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Immediate examples are the functions 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nu(t,x,y,z) & =t-r\equiv t-\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}},\\
\textrm{or }\,\nu(t,x,y,z) & =t-x,\end{align*}

\end_inset

in the Minkowski spacetime (verify this!).
 A null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 defines a null hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A null function can be physically interpreted as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

retarded time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 carried by lightrays emitted by some sources: If a lightray reaches an
 event 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, it was emitted at the time 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 at its source.
 (Here we do not assume that all the rays are emitted by one and the same
 source.) To remember this more easily, recall that time stands still for
 an observer moving at lightspeed, so a lightray 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preserves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 its emission time and shows it at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A peculiar property of null functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is that the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\nu)$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the surface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a null surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 naturally comes with a congruence of null lines, which are the orbits of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 within the surface and the null generators of the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Null functions generate null geodesics
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Null-functions-generate}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usefulness of null functions comes from the fact that any null surface
 consists not just of some null lines, but actually of 
\emph on
null geodesics
\emph default
 (see the following statement).
 These geodesics are the null generators of the surface.
 Since any null surface is a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 for some null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, it will follow that null functions provide a complete description of any
 null surface consisting of lightrays.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is a null function with the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are null geodesics.
 More generally, if a null curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is contained within a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a null geodesic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A stronger statement was proved in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Integrable-vector-fields}

\end_inset

: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is integrable and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, where the constant is not necessarily zero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We shall give a direct derivation that does not use forms.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

, we shall prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 for an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})\\
 & =\mathbf{n}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}+[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}],\mathbf{n}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

(We have used torsion-freeness and compatibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 with the metric.) Since by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})=\mathbf{x}\circ\nu$
\end_inset

 [see also Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:def of n}

\end_inset

)].
 Thus we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}) & =\mathbf{n}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})-g([\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}],\mathbf{n})\\
 & =\mathbf{n}\circ(\mathbf{x}\circ\nu)-([\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x}])\circ\nu=\mathbf{x}\circ(\mathbf{n}\circ\nu)\\
 & =\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are geodesics for integrable null 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A tangent space to a null surface contains only one null direction, and
 that direction is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 So any null curve contained within the surface must be an orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and hence a geodesic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Every lightray comes from null functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following statement demonstrates that any null geodesic can be obtained
 from a suitable null function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any null geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 there exists a null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\nu)$
\end_inset

 on the curve, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a null generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are of course many possible null functions satisfying this condition.
 We shall construct one such null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 by choosing an arbitrary timelike curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 intersecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This curve will be the worldline of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light source.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Suppose that the source emits lightrays in all directions from each point
 of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is one of these lightrays emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is a suitable parameter on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(\sigma)$
\end_inset

, such that the tangent vector is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\zeta}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\zeta}})=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the observer's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proper time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measured along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 We may suppose that the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we define the desired null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

retarded time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 carried by the lightrays from the source.
 More precisely, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\sigma$
\end_inset

 if the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is intersected by a lightray emitted from the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we then have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p_{0})=0$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined in some neighborhood of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

; more precisely, in a neighborhood where the lightcones are well-behaved,
 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
do not form caustics and fill the entire space around the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

, leaving no gaps.
 By construction, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is constant along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and thus the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 lies within the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=0$
\end_inset

, and the null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is everywhere tangent to the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

 is a null function; this is so because 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is by construction a lightcone surface, and we have already proved that
 any lightcone surface is null.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conformal invariance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under a conformal transformation of the metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda}g$
\end_inset

, null vectors obviously remain null.
 Therefore null functions remain null under a conformal transformation (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
they
 are conformally invariant).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conformal invariance}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, shapes of null geodesics are conformally invariant: a null geodesic
 line 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 remains a geodesic after a conformal transformation of the metric.
 This statement is now very easy to prove: a null geodesic is always an
 orbit of a gradient of some null function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(p)$
\end_inset

, the gradient operation 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is independent of the metric, and so the property of being a null function
 is conformally invariant.
 It follows that the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv\hat{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\nu)$
\end_inset

 will change to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{n}}=e^{-2\lambda}\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and thus the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

 are the same as those of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 must of course be changed, but the shape of the lines will remain the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Raychaudhuri equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider a geodesic congruence with a given tangent vector field.
 The distortion of the congruence along its own orbits will be determined
 by the geometry of the given spacetime.
 The distortion satisfies a purely kinematical relation called the Raychaudhuri
 equation.
 We shall derive separate versions of this equation for timelike and for
 null geodesics.
 We begin by introducing some geometric quantities characterizing the distortion
 of geodesic congruences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Distortion tensor
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Distortion-tensor}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we consider a normalized, geodesic vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 which may be either timelike, spacelike, or null.
 We have seen in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Divergence-of-a}

\end_inset

 that the divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 measures the relative rate of change of infinitesimal volume transported
 by the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider an small region of space around a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and imagine that the entire region moves with the flow (we call this a
 
\series bold
comoving
\series default
 region).
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{comoving region}

\end_inset

 This region can be visualized as consisting of a number of small, noninteractin
g particles, each moving along its flow line.
 The region will be generally distorted by the flow, so that not only its
 volume but also its shape will change.
 The distortion of the shape is measured by tensors called the shear and
 the rotation, which we shall now introduce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shape of the comoving region is naturally characterized by connecting
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 to be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 at the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 It then follows from Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1 in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Lightcones-are-null}

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 remains orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There would be no distortion of the region if every connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 were parallelly transported by the flow, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}=0$
\end_inset

 for every connecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, in general we expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}\neq0$
\end_inset

 at least for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the distortion of the volume around the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 during an infinitesimal time will be described by the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 along the flow.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}=\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{u},\]

\end_inset

the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 that can be described by a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

-dependent transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

, which is a (1,1) rank tensor defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}=\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{u}\equiv B(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{c}.\]

\end_inset

In components,
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{\alpha}^{\beta}=\nabla_{\alpha}u^{\beta}\equiv u_{\:;\alpha}^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

The transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 can be also written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
B(\mathbf{u})=\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}},\]

\end_inset

where it is implied that both sides act on a vector field.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
distortion
\series default
 
\series bold
tensor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{distortion tensor}

\end_inset

since it quantifies the deviation of the shape of a small comoving region
 from being parallelly transported.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The divergence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\equiv\nabla_{\alpha}u^{\alpha}=\textrm{Tr }B(\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

Even if the divergence is zero, but 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

, the shape of the region will be changed by the flow.
 To analyze the information provided by 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

, it is convenient to consider the bilinear form
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv g(B(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

We have seen in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Integrable-vector-fields}

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 bilinear form iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is an integrable vector field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the divergence of the null vector field corresponding to a lightcone
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=r$
\end_inset

 in Minkowski spacetime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The vector field is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}=\partial_{t}+\frac{1}{r}\left(x\partial_{x}+y\partial_{y}+z\partial_{z}\right);\]

\end_inset

using the flat connection, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=2r^{-1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rotation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 into symmetric and asymmetric parts,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =\tilde{B}_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+r_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}),\label{eq:B decomp 1}\\
\tilde{B}_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})\right),\nonumber \\
r_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})\right).\nonumber \end{align}

\end_inset

The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
rotation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!rotation of}

\end_inset

 (or the 
\series bold
twist
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{twist}

\end_inset

, or the 
\series bold
vorticity
\series default
) 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vorticity}

\end_inset

of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dgv ab}

\end_inset

) that
\begin_inset Formula \[
r_{(\mathbf{u})}=\frac{1}{2}\textrm{d}\hat{g}\mathbf{u}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\textrm{d}\omega,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form dual to the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 The rotation tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is thus the analog of the familiar three-dimensional curl (rotation) 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 of a vector field.
 A nonzero rotation means that the vector field is not a potential field;
 in our terminology, a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 means that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is not integrable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
More logic needed in development of the material: we have used this 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega$
\end_inset

 a long time ago but didn't call it rotation back then.
 And why not? Also, should the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rotation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}d\omega$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega$
\end_inset

? 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Vorticity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To visualize the shape distortion represented by a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

, consider a flat (Minkowski) spacetime in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is timelike and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is a constant tensor, represented by a constant antisymmetric matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 in an orthogonal basis.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 the transformation corresponding to the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

, so that for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=r_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

 For simplicity, suppose that the symmetric part of the distortion tensor
 vanishes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}_{(\mathbf{u})}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})=\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 and the connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}\tau}\mathbf{c}=B(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{c}=\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{c},\]

\end_inset

with the solution 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}(\tau)=\exp\left(\tau\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right)\mathbf{c}_{0}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is transverse to a timelike direction, it is represented (in an orthogonal
 basis) by an antisymmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix acting in spacelike directions.
 The exponential of such a matrix is a 
\emph on
rotation
\emph default
 matrix, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is related to the initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{0}$
\end_inset

 by a rotation.
 We find that 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 are rotated by the same fixed angle, which is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the entire shape of the initial region is rigidly rotated
 around an axis.
 This motivates the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rotation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introducing Raychaudhuri equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Raychaudhuri equation describes the change of the divergence of a geodesic
 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 along its own orbits.
 We straightforwardly find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}) & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}B_{(\mathbf{u})}\right)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y});\\
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}B_{(\mathbf{u})}\right) & \circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\right)-B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using the metricity condition and the definition of the Riemann tensor,
 we rewrite the first and the third terms as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{y}) & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})\\
=R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})+g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}, & \mathbf{y})+g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x}]}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})\\
=R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})+g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x}]}\mathbf{u}, & \mathbf{y});\end{align*}

\end_inset

finally,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}B_{(\mathbf{u})}\right) & \circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})+g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x}]}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y})-g(B(\mathbf{u})B(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The trace of the last expression with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})=\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-\textrm{Tr}\left(B(\mathbf{u})B(\mathbf{u})\right),\label{eq:Raychaudhuri 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the last term is the trace of the square of the linear transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

.
 This is the initial form of the 
\series bold
Raychaudhuri equation
\series default
 which we shall later analyze in particular cases.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Raychaudhuri equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point we can use the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:B decomp 1}

\end_inset

) which separates the symmetric and the antisymmetric parts of the distortion
 tensor.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}\left(AB\right)$
\end_inset

 is a nondegenerate scalar product in the linear space of square matrices.
 The subspaces of symmetric and antisymmetric matrices are orthogonal with
 respect to this scalar product.
 (Verify this!) Therefore with the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\tilde{B}+r$
\end_inset

 the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}(B^{2})$
\end_inset

 is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}\left(B(\mathbf{u})B(\mathbf{u})\right)=\textrm{Tr}\left(\tilde{B}(\mathbf{u})\tilde{B}(\mathbf{u})\right)+\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is the transformation associated with the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

.
 If the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is integrable, its rotation vanishes and we are left only with the symmetric
 part 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

 of the distortion tensor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further simplification is possible if we separate the trace-free part
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

.
 (This symmetric, trace-free part is called the 
\series bold
shear
\series default
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.) However, this operation depends sensitively on whether the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is null.
 Therefore we shall consider the relevant cases separately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shear for timelike congruences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the distortion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily symmetric, it is always 
\series bold
transverse
\series default
 to the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{transverse tensor}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x}) & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x})=0,\\
B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u}) & =g(\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{u})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=0,\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 This fact allows us to reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 to a bilinear form in a lower-dimensional space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we decompose the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 into the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and its complement, the one-dimensional space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 This decomposition is conveniently expressed using a projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and a complementary projector 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
P+Q=\hat{1},\quad\mathbf{x}=P\mathbf{x}+Q\mathbf{x}\;\textrm{for all }\mathbf{x},\quad P^{2}=P,\; Q^{2}=Q.\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }P=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }Q=1$
\end_inset

.
 The above 
\series bold
decomposition of identity
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{decomposition of identity}

\end_inset

is equivalent to the decomposition of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 into the partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

, see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:hv partial timelike metric}

\end_inset

), and a suitable complement,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h_{\mathbf{u}}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

The contravariant metric is correspondingly decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}=h_{\mathbf{u}}^{-1}+\mathbf{u}\otimes\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed with respect to the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 using the projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=B(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})+B(P\mathbf{x},Q\mathbf{y})+B(Q\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})+B(Q\mathbf{x},Q\mathbf{y}).\label{eq:Bxy decomp 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 So far we have not obtained any new information about 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 However, if the form 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is transverse to the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\cdot,Q\mathbf{y})=0$
\end_inset

, and the above formula simplifies to
\begin_inset Formula \[
B(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=B(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

Since the structure of the projectors crucially depends on whether the vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is null, we must consider the relevant cases separately.
 In this section we treat the easier case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is timelike.
 (The spacelike case is very similar but less important in practice.) Assuming
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=1$
\end_inset

, the projectors are
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{u}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u}),\quad Q\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{u}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

The distortion tensor is effectively three-dimensional since it is nonzero
 only on the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, where it coincides with its projection, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{u})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv B_{(\mathbf{u})}(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=B_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
shear
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!shear of}

\end_inset

of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is, by definition, the symmetric traceless part of the projected distortion
 tensor.
 It is convenient to express the shear using the partial metric for the
 subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h_{\mathbf{u}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv g(P\mathbf{a},P\mathbf{b})=g(\mathbf{a},P\mathbf{b})=g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{a})g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

Note that the partial signature of this metric is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(---\right)$
\end_inset

 and its trace is equal to 3.
 If a symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 is nonzero only on the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, the traceless part of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T-\frac{1}{3}\left(\textrm{Tr }T\right)h.\]

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }B_{(\mathbf{u})}^{\perp}=\textrm{Tr }B_{(\mathbf{u})}=\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
B_{(\mathbf{u})} & =\frac{1}{3}\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)h+\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}+r_{(\mathbf{u})},\label{eq:Bu timelike decomposition}\\
\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})} & \equiv\tilde{B}_{(\mathbf{u})}-\frac{1}{3}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})h;\quad\textrm{Tr }\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}=0.\nonumber \end{align}

\end_inset

The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 describes a linear deformation of the comoving region that changes its
 shape but does not change its volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Raychaudhuri equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Raychaudhuri 0}

\end_inset

) contains the trace of the square of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

, and we can now simplify this term by using the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bu timelike decomposition}

\end_inset

).
 Note that every term in that decomposition is transverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and thus is nonzero only on the three-dimensional subspace on which 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 projects.
 It is important that this subspace has a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with a Euclidean signature; the overall minus sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is unimportant for the present consideration.
 The partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 establishes a correspondence between bilinear forms and transformations,
 and we shall denote transformations by a hat.
 For example, the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
 
\series bold
Why don't we also denote the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 by a hat?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

 This relation uniquely determines the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 within the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the space of bilinear forms with the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr}\left(AB\right)$
\end_inset

, the subspace of symmetric traceless forms is orthogonal to the subspace
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure trace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
bilinear forms proportional to the partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

).
 Both these subspaces are also orthogonal to the subspace of antisymmetric
 forms.
 Therefore we can decompose the trace term as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}\left(B(\mathbf{u})B(\mathbf{u})\right)=\frac{1}{3}\left(\textrm{Tr }B(\mathbf{u})\right)^{2}+\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right)+\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right).\]

\end_inset

The Raychaudhuri equation for timelike geodesics is then written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}) & =\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-\frac{1}{3}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})^{2}\\
 & -\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right)-\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now analyze the individual terms in the above equation.
 Since a trace of a square of a symmetric matrix is nonnegative, we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can demonstrate this fact formally by computing
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}h(\hat{\sigma}\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\sigma(\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\sigma(\mathbf{y},\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{x})\\
 & \equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}h(\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{y},\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{x}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

 We now need to use a metric decomposition (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Index-free-trace}

\end_inset

 for details of trace calculations).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2},\mathbf{s}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis of (spacelike) vectors, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\mathbf{s}_{i},\mathbf{s}_{j})=-\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

, then the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
h^{-1}=-\mathbf{s}_{1}\otimes\mathbf{s}_{1}-\mathbf{s}_{2}\otimes\mathbf{s}_{2}-\mathbf{s}_{3}\otimes\mathbf{s}_{3},\]

\end_inset

and we get
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}h(\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{y},\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{x})=-\sum_{j=1}^{3}h(\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{s}_{j},\hat{\sigma}\mathbf{s}_{j})\geq0\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is negative-definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})})\leq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Same calculation as above, except for
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}r_{(\mathbf{u})}(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=-\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}r_{(\mathbf{u})}(\mathbf{y},\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{u})}\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shear for null congruences
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Shear-for-null}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that for null vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, building a self-adjoint projector\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:null projector}

\end_inset

) into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 requires a choice of an additional null vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 The definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:null projector}

\end_inset

) of the projector can be interpreted as a decomposition of the identity
 operator into the projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and a complementary projector 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{1}=P+Q,\quad Q\mathbf{x}\equiv\mathbf{l}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})+\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }P=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }Q=2$
\end_inset

.
 The above formula is equivalent to a decomposition of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 into the partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

, given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:hn partial null metric}

\end_inset

), and a suitable complement,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})+g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

Note that a tensor decomposition of the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{-1}=\mathbf{l}\otimes\mathbf{n}+\mathbf{n}\otimes\mathbf{l}-\mathbf{s}_{1}\otimes\mathbf{s}_{1}-\mathbf{s}_{2}\otimes\mathbf{s}_{2},\label{eq:g inverse decomp 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal, spacelike vectors, orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

, and spanning the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now decompose the distortion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 using the projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, analogously to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bxy decomp 1}

\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 by transversality, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})+B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{l})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})\\
 & +B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{l},P\mathbf{y})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})+B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The first term, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})\equiv B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

, is effectively a bilinear form on a two-dimensional space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be seen formally by using the general property 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})A(\mathbf{y},...)=A(\mathbf{n},...);\]

\end_inset

in other words, a trace with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 substitutes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 into the rest of the expression.
 However, substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 into any term yields zero since 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y}) & =g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0,\\
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},\mathbf{l})g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y}) & =B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr }B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}=\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we compute the trace needed for the Raychaudhuri equation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}\left(B(\mathbf{n})B(\mathbf{n})\right)\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}B_{(\mathbf{n})}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x}\right)B_{(\mathbf{n})}\left(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{b}\right),\]

\end_inset

it turns out that all the terms vanish except the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 involving only the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

projected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transverse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distortion 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{Tr}\left(B(\mathbf{n})B(\mathbf{n})\right)=\textrm{Tr }B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}.\label{eq:trace of projected distortion}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\series bold
(Verifying this is left as an easy exercise.)
\series default
 Therefore all the other terms in the decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unphysical,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
they do not enter the physically significant equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For null congruences 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, the reduction of the distortion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 to its transverse 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 can be also motivated as follows.
 The distortion tensor describes the change of shape in the comoving 2-volume
 spanned by two spacelike connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that these connecting vectors should be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, connecting vectors could be changed by adding a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1}\rightarrow\mathbf{s}_{1}+\lambda\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function; this will not modify the orthogonality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 However, connecting vectors that differ only by a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 correspond to a change of the parameter in nearby curves of the congruence.
 Therefore, the connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}+\lambda\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 carry the same information about the geometry of the congruence.
 Thus we should only consider equivalence classes of connecting vectors
 up to a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 While there is no canonical choice of representatives for these equivalence
 classes, a relatively straightforward way is to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 within a 2-plane orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and an auxiliary null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the construction used in the present section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now separate the symmetric traceless part 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 of the projected distortion, called the 
\series bold
shear
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector field!shear of}

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure trace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 part proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

, and from the antisymmetric part, which is the projected rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp} & =\frac{1}{2}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})h_{\mathbf{n}}+\sigma_{(\mathbf{n})}+r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp},\\
\sigma_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})\right)-\frac{1}{2}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})h_{\mathbf{n}},\\
r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv r_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})=\frac{1}{2}\left(B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-B_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, which is due to the projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 being two-dimensional.
 The Raychaudhuri equation for null geodesics is then written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}) & =\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})-\frac{1}{2}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})^{2}\\
 & -\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{n})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{n})}\right)-\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}\hat{r}_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Applications of Raychaudhuri equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Energy conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Einstein equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Einstein}

\end_inset

) specifies the matter energy-momentum tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 that would produce any given spacetime.
 However, not every tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to physically reasonable situations.
 There are certain conditions that are convenient to impose on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

; these are summarily called 
\series bold
energy conditions
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{energy conditions}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is reasonable to suppose that the energy density measured locally by
 an observer is everywhere nonnegative.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
This is true for every known classical field but is sometimes violated by
 quantum fields.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This gives the 
\series bold
weak energy condition
\series default

\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{\mu\nu}u^{\mu}u^{\nu}\equiv T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})\geq0\;\textrm{for all timelike }\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

 Since null vectors are limits of timelike vectors, a consequence of this
 condition is the 
\series bold
null energy condition
\series default

\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})\geq0\;\textrm{for all null }\mathbf{n}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some calculations it is necessary to impose conditions directly on the
 Ricci tensor.
 One such condition is the 
\series bold
strong energy condition
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})\leq0\;\textrm{for all timelike }\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

By the Einstein equation, this is equivalent to
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-\frac{g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})}{2}\textrm{Tr }T\geq0\;\textrm{for all timelike }\mathbf{u}.\]

\end_inset

Note that (contrary to what the words suggest) the strong energy condition
 
\emph on
does not
\emph default
 imply the weak one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the 
\series bold
dominant energy condition
\series default
 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
j_{\mu}\equiv T_{\mu\nu}u^{\mu}\;\textrm{is future-directed and }j_{\mu}j^{\mu}\geq0,\]

\end_inset

for all timelike 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 This condition means that the energy-momentum flows along future-directed
 timelike or null lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, a 
\series bold
perfect fluid
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{perfect fluid}

\end_inset

with the velocity field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, and pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is described by the energy-momentum tensor
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
T & =(\rho+p)\mathbf{v}\otimes\mathbf{v}-pg^{-1};\\
T_{\mu\nu} & =\left(\rho+p\right)v_{\mu}v_{\nu}-pg_{\mu\nu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In many situations, the matter EMT can be represented by the perfect fluid
 form with a suitably chosen 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 It is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is timelike and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the trace of the perfect fluid EMT is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr }T=\rho-3p.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Energy conditions can be expressed as inequalities for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as follows: The weak energy condition is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho\geq0,\quad\rho+p\geq0,\]

\end_inset

the null energy condition is just
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho+p\geq0,\]

\end_inset

the strong energy condition is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho+3p\geq0,\quad\rho+p\geq0,\]

\end_inset

and the dominant energy condition is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\rho\geq0,\quad\rho\geq\left|p\right|.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above formulas represent the energy conditions for the perfect fluid
 EMT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Since the energy conditions involve an arbitrary timelike vector 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset


\series default
, it is convenient to decompose that vector with respect to the fluid velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}=a\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w},\quad\mathbf{w}\in\mathbf{v}^{\perp},\; g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=a^{2}-g(\mathbf{w},\mathbf{w})=1,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a suitable constant.
 The value of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 will be irrelevant for the calculations since 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=p+\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{w},\mathbf{w})=-p$
\end_inset

, while the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is constrained only by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the weak energy condition gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=a^{2}T(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})+T(\mathbf{w},\mathbf{w})=a^{2}(\rho+p)-p\geq0,\]

\end_inset

which holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\geq1$
\end_inset

 only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\geq0$
\end_inset

 (at 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho+p\geq0$
\end_inset

 (the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

).
 Other energy conditions are treated similarly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A massless, minimally coupled scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with the EMT
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
T & =\textrm{d}\phi\otimes\textrm{d}\phi-\frac{g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\phi,\textrm{d}\phi)}{2}g,\\
T_{\mu\nu} & \equiv\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\phi_{,\alpha}\phi^{,\alpha},\end{align*}

\end_inset

satisfies the null and the strong energy conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 For any null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi\right)^{2}-\frac{g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})}{2}(...)=\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi\right)^{2}\geq0.\]

\end_inset

For any timelike vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr }T & =-g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\phi,\textrm{d}\phi),\\
T(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})-\frac{1}{2}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\textrm{Tr }T & =\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\phi\right)^{2}\geq0.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Focusing of timelike geodesics
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Focusing-of-timelike}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 of a timelike vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the relative rate of change of a comoving 3-volume
 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 This is so because the 3-volume spanned by vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is any normalized vector orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 are connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 which are orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 initially, they will remain orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, so we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 as the vector 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dV}{d\tau}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}\varepsilon(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)\varepsilon(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\right)V.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a congruence of timelike geodesics such that the tangent vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal.
 Then, as we have seen, the rotation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 vanishes, and the distortion tensor is symmetric.
 The Raychaudhuri equation is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})=R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-\frac{1}{3}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})^{2}-\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\right).\]

\end_inset

Imposing the strong energy condition, which holds for classical matter,
 we find that the right-hand side of the above equation is nonpositive,
 indicating that gravity makes hypersurface-orthogonal geodesics diverge
 less.
 This means that gravity is an attractive force.
 In fact, we can obtain a stronger result,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})\leq-\frac{1}{3}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})^{2}.\]

\end_inset

This inequality can be integrated with an initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}(\tau_{0})=\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, which yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\leq\frac{1}{\theta_{0}^{-1}+\frac{1}{3}\tau}.\]

\end_inset

If the initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is positive, the divergence goes to zero (or becomes negative), and if
 it is initially negative, it diverges to negative infinity within a finite
 time.
 A negative infinite divergence means that the geodesics cross at a 
\series bold
focal point
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{focal point}

\end_inset

.
 The set of all focal points in a given congruence is called a 
\series bold
caustic
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{caustic}

\end_inset

 We conclude that the appearance of a focal point is inevitable within a
 finite proper time once the initial value of the divergence is negative,
 for hypersurface orthogonal geodesic congruences.
 This statement is known as the 
\series bold
focusing theorem
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{focusing theorem}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is an example of a hypersurface orthogonal congruence to which the
 focusing theorem applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A congruence of timelike geodesics emitted from one point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal because it is orthogonal to hypersurfaces of
 constant proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 be the affine tangent vector field for a congruence of geodesics emitted
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We may normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since there are three linearly independent connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 at any point, and since these connecting vectors form a basis of the tangent
 space to a hypersurface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, it is sufficient to show that 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 connecting vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 It will then follow that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the hypersurface of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Now, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, it is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=0$
\end_inset

 (see Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1 in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Lightcones-are-null}

\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 is constant along the lines of the congruence, and so it remains to show
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=0$
\end_inset

 at any one point along each line.
 Since obviously all connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 must vanish at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for every line of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 (Alternatively, we may consider an infinitesimal neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, where the geometry of lines is approximately the same as in the Minkowski
 space, where geodesics are straight lines and the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{u})=0$
\end_inset

 is obviously true.) Thus we have proved the statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Repulsive gravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the energy-momentum tensor contains a 
\series bold
cosmological constant
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cosmological constant}

\end_inset

term
\begin_inset Formula \[
T=T_{(m)}+\frac{\Lambda}{8\pi}g^{-1},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{(m)}$
\end_inset

 is the matter EMT and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda>0$
\end_inset

 is the cosmological constant.
 (The cosmological constant is also called 
\series bold
dark energy
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{dark energy}

\end_inset

 if it is implied that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\Lambda(p)$
\end_inset

 is a slowly-varying dynamical field and its local value near a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is perceived as a cosmological 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.) The effect of introducing a cosmological constant is described by the
 Raychaudhuri equation, which receives an extra term
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{d}{d\tau}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}) & =-\frac{1}{8\pi}\left[T_{(m)}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-\frac{1}{2}\textrm{Tr }T_{(m)}\right]-\frac{1}{3}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})^{2}\\
 & -\textrm{Tr}(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{u})})+\Lambda.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The extra term will decrease the rate of focusing, which indicates that
 a cosmological constant corresponds to a 
\emph on
repulsive
\emph default
 gravitational force.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Focusing of null geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider a congruence of null geodesics with a hypersurface-orthogonal
 tangent vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and we would like to obtain an analogous focusing theorem.
 Compared with the timelike case, we have two differences: Firstly, the
 3-volume spanned by vectors orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 vanishes and so the interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is altered; this issue was treated in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Divergence-of-a-null}

\end_inset

 where we found that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 describes the rate of change of comoving area.
 Secondly, the rotation tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 generally does not vanish for hypersurface-orthogonal null geodesics.
 However, Raychaudhuri equation involves the trace term 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }(r_{(\mathbf{n})}r_{(\mathbf{n})})$
\end_inset

, and we shall now show that this term vanishes for a hypersurface-orthogonal
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, even though the rotation tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 itself does not vanish.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Shear-for-null}

\end_inset

 that the trace terms involve only the projected distortion tensor [Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:trace of projected distortion}

\end_inset

)].
 Therefore the trace term will remain the same after we project the rotation
 tensor onto the subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr }\left(r_{(\mathbf{n})}r_{(\mathbf{n})}\right)=\textrm{Tr }\left(r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}\right).\]

\end_inset

 We now use the fact that the rotation 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv\hat{g}^{-1}\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 1-form dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By the assumption of hypersurface orthogonality and the Frobenius theorem,
 there exist scalar functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\nu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=e^{\lambda}\textrm{d}\nu$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\omega=e^{\lambda}\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\textrm{d}\nu=\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\omega.\]

\end_inset

The projected rotation tensor acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & \equiv(\textrm{d}\omega)\circ(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\omega(P\mathbf{y})(\textrm{d}\lambda)\circ P\mathbf{x}-\omega(P\mathbf{x})(\textrm{d}\lambda)\circ P\mathbf{y}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(P\mathbf{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the projected rotation vanishes, we obtain the Raychaudhuri equation
 for null geodesics in the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})=R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})-\frac{1}{2}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})^{2}-\textrm{Tr}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{n})}\hat{\sigma}_{(\mathbf{n})}\right).\]

\end_inset

Imposing the null energy condition, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the right-hand side of the above equation is nonpositive and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})\leq-\frac{1}{2}(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n})^{2}.\]

\end_inset

This is the focusing theorem 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{focusing theorem}

\end_inset

for the null case.
 The conclusion is that gravity makes null geodesics focus within a finite
 interval of the affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Null tetrad formalism
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Null-tetrad-formalism}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The null tetrad formalism is due to Newman and Penrose and consists of writing
 equations in a basis where 
\emph on
all four
\emph default
 vectors are null and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

as orthogonal as possible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with respect to each other.
 This leads to simplifications when writing tensor equations in components.
 We shall now introduce the null tetrad formalism as an elegant way of expressin
g the projected distortion tensor for the case of null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to change the previously used basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}\}$
\end_inset

, where the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are null and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are spacelike connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, into a null basis.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 is not (and generally cannot be chosen as) a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, we are motivated to drop the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 be connecting vectors but instead demand orthonormality, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{s}_{j},\mathbf{s}_{k})=-\delta_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we define the 
\emph on
complex-valued
\emph default
 null vectors 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{m}\equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\mathbf{s}_{1}+\text{i}\mathbf{s}_{2}\right),\quad\bar{\mathbf{m}}\equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\mathbf{s}_{1}-\text{i}\mathbf{s}_{2}\right).\label{eq:m through s1s2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The fact that these vectors are complex-valued is merely a mathematical
 formality that makes equations more compact; we expect that every physically
 measurable quantity is real-valued.
 The null basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}}\}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
Newman-Penrose null tetrad
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null tetrad}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The null tetrad is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nearly orthogonal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

, and all the other scalar products vanish.
 Hence, the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g inverse decomp 1}

\end_inset

) of the contravariant metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is rewritten through the null tetrad as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}=\mathbf{l}\otimes\mathbf{n}+\mathbf{n}\otimes\mathbf{l}-\mathbf{m}\otimes\bar{\mathbf{m}}-\bar{\mathbf{m}}\otimes\mathbf{m}.\]

\end_inset

The partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 is similarly decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
h_{(\mathbf{n})}^{-1}=-\mathbf{m}\otimes\bar{\mathbf{m}}-\bar{\mathbf{m}}\otimes\mathbf{m},\]

\end_inset

and the projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\mathbf{x}=-\mathbf{m}g(\mathbf{x},\bar{\mathbf{m}})-\bar{\mathbf{m}}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{m}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the null tetrad decomposition above, the divergence of a hypersurface
 orthogonal null geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{div}\mathbf{n} & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n})+B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})-B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})-B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{m})\\
 & =-2B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})\equiv-2g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\bar{\mathbf{m}}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

because the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 is transverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and its projection onto the subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})$
\end_inset

 is rotation-free.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for a geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 hypersurface orthogonal, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $-2B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})$
\end_inset

 is complex-valued, and only its real part is actually equal to the divergence
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complex-valued divergence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\theta\equiv-2B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})\]

\end_inset

 is still useful for the analysis of such cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other ingredient in the Raychaudhuri equation is the projected shear
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, which can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\sigma_{(\mathbf{n})}^{\perp}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =B_{(\mathbf{n})}(P\mathbf{x},P\mathbf{y})-\frac{1}{2}\left(\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}\right)h_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\nonumber \\
 & =g(\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{x})g(\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{y})\sigma+g(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{y})\bar{\sigma}\label{eq:shear through sigma}\end{align}

\end_inset

through the auxiliary (complex-valued) scalar quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma\equiv B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{m}),\]

\end_inset

also called the 
\series bold
scalar shear
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{scalar shear}

\end_inset

Another expression for the scalar shear is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma\equiv g(\mathbf{m},\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n})=g(\mathbf{m},\left[\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\right])+g(\mathbf{m},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m})=g(\mathbf{m},\left[\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\right]).\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 cannot be a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 unless the shear vanishes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The completion of a given vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 to a null tetrad is of course not unique.
 Let us now investigate the freedom in the choice of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 and the resulting uncertainties in the distortion quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma,\theta$
\end_inset

.
 The tetrad vectors are defined by the requirements 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{l})=g(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{m})=g(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=-g(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})=1$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 is related by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:m through s1s2}

\end_inset

) to an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n}\right)^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{l},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{s}_{1},\mathbf{s}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis; the set of transformations that preserve the orthonormality
 of the basis is the Lorentz group; so the admissible transformations of
 the tetrad vectors are precisely the subgroup of the Lorentz group that
 leaves the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 unchanged.
 Let us describe these transformations explicitly.
 Suppose that the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 change to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{m} & \rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{m}}=\alpha\mathbf{m}+\beta\mathbf{n}+\gamma\mathbf{l},\\
\mathbf{l} & \rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{l}}=\lambda\mathbf{l}+\mu\mathbf{m}+\bar{\mu}\bar{\mathbf{m}}+\nu\mathbf{n},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\mu$
\end_inset

 are complex and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\nu$
\end_inset

 are real.
 Then it is straightforward to prove that the orthogonality relations 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\tilde{\bar{\mathbf{m}}})=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\tilde{\mathbf{m}})=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\tilde{\mathbf{l}})=0$
\end_inset

 require that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\bar{\alpha}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\bar{\mu}\alpha$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\mu\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the general form of an admissible transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\mathbf{m} & \rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{m}}=e^{\text{i}\phi}\mathbf{m}+A\mathbf{n},\label{eq:m replacement 1}\\
\mathbf{l} & \rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{l}}=\mathbf{l}+e^{\text{i}\phi}\bar{A}\mathbf{m}+e^{-\text{i}\phi}A\bar{\mathbf{m}}+A\bar{A}\mathbf{n},\label{eq:l replacement 1}\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary scalar functions; note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is real-valued while 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is complex-valued.
 We can easily see that the distortion quantities change under this transformati
on as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma\rightarrow\tilde{\sigma}=e^{2\text{i}\phi}\sigma,\quad\theta\rightarrow\tilde{\theta}=\theta.\label{eq:sigma theta transform}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to obtain closed-form equations for the divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and the scalar shear 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of a geodesic congruence.
 The Raychaudhuri equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Raychaudhuri equation!in null tetrad formalism}

\end_inset

(for a hypersurface orthogonal, null, geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

) acquires a more elegant form,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\theta\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\theta=-\frac{1}{2}\theta^{2}+\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})-2\sigma\bar{\sigma}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\bar{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the transformation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:sigma theta transform}

\end_inset

), the Raychaudhuri equation does not depend on the completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 to a null tetrad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:shear through sigma}

\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Tr }\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}^{\perp}\sigma_{(\mathbf{u})}^{\perp}=2\sigma\bar{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation
\emph default
: Calculation 
\series bold
(omitted)
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under some additional assumptions about the null tetrad, a similar equation
 holds for the scalar shear 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{d\tau}\sigma\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma=-\frac{\theta+\bar{\theta}}{2}\sigma+R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}).\label{eq:shear equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We shall now derive this equation and detail the necessary assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to compute the quantity
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{m}) & \equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})\\
 & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})+g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The appearance of nested covariant derivatives suggests that we introduce
 the Riemann tensor,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})=R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})+g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}]}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}).\]

\end_inset

(We used 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

.) Thus
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma=R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})+g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}]}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})+g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m}).\label{eq:sigma pre 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 By virtue of the following obvious properties,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n}) & =0,\; g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})\equiv\sigma,\; g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\bar{\mathbf{m}})\equiv-\frac{1}{2}\theta,\\
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}) & =\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}g(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n})-g(\mathbf{m},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n})=0,\; g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\mathbf{m})=0,\end{align*}

\end_inset

we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n} & =-\sigma\bar{\mathbf{m}}+\frac{1}{2}\theta\mathbf{m}+\alpha\mathbf{n},\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m} & =\zeta\mathbf{m}+\gamma\mathbf{n},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we introduced unknown scalar functions
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l}),\;\zeta\equiv-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}}),\;\gamma\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\mathbf{l}).\]

\end_inset

 These constants depend on the completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 to a null tetrad and should not enter the final expression.
 Now we can straightforwardly evaluate:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{m}}\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m}) & =\zeta\sigma,\\
\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}\right] & =\left(\zeta-\frac{1}{2}\theta\right)\mathbf{m}+\sigma\bar{\mathbf{m}}+(\gamma-\alpha)\mathbf{n},\\
g(\nabla_{[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}]}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}) & =B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\left[\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}\right],\mathbf{m})\\
 & =\left(\zeta-\frac{1}{2}\theta\right)B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\mathbf{m},\mathbf{m})+\sigma B_{(\mathbf{n})}(\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{m})\\
 & =\left(\zeta-\frac{1}{2}\theta\right)\sigma-\frac{1}{2}\bar{\theta}\sigma.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Finally, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:sigma pre 1}

\end_inset

) is rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma=R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m})-\frac{1}{2}(\theta+\bar{\theta})\sigma+2\zeta\sigma.\]

\end_inset

This equation still contains the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\equiv-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})$
\end_inset

 that depends on the completion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 to a null tetrad and is thus arbitrary.
 We would like to eliminate this ``gauge dependence.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Note that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 always has pure imaginary values and changes under the replacement\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:m replacement 1}

\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta\rightarrow\tilde{\zeta}=\zeta+\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, for a given null tetrad, there exists a suitable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that new null tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{n},e^{\text{i}\phi}\mathbf{m},e^{-\text{i}\phi}\bar{\mathbf{m}}\}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\zeta}=0$
\end_inset

.
 (Obviously, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}\zeta$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.) Once we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0$
\end_inset

, the required equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:shear equation}

\end_inset

) follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, we may 
\emph on
redefine
\emph default
 the scalar shear for a given null tetrad as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{g}\equiv e^{2\text{i}\lambda}\sigma,\]

\end_inset

where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}}).\]

\end_inset

(There is, of course, a considerable freedom in choosing the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.) The redefined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gauge-covariant shear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 still depends on the choice of the tetrad and of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, but is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gauge-covariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that a tetrad transformation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:m replacement 1}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:sigma theta transform}

\end_inset

) yields 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\sigma}_{g}=e^{2\text{i}\phi}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma_{g}.\]

\end_inset

The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}\bar{\sigma}_{g}$
\end_inset

 remains invariant as before, and Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:shear equation}

\end_inset

) holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 with any choice of tetrad.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Verify the above equation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}=e^{2\text{i}\phi}\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}_{g}\equiv e^{2\text{i}\tilde{\lambda}}\tilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 be the required function for the original tetrad and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for the modified tetrad with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{m}}=e^{\text{i}\phi}\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we compute 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma_{g} & =(2\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda)\sigma_{g}+e^{2\text{i}\lambda}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma,\\
\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\lambda} & =g(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}e^{\text{i}\phi}\mathbf{m},e^{-\text{i}\phi}\bar{\mathbf{m}})=\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda-\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi,\\
\tilde{\lambda} & =\lambda-\phi,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\sigma}_{g} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}(e^{2\text{i}\tilde{\lambda}}\tilde{\sigma})=(2\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\lambda})\tilde{\sigma}_{g}+e^{2\text{i}\tilde{\lambda}}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\sigma}\\
 & =2\text{i}\tilde{\sigma}_{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}(\lambda-\phi)+(2\text{i}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi)\tilde{\sigma}_{g}+e^{2\text{i}\tilde{\lambda}+2\text{i}\phi}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma\\
 & =e^{2\text{i}\phi}\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\sigma_{g}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Asymptotically flat spacetimes
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cha:Asymptotically-flat-spacetimes}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a spacetime contains a finite island of matter surrounded by an infinite
 sea of vacuum, we intuitively expect that the spacetime is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost flat sufficiently far from the matter.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For example, the metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Schwarzschild}

\end_inset

) for the Schwarzschild spacetime is approximately equal to the Minkowski
 metric in spherical coordinates in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Such spacetimes containing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

well-isolated systems
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
asymptotically flat
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{asymptotically flat spacetime}

\end_inset

In this chapter we shall formulate and explore the property of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asymptotic flatness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in more detail.
 We begin by considering an easier case of stationary spacetimes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stationary spacetimes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is given in coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 are independent of one of the coordinates, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x^{1}}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Killing vector}

\end_inset

for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

; in other words, the flow of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x^{1}}$
\end_inset

 leaves the metric invariant.
 Thus, Killing vectors provide a formalization of the concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordinate symmetry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the metric.
 Using Killing vectors, the heuristic concept of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time-independent metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is made precise in the following way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A spacetime is called 
\series bold
stationary
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{stationary spacetime}

\end_inset

if it possesses a timelike Killing vector field.
 The existence of such a vector field leads to many useful properties that
 we shall now explore.
 A stronger property is being 
\emph on
static
\emph default
 rather than stationary.
 A spacetime is 
\series bold
static
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{static spacetime}

\end_inset

 if it is stationary 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 the timelike Killing vector is hypersurface-orthogonal.
 For now, it suffices to consider stationary spacetimes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a stationary spacetime, the orbits of the Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 can be seen as preferred worldlines along which the geometry does not change.
 It is useful to consider imaginary observers moving along these worldlines.
 These
\series bold
 
\series default
are called
\series bold
 stationary observers
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{stationary observer}

\end_inset

and have 4-velocities 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}}\mathbf{k}.\label{eq:def of stationary observer}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Stationary observers find that the geometry of the spacetime around them
 is the same at all times.
 However, these stationary observers are not necessarily geodesic observers,
 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
they are not necessarily freely falling.
 For example, an observer sitting at the surface of a nonrotating planet
 observers that the geometry is time-independent.
 This is a stationary observer who is, obviously, not freely falling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following statement lists the most important properties of Killing vectors
 with regard to being geodesic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Killing-vector-normalization}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Killing-vector-normalization}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 For a Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})=0$
\end_inset

 holds.
 
\series bold
(b)
\series default
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 is everywhere constant iff the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is geodesic.
 
\series bold
(c)
\series default
 In the domain where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})\neq0$
\end_inset

, the normalized vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:def of stationary observer}

\end_inset

) is geodesic iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is geodesic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Idea of proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 with an arbitrary vector and use the Killing equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-Killing-vector-normalization}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 The property 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})=0$
\end_inset

 follows directly from the Killing equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

).
 
\series bold
(b)
\series default
 For an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{x})=-g(\mathbf{k},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{k})=-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}).\]

\end_inset

Thus, the scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 with an arbitrary vector vanishes iff the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 in an arbitrary direction vanishes.
 
\series bold
(c)
\series default
 Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})\neq0$
\end_inset

, we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u} & =\frac{1}{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}+\frac{\mathbf{k}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, a Killing vector is not normalized, so stationary worldlines
 generally correspond to 
\emph on
accelerated
\emph default
 observers rather than to freely falling observers.
 For example, the stationary worldlines in the Schwarzschild spacetime describe
 observers remaining at a constant distance from the center of mass.
 These observers move with a constant acceleration and thus feel a constant
 pull of gravity.
 Accordingly, the Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 is not normalized in the Schwarzschild spacetime, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})\neq\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Newtonian limit
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Newtonian-limit}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the framework of General Relativity, the 
\series bold
Newtonian limit
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Newtonian limit of GR}

\end_inset

is the assumption that gravitation is weak and that there exists a globally
 inertial reference frame---the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute spacetime.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In other words, a Newtonian setting considers a set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers who see each other as motionless or moving with constant velocities
 at all times.
 (Of course, this assumption is only 
\emph on
approximately
\emph default
 correct in the actual curved spacetime; also the clocks at different points
 run at different rates and cannot be exactly synchronized everywhere at
 all times.) For example, someone sitting on the surface of the Earth could
 be such an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observer.
 Since 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers do not necessarily move along geodesic lines, they will perceive
 the motion of freely falling bodies as an 
\emph on
accelerated
\emph default
 motion occurring in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reference frame.
 The Newtonian theory explains this apparently accelerated motion as being
 due to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational forces.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 We now formalize these assumptions and derive the Newtonian equations of
 gravitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A congruence of the world-lines of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers is described by a timelike vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, normalized as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 The observers measure the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absolute time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The central assumption of the Newtonian limit is that these observers are
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with respect to each other, so any neighbor observers appear to move without
 relative acceleration.
 In other words, 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 connecting vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, appears (approximately!) unaccelerated, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}\approx0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us find out how the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers perceive the motion of freely falling (geodesic) particles.
 If a geodesic has instantaneously the same tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as one of the fixed observers, the observer's acceleration relative to
 the geodesic is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, therefore the observer will measure the acceleration of the freely falling
 particle as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\equiv-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Our goal is to derive a formula describing the acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The plan of the derivation is the following.
 First we use the properties of connecting vectors to deduce that the vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is integrable.
 It will follow that there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\phi$
\end_inset

.
 This scalar function is called the 
\series bold
gravitational potential
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{gravitational potential}

\end_inset

 Then we shall derive an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, using the Einstein equation with matter sources consisting of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matter (not moving with respect to the fixed observers) with mass density
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

.
 This equation will coincide with the (three-dimensional) Poisson equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi=4\pi\rho$
\end_inset

, which is equivalent to Newton's law of gravity.
 In this way we reproduce the Newtonian theory of gravitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceleration field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is integrable if the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bv def}

\end_inset

) is symmetric.
 The form of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})\]

\end_inset

suggests that we should consider the combination
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}-\nabla_{\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}\right]}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})\]

\end_inset

and try to simplify it using the given information about the connecting
 vectors.
 We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c},\mathbf{y})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})+g(\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})\]

\end_inset

and therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{y})\equiv-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{c}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y}).\label{eq:Ba R}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{y})=B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{c}).\]

\end_inset

In fact, the above relation holds for arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 at any point, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=B_{(\mathbf{a})}(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, because it involves only the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of the connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 at one point, and not the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a connecting vector.
 Hence, the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{a})}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is integrable, and there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, we use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Ba R}

\end_inset

) and the definition of divergence,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{a}=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{div}\mathbf{a}=-\textrm{div}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}\right)=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{div}\mathbf{a} & =\textrm{div}\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\phi\\
 & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\phi,\mathbf{y})\\
 & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\textrm{d}\phi\right)\circ\mathbf{y}=\square\phi,\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where the 
\series bold
D'Alembertian
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{D'Alembertian}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\square\phi$
\end_inset

 is defined as the trace of the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{...}\nabla_{...}\phi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square\phi\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}(\nabla_{...}\nabla_{...}\phi)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\phi-\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}}\phi).\]

\end_inset

In components, 
\begin_inset Formula $\square\phi=\nabla_{\mu}\nabla^{\mu}\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we obtain the following equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square\phi=\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain a concrete expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

, we need to relate the curvature to the matter content of the spacetime.
 In the Newtonian approximation, the matter sources are approximately motionless
 particles, so the energy-momentum tensor of matter is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}=\rho v_{\mu}v_{\nu}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 is the mass density.
 The Einstein equation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R_{\alpha}^{\alpha}=-8\pi T_{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}=-8\pi\left(T_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}T_{\alpha}^{\alpha}\right).\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mu}v^{\mu}=1$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu}^{\mu}=\rho$
\end_inset

 and finally
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square\phi=R_{\mu\nu}v^{\mu}v^{\nu}=-4\pi\rho.\]

\end_inset

This is in fact the familiar Poisson equation relating the Newtonian gravitation
al potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to the density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 of matter, written in a Lorentz-covariant way.
 In an almost-flat spacetime, we can choose the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and then we have approximately
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square\phi=\left(\partial_{t}^{2}-\Delta\right)\phi=-4\pi\rho,\quad\Delta\equiv\partial_{x}^{2}+\partial_{y}^{2}+\partial_{z}^{2}.\]

\end_inset

The time derivatives are negligible since the distribution of matter is
 almost stationary (in the SI units, this is made more explicit by the factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{c^{2}}\partial_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, we recover the three-dimensional 
\series bold
Poisson equation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Poisson equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta\phi=4\pi\rho.\]

\end_inset

Note that the three-dimensional acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=-\partial_{i}\phi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=x,y,z$
\end_inset

, because of the negative sign of the spatial part of the metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Example: Schwarzschild spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Schwarzschild spacetime}

\end_inset

The metric is given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Schwarzschild}

\end_inset

) and the stationary observers follow lines of fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $r,\phi,\theta$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r>2m$
\end_inset

.
 We expect the Newtonian approximation to hold for large 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2m$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is thus proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

, and normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{-1/2}\partial_{t}.\]

\end_inset

The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\theta},\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 are connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}$
\end_inset

 is not,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{v},\partial_{r}\right]=\frac{m}{r(r-2m)}\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

However, the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v},\partial_{r}\right]\approx0$
\end_inset

 is good for large 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, namely for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A calculation shows that the acceleration field 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 integrable (not only in the Newtonian approximation).
 Let us compute the scalar products of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\partial_{r},\partial_{\theta},\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}) & =\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0,\\
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\partial_{\theta}) & =-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\partial_{\theta},\mathbf{v})=-g(\nabla_{\partial_{\theta}}\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0,\\
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\partial_{\phi}) & =0,\\
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\partial_{r}) & =-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\partial_{r},\mathbf{v})=-g(\mathbf{v},[\mathbf{v},\partial_{r}])-g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\partial_{r}}\mathbf{v})\\
 & =-\frac{m}{r(r-2m)}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=\frac{g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v},\partial_{r})}{g(\partial_{r},\partial_{r})}\partial_{r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}}\partial_{r}.\]

\end_inset

The potential is easier to find from the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which is expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\hat{g}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v} & =-\frac{m}{r(r-2m)}\textrm{d}r\equiv\textrm{d}\Phi(r),\nonumber \\
\Phi(r) & \equiv\frac{1}{2}\ln\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right).\label{eq:Phi potential}\end{align}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(r)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the gravitational force
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Schwarzschild spacetime!gravitational potential}

\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{gravitational potential!for Schwarzschild spacetime}

\end_inset

 measured by the stationary observers in the Schwarzschild spacetime.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2m$
\end_inset

 the potential becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $-m/r$
\end_inset

, which is the familiar Newtonian potential due to a point mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow2m$
\end_inset

 the gravitational force approaches infinity.
 (Note that the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 does not coincide with the physical distance.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Self-test question:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is the motion of test particles in the Schwarzschild spacetime actually
 the same as the Newtonian motion in the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(r)$
\end_inset

 or in some other potential?
\emph on
 Answer:
\emph default
 No.
 (The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 depends on velocity as well.) 
\series bold
Not sure how to explain! Need to make this clear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that the Schwarzschild spacetime admits a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(r)$
\end_inset

 is a consequence of spherical symmetry and time-independence, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the metric
 depends only on the radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 (More formally: The presence of an integrable Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 shows that the spacetime is static; additionally, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

angular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Killing vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 indicate the spherical symmetry.) Thus the acceleration of an observer at
 constant 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a vector directed along 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{r}$
\end_inset

 whose magnitude is a function only of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore this acceleration must be equal to a gradient of some function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(r)$
\end_inset

.
 In general, all stationary spacetimes admit such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 although it may not be spherically symmetric; see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Gravitational-potential}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Example: de Sitter spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{de Sitter spacetime}

\end_inset

The metric is given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:de Sitter}

\end_inset

) and the stationary observers follow lines of fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is simply equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the basis of connecting vectors is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x},\partial_{y},\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is integrable and normalized, it is geodesic and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, stationary observers are at the same time freely falling and do
 not feel any gravity at all.
 However, the Newtonian approximation breaks down at sufficiently large
 distances.
 This can be seen by computing the relative acceleration of two nearby observers
 (see the following calculation),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\partial_{x}=H^{2}\partial_{x}.\]

\end_inset

At small distances 
\begin_inset Formula $L\ll H^{-1}$
\end_inset

, we are allowed to use the approximation that stationary observers are
 not accelerated relative to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 which is one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x},\partial_{y},\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}=H\mathbf{c}\label{eq:Hubble law}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and thus derive the above equation.
 The relation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hubble law}

\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
Hubble law
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hubble law}

\end_inset

 (In a uniformly expanding spacetime, the velocity of a comoving observer
 is proportional to the distance to the observer.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 We can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 by taking scalar products; for instance,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c},\mathbf{c})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{c})=-He^{2Ht},\]

\end_inset

while scalar products of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 with other basis vectors vanish.
 Thus we obtain Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hubble law}

\end_inset

) and as a trivial consequence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}=H^{2}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Redshift
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Redshift}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a stationary spacetime, the magnitude of the Killing vector defines a
 scalar function, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
redshift factor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{redshift factor}

\end_inset

because, as we shall now show, the local values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 characterize the variation of the photon frequency measured by different
 stationary observers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A null geodesic with a null tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 represents a path of a photon.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 may be rescaled in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 represents the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of the photon in the rest frame of a timelike observer with 4-velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 From the Planck relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=h\nu$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is Planck's constant, we find that the measured frequency of the photon
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=h^{-1}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

.
 In a stationary spacetime, stationary observers have worldlines with 4-velocity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}}\mathbf{k}=z^{-1}\mathbf{k}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, a stationary observer at a given location will measure the frequency
 of a given lightray with a (null) worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h\nu=g(z^{-1}\mathbf{k},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}).\]

\end_inset

By Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Killing-property-geodesic}

\end_inset

 below, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})$
\end_inset

 remains constant along lightrays.
 Thus, for a given single photon moving along a null geodesic, the frequency
 measured by a stationary observer is proportional to the local value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This justifies the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

redshift factor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Killing-property-geodesic}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Killing-property-geodesic}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector, so that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

) holds, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a geodesic, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})$
\end_inset

 is constant along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-Killing-property-geodesic}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-Killing-property-geodesic}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 be a geodesic vector field containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

; then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 and we compute
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=-g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{k}),\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Killing-vector-normalization}

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}z=0$
\end_inset

; in other words, the redshift factor is constant for a given stationary
 observer.
 It also follows that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
everywhere
\emph default
 constant (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
there is no redshift) iff the stationary observers are geodesic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conformal Killing vectors
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Conformal-Killing-vectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In cosmology, one usually considers spacetimes that are not stationary,
 so no timelike Killing vectors are present.
 Nevertheless, sometimes there exists a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conformal Killing vector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and then the redshift function 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 is still useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, a 
\series bold
conformal Killing vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conformal Killing vector}

\end_inset

is a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=2\lambda g,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is some scalar function.
 It follows directly from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lie derivative of metric formula}

\end_inset

) that a conformal Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{b})+g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{k})=2\lambda g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary vectors.
 This is a modified version of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Killing nabla cond}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a spacetime admits a conformal Killing vector, the redshift function
 is again useful, as demonstrated by the following statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Conformal-Killing-vectors-redshift}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Conformal-Killing-vectors-redshift}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that a spacetime admits a timelike conformal Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, and call observers moving along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conformally stationary.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Then the frequency of a photon measured by conformally stationary observers
 is inversely proportional to the redshift function 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-Conformal-Killing-vectors-redshift}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an arbitrary geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=\lambda g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

If the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is null (
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

) then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=0,\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 remains constant along the geodesic lines, just as in the case of ordinary
 Killing vectors.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\equiv z^{-1}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, we again find
\begin_inset Formula \[
h\nu\equiv g(\mathbf{u},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=z^{-1}g(\mathbf{k},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\propto z^{-1}.\]

\end_inset

 The photon's frequency is inversely proportional to the redshift factor.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note however that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})=2\lambda g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

, so the redshift factor 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not constant
\emph default
 along the worldlines of stationary observers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Example-de-Sitter-conformal-Killing}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Example-de-Sitter-conformal-Killing}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a de Sitter spacetime with the metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:de Sitter}

\end_inset

), it is reasonable to guess that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=f(t)\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a conformal Killing vector if the scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is chosen correctly.
 Let us determine 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

, the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, and the redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It suffices to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\partial_{t},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 either 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{t}=H\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the only nonzero derivative (similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\partial_{t}}f\partial_{t},\partial_{t})=\dot{f}g(\partial_{t},\partial_{t}),\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{f}=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Further,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\partial_{x}}f\partial_{t},\partial_{x})=fH\, g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x})\equiv\lambda g(\partial_{x},\partial_{x}),\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=fH=\dot{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=e^{Ht}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=He^{Ht}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}=e^{Ht}$
\end_inset

.
 The frequency of photons decays with time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-Ht}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a flat Friedmann-Robertson-Walker metric, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)(dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dz^{2}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero function, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=a(t)\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a conformal Killing vector with the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\dot{a}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the case of null geodesics, the behavior of timelike geodesics in
 the presence of a conformal Killing vector is not as straightforward to
 describe without additional assumptions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has a conformal Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, and consider particles moving along a timelike geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 normalized as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 The relative velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 of the particles with respect to the conformally stationary observers is
 characterized by the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 according to the standard special relativistic formula for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gamma factor,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma\equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\left(\delta\vec{v}\right)^{2}}}=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

We would like to derive an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 along a particle's wordline parameterized by the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This is possible in the following special case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-de-Sitter-friction}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-de-Sitter-friction}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider stationary observers whose worldlines are parallel to the conformal
 Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=e^{Ht}\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 for de Sitter spacetime with the metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:de Sitter}

\end_inset

).
 A point particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is moving along a timelike geodesic; the motion is slow relative to the
 conformally stationary observers.
 Show that the relative 3-velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 of the particle decreases exponentially at late times.
 In the Newtonian approximation, the slowdown can be ascribed to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational friction force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}$
\end_inset

 which is proportional to the velocity according to the law 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{F}=-mH\delta\vec{v}.\]

\end_inset

(Details 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-de-Sitter-friction}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a more general situation, a closed equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be derived if we assume additionally that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
integrable
\emph default
 vector field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Integrable-conformal-Killing}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-Integrable-conformal-Killing}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is an integrable, timelike conformal Killing vector field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=2\lambda g$
\end_inset

; the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=z^{-1}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the redshift function, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a timelike geodesic normalized by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\equiv g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\gamma=\left(1-\gamma^{2}\right)\lambda z^{-1}.\label{eq:conformal Killing timelike trajectory}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-Integrable-conformal-Killing}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particle moving with a small relative velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 with respect to conformally stationary observers, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:conformal Killing timelike trajectory}

\end_inset

) can be interpreted in the Newtonian limit.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\approx1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\delta\vec{v}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, so Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:conformal Killing timelike trajectory}

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as the equation for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local kinetic energy,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}E_{\text{kin}}=\delta\vec{v}\cdot\vec{F},\quad\vec{F}\equiv-m\lambda z^{-1}\delta\vec{v},\quad E_{\text{kin}}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(\delta\vec{v}\right)^{2}.\]

\end_inset

According to the Newtonian description from the viewpoint of a conformally
 stationary observer, the kinetic energy of the particle is decreased due
 to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

force of gravitational friction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}$
\end_inset

 that acts opposite and proportional to the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 of the particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gravitational potential
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Gravitational-potential}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Newtonian-limit}

\end_inset

 we have seen that the Schwarzschild spacetime possesses a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 such that the 3-acceleration of freely falling bodies in stationary reference
 frames is described by the Newtonian formula, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=-\vec{\nabla}\Phi$
\end_inset

.
 This fact is a manifestation of a more general property: Every stationary
 spacetime admits a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this sense.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{gravitational potential}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
After problem 4a in chapter 6 of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a Killing vector, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is integrable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is timelike (a stationary spacetime), show that the acceleration field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is integrable for a stationary observer with the 4-velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=z^{-1}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\sqrt{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 is the redshift factor.
 Derive the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the acceleration field 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Derivation:
\emph default
 For an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{x})=-g(\mathbf{k},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{k})=-\mathbf{x}\circ\frac{1}{2}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})=-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}z^{2},\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}=\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}f$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv-\frac{1}{2}z^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=z^{-1}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}z=0$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u} & =\frac{1}{z}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\frac{\mathbf{k}}{z}\right)=\frac{1}{z^{2}}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}+\frac{\mathbf{k}}{z}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{1}{z}\\
 & =\frac{1}{z^{2}}\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k}=-\frac{1}{2}\hat{g}^{-1}\frac{1}{z^{2}}\textrm{d}\left(z^{2}\right)\\
 & =-\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\ln z.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gravitational potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi=\ln z=\frac{1}{2}\ln g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}),\quad\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}=-\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\Phi.\]

\end_inset

(Note the minus sign in the above formula: The 4-acceleration of a freely
 falling body in a stationary frame is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, and the 3-acceleration, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=-\vec{\nabla}\Phi$
\end_inset

, has the opposite sign relative to the 4-acceleration.
 
\series bold
***Alarm: what about the minus sign we get while computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\Phi$
\end_inset

 from the minus sign in the spatial components of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

?
\series default
) This general expression agrees with the result\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Phi potential}

\end_inset

) derived above for the Schwarzschild spacetime with the Killing vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\equiv\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi=\frac{1}{2}\ln g(\partial_{t},\partial_{t})=\frac{1}{2}\ln\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to our (so far) heuristic picture of an asymptotically flat spacetime
 as something generated by a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

well-isolated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 clump of gravitating matter, we expect that at large distances the acceleration
 of stationary observers goes to zero, thus the gravitational potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 becomes constant.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi=\ln z$
\end_inset

, this is equivalent to assuming that the redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 becomes constant at infinite distances.
 Then it is convenient to multiply the Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 by a constant to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 at infinity.
 After this rescaling, the redshift function 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 describes the redshift of lightrays with respect to observers at infinite
 distances.
 
\end_layout

