\begin_layout Subsection
Energy 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a stationary spacetime, the Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 generates time translations along the stationary worldlines.
 The local geometry of the spacetime is invariant under these time translations:
 for instance, the scalar product of connecting vectors remains constant.
 The existence of such time translations, in turn, leads to a conserved
 quantity, interpreted as the total energy of the spacetime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the distortion 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 of a Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{k})}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{y})=-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

In the index notation, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
B_{(\mathbf{k})\alpha\beta}=\nabla_{\alpha}k_{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

 The divergence of this 2-form is a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e_{\beta}\equiv\nabla^{\alpha}B_{(\mathbf{k})\alpha\beta}=\nabla^{\alpha}\nabla_{\alpha}k_{\beta}\equiv\square k_{\beta};\quad\mathbf{e}=\square\mathbf{k}.\]

\end_inset

Written in the index-free notation, the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is significantly more cumbersome,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
e\circ\mathbf{z} & \equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}B_{(\mathbf{k})}\right]\circ(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\\
 & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{z})-g(\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y}},\mathbf{z})-g(\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{k},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{z})\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we shall use the index notation in the following calculations.
 The 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is divergence-free,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is divergence-free can be also understood as a consequence of the identity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{dd}*B_{(\mathbf{k})}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 is the Hodge star 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hodge star}

\end_inset

operation.
 Thus the integral of the 3-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}*B_{(\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 over a 3-volume can be expressed through an integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $*B_{(\mathbf{k})}$
\end_inset

 over a closed 2-surface.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla^{\beta}e_{\beta}=\nabla^{\beta}\nabla^{\alpha}B_{(\mathbf{k})\alpha\beta}=0,\]

\end_inset

therefore it defines a conserved vector current 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}\equiv\hat{g}^{-1}e$
\end_inset

.
 The flux of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 through a (spacelike) 3-volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with a (timelike) normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is constant, up to boundary terms.
 Assuming that the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extends to infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and that the current 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 vanishes sufficiently quickly at infinity so that all the boundary terms
 vanish, we find that the quantity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{E}\equiv\int_{V}\left(e\circ\mathbf{v}\right)\textrm{d}^{3}V\equiv\int_{V}e_{\beta}v^{\beta}\textrm{d}^{3}V=\int_{V}\left(\square k_{\beta}\right)v^{\beta}\textrm{d}^{3}V\]

\end_inset

is independent of the choice of the 3-volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conserved charge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that corresponds to the conserved current 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}$
\end_inset

 can be written as an integral over a closed spacelike 2-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 which is the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{E}=\oint_{\Sigma}\left(\nabla_{\alpha}k_{\beta}\right)v^{\alpha}n^{\beta}\textrm{d}^{2}\Sigma,\label{eq:energy surface integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are normal to the 2-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The 2-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 lies outside of any matter sources and encircles the entire matter distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now express 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}$
\end_inset

 through the matter distribution using the Einstein equation.
 It is again more convenient to work in the index notation.
 We have seen in Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Exercise:nabla nabla Killing}

\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}k_{\alpha}=R_{\nu\alpha\mu}{}^{\beta}k_{\beta}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
e_{\beta} & =\square k_{\beta}=g^{\alpha\gamma}R_{\alpha\beta\gamma}{}^{\delta}k_{\delta}=R_{\beta\delta}k^{\delta},\\
e\circ\mathbf{x} & =\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{k}),\\
\tilde{E} & =\int_{V}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{k})\textrm{d}^{3}V=\int_{V}R_{\mu\nu}v^{\mu}k^{\nu}\textrm{d}^{3}V.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{E}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the total energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of the gravitating system in the Newtonian limit, where the gravitating
 matter is an isolated, stationary distribution of dust with density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The energy of such a system is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=\int_{V}\rho\textrm{d}^{3}V,\]

\end_inset

and the energy-momentum tensor is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{\mu\nu}=\rho v_{\mu}v_{\nu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\approx\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 are the stationary worldlines of matter particles.
 By the Einstein equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Einstein}

\end_inset

), we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}=-8\pi(T_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}Tg_{\mu\nu}),\]

\end_inset

therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}v^{\mu}k^{\nu}=-4\pi\rho v_{\mu}v_{\nu}v^{\mu}k^{\nu}\approx-4\pi\rho\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{E}=\int_{V}R_{\mu\nu}v^{\mu}k^{\nu}\textrm{d}^{3}V\approx-4\pi\int_{V}\rho\textrm{d}^{3}V=-4\pi E.\]

\end_inset

 Thus the total energy of the system is, in the Newtonian approximation,
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E\approx-\frac{1}{4\pi}\tilde{E}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are therefore motivated to 
\emph on
define
\emph default
 the total energy contained in a stationary spacetime by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\tilde{E}=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\int_{V}\left(\square k_{\beta}\right)v^{\beta}\textrm{d}^{3}V.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the total energy of the Schwarzschild spacetime with the metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Schwarzschild}

\end_inset

).
 The Killing vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\equiv\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 It is convenient to use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:energy surface integral}

\end_inset

) and integrate over a 2-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 of a large radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing the normal vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=z^{-1}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=z\partial_{r}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\oint_{\Sigma}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{n})\textrm{d}^{2}\Sigma=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\oint_{\Sigma}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k},\partial_{r})\textrm{d}^{2}\Sigma.\]

\end_inset

Since (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Gravitational-potential}

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
z & =z(r)=\sqrt{1-\frac{2m}{r}},\\
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{k},\partial_{r}) & =-\frac{1}{2}\partial_{r}z^{2}=-\frac{m}{r^{2}},\end{align*}

\end_inset

we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=\frac{1}{4\pi}\oint_{\Sigma}\frac{m}{r^{2}}\textrm{d}^{2}\Sigma=m.\]

\end_inset

Thus the total energy of the Schwarzschild spacetime is equal to the mass
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 of the source of gravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total momentum and the total angular momentum of an isolated system
 are so far undefined.
 (There is no preferred reference frame with respect to which one would
 measure the total momentum or angular momentum.) A satisfactory definition
 of these quantities requires more information than the existence of a timelike
 Killing vector.
 For instance, symmetry with respect to rotations around an axis leads to
 conservation of the corresponding component of the angular momentum.
 In a curved spacetime, there are no preferred axes, so instead the rotational
 symmetry is formulated as the existence of a spacelike Killing vector with
 closed orbits (these orbits play the role of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

circles of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $r,\theta$
\end_inset

 around the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In a stationary spacetime there exists also a timelike Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
 If these two Killing vectors commute, the spacetime is called 
\series bold
azimuthally symmetric
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{azimuthally symmetric spacetime}

\end_inset

 In such a spacetime, the total angular momentum is well-defined and conserved.
 In the Newtonian limit, this quantity will correspond to the total angular
 momentum with respect to the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conformal infinity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we considered a stationary spacetime where the
 total energy of an isolated system can be defined through an integral over
 an infinitely remote 2-surface [see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:energy surface integral}

\end_inset

)].
 It appears that such a definition only requires that a spacetime be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asymptotically stationary,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is, almost stationary sufficiently far from the matter sources.
 In fact, it would be convenient if we could evaluate the 2-surface integral
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where the spacetime is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exactly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stationary (in a heuristic sense).
 The notion of conformal infinity allows one to make these ideas precise.
 We shall approach this notion by considering the elementary example of
 a flat Minkowski spacetime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conformal infinity for Minkowski spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall be able to evaluate quantities 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if we extend the spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by adding 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

points at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to it.
 A convenient way to produce such an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extended
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spacetime manifold is by using a conformal transformation of the metric,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda}g$
\end_inset

, such that the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\lambda}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at infinity.
 Then the infinitely remote points can be located at finite distances according
 to the new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, the new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
unphysical
\emph default
 since it does not describe actual distances or time intervals in the spacetime.
 However, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 is related to the physical metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by a conformal transformation, which preserves important causal properties
 of the spacetime.
 Here we describe such a conformal transformation for the Minkowski metric;
 later, we will consider more general spacetimes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the 
\series bold
lightcone coordinates
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{lightcone coordinates}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u,v,\theta,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the Minkowski spacetime, which are defined through the standard spherical
 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,r,\theta,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

 via
\begin_inset Formula \[
u\equiv t+r,\quad v\equiv t-r.\]

\end_inset

The 
\series bold
radial lightrays
\series default
 are then lines of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The metric has the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=du\, dv-\frac{\left(u-v\right)^{2}}{4}dS^{2},\quad dS^{2}\equiv d\theta^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta d\phi^{2}.\]

\end_inset

A conformal transformation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conformal transformation}

\end_inset

of the metric, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda(u,v)}g,\label{eq:transf g conf 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(u,v)$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (but not of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\phi$
\end_inset

), leaves the radial lightrays invariant (see Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:conf-leaves-radial}

\end_inset

).
 The transformed (unphysical) metric can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{g}=d\tilde{u}\, d\tilde{v}-e^{2\lambda}\frac{\left(u-v\right)^{2}}{4}dS^{2}\equiv d\tilde{u}\, d\tilde{v}-\tilde{r}^{2}dS^{2},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u},\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 are new lightcone coordinates,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{u}=f_{1}(u),\quad\tilde{v}=f_{1}(v).\]

\end_inset

For simplicity, let us choose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(s)=f_{2}(s)=f(s)$
\end_inset

.
 (Choosing more complicated functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 is certainly admissible but will make our work harder.) Then we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
e^{2\lambda}=f^{\prime}(u)f^{\prime}(v);\quad\tilde{r}^{2}=f^{\prime}(u)f^{\prime}(v)\frac{(u-v)^{2}}{4}.\]

\end_inset

It is obvious that the lines of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 are at the same time lines of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the radial lines of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 are null generators of a 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, which are always geodesics (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Null-functions-generate}

\end_inset

).
 In this case, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(u,v)$
\end_inset

 has a particularly simple form; the following statement shows that radial
 lightrays remain geodesics in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=e^{2\lambda(u,v)}g$
\end_inset

 even with an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(u,v)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-:conf-leaves-radial}

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-:conf-leaves-radial}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 In a two-dimensional spacetime, 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 null curve is a geodesic curve.
 
\series bold
(b)
\series default
 The radial null geodesics (lightrays) are invariant under a conformal transform
ation of the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:transf g conf 1}

\end_inset

), where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a flat metric.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-conf-leaves-radial}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next important step is the following: the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 can be chosen such that the new lightcone coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u},\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 have a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 
\emph on
range
\emph default
.
 There are many possible choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

; for example,
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(s)=\frac{2}{\pi}\arctan s;\quad f(s)=\tanh s;\quad f(s)=\textrm{erf }s;\]

\end_inset

etc.
 With any of the above choices, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $s\rightarrow\pm\infty$
\end_inset

.
 So at large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 the unphysical metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 is flat on the sections of constant angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,\theta$
\end_inset

 and describes the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u},\tilde{v}=\pm1$
\end_inset

 as being at finite (unphysical) distances, although physically these points
 correspond to infinitely remote events 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v=\pm\infty$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, one can introduce the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{t},\tilde{r},\theta,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

 by defining
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{u}\equiv\tilde{t}+\tilde{r},\quad\tilde{v}\equiv\tilde{t}-\tilde{r}.\]

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{t},\tilde{r}\right\} $
\end_inset

 (
\series bold
time-radial
\series default
) section of the spacetime (with the angular coordinates omitted) is sketched
 in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Unphysical-manifold}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

