\begin_layout Standard
As we described above, the unphysical manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 is constructed from the original spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by changing the metric from 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 and adding the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely far away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 domains 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}=\pm1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
manifold
\emph default
 
\emph on
with boundary
\emph default
.
 The boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 consists of null lines (future null infinity and past null infinity), the
 spacelike infinity domain 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{0}$
\end_inset

, and timelike future infinity/past infinity points 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\pm}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\lambda}$
\end_inset

 vanishes on the boundary; this is what brings infinity to finite distances
 in the unphysical manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see that the choice of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 is not entirely arbitrary, consider the spacelike infinity domain 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow\infty,v\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

).
 This domain is formally a 2-sphere of radius
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\tilde{r}^{2}(i^{0}) & =\lim_{r\rightarrow\infty}e^{\lambda}r^{2}=\lim_{{v\rightarrow-\infty\atop u\rightarrow\infty}}f^{\prime}(u)f^{\prime}(v)\frac{(u-v)^{2}}{4}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)\rightarrow\pm1$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $s\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(s)$
\end_inset

 must go to zero at large 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(s)$
\end_inset

 tends to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim s^{-n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

; then the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r}^{2}(i^{0})$
\end_inset

 depends on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 then the limit is zero, meaning that the domain of a ``spacelike infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a sphere of zero radius, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a 
\emph on
point
\emph default
.
 In the opposite case, 
\begin_inset Formula $n<2$
\end_inset

, the limit is infinite, which means that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 diverges (is not regular) at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we are motivated to consider only the regular case 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may restrict the choice of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

 further.
 Let us consider the limit of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 along a fixed lightray, say 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r}^{2}$
\end_inset

 of the metric is then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{r}^{2}=\lim_{v\rightarrow\infty}f^{\prime}(u_{0})f^{\prime}(v)\frac{(u_{0}-v)^{2}}{4}.\]

\end_inset

This limit is equal to zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

 but is finite and nonzero when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(s)\sim f_{0}s^{-2}$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{r}^{2}(\mathscr I^{+})=\frac{1}{4}f_{0}f^{\prime}(u_{0})>0.\]

\end_inset

 We expect that the structure of the null infinity should reflect the fact
 that null rays can be emitted in all directions spanning a 2-sphere.
 Thus, the null infinity at a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}=f(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 should have a metric structure of a 2-sphere with a nonzero radius.
 This is the case only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(s)\propto s^{-2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\rightarrow\pm\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we shall only consider these choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the future null infinity, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scri-plus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), has the topological structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times S^{2}$
\end_inset

 (a 2-sphere for each value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}=\alpha$
\end_inset

), while a spacelike infinity is represented by a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic form of the unphysical metric near a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u=u_{0},v=\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{g}\approx d\tilde{u}\, d\tilde{v}-\frac{f_{0}f^{\prime}(u_{0})}{4}dS^{2},\]

\end_inset

while the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega\approx\frac{1}{f_{0}}\left(1-\tilde{u}\right)\left(1-\tilde{v}\right).\]

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\sim r^{-1}$
\end_inset

 at large distances.
