\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, it is also easy to see that the null infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 is a null surface: The normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv\hat{\tilde{g}}^{-1}\textrm{d}\Omega$
\end_inset

 is null on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 (but not away from it!) since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\tilde{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\Omega,\textrm{d}\Omega)\propto\left(1-\tilde{u}\right)\left(1-\tilde{v}\right)\propto\Omega=0\;\textrm{ on }\mathscr I^{+}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that there still remains a considerable freedom in choosing the conformal
 transformations.
 However, within the present scheme every lightray will always be represented
 in a diagram by a straight line drawn at 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 angles, and the null future boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 will be a null surface.
 
\end_layout

