\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that the Riemann tensor has only one independent component in a 2-dimension
al spacetime.
 Then use the following expression for the curvature scalar in the unphysical
 metric,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}=\Omega^{-2}R+6\Omega^{-3}\square\Omega,\label{eq:R conformal transf}\end{equation}

\end_inset

to show that any 2-dimensional metric can be transformed into a 
\emph on
flat
\emph default
 metric by a choice of a conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 (The above equation is derived e.g.\InsetSpace ~
in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Gero77}

\end_inset

.
 See also Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{par:Statement-:Riemann-conformal}

\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric bilinear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\wedge\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

; for a 2-dimensional vector space with a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, any exterior product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the basis product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, so the space of exterior products 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 is effectively a symmetric bilinear function in one-dimensional space.
 Such a function is fully specified by one coefficient, say 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2})$
\end_inset

, or equivalently by the curvature scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $R=2R(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear from the given relation that the curvature scalar can be made
 to vanish by a choice of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Then the unphysical spacetime will have an identically vanishing Riemann
 tensor, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
it will be flat.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conformal diagrams 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section we explored the construction of a conformal infinity
 for Minkowski spacetime.
 The result was an unphysical 4-dimensional manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 containing all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and additionally some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely remote points.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unphysical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since it did not represent actual distances.
 However, this unphysical manifold allows one to evaluate quantities 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and hence is useful for the analysis of asymptotic behavior of fields in
 the real spacetime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important application of the unphysical manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 is as a tool to help visualize the causal structure of the physical spacetime
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a visualization is possible if one considers a 1+1-dimensional slice
 of the physical spacetime.
 This slice is a 1+1-dimensional spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{(1+1)}$
\end_inset

 having a certain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reduced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metric.
 This metric can be transformed into a flat Minkowski metric by a conformal
 transformation.
 Then, a coordinate transformation can be performed such that the manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{(1+1)}$
\end_inset

 is mapped into into a 1+1-dimensional unphysical manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 having a finite extent in all directions.
 The resulting manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 can be simply drawn as a figure on a plane.
 (Implicitly, the plane carries the unphysical flat Minkowski metric; in
 particular, straight lines drawn at 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 angles are null geodesics.) An example of such a drawing is Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Unphysical-manifold}

\end_inset

.
 Figures of this kind are called 
\series bold
conformal diagrams
\series default
 (also 
\series bold
Carter-Penrose diagrams
\series default
).
 We now explore conformal diagrams in more detail.
