\begin_layout Subsection*
Standard procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A conformal diagram is defined for a 1+1-dimensional spacetime with a given
 line element 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ab}dx^{a}dx^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0,1$
\end_inset

) must cover the 
\emph on
entire
\emph default
 spacetime, and several sets of overlapping coordinate patches may be used
 if necessary.
 The standard construction of the conformal diagram may be formulated as
 follows (see e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BirDav82}

\end_inset

, chapter\InsetSpace ~
3).
 One first finds a change of coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 such that the new variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{a}$
\end_inset

 have a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 range of variation; the components of the metric change according to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ab}(x)dx^{a}dx^{b}=\tilde{g}_{ab}(\tilde{x})d\tilde{x}^{a}d\tilde{x}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 One then chooses a conformal transformation of the metric (in the new coordinat
es), 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{g}_{ab}\rightarrow\gamma_{ab}\left(\tilde{x}\right)=\Omega^{2}\left(\tilde{x}\right)\tilde{g}_{ab},\quad\Omega\left(\tilde{x}\right)\neq0,\label{eq:g transf}\end{equation}

\end_inset

such that the new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is flat, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
has zero curvature.
 A suitable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(\tilde{x})$
\end_inset

 always exists because all two-dimensional metrics are conformally flat.
 The new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

 describes an unphysical, auxiliary flat spacetime.
 Since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is flat, a further change of coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\tilde{x}}$
\end_inset

 (the new variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\tilde{x}}$
\end_inset

 again having a finite extent) can be found to transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ab}$
\end_inset

 explicitly into the Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{ab}\left(\tilde{x}\right)d\tilde{x}^{a}d\tilde{x}^{b}=\eta_{ab}d\tilde{\tilde{x}}^{a}d\tilde{\tilde{x}}^{b},\quad\eta_{ab}\equiv\textrm{diag}\left(1,-1\right).\label{eq:omega eta}\end{equation}

\end_inset

For brevity we incorporate all the required coordinate changes into one,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\tilde{x}(x)$
\end_inset

, and summarize the transformation of the metric as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega^{2}\left(x\right)g_{ab}dx^{a}dx^{b}=\eta_{ab}d\tilde{x}^{a}d\tilde{x}^{b}.\label{eq:g transf short}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Thus the new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{a}$
\end_inset

 map the initial spacetime onto a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 domain within a 1+1-dimensional Minkowski plane.
 This finite domain is a 
\series bold
conformal diagram
\series default
 of the initial (physical) 1+1-dimensional spacetime.
 The diagram is drawn on a sheet of paper which implicitly carries the fiducial
 Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

, the vertical axis usually representing the timelike coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coordinate and conformal transformations severely distort the geometry
 of the spacetime since they bring infinite spacetime points to finite distances
 in the diagram plane.
 So one cannot expect in general that straight lines in the diagram correspond
 to geodesics in the physical spacetime.
 However, it is well known that straight lines drawn at 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 angles in a conformal diagram represent null geodesics in the physical
 spacetime.
 This follows from the fact that any null trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 in 1+1 dimensions, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
any solution of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{ab}\dot{x}^{a}\dot{x}^{b}=0,\quad\dot{x}^{a}\equiv\frac{dx^{a}}{d\tau},\label{eq:g x x}\end{equation}

\end_inset

is necessarily a geodesic (this is not true in higher dimensions), and Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g x x}

\end_inset

) is invariant under conformal transformations of the metric.
 By drawing lightrays emitted from various points in the diagram, one can
 illustrate the causal structure of the spacetime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A textbook example is the conformal diagram for the flat Minkowski spacetime
 with the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ab}\equiv\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Calculations are conveniently done in the lightcone coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u\equiv x^{0}-x^{1},\; v\equiv x^{0}+x^{1},\;\eta_{ab}dx^{a}dx^{b}=du\, dv,\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and a suitable coordinate transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{u}=\tanh u,\;\tilde{v}=\tanh v,\; du\, dv=\frac{d\tilde{u}\, d\tilde{v}}{\left(1-\tilde{u}^{2}\right)\left(1-\tilde{v}^{2}\right)}.\label{eq:Mink lightcone}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u},\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 extend from 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying the metric by the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}(\tilde{u},\tilde{v})\equiv\left(1-\tilde{u}^{2}\right)\left(1-\tilde{v}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, we obtain the fiducial spacetime,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
 & \Omega^{2}du\, dv=d\tilde{u}\, d\tilde{v}=\eta_{ab}d\tilde{x}^{a}d\tilde{x}^{b},\\
 & \tilde{u}\equiv\tilde{x}^{0}-\tilde{x}^{1},\quad\tilde{v}\equiv\tilde{x}^{0}+\tilde{x}^{1}.\end{align}

\end_inset

The new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{a}$
\end_inset

 have a finite extent, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}^{0}\pm\tilde{x}^{1}\right|<1$
\end_inset

, and the resulting diagram has a diamond shape shown in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Minkowski}

\end_inset

.
 To appreciate the distortion of the spacetime geometry, we can draw the
 worldline of an inertial observer moving with a constant velocity.
 Note that the angle at which this trajectory enters the endpoints depends
 on the chosen conformal transformation and thus cannot serve as an indication
 of the observer's velocity.
\end_layout

