Before presenting examples, I comment on the proposed definition of conformal
 diagrams.
 The definition may appear to be too broad, allowing many geometric shapes
 to represent the same spacetime.
 However, the old procedure also does not specify a particular conformal
 transformation of the metric and in effect admits precisely as much freedom.
 According to the new definition, any two different conformal diagrams of
 the same spacetime are equivalent in the sense that all the lightrays in
 those two diagrams will be in an intersection-preserving one-to-one corresponde
nce.
 In the old language, there must exist a conformal transformation bringing
 one diagram into the other.
 Equivalent diagrams carry identical information about the causal structure
 of the physical spacetime.
 In the next sections I shall give examples illustrating the arbitrary and
 the necessary choices involved in drawing conformal diagrams.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A conformal diagram delivers information mainly through the shape of its
 boundary line.
 The boundary of a conformal diagram generally contains points representing
 a spacelike, timelike, or null infinity, and points belonging to explicit
 boundaries of the spacetime manifold (e.g.\InsetSpace ~
singularities) where lightrays
 end in the physical spacetime.
 The latter boundaries will be called
\series bold
 physical boundaries
\series default
 to distinguish them from putative
\series bold
 infinite boundaries 
\series default
whose points do not correspond to any events in the physical spacetime.
 (The definition of conformal diagrams contains the requirement that the
 diagram domain be topologically open, and so the boundary points are not
 supposed to belong to the diagram.) The infinite boundary is of course the
 most interesting feature of a diagram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly, I would like to emphasize that conformal diagrams can be drawn not
 only for geodesically complete spacetimes but also for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

artificially incomplete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spacetimes, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
for selected subdomains of larger manifolds.
 In fact such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

artificially incomplete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spacetimes are often needed in cosmological applications.
 Examples are a description of a collapsing star using a subdomain of the
 Kruskal spacetime and a description of an inflationary universe using a
 subdomain of the de Sitter spacetime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Minkowski spacetime
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Minkowski-spacetime}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new definition merely lists the conditions to be satisfied by a conformal
 diagram.
 Based on these conditions, I now develop a practical procedure for drawing
 the diagrams, using the Minkowski spacetime as the first example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by choosing a Cauchy surface in the physical spacetime.
 In 1+1 dimensions, a Cauchy surface is a line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 such that intersections of lightrays emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 entirely cover the part of the spacetime to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 In the Minkowski spacetime, we may choose the line 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}=0$
\end_inset

 as the Cauchy surface 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The image of the Cauchy surface 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in the conformal diagram must be a finite curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}$
\end_inset

 from which lightrays can be emitted in both spatial directions.
 Therefore the slope of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}$
\end_inset

