\begin_layout Subsection
How to draw conformal diagrams
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:General-procedure}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now outline a general procedure for building a conformal diagram
 for a given 1+1-dimensional spacetime using the method of lightrays.
 The procedure can be applied not only to geodesically complete spacetimes
 but also to spacetimes with explicitly specified boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One starts by considering the future-directed part of the spacetime and
 by choosing a suitable Cauchy surface and, possibly, some timelike boundaries.
 These lines are represented in the diagram by arbitrarily drawn horizontal
 and vertical curves of finite extent.
 The endpoints of these curves correspond either to the intersection points
 of Cauchy lines and timelike boundaries, or to imaginary points at spacelike
 and timelike infinity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Cauchy surfaces and timelike boundaries are the lines on which
 boundary conditions for e.g.\InsetSpace ~
a wave equation must be specified to obtain a
 unique solution within a domain.
 One expects that any physically relevant spacetime should contain a suitable
 set of Cauchy surfaces and timelike boundaries, if the classical field
 theory is to have predictive power.
 Qualitative knowledge of the geometry and topology of these boundaries
 is required for building a conformal diagram using the method of lightrays.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After drawing the curves for the physical boundaries, it remains to determine
 the shape of the infinite (timelike and null) boundaries of the diagram.
 To this end, one can first consider 
\emph on
right-directed
\emph default
 lightrays emitted from various points on the Cauchy line and from the boundarie
s, including the limit points at infinity.
 For each right-directed lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 there exists a certain subset 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal S}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of (left-directed) lightrays that intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since the subset 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal S}_{X}$
\end_inset

 has a finite extent, there exists a rightmost ray 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X}\in{\cal S}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 (In the de Sitter example above, the rightmost ray 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the ray 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and the rightmost ray 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.) By definition of the conformal diagram, the lightrays are straight lines
 limited only by the boundary of the conformal diagram, therefore the intersecti
on point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X}$
\end_inset

 must belong to the boundary.
 In this way we have established the location of one point of the unknown
 boundary line, namely the endpoint of the ray 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the local direction of the boundary line at that point, we
 use the following argument.
 For each right-directed lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can consider a right-directed ray 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 infinitesimally close and to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (if no ray 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 can be found to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, it means that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 itself belongs to the boundary of the diagram).
 Then there are two possibilities (see Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:general procedure}

\end_inset

