\begin_inset Formula $r_{X}$
\end_inset

 is also the rightmost ray 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X'}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

, or the ray 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X'}$
\end_inset

 is located to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 In the first case, the boundary line has a 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 slope and locally coincides with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{X}$
\end_inset

, while in the second case the boundary line is horizontally-directed.
 Thus we can draw a right-directed fragment of the infinite boundary that
 limits the ray 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We then continue by moving further to the right and consider the endpoint
 of the ray 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

, etc.
\end_layout

