\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us briefly consider the pasting of conformal diagrams in general.
 When two spacetime domains are separated by a timelike worldline, the correspon
ding conformal diagrams can be pasted together along the boundary line.
 To verify this almost obvious statement more formally, we begin by drawing
 the timelike boundary as a vertically-directed line in the diagram.
 The shape of the conformal diagram to the right of the boundary is determined
 solely by the intersections of lightrays within the right half of the spacetime.
 Hence, the conformal diagram for the right half of the spacetime can be
 pasted to the right of the timelike boundary line.
 The same holds for the left half of the spacetime.
 This justifies pasting of diagrams along a common timelike boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Further examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Collapsing star
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of lightrays does not require explicit formulae for the spacetime
 metric if the qualitative behavior of lightrays is known.
 As another example of using the lightray method, let us consider an asymptotica
lly flat spacetime with a star collapsing to a black hole (BH).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reduce the spacetime to 1+1 dimensions, we assume spherical symmetry
 and consider only the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,t\right)$
\end_inset

 plane, where 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<+\infty$
\end_inset

 and the line 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, the center of the star, is an artificial boundary.
 As before, we start with the future-directed part of the diagram.
 We must first choose a Cauchy surface; a suitable Cauchy surface is the
 line 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a time chosen before the collapse of the star.
 We represent the Cauchy surface by the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 in the diagram (Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:build star}

\end_inset

).
 The point 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponds to (
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

), while 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a spatial infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r=\infty,t=t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The artificial boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 is represented by the vertical line 
\begin_inset Formula $AC$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To investigate the shape of the future part of the diagram, we need to analyze
 the intersections of lightrays emitted from faraway points of the Cauchy
 surface.
 We know from qualitative considerations of the black hole formation that
 lightrays can escape from the star interior only until the appearance of
 the BH horizon.
 Shortly thereafter the star center becomes a singularity that cannot emit
 any lightrays.
