\begin_layout Standard
The concept of an asymptotically flat spacetime was invented to formalize
 the picture of a spacetime which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

similar to Minkowski near infinity.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Informally, a spacetime is asymptotically flat if it can be extended via
 a conformal transformation to include the infinity domain, and then if
 the structure of the infinity is the same as that of the Minkowski spacetime.
 A definition can be given more formally as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
asymptotically flat
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{asymptotically flat spacetime}

\end_inset

in the null future direction if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 to an (unphysical) manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 with an (unphysical) regular metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 and boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=\Omega^{2}g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 on the boundary, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}\Omega\neq0$
\end_inset

 everywhere (we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 the covariant derivative with respect to the unphysical metric).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 is a null surface (in the unphysical metric), i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a null function on the boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The boundary surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 has topology 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $-\tilde{\nabla}\Omega$
\end_inset

 is future-pointing at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 (as appropriate for the future boundary).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The energy-momentum tensor of matter (equivalently, the Ricci tensor) vanishes
 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 (This condition may be relaxed to vanishing only as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{4}$
\end_inset

 or faster.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these conditions, we shall now derive the existence of Minkowski-like
 coordinates 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at large distances.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 be the null vector dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $-d\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 First, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 implies that the auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv\Omega^{-1}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})$
\end_inset

 is smooth on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Secondly, there is a freedom to rescale the unphysical metric by a nowhere
 vanishing factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Under such a rescaling, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 changes as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f\rightarrow e^{-\lambda}\left(f+2\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda\right)\:\textrm{ on }\mathscr I^{+}.\label{eq:f change eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, a suitable choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 will make 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 There will remain the freedom to perform conformal transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}\rightarrow e^{2\lambda}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\lambda=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
with the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 constant along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f change eq}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 A replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}\rightarrow e^{2\lambda}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\rightarrow e^{\lambda}\Omega$
\end_inset

 because the physical metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-2}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 must remain fixed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\tilde{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\Omega,\textrm{d}\Omega)$
\end_inset

 and the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is metric-independent, we find that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 transforms under the above replacements as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
f & =\Omega^{-1}\tilde{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}\Omega,\textrm{d}\Omega)\\
 & \rightarrow e^{-\lambda}\Omega^{-1}e^{-2\lambda}\tilde{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}(e^{\lambda}\Omega),\textrm{d}(e^{\lambda}\Omega))\\
 & =e^{-\lambda}f+2e^{-2\lambda}\tilde{g}^{-1}(\textrm{d}e^{\lambda},\textrm{d}\Omega)+O(\Omega)\\
 & =e^{-\lambda}f+2e^{-2\lambda}\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}e^{\lambda}+O(\Omega).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we obtain the desired relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Need to check all conformal transformation equations against Appendix D
 of Wald!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A calculation shows that the unphysical Ricci tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is related to the physical one, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, by (see\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

 Appendix D)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
R_{\mu\nu} & =\tilde{R}_{\mu\nu}-2\Omega^{-1}\tilde{\nabla}_{\mu}\tilde{\nabla}_{\nu}\Omega\nonumber \\
 & -\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}\left(\Omega^{-1}\tilde{\nabla}_{\alpha}\tilde{\nabla}^{\alpha}\Omega-3\Omega^{-2}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})\right).\label{eq:R Rtilde}\end{align}

\end_inset

 We now multiply both sides of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R Rtilde}

\end_inset

) by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 vanishes in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is regular everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

 since it is a nonsingular manifold.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=O(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
2\tilde{\nabla}_{\mu}\tilde{\nabla}_{\nu}\Omega+\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}\tilde{\nabla}_{\alpha}\tilde{\nabla}^{\alpha}\Omega=0\:\textrm{ on }\mathscr I^{+}.\]

\end_inset

Contracting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}_{\mu}\tilde{\nabla}_{\nu}\Omega=0$
\end_inset

 or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a (null) geodesic, shear-free, and divergence-free vector field on 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 (The entire distortion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{(\mathbf{n})}$
\end_inset

 vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.) Note that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=0$
\end_inset

 could be also obtained from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R Rtilde}

\end_inset

) if we multiply both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 has the topology 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times S^{2}$
\end_inset

, we can select coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\phi$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 sections such that the partial metric is that of a sphere,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}S^{2}=\left(\textrm{d}\theta\otimes\textrm{d}\theta+\sin^{2}\theta\textrm{d}\phi\otimes\textrm{d}\phi\right)V.\]

\end_inset

 Since the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is divergence-free, the cross-section area of the 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 sections remains constant along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, thus the partial metric will have equal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 on every 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 section.
 So the remaining conformal freedom (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}\rightarrow e^{2\lambda}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

) can be used to set 
\begin_inset Formula $V=1$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined coordinate near 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv\hat{\tilde{g}}^{-1}d\Omega\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we can select a fourth coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 parametrizing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}=\mathbb{R}\times S^{2}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\circ u=1$
\end_inset

.
 The coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,\Omega,\theta,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

, where the metric has the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{g}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\textrm{d}u\otimes\textrm{d}\Omega+\textrm{d}\Omega\otimes\textrm{d}u\right)-\textrm{d}\theta\otimes\textrm{d}\theta-\sin^{2}\theta\textrm{d}\phi\otimes\textrm{d}\phi.\]

\end_inset

 A coordinate system in the physical manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by the replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 will then serve as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radial coordinate near infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a calculation showing the physical significance of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 (This seems VERY STRANGE.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is undefined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

; second, we can't use 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\emph on
physical
\emph default
 spacetime if we showed that its derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 are correct.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exercise: (probably incorrect!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\Omega^{-1}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\Omega^{-1}=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

, assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=O(\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is an affine parameter for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\circ\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is constant along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\Omega^{-1} & =\tilde{g}^{-1}(d\Omega,d\frac{1}{\Omega})=-\frac{1}{\Omega^{2}}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n});\\
\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\Omega^{-1} & =\frac{2}{\Omega^{3}}(\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{n}}\Omega)\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=\frac{2}{\Omega}\left[\frac{\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})}{\Omega}\right]^{2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1}\tilde{g}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=O(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, the r.h.s.\InsetSpace ~
above vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be used in the physical spacetime in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 as an affine parameter for the (almost) null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,r,\theta,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 is extended away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 into the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is chosen as a null function, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}\equiv\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}u$
\end_inset

 is a null vector such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is defined as an affine parameter along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}\circ r=1$
\end_inset

.
 The angular coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\phi$
\end_inset

 are kept constant along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{l}}\phi=\nabla_{\mathbf{l}}\theta=0$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting coordinate system asymptotically corresponds to spherical
 Minkowski coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,r,\theta,\phi\right\} $
\end_inset

 if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $u\equiv t+r$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

