This statement is justified in more detail in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

, p.
 280.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This local coordinate system is called the 
\series bold
Bondi coordinate system
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Bondi coordinate system}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we conclude that the assumptions of asymptotic flatness are a precise
 way of formulating the notion of a spacetime that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost Minkowski at large distances.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conformal radiation fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Very far from an isolated system, the spacetime is almost flat but there
 may still remain radiation (gravitational, electromagnetic, or other).
 We are interested in studying the structure of the radiation field at large
 distances.
 The construction of conformal infinity is especially helpful for this task,
 because radiation fields are 
\emph on
conformally invariant
\emph default
.
 Let us review some examples of conformally invariant fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scalar field in 1+1 dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action for a massless scalar field in a 1+1-dimensional spacetime is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[g,\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int\textrm{d}^{2}x\sqrt{-g}\, g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\phi,\textrm{d}\phi),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\equiv\sqrt{-\det g}$
\end_inset

 is the determinant of the 
\emph on
covariant
\emph default
 metric, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{2}x$
\end_inset

 is the invariant 2-volume element.
 This action is invariant under the conformal transformation of the metric,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=\Omega^{2}g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that the action is invariant under the above transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint:
\emph default
 In a 1+1-dimensional spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-\tilde{g}}=\Omega^{2}\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

.
 Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\Omega^{-2}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 into the action and use the independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from the metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scalar field in 3+1 dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action for a massless, conformally coupled scalar field is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[g,\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left(g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\phi,\textrm{d}\phi)-\frac{1}{6}R\phi^{2}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the scalar curvature.
 Again one can verify that the action is invariant under a conformal transformat
ion 
\begin_inset Formula $g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=\Omega^{2}g$
\end_inset

 (up to boundary terms), provided that the field is also transformed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}=\Omega^{-1}\phi.\]

\end_inset

The power of the conformal factor needed for the correct transformation
 law is called the 
\series bold
conformal weight
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conformal weight}

\end_inset

of the field.
 Thus a scalar field has conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 1+1 dimensions and weight 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 in 3+1 dimensions.
 Conformal invariance means that a solution of the equation of motion for
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 also gives a solution for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R conformal transf}

\end_inset

), show that the action is invariant under the above transformations (up
 to boundary terms).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint: 
\emph default
An integration by parts yields an equivalent form of the action,
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[g,\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left(-\phi\square\phi-\frac{1}{6}R\phi^{2}\right),\quad\square\equiv\nabla_{\alpha}\nabla^{\alpha}.\]

\end_inset

Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\Omega^{-2}\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\Omega\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 into this action, and replace 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R conformal transf}

\end_inset

).
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\square(\Omega\tilde{\phi})=\Omega\square\tilde{\phi}+\tilde{\phi}\square\Omega+2(\nabla_{\alpha}\Omega)(\nabla^{\alpha}\tilde{\phi}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electromagnetic field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electromagnetic field is described by the Maxwell tensor which is a
 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
F=\textrm{d}A,\quad F_{\mu\nu}=\partial_{\mu}A_{\nu}-\partial_{\nu}A_{\mu},\]

\end_inset

where the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the electromagnetic potential.
 The action for the Maxwell field is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[g,F]=\frac{1}{16\pi}\int\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x\, g^{\lambda\nu}g^{\mu\rho}F_{\lambda\mu}F_{\nu\rho}.\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that this action is conformally invariant (in 3+1-dimensional
 spacetimes), the Maxwell field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 having conformal weight 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gravitational radiation field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Einstein equation relates the Ricci tensor to the distribution of matter
 in an algebraic way (if there is no matter at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the Ricci tensor is zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

).
 The Ricci tensor, however, is only the trace of the full Riemann tensor.
 Therefore, the curvature of spacetime contains degrees of freedom not algebraic
ally related to the distribution of matter.
 These degrees of freedom are described by the trace-free part of the Riemann
 tensor called the 
\series bold
Weyl tensor
\series default
,
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{\alpha\beta}{}_{\gamma\delta}=R^{\alpha\beta}{}_{\gamma\delta}+\frac{1}{2}\delta_{[\gamma}^{[\alpha}S_{\;\delta]}^{\beta]},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{\alpha\beta}\equiv R_{\alpha\beta}-\frac{1}{6}Rg_{\alpha\beta}\]

\end_inset

 is an auxiliary tensor carrying equivalent information to the Ricci tensor.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}=C_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}$
\end_inset

 in vacuum (where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha\beta}=0$
\end_inset

).
 It can be shown that the second Bianchi identity implies the constraints
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla^{\mu}C_{\mu\alpha\beta\gamma}+\nabla_{[\alpha}S_{\beta]\gamma} & =0,\\
\nabla^{\mu}S_{\alpha\mu}-\nabla_{\alpha}S_{\;\mu}^{\mu} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the absence of matter, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha\beta}=0$
\end_inset

 and thus we obtain the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{\mu}C_{\mu\alpha\beta\gamma}=0$
\end_inset

 which determines the dynamics of pure gravitational waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Weyl tensor has the simple and useful conformal transformation property
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{C}_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}=\Omega^{2}C_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}\quad\textrm{for}\quad\tilde{g}=\Omega^{2}g.\]

\end_inset

Another way to express this property is to say that the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}{}_{\beta\gamma\delta}$
\end_inset

 is conformally invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Asymptotic behavior of radiation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Radiation fields are massless and propagate along null geodesics (lightrays).
 Let us consider a lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that approaches null infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now characterize a radiation field along the lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, in the asymptotically far region near infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 the affine tangent vector to the lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 In the unphysical metric (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=\Omega^{2}g$
\end_inset

), the affine parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 should be replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}\tau$
\end_inset

, so that the corresponding affine tangent vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}=\Omega^{-2}\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 (see Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-Null-geodesic-conformal}

\end_inset

).
 Since the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}$
\end_inset

 is regular in the unphysical manifold, it should have a well-defined value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_{0}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the physical-space tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 must decay at infinity as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}\sim\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_{0}\Omega^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now complete 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 to a null tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\}$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Null-tetrad-formalism}

\end_inset

), obtain similar asymptotic properties for the tetrad at infinity, and
 study the asymptotic behavior of radiation fields using the tetrad components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Since the geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 should approach infinity, we may assume that (in the unphysical spacetime)
 the conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is an affine parameter for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}\circ\Omega=-1$
\end_inset

 (the minus sign is appropriate since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 decreases towards infinity), at least with a suitable choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the radius function 
\begin_inset Formula $r\equiv\Omega^{-1}$
\end_inset

 will be an affine parameter for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 in the physical spacetime since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}\circ\Omega^{-1}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
[This argument seems to be confusing and unnecessary!]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be completed to a null tetrad using the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{n}}\equiv-\hat{\tilde{g}}^{-1}\textrm{d}\Omega$
\end_inset

 and a complex-valued vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 is chosen in the orthogonal complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\mathbf{n}},\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_{0}\}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 The (unphysical) null tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_{0},\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\tilde{\mathbf{n}}\}$
\end_inset

 can be parallelly transported from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 using the unphysical metric, which produces null vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\tilde{\mathbf{n}}\}$
\end_inset

 defined along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\tilde{\mathbf{n}},\tilde{\mathbf{l}})=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\bar{\tilde{\mathbf{m}}})=-1$
\end_inset

 at every point.
 However, we need to find a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tetrad, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\}$
\end_inset

, normalized and parallelly transported along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 using the physical metric.
 We have already seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}=\Omega^{2}\tilde{\mathbf{l}}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector
\emph on
 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 of the physical tetrad can be chosen as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\tilde{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

 since we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(\tilde{\mathbf{n}},\tilde{\mathbf{l}})=g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})=1$
\end_inset

 everywhere along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the complex-valued vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 is selected from the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l}\}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 to be proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 The normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})=\tilde{g}(\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\bar{\tilde{\mathbf{m}}})=-1$
\end_inset

 shows that the unphysical-space vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{m}}$
\end_inset

 must be chosen as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{m}}=\Omega^{-1}\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the physical null tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and the unphysical one, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\tilde{\mathbf{n}}\}$
\end_inset

, must be related by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\{\Omega^{2}\tilde{\mathbf{l}},\Omega\tilde{\mathbf{m}},\tilde{\mathbf{n}}\}=\{\mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n}\}\]

\end_inset

everywhere along the lightray 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The convenience of the null tetrads is in the concise way they describe
 components of tensors.
 For example, the antisymmetric Maxwell tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 for the electromagnetic field is represented by three 
\series bold
tetrad components
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tetrad components of Maxwell tensor}

\end_inset

usually chosen as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\Phi_{0} & \equiv F(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m}),\\
\Phi_{1} & \equiv\frac{1}{2}F(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})-\frac{1}{2}F(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}}),\\
\Phi_{2} & \equiv F(\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{l}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

(The properties of the tetrad components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 are studied in the Statement below.) The unphysical components 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Phi}_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2$
\end_inset

, are given by the same equations with the unphysical tetrad.
 The relation between the physical and the unphysical components is therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_{0}=\Omega\tilde{\Phi}_{0},\quad\Phi_{1}=\Omega^{2}\tilde{\Phi}_{1},\quad\Phi_{2}=\Omega^{3}\tilde{\Phi}_{2}.\]

\end_inset

Since the Maxwell field is conformally invariant, the unphysical components
 will also satisfy the Maxwell equations and will have regular solutions
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 It is now easy to see that the component 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be the slowest-decaying one, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Phi_{0}\sim\Omega\sim\frac{1}{r},\]

\end_inset

while other components will decay faster.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 represent the field strength, which should decay as 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for a radiation field.
 Hence, it is clear that the the intensity of 
\emph on
outgoing radiation
\emph default
 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
energy carried away to infinity) must be independent of the two other
 components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, the radiated power is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Phi_{0}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the unphysical component 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Phi}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is constant at infinity, the differential intensity of radiation in a given
 (null) direction can be obtained directly by evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $|\tilde{\Phi}_{0}|^{2}$
\end_inset

 at a point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr I^{+}$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to the required asymptotic direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other radiation fields exhibit analogous properties.
 For example, a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 has the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radiation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 component 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\phi$
\end_inset

, while the gravitational radiation is described by the component
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Psi_{0}\equiv C_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}n^{\alpha}m^{\beta}n^{\gamma}m^{\delta}=R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{m});\]

\end_inset

note that this component of the Weyl tensor coincides with that of the Riemann
 tensor.
 The component 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 decays as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\Omega=r^{-1}$
\end_inset

 at infinity, and the intensity of gravitational radiation is proportional
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{0}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 All the other components of the Weyl tensor decay faster at infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The splitting of components according to their falloff behavior along null
 geodesics is called the 
\series bold
peeling property
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{peeling property}

\end_inset

 This property holds in general (even-dimensional) asymptotically flat spacetime
s and for all massless fields (of arbitrary spin).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Lorentz transformation of the tetrad that leaves the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 constant,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{m} & \rightarrow e^{\text{i}\phi}\mathbf{m}+A\mathbf{l},\\
\mathbf{n} & \rightarrow\mathbf{n}+e^{\text{i}\phi}\bar{A}\mathbf{m}+e^{-\text{i}\phi}A\bar{\mathbf{m}}+A\bar{A}\mathbf{l},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is real and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is complex.
 Under this transformation, the tetrad components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 of the Maxwell tensor change as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\Phi_{0} & \rightarrow e^{\text{i}\phi}\Phi_{0}+2A\Phi_{1}+A^{2}e^{-\text{i}\phi}\Phi_{2},\\
\Phi_{1} & \rightarrow\Phi_{1},\\
\Phi_{2} & \rightarrow e^{-\text{i}\phi}\Phi_{2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that the leading falloff behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{0}\sim r^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of the null tetrad.
 The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{l})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}})$
\end_inset

, taken separately, do not carry tetrad-independent information (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
one of
 these may be set to zero by a choice of tetrad).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Global techniques
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under 
\series bold
global techniques
\series default
 we understand considerations that involve entire manifolds or large domains,
 rather than 
\emph on
local
\emph default
 considerations (e.g.\InsetSpace ~
calculations involving properties of tensors and their
 derivatives at a single point).
 Global techniques can be used to answer questions such as whether there
 is a singularity anywhere, or whether a certain interesting subdomain of
 the spacetime is finite or infinite.
 In this chapter we shall introduce some of these techniques and consider
 some applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Singularity theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional literature: 
