\begin_layout Subsection
Singularities and geodesic incompleteness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that some spacetimes occurring in general relativity contain
 points where the force of gravity becomes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely large
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (more precisely, the geometric description of the spacetime breaks down).
 Such spacetimes are called 
\series bold
singular
\series default
.
 Two major examples of singular spacetimes are the Schwarzschild spacetime
 and a generic Friedmann-Robertson-Walker (FRW) spacetime.
 In the Schwarzschild spacetime, it is relatively easy to understand that
 the black hole center 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 represents a singularity because the curvature becomes infinite as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, indicating the presence of unboundedly large tidal forces.
 Also, every timelike or null geodesic entering the Schwarzschild radius
 cannot escape hitting the center within a finite time.
 No lightrays or timelike geodesics can be continued past that point because
 the geometry is singular and the geodesic equation becomes undefined (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
it
 does not predict how a body will move past the center).
 Since the tidal forces will tear apart any material objects approaching
 the center, it is reasonable to conclude that there is no sensible way
 to describe the evolution of an observer past the center of a black hole.
 Thus the center is a place where the geometry of the spacetime cannot be
 described by general relativity.
 In an FRW spacetime with the scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the curvature is unbounded near 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly to the Schwarzschild case, geodesics cannot be extended to the
 past beyond 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, so one cannot describe what happened to an observer before 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

beginning of time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for an FRW spacetime.
 It is reasonable to say that the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 in an FRW spacetime is singular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the spacetime manifold is not smooth at 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 points, it is natural to excise such points from the spacetime and to restrict
 the calculations to regular (nonsingular) points.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
It is conjectured that a quantum theory of gravity (to be developed) will
 replace 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singularities
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by some well-defined and finite new physics.
 At this point, it is safe to say that the classical theory of general relativit
y breaks down at singularities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Hence, one finds a curious situation: gravitational singularities are not
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

places
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and are not present 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anywhere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the spacetime manifold.
 Since all the singular points are removed, it is difficult to formulate
 a general definition of a singularity in terms of internal properties of
 the remaining nonsingular manifold.
 Nevertheless, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

presence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of singularities is usually manifested in several ways.
 For instance, the curvature may become infinite along a certain geodesic
 worldline, indicating that a freely falling observer following that worldline
 will experience unbounded tidal forces.
 Or, certain geodesics may have only a finite range of the affine parameter,
 because these geodesics 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hit a singularity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and cannot be extended any further.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An accepted way to define a singular spacetime is through the non-extensibility
 of geodesics.
 Intuitively, a geodesic should be able to extend 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

arbitrarily far
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (for an infinite range of the affine parameter) unless there is a singularity
 in the way.
 A spacetime is called 
\series bold
geodesically complete
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{geodesically complete spacetime}

\end_inset

if any geodesic is extendible to arbitrary values of the affine parameter.
 A geodesically 
\emph on
in
\emph default
complete spacetime is interpreted as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in some way.
 Usually, only timelike and null geodesics are used to determine geodesic
 completeness.
 (Note that a spacetime can be intuitively 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without containing any incomplete timelike and null geodesics because the
 singularity may be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely far away,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approachable after finite proper time only by a sufficiently highly accelerated
 observer, or by a spacelike geodesic.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presently known 
\series bold
singularity theorems
\series default
 are mathematical statements about conditions for a spacetime to be geodesically
 incomplete.
 Thus, these theorems only indicate the presence of singularities but neither
 predict their 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 nor characterize their physical properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
After 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

, Problem 9.1.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 be a timelike Killing vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 a (non-geodesic) timelike curve with tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|\leq\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|\left|\mathbf{a}\right|,\]

\end_inset

where the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}(\tau)\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the proper acceleration of the curve and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}\right|\equiv\sqrt{-g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})}$
\end_inset

.
 Deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 can change only by a finite amount along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\infty}\left|\mathbf{a}(\tau)\right|\textrm{d}\tau<\infty$
\end_inset

, which means that the worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be realized by a rocket with a finite amount of fuel.
 Show that the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 cannot reach any spacetime regions where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 becomes unbounded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 By the Killing property, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})=g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a})\right|<\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{a}\right|$
\end_inset

 for timelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and spacelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 We may decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=\alpha\mathbf{a}+\beta\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha\equiv\frac{g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a})}{g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})},\quad\beta\equiv g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 is a spacelike vector orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})>0$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})=\beta^{2}-\alpha^{2}\left|\mathbf{a}\right|^{2}-\left|\mathbf{s}\right|^{2}>0,\]

\end_inset

hence 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\beta\right|=\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|>\left|\alpha\right|\left|\mathbf{a}\right|=\frac{1}{\left|\mathbf{a}\right|}\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{a})\right|,\]

\end_inset

 which is equivalent to the desired inequality.
 Rewriting it as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\ln g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|<\left|\mathbf{a}\right|,\]

\end_inset

and integrating both sides, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left|\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\infty}\textrm{d}\tau\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\ln g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right| & \leq\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\infty}\textrm{d}\tau\left|\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\ln g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|\\
 & \leq\int\left|\mathbf{a}\right|\textrm{d}\tau<\infty.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore the total change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Since for any timelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 we have the inequality
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{y})\leq\left[g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\right]^{2},\]

\end_inset

it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})\leq\left|g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{v})\right|$
\end_inset

 and thus the total change of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is bounded for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Past-incompleteness of inflation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get a taste of singularity theorems, we start with a simple statement
 about the past timelike geodesic incompleteness of an inflationary spacetime.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
This section is based on the paper 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BVG03}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cosmological 
\series bold
inflation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{inflation}

\end_inset

is a period of accelerated expansion of spacetime.
 For instance, a spatially flat FRW metric with a given scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
g & =\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}t-a^{2}(t)\textrm{d}^{2}r,\label{eq:g FRW}\\
\textrm{d}^{2}r & \equiv\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}x+\textrm{d}y\otimes\textrm{d}y+\textrm{d}z\otimes\textrm{d}z,\nonumber \end{align}

\end_inset

represents inflation for those times 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{a}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{a}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
Hubble expansion rate
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hubble rate}

\end_inset

is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
H(t)=\frac{d}{dt}\ln a,\]

\end_inset

so the conditions for the presence of inflation are 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{H}+H^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0$
\end_inset

.
 A full discussion of possible varieties of cosmological inflation is beyond
 the scope of this text.
 We shall restrict our attention to a class of spacetimes that are qualitatively
 similar to the inflating FRW case, namely, to spacetimes with a metric
 of approximately the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g FRW}

\end_inset

), in suitable local coordinates.
 Locally, the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 will be well-defined and should satisfy the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $H>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{H}+H^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The processes that generate inflation may result in local fluctuations
 of the Hubble rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, but these fluctuations will occur on distance and time scales typically
 much larger than the horizon size 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that inflation can continue forever to the future.
 The main statement is that such an inflationary spacetime cannot be also
 eternal to the past.
 The way to prove this is to show that a past-directed timelike geodesic
 will have only a finite range of proper time.
 Events that preceded that time are not described by the inflationary spacetime
 and so may be interpreted as the presence of an initial singularity (the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

beginning of time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first describe the inflationary character of the spacetime in a coordinate-fr
ee manner.
 A salient property of the spacetime\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g FRW}

\end_inset

) is the existence of a congruence of timelike geodesics with tangent vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\equiv\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{1,2,3}=\partial_{x},\partial_{y},\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the Hubble law\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hubble law}

\end_inset

).
 These geodesics have everywhere positive divergence (see the following
 calculation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g FRW}

\end_inset

), show that the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{1,2,3}\equiv\partial_{x},\partial_{y},\partial_{z}$
\end_inset

 are connecting for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\equiv\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 and satisfy the Hubble law\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hubble law}

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\dot{a}/a$
\end_inset

.
 Then show that the divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div }\mathbf{v}=3H$
\end_inset

 and hence is everywhere positive during inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The Hubble law, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}_{j}=H\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

, follows from
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}_{j},\mathbf{c}_{j})=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}g(\mathbf{c}_{j},\mathbf{c}_{j})=-\frac{1}{2}\partial_{t}a^{2}=-a^{2}H.\]

\end_inset

Then we compute the divergence using the decomposition
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}=\mathbf{v}\otimes\mathbf{v}-a^{-2}\sum_{j=1}^{3}\mathbf{c}_{j}\otimes\mathbf{c}_{j}\]

\end_inset

that follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v},a^{-1}\mathbf{c}_{1},a^{-1}\mathbf{c}_{2},a^{-1}\mathbf{c}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{div }\mathbf{v} & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}g(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{v})\\
 & =g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})-a^{-2}\sum_{j=1}^{3}g(\mathbf{c}_{j},\nabla_{\mathbf{c}_{j}}\mathbf{v})\\
 & =-a^{-2}\sum_{j=1}^{3}g(\mathbf{c}_{j},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{c}_{j})=3H>0.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we reformulate our assumption of the presence of inflation throughout
 the entire 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

past portion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the spacetime: We require the existence of a timelike geodesic congruence
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 covering the entire past, with everywhere positive divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{v}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Here, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

past portion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the spacetime is understood as the past of some Cauchy 3-surface.
 Note that the existence of an everywhere diverging congruence is a nontrivial
 condition.
 In any spacetime, one can always find geodesic congruences having arbitrary,
 positive or negative, divergence at any given point, but not necessarily
 
\emph on
everywhere
\emph default
 to the past of a Cauchy surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an everywhere diverging geodesic congruence, we define the local Hubble
 expansion rate to be 
\begin_inset Formula $H\equiv\frac{1}{3}\textrm{div}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall assume, for simplicity, that there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\geq H_{0}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 (This condition can be significantly relaxed without affecting the conclusions.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we imagine that some dust-like particles follow the geodesic congruence
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 everywhere, and consider a geodesic observer who moves through the universe
 and measures the velocities of the dust particles.
 This observer can conclude that the spacetime is inflating and measure
 the local value of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in the following way.
 Let the observer's worldline be 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 with an affine tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\equiv\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=1$
\end_inset

.
 In principle, the observer can measure the following two (3-dimensional)
 quantities: the relative velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{\textrm{rel}}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, of the particle that passes by the observer at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, and the displacement vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{x}(\tau;\tau')$
\end_inset

, in the observer's rest frame, between nearby particles that passed the
 observer at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

.
 After registering two nearby particles at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'\equiv\tau+\delta\tau$
\end_inset

, the observer can calculate the separation and the relative velocity of
 the two particles in the (approximate) local rest frame of the particles.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 be a normalized, spacelike vector describing the separation between two
 particles in the particle rest frame.
 Then the observer can compute the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 and thus estimate the local Hubble rate from the rate of change of the
 separation in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
H\equiv\frac{1}{3}\textrm{div}\mathbf{v}\approx-g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v})\]

\end_inset

(the minus sign compensates for the spacelike character of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

).
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 must be normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=-1$
\end_inset

, so the observed Hubble rate depends only on the direction of the observer's
 motion but not on its speed.
 Since the spacetime is approximately isotropic, the estimate of the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 from a single direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is expected to be reasonably accurate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next calculations derive a formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in terms of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 It will be convenient to denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\tau)\equiv g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 factor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of special relativity, describing the time dilation between the observer
 and the particle rest frames.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})>1$
\end_inset

 for two future-directed timelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\neq\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 normalized to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since we assume that the observer is not at rest with respect to any of
 the particles, we will always have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the geodesic property of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, show that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 and the instantaneous Hubble rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are expressed by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}=\frac{\mathbf{u}-\alpha\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-1}},\quad H=-\frac{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\alpha}{\alpha^{2}-1}.\]

\end_inset

 Derive the relationship between the observed 3-dimensional quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{\textrm{rel}}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{\textrm{rel}}(\tau+d\tau)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\vec{x}(\tau;\tau+d\tau)$
\end_inset

, and the 4-dimensional vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\alpha$
\end_inset

, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}dt$
\end_inset

 should represent the infinitesimal displacement of the observer in the
 particle rest frame, where the time interval is 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

.
 Spatial vectors in the particle rest frame are (spacelike) vectors orthogonal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 onto the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{n}=\frac{\mathbf{u}-\mathbf{v}g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})}{\left|\mathbf{u}-\mathbf{v}g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\right|}=\frac{\mathbf{u}-\alpha\mathbf{v}}{\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-1}},\]

\end_inset

where we have used 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can directly compute 
\begin_inset Formula $H\equiv-g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is normalized and geodesic, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{v})=0=g(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 So the only surviving term in 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
H=-g(\mathbf{n},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{u})=-\frac{g(\mathbf{u},\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v})}{\alpha^{2}-1}=-\frac{\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\alpha}{\alpha^{2}-1}.\]

\end_inset

This is the desired formula.
 In the instantaneous inertial frame where the observer is at rest, we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\left\{ 1,0,0,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\left\{ \alpha,\alpha\vec{v}_{\textrm{rel}}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha(\tau)\equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\vec{v}_{\textrm{rel}}^{2}(\tau)}}\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the observer's proper time.
 In this way, the observer can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\alpha\equiv\partial_{\tau}\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, we can simplify the formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula \[
H(\tau)=\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\tau}\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau)+1}{\alpha(\tau)-1}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau)+1}{\alpha(\tau)-1}>0\quad\textrm{for all }\tau.\]

\end_inset

 Finally, our hypothetical observer can integrate the instantaneous value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\tau)$
\end_inset

 along the worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $H\geq H_{0}$
\end_inset

, therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}H(\tau)\textrm{d}\tau\geq H_{0}(\tau_{2}-\tau_{1})\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1},\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}H(\tau)\textrm{d}\tau & =\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau_{2})+1}{\alpha(\tau_{2})-1}-\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau_{1})+1}{\alpha(\tau_{1})-1}\\
 & <\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau_{2})+1}{\alpha(\tau_{2})-1}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence, there is a lower bound on the admissible values 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 of the proper time,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau_{1}>\tau_{2}-\frac{1}{2H_{0}}\ln\frac{\alpha(\tau_{2})+1}{\alpha(\tau_{2})-1}\equiv\tau_{\min}(\tau_{2}).\]

\end_inset

This means that no timelike geodesic can be extended to the past further
 than to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\min}(\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the spacetime is geodesically incomplete to the past.
 (A similar argument shows that null geodesics are also past-incomplete.)
 The only geodesic worldlines that might be complete to the past are the
 particle worldlines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What could the observer see at earlier times 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\leq\tau_{\min}$
\end_inset

? One possibility is that the observer did not exist at those times because
 the spacetime is singular in the distant past.
 In this case, we can say that a past-directed geodesic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hits a singularity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{\min}$
\end_inset

 or sooner, but we cannot deduce any more information about the singularity.
 For instance, different observers might hit different, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

separate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 singularities.
 The only alternative to the presence of singularities is to conclude that
 the spacetime was not inflating at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau<\tau_{\min}$
\end_inset

.
 In both cases, the inflationary epoch could not be past-eternal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conjugate points on geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proofs of several singularity theorems are based on the properties of geodesic
 curves.
 In this and the following sections we shall obtain some necessary geometric
 results about geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 be a tangent vector field to a congruence which consists of geodesics emitted
 from a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a focal point for the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 There is a possibility that some of the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 will focus again at another focal point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 The condition for this possibility is easy to derive using the geodesic
 deviation equation (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Deviation-of-geodesics}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Namely, consider a connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the geodesic deviation equation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}-R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{c})\mathbf{u}=0.\label{eq:geodesic deviation c u}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We now pick a single geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

