 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a focal point for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 We may pick the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}(\tau=0)$
\end_inset

 arbitrarily, and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 from the deviation equation.
 Suppose that there exists a particular solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau_{1})=0$
\end_inset

 at some other point 
\begin_inset Formula $q\equiv\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 on the curve.
 It means that an
