\begin_layout Standard
A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Jacobi field
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Jacobi field}

\end_inset

for a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 if it satisfies Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic deviation c u}

\end_inset

) along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\equiv\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that Jacobi fields are essentially connecting vectors for a
 family of geodesics around 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 One uses the concept of Jacobi fields when one would like to examine the
 focusing properties of a single curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and to avoid the need to introduce a whole congruence of geodesics around
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and to talk about intersections of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimally close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 geodesics.
 For instance, one can define conjugate points without involving a congruence,
 in the following way: Two points 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\gamma(\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 on a geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 are conjugate if there exists a Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, not identically zero, which vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is intuitively obvious that the divergence of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 tends to infinity at a focal point.
 To show this more formally, consider the defining property of the divergence
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}V=\partial_{\tau}V=(\textrm{div}\mathbf{u})V,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a 3-volume spanned by three connecting vectors transverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 As we cross a focal point, at least one of the connecting vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 that span 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 will vanish.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 at a focal point; in the generic case where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\tau)$
\end_inset

 has only simple zeros, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 will also change sign after a focal point.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\tau}V\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}V$
\end_inset

 is always finite since 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\varepsilon(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{c}_{1},\mathbf{c}_{2},\mathbf{c}_{3})$
\end_inset

 and every connecting vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

 satisfies a linear equation and thus cannot become infinite.
 Therefore, any point where 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 becomes infinite must be a focal point where 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we can rewrite the above equation as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}=\partial_{\tau}\ln V$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 remains finite, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln V$
\end_inset

 cannot go to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 within a finite time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 at a focal point.
 (In the generic case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 before a focal point and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset

 after a focal point.) Thus we have proved that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is necessary and sufficient for the existence of a focal point of a field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, let us develop a qualitative picture of why conjugate points occur.
 We have seen that gravity generally acts as an attractive force that makes
 geodesics converge.
 Therefore, a bunch of geodesics emitted from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will usually tend to refocus at a later point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 The refocusing may take a while, but once the divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 becomes negative along one line, refocusing is inevitable within a finite
 time.
 (Note that the focusing theorem applies to hypersurface orthogonal geodesics,
 and the congruence emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is hypersurface orthogonal by Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 from Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Focusing-of-timelike}

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, this congruence is integrable by Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 from Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Frobenius-theorem}

\end_inset

.) Focal points can occur along a caustic surface or caustic line, so we
 select one geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 on which focusing occurs at one point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the point conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

; other geodesics 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma'$
\end_inset

 may possess different conjugate points to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and also there may exist several conjugate points 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q'$
\end_inset

, ..., to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 along a single curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the property of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to be conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a property of the local geometry around a selected geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Note also that the focusing of geodesics does not yet indicate any singularitie
s in the spacetime; after all, we can select congruences that focus at any
 point by simply emitting geodesics from that point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The focusing theorem (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Focusing-of-timelike}

\end_inset

) shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 will reach infinity within a finite proper time if the congruence initially
 has negative divergence and if the strong energy condition holds.
 Hence, conjugate points must exist along each curve of the congruence,
 under the same assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Generic condition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on spacetime: each geodesic contains some point where 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then use Raychaudhuri equation to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 quickly, then it encounters the place where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 becomes negative, then focuses.
 Thus any geodesic contains at least one pair of conjugate points.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Second variation of proper length
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Derivation of geodesic equation}

\end_inset

 we have seen that a geodesic curve extremizes the proper length among all
 curves connecting two fixed points.
 For instance, in the Minkowski space, timelike geodesics 
\emph on
maximize
\emph default
 the proper time; note that spacelike geodesics do not 
\emph on
minimize
\emph default
 the proper distance, since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has the signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+--\,-\right)$
\end_inset

.
 However, in more general spacetimes the proper length of a geodesic does
 not always deliver the maximum proper time.
 We shall now see that the maximization of proper length is closely related
 to the existence of conjugate points for neighbor geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The infinitesimal change of the proper length of a curve under an infinitesimal
 variation is described by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic pre deriv}

\end_inset

) of Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Derivation of geodesic equation}

\end_inset

.
 For a timelike curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 with a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 normalized by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

, perturbed by the flow of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 with a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 along the flow, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\sigma}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]=-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\tau.\]

\end_inset

The derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dL[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma$
\end_inset

 vanishes when 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a geodesic, but this is not sufficient to have an actual 
\emph on
maximum
\emph default
 of the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The proper length is maximized if 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L/d\sigma^{2}<0$
\end_inset

.
 To verify this condition, we again consider a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 created by transporting the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}] & =-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\tau\\
 & =-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\tau-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})\textrm{d}\tau.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}\neq0$
\end_inset

 away from the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.) Since 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t}]=0$
\end_inset

, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is expressed through the Riemann tensor as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{t}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v})=R(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})+g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t}).\]

\end_inset

Finally, on the geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 and thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})-g(\mathbf{t},\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t})\right)\textrm{d}\tau.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral expression in the right-hand side above must be nonpositive
 for all vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 (and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) if the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 maximizes the proper length under infinitesimal variations.
 We cannot simplify 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 any further, but we note that the expression in the right-hand side is
 similar to the geodesic deviation equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic deviation c u}

\end_inset

).
 Denoting by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 the linear operator involved in that equation, we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\hat{G}\mathbf{t}-\ddot{\mathbf{t}})\textrm{d}\tau,\]

\end_inset

where the precise definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{G}\mathbf{t}\equiv R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{t})\mathbf{v},\quad\ddot{\mathbf{t}}\equiv\partial_{\tau}\partial_{\tau}\mathbf{t}\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{t}.\]

\end_inset

 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 will be a Jacobi field if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\mathbf{t}}-\hat{G}\mathbf{t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 will vanish if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is a Jacobi field.
 In the present case, the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 plays the role of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perturbation field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is fixed at endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus an admissible field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 must vanish at endpoints.
 But a Jacobi field that vanishes at the endpoints can exist only if both
 endpoints are conjugate points with respect to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 The functional 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a quadratic functional of the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Heuristically, one expects that a negative-definite quadratic functional
 will not vanish at nonzero values of its argument.
 Hence, we expect that the proper length cannot be maximized if there exists
 a Jacobi field that vanishes at both the endpoints, or (as will be shown
 below) if one of the endpoints is conjugate to a point within the curve.
 Thus we found a crucial link between the existence of conjugate points
 and the maximization of proper length.
 This link is formalized in the following statement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 1: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{HaEl73}

\end_inset

, Proposition 4.5.8.
\end_layout

\end_inset

A geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 maximizes the proper length between points 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 with respect to infinitesimal variations iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 has no conjugate points to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\tau_{1},\tau_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Sketch of proof: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there are no conjugate points then there is a one-to-one map between
 a Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and the initial value of the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

.
 This map is specified by a nondegenerate transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The functional 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 evaluated on an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through the auxiliary vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}\equiv A^{-1}\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

, and shown to be a negative-definite functional of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 by an explicit calculation that uses the integrability of the geodesic
 congruence emitted at 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, if there exists a focal point 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau_{*})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

 is between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, not identically zero, and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau_{1})=\mathbf{c}(\tau_{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 To show that the proper length is not maximized, it is sufficient to find
 even a single example of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 If we define the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}(\tau)\equiv\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}<\tau<\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}(\tau)\equiv0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{*}<\tau<\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

, then we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}_{0}]/d\sigma^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 except at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corner.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Now, one can deform this field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 by an infinitesimal amount and construct a smooth field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that still 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 goes heuristically as follows: The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is almost equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

, which produces an almost zero value of the integral, and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to be almost zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{*}<\tau<\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

 and such that the resulting integral is positive.
 (The curve corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}_{0}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 has a corner that can be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

straightened out.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
More detailed proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we prove that there is a maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\gamma]$
\end_inset

 if no conjugate points are present on 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 For brevity, we denote (covariant) derivatives along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 by an overdot.
 The time-dependent transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that maps initial values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{c}}(\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 to final values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the (transformation-valued) solution of the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ddot{\hat{A}}-\hat{G}\hat{A}=0,\quad\hat{A}(\tau_{1})=0,\;\dot{\hat{A}}(\tau_{1})=\hat{1}.\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\hat{G}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 is transverse to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 are effectively three-dimensional transformations acting in the subspace
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 If there are no conjugate points, the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, we will now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}\leq0$
\end_inset

 for all vector functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau_{1})=\mathbf{t}(\tau_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 This will be sufficient to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\gamma]$
\end_inset

 has a maximum.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined, we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}(\tau)\equiv\hat{A}^{-1}(\tau)\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

; the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 will then belong to the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 We can express 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}] & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\hat{G}\hat{A}\mathbf{z}-\partial_{\tau}\partial_{\tau}(\hat{A}\mathbf{z}))\textrm{d}\tau\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left[-g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},2\dot{\hat{A}}\dot{\mathbf{z}})-g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\hat{A}\ddot{\mathbf{z}})\right]\textrm{d}\tau\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left[g(\dot{\hat{A}}\mathbf{z},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}})-g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\dot{\hat{A}}\dot{\mathbf{z}})+g(\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}}\right]\textrm{d}\tau,\label{eq:d2L gamma 1}\end{align}

\end_inset

where in the last line we have canceled the total derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\tau}g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}})$
\end_inset

.
 Now let us rewrite the first two terms in the last line in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:d2L gamma 1}

\end_inset

) through the adjoint operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\dot{\hat{A}}\mathbf{z},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}})-g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\dot{\hat{A}}\dot{\mathbf{z}})=g(\mathbf{z},(\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\dot{\hat{A}})\dot{\mathbf{z}}).\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\hat{G}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

, so the known symmetry of the Riemann tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})=R(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

, means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}^{T}=\hat{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{T}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ddot{\hat{A}}^{T}-\hat{A}^{T}\hat{G}=0,\quad\hat{A}^{T}(\tau_{1})=0,\;\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}(\tau_{1})=\hat{1}.\]

\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\dot{\hat{A}}$
\end_inset

 is analogous to a Wronskian and is time-independent because
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial_{\tau}\left(\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\dot{\hat{A}}\right)=\hat{A}^{T}\hat{G}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\hat{G}\hat{A}=0.\]

\end_inset

Since the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\dot{\hat{A}}$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 due to the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(\tau_{1})=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{A}}^{T}\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{T}\dot{\hat{A}}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\dot{\hat{A}}\mathbf{z},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}})-g(\hat{A}\mathbf{z},\dot{\hat{A}}\dot{\mathbf{z}})\equiv0\]

\end_inset

and the expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:d2L gamma 1}

\end_inset

) is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}},\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}})\textrm{d}\tau.\]

\end_inset

Since the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\dot{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, it is spacelike, hence the above expression is always nonpositive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider the second case where a conjugate point is present.
 We will then show that 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\gamma]$
\end_inset

 does not have a maximum.
 The presence of a conjugate point means that there exists a Jacobi field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, not everywhere zero, satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\mathbf{c}}=\hat{G}\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau_{1})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}<\tau_{*}<\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now demonstrate that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]/d\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 with a specific choice of the perturbation vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 will be defined by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smoothing the corner
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

, with a small additional perturbation:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{t}(\tau)\equiv s(\tau)\mathbf{c}(\tau)+\varepsilon q(\tau)\mathbf{a},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth step-like function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau<\tau_{*})\approx1$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau>\tau_{*})\approx0$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function that vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and is positive for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}<\tau<\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\tau)=(\tau-\tau_{1})(\tau_{2}-\tau)$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
constant
\emph default
 spacelike vector (to be determined later).
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is chosen to be nonconstant only within a very narrow interval around 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The idea is to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 very small and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau)$
\end_inset

 very close to the Heaviside step function, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is smooth but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)\approx\mathbf{c}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}<\tau<\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)\approx0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{*}<\tau<\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 exactly vanishes at the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 With the above definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, we can directly compute the relevant quantities, neglecting unimportant
 terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{G}\mathbf{t}-\ddot{\mathbf{t}} & =\varepsilon q(\tau)\hat{G}\mathbf{a}-2\dot{s}\dot{\mathbf{c}}-\ddot{s}\mathbf{c},\\
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}] & =\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{t},\hat{G}\mathbf{t}-\ddot{\mathbf{t}})\textrm{d}\tau=-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(s\mathbf{c},2\dot{s}\dot{\mathbf{c}}+\ddot{s}\mathbf{c})\textrm{d}\tau\\
 & -2\varepsilon\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}q(\tau)g(\mathbf{a},2\dot{s}\dot{\mathbf{c}}+\ddot{s}\mathbf{c})\textrm{d}\tau+O(\varepsilon^{2}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where in the last line we have used the self-adjointness property (derived
 using integration by parts),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\mathbf{x},\hat{G}\mathbf{y}-\ddot{\mathbf{y}})\textrm{d}\tau=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}g(\hat{G}\mathbf{x}-\ddot{\mathbf{x}},\mathbf{y})\textrm{d}\tau,\]

\end_inset

which holds for vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 that vanish at endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{s}$
\end_inset

 are nonzero only in a narrow interval around 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

, it is sufficient to approximate
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{c}(\tau) & \approx\left(\tau-\tau_{*}\right)\mathbf{b},\quad\mathbf{b}\equiv\dot{\mathbf{c}}(\tau_{*})\\
\mathbf{t}(\tau) & \approx\left(\tau-\tau_{*}\right)s(\tau)\mathbf{b}+\varepsilon q(\tau_{*})\mathbf{a},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is a known spacelike vector.
 (With a suitable choice of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau)$
\end_inset

, the error of this approximation will be of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{2}$
\end_inset

.) Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}^{2}L[\mathbf{t}]}{\textrm{d}\sigma^{2}} & =O(\varepsilon^{2})-g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{b})\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}(\tau-\tau_{*})\left(2s\dot{s}+(\tau-\tau_{*})s\ddot{s}\right)\textrm{d}\tau\\
 & -2\varepsilon q(\tau_{*})g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\negmedspace\left(2\dot{s}+(\tau-\tau_{*})\ddot{s}\right)\textrm{d}\tau.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The step-like function 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can be chosen so that the first integral in the above equation is arbitrarily
 small, e.g.\InsetSpace ~
of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, integration by parts yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}(\tau-\tau_{*})\left(2s\dot{s}+(\tau-\tau_{*})s\ddot{s}\right)\textrm{d}\tau=-\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}(\tau-\tau_{*})^{2}\dot{s}^{2}\textrm{d}\tau;\]

\end_inset

 heuristically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{s}(\tau)\approx\delta(\tau-\tau_{*})$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau-\tau_{*})\dot{s}\approx0$
\end_inset

.
 These statements can be made mathematically precise, for instance, by using
 an explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining integral is easily evaluated,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left(2\dot{s}+(\tau-\tau_{*})\ddot{s}\right)\textrm{d}\tau=\int_{\tau_{1}}^{\tau_{2}}\left[\dot{s}+\partial_{\tau}\left((\tau-\tau_{*})\dot{s}\right)\right]\textrm{d}\tau=-1.\]

\end_inset

Finally, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\neq0$
\end_inset

, since by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is not everywhere zero and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=\dot{\mathbf{c}}\neq0$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\tau_{*})>0$
\end_inset

.
 So we can choose the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
2q(\tau_{*})g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=1.\]

\end_inset

 With this choice, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d^{2}}{d\sigma^{2}}L[\gamma;\mathbf{t}]=\varepsilon+O(\varepsilon^{2}),\]

\end_inset

which will be positive for small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 This concludes the proof of Statement\InsetSpace ~
1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in the presence of (at least one) conjugate point on a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, the maximum proper length is not achieved by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 For example, a body on a circular orbit in a central gravitational field
 does not maximize the proper time over one period after it comes back to
 an initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, since the elapsed proper time is smaller than that of a body at rest at
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, the proper time is maximized by another geodesic, corresponding
 to a body thrown away from the center of gravity from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that it comes back to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at the right time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A related situation is a congruence of timelike geodesics normal to a given
 spacelike 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then this congruence is hypersurface orthogonal everywhere (not just at
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

), by an argument analogous to that of Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Focusing-of-timelike}

\end_inset

.
 For a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, there may or may not be a geodesic that maximizes the proper distance
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
