\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 As before, a definition can be given in terms of Jacobi fields: A point
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 on a geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
conjugate to
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conjugate point}

\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 if there exists a Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\neq0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly to Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 above, one can prove the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 2:
