\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 4:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the conditions of Statement\InsetSpace ~
3 hold, and additionally 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\leq-\theta_{0}<0$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 If a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 can be connected to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 by a timelike curve of proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 then there is no timelike curve of maximum length connecting 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a timelike curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of maximal proper length exists and reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 must be a timelike geodesic that is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (or else we can deform 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 or shift the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and increase the proper length).
 However, if the proper length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, there exists a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 does not maximize the proper length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of this situation is a half-hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}-r^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

, in the Minkowski spacetime.
 This spacelike 3-surface is orthogonal to every straight line (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
to every
 geodesic) passing through the origin.
 Thus, the origin is the focal point for all the geodesics emitted orthogonally
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The half-lightcone, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}-r^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

, bounds the domain where conjugate points do not arise.
 For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}-r^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leq0$
\end_inset

, and for any point in the upper half-spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0$
\end_inset

, one can find timelike curves of arbitrarily large proper length leading
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to some point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the maximal-length curve connecting some point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 must have proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $<1$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the divergence of the future-directed normal vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 to the half-hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}-x^{2}-y^{2}-z^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

, in the Minkowski spacetime, and show that this 3-surface satisfies the
 conditions of Statement\InsetSpace ~
4 as well as its conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The hyperboloid is specified by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\equiv(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 is the position vector.
 The future-directed normal vector field is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}=-\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})}},\]

\end_inset

 and the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla=\partial$
\end_inset

, so we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and thus (on the surface)
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{u}=-\partial_{\mathbf{a}}\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\sqrt{g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})}}=-\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{x}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

 The divergence is found as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{div}\mathbf{u} & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{b})\\
 & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}\left[g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x})-g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\right]=1-4=-3.\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we may set 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}=3$
\end_inset

 and apply Statement\InsetSpace ~
4.
 The proper length to the focus is 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, in agreement with the geometric result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we state an analogous theorem for null geodesics.
 The differences between the timelike and the null case are purely technical:
 1) Jacobi fields for null geodesics
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are effectively two-dimensional because connecting vectors differing by
 a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are equivalent.
 2) Null geodesics containing conjugate points do not maximize the proper
 length between endpoints, thus the maximal proper length is positive, and
 there is a timelike curve connecting the endpoints.
 3) One considers a spacelike 2-surface to which null geodesics are orthogonal
 (note that there are two null directions orthogonal to a spacelike 2-surface,
 but no null vectors orthogonal to a spacelike 3-surface).
 4) One uses the null energy condition instead of the strong energy condition.
 5) The focusing theorem for null geodesics predicts focusing within parameter
 interval 
\begin_inset Formula $2/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the timelike case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 5:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a spacelike 2-surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a null vector field orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{n}\equiv-\theta_{0}<0$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S$
\end_inset

, and the null energy condition holds, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\leq0$
\end_inset

 for all null 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the null geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, with initial tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, contains a conjugate point to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 within the affine parameter interval 
\begin_inset Formula $2/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If the geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 can be extended beyond the conjugate point to some point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 does not maximize the proper length between 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 can be connected to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by a timelike curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Singularity in collapsing or expanding universe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now derive some basic singularity theorems.
 Both theorems below are due to S.
 W.
 Hawking.
 (Stronger theorems exist but require much more technical work.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive picture of a gravitational collapse is that of a cloud of particles
 that keep moving closer to each other.
 The mathematical expression of this property is that the congruence of
 the particle worldlines has a negative divergence.
 According to the focusing theorem, a consequence of negative divergence
 is a focusing of the geodesics.
 As a result, the geodesics fail to maximize proper length.
 This is the technical basis of the singularity theorems.
 Of course, the geodesic focusing by itself does not signal any singularities;
 we need additional conditions on the initial velocities of the particles
 to conclude that singularities will develop.
 In the first singularity theorem, these conditions are formulated as requiremen
ts on a spacelike 3-surface to which the particle worldlines are orthogonal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a 
\series bold
Cauchy surface
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 for a domain is a 3-surface such that any timelike curve within the domain
 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 exactly once.
 The intuitive meaning of a Cauchy surface is that a partial differential
 equation has a unique solution throughout the domain if appropriate initial
 data are specified on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The theorem states that a Cauchy surface having an everywhere negative
 divergence leads to a singularity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 1: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a spacelike Cauchy surface for the entire spacetime, with a normal vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 whose divergence is everywhere negative-bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div}\mathbf{u}\leq\theta_{0}<0$
\end_inset

, and if the strong energy condition holds, then every timelike geodesic
 normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 has finite proper length no greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Sketch of a proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Every timelike geodesic leading from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 must intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 exactly once.
 The points of intersection form an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\Sigma;p)$
\end_inset

 bounded by intersection points with null geodesics from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Timelike geodesics intersecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 near the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\Sigma;p)$
\end_inset

 have very small proper length, so we may consider the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)\subset I(\Sigma;p)$
\end_inset

 of intersection points for curves with proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq L$
\end_inset

 for some lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 We can select 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, and then the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 (These intuitively clear topological statements will be given a formal
 proof in Lemma\InsetSpace ~
1 below.) Therefore, the proper time is maximized by 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 geodesic curve leading from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 However, by Statement\InsetSpace ~
4 in the previous section, we know that there are
 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 curves maximizing the proper length and stretching further than 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the spacetime cannot include points at a proper length greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, every timelike geodesic emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 must be 
\emph on
future incomplete
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lemma 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)$
\end_inset

 be the set of intersection points of timelike geodesics leading from a
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to a Cauchy surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, whose proper length is 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L>0$
\end_inset

 is a given constant.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)$
\end_inset

 is a compact set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{I}(\Sigma;p;L)$
\end_inset

 is not compact.
 Then there exists a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \gamma_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of geodesics, whose proper lengths are 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq L$
\end_inset

, such that the corresponding intersection points 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 constitute a sequence without accumulation points within 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\Sigma;p;L$
\end_inset

).
 However, the initial tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{j}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are within the past lightcone within 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, which is a compact set if we also include the null directions.
 Hence, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of tangent vectors must have an accumulation point 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 within the past lightcone.
 We can emit a geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with the initial tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 must be an accumulation point for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Hence the proper length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 cannot be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\infty}\in I(\Sigma;p;L)$
\end_inset

.
 This yields a contradiction with the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 has no accumulation points within 
\begin_inset Formula $I(\Sigma;p;L$
\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 cannot intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Since every timelike curve intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, we see that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 must be null and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a null geodesic.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 does not intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that does not intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 It is then possible to find a timelike curve (which is not necessarily
 a geodesic, not necessarily starting at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) that runs along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and always remains away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of an inextendible timelike curve that never crosses 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 contradicts the definition of a Cauchy surface.
 This concludes the proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interpretation of the first theorem is the following: If we see a universe
 that is everywhere contracting (everywhere along a single Cauchy surface),
 we should expect to hit a singularity within a finite time.
 By inverting the direction of time, we also come to the conclusion that
 a Cauchy surface with everywhere positive divergence contains a singularity
 in its past.
 Thus, if our universe is everywhere expanding, and if the strong or the
 null energy condition is satisfied, then the universe must have begun at
 a singularity at a finite time in the past.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Self-test question:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The half-hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}-x^{2}-y^{2}-z^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

, in the Minkowski spacetime, is an infinite spacelike surface whose normal
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 has an everywhere negative divergence.
 Does it follow from Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 that the Minkowski spacetime must contain
 a singularity to the future of the half-hyperboloid?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Answer:
\emph default
 No.
 (The half-hyperboloid is not a Cauchy surface.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Singularity in a closed universe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption that a given 3-surface is a Cauchy surface for the spacetime
 is quite strong, since it is a global relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and the entire spacetime, and not merely a local property of the surface
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 One can replace this assumption by the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 be 
\emph on
compact
\emph default
 (this will apply to closed universes).
 The result will be the incompleteness of 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 geodesics emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, which may fill only a part of the entire spacetime.
 Here is how this conclusion can be derived.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We restrict our attention to the part of the spacetime consisting of points
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for which there exists a timelike curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This part of the spacetime is called the 
\series bold
domain of dependence
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{domain of dependence}

\end_inset

of the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 contains some incomplete geodesics if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 satisfies the conditions of Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 above, except for being a Cauchy
 surface.
 It follows from the proof of Statement\InsetSpace ~
1 that, within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

, a geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 connecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $>3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 does not maximize the proper length.
 Therefore, any geodesic that 
\emph on
does
\emph default
 maximize the proper length must be shorter than 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)\equiv\partial\mathcal{D}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 the boundary of the domain of dependence; it is a 3-surface called the
 
\series bold
Cauchy horizon
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Cauchy horizon}

\end_inset

It can be seen that the Cauchy horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is locally a null surface (although it may also contain some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corners
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 The fact that a boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 of a domain of dependence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is a null 3-surface will be derived below (see the proof of Statement\InsetSpace ~
1
 in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Hawking's-area-theorem}

\end_inset

).
 There are now two interesting possibilities: either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is compact, or it is not compact.
 Suppose first that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is a compact set.
 Note that a null surface is generated by null geodesics (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Null-functions-generate}

\end_inset

).
 Then the null generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 must wind around it, coming arbitrarily near to themselves infinitely many
 times; informally, we may call such curves 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 curves.
 Since timelike geodesics can be found arbitrarily close to null geodesics,
 the presence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 null geodesics is an undesirable feature of the spacetime, similar to a
 causality violation or the presence of a time machine.
 A spacetime is called 
\series bold
strongly causal
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{strongly causal spacetime}

\end_inset

if it does not admit timelike curves that repeatedly come arbitrarily close
 to some points.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 cannot be compact in a strongly causal spacetime.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is not compact; then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 contains a sequence of points 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., which does not have an accumulation point within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 We may choose a sequence of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{q}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 arbitrarily close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 but within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}(\Sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

 lies on at least one timelike curve intersecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the length of that curve; then the set of all timelike curves with length
 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq L$
\end_inset

 is compact, so one of these curves has the largest proper length.
 So, for each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

 we have a timelike geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that has the maximal proper length among all the timelike curves connecting
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 (We have already shown that each of these curves has proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\max}<3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}(0)$
\end_inset

 is on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 be the point where the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{j}\equiv\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{j}(0)$
\end_inset

 be the initial tangent vector.
 The intersection points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., and the corresponding initial tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., are sequences on a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and thus must accumulate at some point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 and vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we can show that the geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 emitted from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 with the initial tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 cannot be extended past the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 were well-defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 then we would have a narrow tube-shaped neighborhood stretching along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\tau\leq3/\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, such that infinitely many geodesics 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 are inside that tube.
 Thus the point sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{q}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

