\begin_layout Standard
The condition that singularities do not occur at the horizon is motivated
 as follows.
 We expect that the future history of an asymptotically flat spacetime is
 completely predictable from initial data on a Cauchy 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 preceding the gravitational collapse.
 Thus, any null curve escaping to infinity must intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 at one point.
 (This condition is called 
\series bold
asymptotic predictability
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{asymptotic predictability}

\end_inset

with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.) If a null generator 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of a horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 stops at a singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, it means that the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 cannot be continued past 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since there exist null curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma'\not\subset\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 infinitely close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and reaching infinity, it follows that there exists a (null and/or spacelike)
 curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma''$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

starts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at the singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and reaches infinity.
 To an observer at infinity, this curve appears to be a past-directed curve
 that stops at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma''$
\end_inset

 does not intersect 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 and the asymptotic behavior at infinity in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma''$
\end_inset

 cannot be predicted from initial data on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Another way to express this is to say that the singularity is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directly visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to an observer at infinity.
 There is a (so far, not proved but strongly supported) conjecture that
 any singularities that can occur in reasonable physical processes, such
 as gravitational collapse, must be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hidden
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 behind event horizons and are thus invisible to observers at infinity.
 This statement is called the 
\series bold
cosmic censorship 
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cosmic censorship}

\end_inset

conjecture (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nature abhors naked singularities
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 There are some artificial examples of spacetimes with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naked
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 singularities, but all such examples are pathological in one or another
 way.
 Therefore, the assumption of asymptotic predictability appears reasonable.
\end_layout

