\begin_layout Standard
The area theorem has had a wide-reaching impact on all of fundamental physics.
 It has lead to the hypothesis of black hole entropy, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S=\frac{1}{4}A=4\pi m^{2},\]

\end_inset

 and to the holographic principle.
 Let us consider a simple application of the area theorem.
 In an asymptotically flat spacetime containing two distant black holes
 with masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, there may be some process that lets the two black holes come closer together
 and eventually merge.
 Initially, the total area of the event horizon of this spacetime is 
\begin_inset Formula $16\pi(m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 After merging, the spacetime contains a larger black hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, with the area of the event horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $16\pi M^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The area theorem says that 
\begin_inset Formula $16\pi M^{2}\geq16\pi(m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2})$
\end_inset

 regardless of the details of the merger, and regardless of whether any
 extra matter or radiation was absorbed or emitted in the process of merging.
 This inequality sets a fundamental bound on the amount of energy that can
 be extracted from a black hole merger.
\end_layout

