\begin_layout Section
Lagrangian formulation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classical field theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical field theory describes 
\series bold
fields
\series default
, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
functions on spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 or sections of some vector bundle with the spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as the base.
 The fields under consideration may be scalar fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

, ...; vector fields, spinor fields, and so on.
 Let us denote all the fields collectively by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an index enumerating each individual field and each of their components.
 Field theory is based on the variational principle (or 
\series bold
Hamilton's principle of stationary of action
\series default
, or 
\series bold
action principle
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{action principle}

\end_inset

for short): The field equations are the conditions for having a local extremum
 of the action functional, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{action principle}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S\left[\phi\right]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}x\, L\left(\phi_{i},\nabla_{\mu}\phi_{i},...\right)\label{eq:S local func}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the Lagrangian density 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 depends on the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 and its (covariant) derivatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action principle states that a physically realized configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 must be an extremum of the action functional.
 The variation of the action under a small change 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi^{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta S[\phi]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}x\sum_{j}\frac{\delta S}{\delta\phi^{j}(x)}\delta\phi^{j}(x)+O\left(\left[\delta\phi^{j}\right]^{2}\right).\]

\end_inset

This yields the 
\series bold
Euler-Lagrange equation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Euler-Lagrange equation}

\end_inset

for the field, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta S}{\delta\phi^{j}(x)}=0.\]

\end_inset

This method of deriving field equations is called a 
\series bold
Lagrangian formulation
\series default
 of a field theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The currently established field theories (electrodynamics, gravitation,
 weak and strong interactions) are described by Lagrangian densities which
 depend only on the fields and their first derivatives, 
\begin_inset Formula $L=L\left(\phi^{j},\phi_{,\mu}^{j}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For such Lagrangians, the first-order variation of the action is given
 by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta S=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}x\sum_{j}\left(\frac{\partial L\left(\phi^{i},\nabla\phi^{i}\right)}{\partial\phi^{j}}-\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}\frac{\partial L\left(\phi^{i},\nabla\phi^{i}\right)}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}^{j}}\right)\delta\phi^{j}(x),\]

\end_inset

where the summation over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is implied.
 The boundary terms vanish if 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{j}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}^{j}}\delta\phi^{j}\rightarrow0\;\textrm{sufficiently rapidly as}\;\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\rightarrow\infty,\:\left|t\right|\rightarrow\infty,\]

\end_inset

 which is the usual assumption.
 Thus we obtain the following Euler-Lagrange equations for the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{j}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Euler-Lagrange equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\delta S\left[\phi\right]}{\delta\phi^{j}(x)}\equiv\frac{\partial L\left(\phi^{i},\nabla\phi^{i}\right)}{\partial\phi^{j}}-\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}\frac{\partial L\left(\phi^{i},\nabla\phi^{i}\right)}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}^{j}}=0.\label{eq:field EL}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:field EL}

\end_inset

) holds for all Lagrangians that depend on fields and their first derivatives.
 If a Lagrangian for a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 contains second-order derivatives such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{;\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, the corresponding Euler-Lagrange equations will generally contain derivatives
 of third and fourth order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a classical field theory is to be compatible with general relativity,
 the Lagrangian must be generally covariant.
 In practice, this means that the Lagrangian should be an invariant combination
 of covariant derivatives of fields and the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The integration must be performed with the volume element 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{4}x\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g\equiv\det\left(g_{\mu\nu}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the determinant of the covariant metric tensor.
 Normally, this factor is included into the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest example of a field is a scalar field.
 The Lagrangian density for a real-valued scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L\left(\phi,\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)=\left[\frac{1}{2}g^{\mu\nu}\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}-V(\phi)\right]\sqrt{-g},\label{eq:Lagr scalar}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a potential that describes self-interaction of the field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Covariant volume element 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{4}x$
\end_inset

 does not give the correct volume element if the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are not Cartesian or if the spacetime is curved.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{covariant volume element}

\end_inset

It is not difficult to show that the volume element in any number of dimensions
 is given by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}V=\textrm{d}^{n}x\sqrt{\left|g(x)\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are some vectors in a Euclidean space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}\equiv\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{u}_{j}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix of their pairwise scalar products.
 Then the volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional parallelepiped spanned by the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\sqrt{\left|\det G\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 We can prove this standard statement by considering the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{j}$
\end_inset

 of components of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 in an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{u}_{i}=\sum_{j}U_{i}^{j}\mathbf{e}_{j}.\]

\end_inset

 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be also understood as a linear transformation that maps the unit parallelep
iped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 to a parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{u}_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A standard definition of the determinant of a linear transformation is
 the volume of the image of a unit parallelepiped after the transformation.
 Therefore, the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\det U$
\end_inset

.
 Then we observe that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $G=U^{T}U$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\det G=(\det U)^{2}=V^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\sqrt{\left|\det G\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general relativity, the spacetime has a metric with signature 
\begin_inset Formula $(+,-,-,-)$
\end_inset

 and the determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is always negative (except at singular points where it may be zero or infinite).
 Therefore we change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and write the volume element as 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{4}x\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Minimal coupling to gravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action for a scalar field,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S[\phi]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left[\frac{1}{2}g^{\mu\nu}\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}-V(\phi)\right],\label{eq:S scalar min}\end{equation}

\end_inset

explicitly depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and thus describes a field coupled to gravity.
 This 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{minimal coupling!to gravity}

\end_inset

form of coupling is called the 
\series bold
minimal coupling
\series default
 to gravity; this is the minimal required interaction of a field with gravitatio
n which necessarily follows from the requirement of compatibility with general
 relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Euler-Lagrange equation for a minimally coupled field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 follows from the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:S scalar min}

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial_{\alpha}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\alpha}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}=\left(\sqrt{-g}g^{\alpha\beta}\phi_{,\beta}\right)_{,\alpha}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial\phi}=0.\]

\end_inset

This equation can be rewritten in a manifestly covariant form as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi_{;\alpha}^{;\alpha}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial\phi}=0.\]

\end_inset

This is similar to the Klein-Gordon equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{,\alpha}^{,\alpha}+m^{2}\phi=0$
\end_inset

, except for the presence of covariant derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
free
\series default
 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
noninteracting) 
\series bold
field
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{free field}

\end_inset

has the potential 
\begin_inset Formula \[
V(\phi)=\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi^{2}.\]

\end_inset

This is the simplest nontrivial potential; an additional linear term 
\begin_inset Formula $A\phi$
\end_inset

 can be removed by a field redefinition 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)=\tilde{\phi}(x)+\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the rest mass of the particles described by the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in quantum theory.
 The equation of motion for a free field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 and thus describes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

waves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that can cross without distorting each other.
 In other words, the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 has 
\series bold
no self-interaction
\series default
.
 A field would have self-interaction if the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 were such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V'''\neq0$
\end_inset

, so that the equation of motion would be nonlinear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Gauss's law with covariant derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
