status open

\begin_layout Standard
This is to be moved to the GR appendix.
 Also, need to make this more clear.
 What happens to vectors under div? to tensors? How is this different from
 the normal Gauss law?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When computing the variation of a generally covariant action such as the
 action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:S scalar min}

\end_inset

), one needs to integrate by parts.
 A useful shortcut in such calculations is an analog of Gauss's law with
 covariant derivatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariant divergence of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\,;\mu}^{\mu}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{-g}}\partial_{\mu}\left(\sqrt{-g}A^{\mu}\right).\]

\end_inset

 The formula analogous to the Gauss law is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{V}A^{\mu}{}_{;\mu}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{n}x=\oint_{\partial V}\sqrt{-h}A^{\mu}\textrm{d}^{n-1}S_{\mu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the partial metric on the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{n-1}S_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the oriented element of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-volume on the hypersurface.
 Using this formula, we may reduce volume integrals of total divergences
 to boundary integrals.
 Assuming that the contribution of the boundary terms vanishes, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int\textrm{d}^{n}x\sqrt{-g}A_{\,;\mu}^{\mu}B=-\int\textrm{d}^{n}x\sqrt{-g}A^{\mu}B_{,\mu}.\label{eq:modified Gauss}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This formula can be used to integrate by parts: We set 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\mu}\equiv\phi_{,\alpha}g^{\alpha\mu}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B\equiv\psi$
\end_inset

, and find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\phi_{,\alpha}\psi_{,\beta}g^{\alpha\beta}=-\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left(\phi_{,\alpha}g^{\alpha\beta}\right)_{;\beta}\psi.\]

\end_inset

 Note that the covariant derivative of the metric is zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}^{\,;\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

, so we may lower or raise the indices under covariant derivatives at will;
 for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\,;\mu}^{\mu}=A_{\mu}^{\,;\mu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Einstein-Hilbert action
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Einstein-Hilbert-action}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, one can compute the Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\kappa\lambda\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the Ricci tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Einstein postulated that the metric in a spacetime must be such that the
 Ricci tensor satisfies the 
\series bold
Einstein equation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R=-8\pi GT_{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\equiv R_{\mu\nu}g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the energy-momentum tensor of matter.
 This equation can be derived from a variational principle by extremizing
 an appropriately chosen action functional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall begin with the 
\series bold
vacuum
\series default
 Einstein equation (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the Einstein equation in the absence of matter, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}=0$
\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R=0.\label{eq:vacuum Einstein}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation can be derived from the 
\series bold
Einstein-Hilbert action
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein-Hilbert action}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{EH}[g]\equiv\frac{1}{16\pi G}\int_{\mathcal{M}}R\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x,\frac{1}{16\pi G}\label{eq:EH action}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is Newton's gravitational constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\equiv\sqrt{-\det g_{\mu\nu}}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}d^{4}x$
\end_inset

 is the covariant volume element.
 The integration in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:EH action}

\end_inset

) is performed over the entire spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Such an integral might diverge when the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is noncompact and if the curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 does not vanish at infinity, in which case one should limit the integration
 to a very large but finite subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the framework of the variational principle, one considers a small change
 in the metric,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}\rightarrow g_{\mu\nu}+\lambda h_{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 number and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary symmetric tensor field, which is assumed to vanish outside
 of the subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

.
 The first-order variation of the EH action 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 that can be defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{n}p\, h_{\mu\nu}(p)\frac{\delta S_{EH}[g]}{\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)}\equiv\left.\frac{d}{d\lambda}\right|_{\lambda=0}S_{EH}[g+\lambda h].\]

\end_inset

Note that the integration above is performed over all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and involves the coordinate-based volume element 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}^{n}p$
\end_inset

 rather than the invariant volume element 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{n}x$
\end_inset

.
 The point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 plays the role of a label, much like the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

, and thus a simple 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

summation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 over all the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\frac{d}{d\lambda}\right|_{\lambda=0}S_{EH}[g+\lambda h]\]

\end_inset

can be interpreted as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directional derivative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the action functional 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 (I put the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in quotes because 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a tensor-valued function on the manifold that describes an arbitrary
 modification of the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 at every point.) The action 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}$
\end_inset

 is extremized if its derivative vanishes in every 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S_{EH}/\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This yields an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 This method of deriving the Einstein equation is the Lagrangian formulation
 of general relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us adopt the following, somewhat more abstract geometric picture of
 the variational principle.
 The set of all the possible metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 can be considered as an (infinite-dimensional) manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, every individual metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 being a single 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 The Einstein-Hilbert functional 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 is then a real-valued scalar 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on this manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}:\mathcal{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 As usual, the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 to the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all directional derivatives at a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}\equiv\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{n}p\, h_{\mu\nu}(p)\frac{\delta}{\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)}\]

\end_inset

defines the derivative in a particular 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}$
\end_inset

 acts on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}\circ S_{EH}\equiv\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{n}p\, h_{\mu\nu}(p)\frac{\delta S_{EH}[g]}{\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)},\]

\end_inset

 which is the first-order variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be also written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{M}}d^{n}p\, h_{\mu\nu}(p)\frac{\delta S_{EH}[g]}{\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)}\equiv\left(dS_{EH}[g]\right)\circ\mathbf{h},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $dS_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 is the naturally defined 1-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gradient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}$
\end_inset

 in the space of metrics.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $dS_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S_{EH}/\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

, where we interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

index
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on par with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu$
\end_inset

.
 The action 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}$
\end_inset

 has a (local) extremum at a particular 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 if the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $dS_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the rest of this section, we shall show, by a direct calculation, that
 the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S_{EH}/\delta g_{\mu\nu}(p)=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the vacuum Einstein equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to compute the first-order variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 with respect to the 
\emph on
inverse
\emph default
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 rather than with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to find the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\equiv g^{\mu\nu}R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the Ricci tensor, under an infinitesimal change 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}\rightarrow g^{\mu\nu}+\delta g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

 is easy if we use the standard formula for the derivative of the determinant
 of a matrix (note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}=\sqrt{-\det(g_{\mu\nu})}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(g^{\mu\nu})=1/\det(g_{\mu\nu})=g^{-1}$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial\sqrt{-g}}{\partial g^{\mu\nu}}=-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\sqrt{-g}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the formula 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial}{\partial A_{jk}}\det A=(\det A)\left(A^{-1}\right)_{jk},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv A_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is a finite-dimensional square matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint:
\emph default
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det\left(\hat{1}+\lambda B\right)=1+\lambda\textrm{Tr }B+O(\lambda^{2}),\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small enough,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]$
\end_inset

 can be split into three terms,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta S_{EH}[g] & =\delta\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}p\, R_{\mu\nu}g^{\mu\nu}\sqrt{-g}\\
 & =\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}p\sqrt{-g}\left[g^{\mu\nu}\delta R_{\mu\nu}+R_{\mu\nu}\delta g^{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{\mu\nu}\delta g^{\mu\nu}\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

Shortly, we shall show that the first term in parentheses above,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}p\sqrt{-g}g^{\mu\nu}\delta R_{\mu\nu},\label{eq:boundary term}\end{equation}

\end_inset

vanishes (under suitable boundary conditions) because it is a total divergence.
 Thus, we shall have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta S_{EH}[g]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}p\sqrt{-g}\left(R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{\mu\nu}\right)\delta g^{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

which is equivalent to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\delta S_{EH}[g]}{\delta g^{\mu\nu}(p)}=R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{\mu\nu}.\label{eq:Einstein equ from var}\end{equation}

\end_inset

So the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S_{EH}/\delta g^{\mu\nu}=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the vacuum Einstein equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vacuum Einstein}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to analyze the term\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:boundary term}

\end_inset

).
 We shall now use the index-free notation for clarity.
 The term of interest is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{\mu\nu}\delta R_{\mu\nu}=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\delta\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\label{eq:Trace of Ricci}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The Ricci tensor is a contraction of the Riemann tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

To determine the variation of the Riemann tensor, we need to consider the
 change in the Levi-Civita connection, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\rightarrow\tilde{\nabla}$
\end_inset

, under 
\begin_inset Formula $g\rightarrow\tilde{g}=g+\delta g$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to show that the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\nabla}-\nabla$
\end_inset

 between any two connections does not contain derivatives,
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\tilde{\nabla}-\nabla)\left(f\mathbf{x}\right)=f\cdot(\tilde{\nabla}-\nabla)\mathbf{x},\]

\end_inset

 and hence acts as a transformation-valued 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Gamma$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\nabla}_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x}-\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{x}\equiv\delta\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{x}.\]

\end_inset

An explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Gamma$
\end_inset

 can be derived (see the Calculation below) but is not required for the
 present derivation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we use the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R2 def}

\end_inset

) to express the variation of the Riemann tensor through 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Gamma$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\delta R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w} & =\left[\delta\Gamma(\mathbf{u}),\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\right]\mathbf{w}+\left[\nabla_{\mathbf{u}},\delta\Gamma(\mathbf{v})\right]\mathbf{w}-\delta\Gamma([\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}])\mathbf{w}\nonumber \\
 & =(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\delta\Gamma)(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}-(\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\delta\Gamma)(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{w}.\label{eq:variation Riemann}\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
