\begin_layout Standard
In the Lagrangian formulation of field theory, every field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is described by an action functional, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{\mathcal{M}}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{n}p\, L[\phi],\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is an appropriate Lagrangian.
 Thus, Einstein's theory of gravity can be viewed as a field theory where
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the point-dependent metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 and the Lagrangian is the Einstein-Hilbert one, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:EH action}

\end_inset

).
 If we choose a different Lagrangian, we may obtain a different theory of
 gravity.
 Many alternative theories of gravity have been considered (and most of
 them have been rejected).
 Motivated by the requirement of general covariance, one usually constrains
 the choice of gravitational Lagrangians to combinations of invariant quantities
, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}R^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\kappa\lambda\mu\nu}R^{\kappa\lambda\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\square R$
\end_inset

, etc.
 These modified theories of gravity give rise to equations with high-order
 derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 because the Ricci scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $R[g_{\mu\nu}]$
\end_inset

 contains second derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

