\begin_layout Standard
In classical mechanics, the dynamics of a system may be described by the
 action
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\mathbf{q}]=\int L(\mathbf{q},\dot{\mathbf{q}})dt,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the trajectory of the system, which we will assume to be a vector-valued
 function of time.
 If the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\mathbf{q},\dot{\mathbf{q}}]$
\end_inset

 depends on first derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}(t)$
\end_inset

 nonlinearly (which is usually the case), the equations of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}(t)$
\end_inset

 are second-order (they contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\mathbf{q}}$
\end_inset

).
 Suppose we would like to reduce the Lagrangian to a simpler form that generates
 only first-order equations of motion.
 One way is to introduce a new independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(t)$
\end_inset

 which is equal to the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{q}}(t)$
\end_inset

; then one expects to obtain a system of first-order equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{q}(t),\mathbf{v}(t)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A straightforward way to replace velocities with an independent variable
 is to add a constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{q}}-\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

 to the Lagrangian with a Lagrange multiplier.
 Since we have a vector-valued constraint at every moment of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the Lagrange multiplier must also be vector-valued function of time.
 Let us denote this vector-valued Lagrange multiplier by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the modified action can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{S}[\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{s}]=\int\left[L(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v})+\mathbf{s}\cdot\left(\dot{\mathbf{q}}-\mathbf{v}\right)\right]dt.\label{eq:action q v s}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The variation of the new action 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 with respect to three independent vector-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 yields equations of motion that are equivalent to the original ones.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

