\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 As we suspect that two Lagrange multipliers constraining a single function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 are too many, we would like to eliminate one of these Lagrange multipliers.
 To this end, let us compute the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta\tilde{S}[\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{s}]}{\delta\mathbf{v}(t)}=\frac{\partial L(\mathbf{q}(t),\mathbf{v}(t))}{\partial\mathbf{v}}-\mathbf{s}(t).\]

\end_inset

This is an algebraic equation that can be solved with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear and nondegenerate function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

).
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

 the functions that express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s}).\]

\end_inset

Since the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:action q v s}

\end_inset

) contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 merely as a Lagrange multiplier (no derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are involved), we may now substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s})$
\end_inset

 into the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:action q v s}

\end_inset

) and obtain an equivalent action that depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{S}[\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s}]=\int\left[L(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s}))-\mathbf{s}\cdot\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{s})+\mathbf{s}\cdot\dot{\mathbf{q}}\right]dt.\]

\end_inset

 This action is linear in time derivatives, and hence the equations of motion
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}(t),\mathbf{s}(t)$
\end_inset

 are first-order in the time derivatives.
 One may recognize this as the Hamiltonian action, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical momentum corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula \[
L-\mathbf{s}\cdot\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{q})\equiv H(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{q})\]

\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen, the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 has the significance of the canonical momentum.
 Usually, the canonical momentum corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 would be denoted by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

.
 In the present derivation, I chose a different letter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

, because I wanted to emphasize that we do not know the significance of
 the new variables in advance.
 It will not be always the case that the new variables introduced through
 the Lagrange multiplier method have the significance of canonical momenta.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of Lagrange multipliers is more general than the familiar passage
 from the Lagrangian to the Hamiltonian description.
 For instance, one could treat Lagrangians containing higher derivatives
 in the same systematic manner.
 One could also replace only 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 of the higher derivatives but not all, if this proves to be convenient
 in a particular situation.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now apply the method of Lagrange multipliers to the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:nonlinear f(R) gravity action}

\end_inset

).
 At this point, we do not have the purpose of reducing the system to first-order
 equations, but rather to remove the nonlinearity in the 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

 term.
 Therefore, we are motivated to introduce a new field 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 equal to the Ricci scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $R[g_{\mu\nu}]$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, an action equivalent to the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:nonlinear f(R) gravity action}

\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{\mathcal{M}}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{n}p\left[f(r)+\left(R[g_{\mu\nu}]-r\right)\lambda\right],\label{eq:f(R) action 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a Lagrange multiplier field.
 Variation of the above action with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 yields the algebraic equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
f'(r)=\lambda,\]

\end_inset

which can be solved to express 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (since by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(r)\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $r(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 the function obtained by solving the algebraic equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(r)=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 We can then substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 into the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) action 1}

\end_inset

) and obtain an equivalent action,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S[g_{\mu\nu},\lambda]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{n}p\left[f(r(\lambda))-r(\lambda)\lambda+\lambda R[g_{\mu\nu}]\right],\label{eq:f(R) action 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which now depends only on the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the new field 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be varied independently of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

; the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $R[g_{\mu\nu}]=r(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 will be a consequence of the equations of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point, the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) action 2}

\end_inset

) depends 
\emph on
linearly
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and we can use another trick to simplify the equations further.
 Namely, we perform a suitable conformal transformation of the metric.
 According to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R Rtilde}

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=4$
\end_inset

, a conformal transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}\rightarrow\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 with a conformal factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2\Omega}\neq0$
\end_inset

 will change the variables as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g_{\mu\nu} & =e^{2\Omega}\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu},\quad\sqrt{-g}=e^{4\Omega}\sqrt{-\tilde{g}},\\
R[g_{\mu\nu}] & =e^{-2\Omega}\left(R[\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}]+6\tilde{\square}\Omega+6\tilde{g}^{\mu\nu}\Omega_{,\mu}\Omega_{,\nu}\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the D'Alembert operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\square}$
\end_inset

 is defined with respect to the new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 We can now express the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) action 2}

\end_inset

) through the new metric.
 An appropriate choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega=-\frac{1}{2}\ln\lambda,\quad e^{2\Omega}=\frac{1}{\lambda},\label{eq:f(R) Omega lambda}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 cancels the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) action 2}

\end_inset

).
 The action in the new variables is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
S[g_{\mu\nu},\lambda] & \equiv\tilde{S}[\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu},\Omega]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\sqrt{-\tilde{g}}\textrm{d}^{n}p\left[\frac{f(r(\lambda))-r(\lambda)\lambda}{\lambda^{2}}\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.+R[\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}]+6\tilde{\square}\Omega+6\tilde{g}^{\mu\nu}\Omega_{,\mu}\Omega_{,\nu}\right].\label{eq:f(R) action 3}\end{align}

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $6\tilde{\square}\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a total covariant derivative and can be omitted from the action.
 Also, we may express 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) Omega lambda}

\end_inset

) and regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as a new scalar field.
 Introducing the auxiliary function
\begin_inset Formula \[
V(\Omega)\equiv\left.\frac{r(\lambda)\lambda-f(r(\lambda))}{\lambda^{2}}\right|_{\lambda=\lambda(\Omega)},\]

\end_inset

we rewrite the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:f(R) action 3}

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{S}[\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu},\Omega]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\sqrt{-\tilde{g}}\textrm{d}^{n}p\left[R[\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}]+6\tilde{g}^{\mu\nu}\Omega_{,\mu}\Omega_{,\nu}-V(\Omega)\right].\]

\end_inset

This is the action of usual, unmodified Einstein gravity, minimally coupled
 to a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 with a self-interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\Omega)$
\end_inset

.
 The form of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\Omega)$
\end_inset

 is ultimately determined by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

 in the original action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:nonlinear f(R) gravity action}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
The form of the above equation suggests that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(R)$
\end_inset

 is a good choice for a new field, so let us define a new scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv f'(R)$
\end_inset

.
 We shall assume that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

 is such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p=f'(R)$
\end_inset

 can be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (this is the usual assumption for a Legendre transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(R)\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=r(p)$
\end_inset

 be the solution of the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p=f'(R)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we obtain the system of second-order equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{f(r(p))}{p}g_{\mu\nu}+g_{\mu\nu}p^{-1}\square p-p^{-1}p_{;\mu\nu} & =0,\\
R & =r(p).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The appearance of terms 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mu\nu}-p^{-1}p_{;\mu\nu}+g_{\mu\nu}p^{-1}\square p$
\end_inset

 suggests to perform a conformal transformation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}\rightarrow\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}\equiv pg_{\mu\nu},\]

\end_inset

after which these terms will be partially cancelled by the Ricci tensor
 of the conformally rescaled metric [cf.\InsetSpace ~
Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R Rtilde}

\end_inset

)].
 It also appears convenient to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p$
\end_inset

.
 The customary change of variables is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi\equiv\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}\ln p,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary scalar field.
 After a considerable amount of algebra, one can show that the equations
 for the new variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be derived from the following simple Lagrangian,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{S}[\phi,\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-\tilde{g}}\left[\tilde{R}+\frac{1}{2}\tilde{g}^{\mu\nu}\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}-V(\phi)\right],\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
V(\phi)\equiv\frac{pR-f(R)}{p^{2}},\]

\end_inset

and it is implied that the term in the right-hand side is expressed through
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 using the function 
\begin_inset Formula $R=r(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the nonlinear 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

 gravity theory is equivalent to the standard Einstein gravity with a scalar
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, which has a specific self-interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 determined by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogous reductions are possible for gravity theories with Lagrangians
 depending also on 
\begin_inset Formula $\square R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\square^{2}R$
\end_inset

, etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The additional scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be heuristically viewed as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scalar component
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the original gravitational field 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 alone is insufficient to describe the effects of gravity in these nonlinear
 theories.
 Therefore, these models are also called 
\series bold
scalar-tensor theories
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{scalar-tensor gravity}

\end_inset

of gravity.
 The original field variable 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
Jordan frame
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Jordan frame}

\end_inset


\series default
 variables, while the transformed variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Omega,\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
Einstein frame
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein frame}

\end_inset


\series default
 variables.
 The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Einstein frame
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means that in that frame the theory looks like the ordinary Einstein gravity
 coupled to some additional matter fields.
 Calculations are often easier in the Einstein frame.
 However, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary variable that does not describe the physically observed
 metric (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the action for other matter fields, such as the electromagnetic
 field, contains 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

).
 So one needs to perform the conformal transformation back to the Jordan
 frame to recover the physical metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this brief excursion into alternative theories of gravitation, I continue
 to consider only the currently standard theory (Einstein's General Relativity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Energy-momentum tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a field theory that contains some matter fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 interacting with gravity.
 In the Lagrangian formulation, the total system is described by an action
 of the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]=\int_{\mathcal{M}}\left(L_{EH}[g]+L[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]\right)\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]$
\end_inset

 is a Lagrangian for the matter fields and their interactions among themselves,
 while
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{EH}[g]\equiv\frac{1}{16\pi G}R\]

\end_inset

is the Einstein-Hilbert Lagrangian for gravity.
 The Euler-Lagrange equation for a matter field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 is then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta L[\phi;g_{\mu\nu}]}{\delta\phi_{j}}=0,\]

\end_inset

while the equation for the gravitational field is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta L_{EH}[g]}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}+\frac{\delta L[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}=0.\]

\end_inset

We have already computed 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L_{EH}/\delta g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

, and so we can rewrite this equation as the 
\series bold
Einstein equation
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Einstein equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\alpha\beta}-\frac{1}{2}Rg_{\alpha\beta}=16\pi G\frac{\delta L[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}\equiv-8\pi GT_{\alpha\beta},\]

\end_inset

where we have defined the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
energy-momentum tensor
\series default
 (EMT) of matter,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\alpha\beta}\equiv\frac{2}{\sqrt{-g}}\frac{\delta L[\phi_{j};g_{\mu\nu}]}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}.\label{eq:metric EMT}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This tensor plays the role of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the gravitational field.
 In most field theories, this tensor also describes the distribution of
 local energy and momentum density of the field, defined in the conventional
 sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a minimally coupled scalar field with the Lagrangian\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lagr scalar}

\end_inset

) has the EMT
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\alpha\beta}=\phi_{,\alpha}\phi_{,\beta}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\alpha\beta}\phi_{,\mu}\phi^{,\mu}+V(\phi)g_{\alpha\beta}.\label{eq:scalar field EMT}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The electromagnetic field is described by the Maxwell tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the Maxwell equations.
 These equations can be derived from the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{EM}[F;g]=-\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{16\pi}F_{\alpha\beta}F^{\alpha\beta}=-\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{16\pi}F_{\alpha\beta}F_{\mu\nu}g^{\alpha\mu}g^{\beta\nu},\label{eq:Maxwell Lagrangian}\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which also follows the EMT
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{\mu\nu}=\frac{1}{4\pi}\left(\frac{1}{4}g_{\mu\nu}F_{\alpha\beta}F^{\alpha\beta}-F_{\alpha\mu}F_{\beta\nu}g^{\alpha\beta}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the above expressions for the EMT of a scalar field and of the Maxwell
 field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 If a Lagrangian is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\sqrt{-g}L$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{2}{\sqrt{-g}}\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}=-Lg_{\alpha\beta}+2\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}}.\]

\end_inset

In the scalar field Lagrangian, the only term that depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}g^{\mu\nu}\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\delta L[g,\phi]}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}} & =\frac{1}{2}\phi_{,\alpha}\phi_{,\beta},\\
T_{\alpha\beta} & =\phi_{,\alpha}\phi_{,\beta}-g_{\alpha\beta}L\end{align*}

\end_inset

as required.
 The same procedure for the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{EM}$
\end_inset

 yields the required answer since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\mu\nu}}=-\frac{1}{16\pi}\left(F_{\alpha\mu}F_{\beta\nu}g^{\alpha\beta}+F_{\mu\alpha}F_{\nu\beta}g^{\alpha\beta}\right)=-\frac{g^{\alpha\beta}}{8\pi}F_{\alpha\mu}F_{\beta\nu}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the 0-0 component of the electromagnetic EMT and show that it coincides
 with the familiar expression for the energy density of the electromagnetic
 field,
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{00}=\frac{1}{8\pi}\left(|\vec{E}|^{2}+|\vec{B}|^{2}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General covariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a field theory where every matter field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,N$
\end_inset

, is coupled to gravity through the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 Such a field theory is invariant under general coordinate transformations;
 this property is called the 
\series bold
general covariance
\series default
 of the theory.
 General coordinate transformations can be parametrized by four functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 According to the Noether theorem, the invariance with respect to gauge
 transformations leads to mathematical identities that hold regardless of
 the equations of motion.
 However, we 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 obtain useful conservation laws out of a gauge symmetry if we 
\emph on
do
\emph default
 use the equations of motion.
 We shall now show that the requirement of general covariance for a set
 of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 with a Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi_{i};g]$
\end_inset

, together with the Euler-Lagrange equation of motion,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\delta L}{\delta\phi_{i}(x)}=0,\label{eq:phi equ Sm}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 yields a conservation law for the field's energy-momentum tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric EMT}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the conservation law, we consider an infinitesimal coordinate
 transformation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\varepsilon\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 is a vector field, which is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the transformation (points are shifted along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

).
 The matter fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are transformed by the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 according to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}_{i}(\mathbf{x})=\phi_{i}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}})+\delta q_{i}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q_{i}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is defined appropriately for each field, such that the local variation
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi_{i}=\varepsilon\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{f}}\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is transformed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{g}^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})=g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})+\varepsilon\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{f}}g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})=g^{\alpha\beta}+\varepsilon\left(f^{\alpha;\beta}+f^{\beta;\alpha}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the action is invariant under the transformation, therefore
 the variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\int Ld^{4}x$
\end_inset

 must vanish:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
0 & =\delta\int Ld^{4}x=\int\left[\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})}\delta g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})+\frac{\delta L}{\delta\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})}\delta\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})\right]\textrm{d}^{4}x\nonumber \\
 & =\int\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})}\varepsilon\left(f^{\alpha;\beta}+f^{\beta;\alpha}\right)\textrm{d}^{4}x+\int\frac{\delta L}{\delta\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})}\delta\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})\textrm{d}^{4}x.\label{eq:ds var xi}\end{align}

\end_inset

 Since the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi equ Sm}

\end_inset

), the second term vanishes.
 Expressing the first term through the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\int T_{\alpha\beta}f^{\beta;\alpha}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x & =\int\left[\left(T_{\alpha\beta}f^{\beta}\right)^{;\alpha}-T_{\alpha\beta}^{\,;\alpha}f^{\beta}\right]\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x\nonumber \\
 & =-\int T_{\alpha\beta}^{\,;\alpha}f^{\beta}\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x=0.\label{eq:Tab xi}\end{align}

\end_inset

Here we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at infinity sufficiently quickly.
 Since Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Tab xi}

\end_inset

) must be satisfied for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\alpha}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, we conclude that the conservation law 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\,;\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

 holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The absence of the covariant volume factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ds var xi}

\end_inset

) is not a mistake; the result is nevertheless a covariant quantity.
 The derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is calculated using the chain rule, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\int L\textrm{d}^{4}x=\int\left[\frac{\delta L}{\delta g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})}\delta g^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{x})+\frac{\delta L}{\delta\phi_{i}}\delta\phi_{i}(\mathbf{x})\right]\textrm{d}^{4}x,\]

\end_inset

and the rule requires a simple integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{4}x$
\end_inset

.
 The correct covariant behavior is supplied by the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that itself contains a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a flat spacetime, the laws of energy and momentum conservation follow
 from the invariance of the action under spacetime translations.
 In the presence of gravitation the spacetime is curved, so in general the
 spacetime translations are not a physical symmetry any more.
 However, the action is covariant with respect to arbitrary coordinate transform
ations.
 The corresponding conservation law is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covariant conservation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the EMT, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\,;\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, this law does not actually express the conservation of energy
 or momentum of the matter field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 because of the presence of the covariant derivative.
 That equation would be a conservation law if it had the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}\left(\sqrt{-g}T^{\mu\nu}\right)=0$
\end_inset

, but instead it can be shown that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial_{\mu}\left(\sqrt{-g}T^{\mu\nu}\right)=-\sqrt{-g}\Gamma_{\mu\lambda}^{\nu}T^{\mu\lambda}\neq0,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\mu\lambda}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the Christoffel symbol.
 The energy of the matter fields alone, described by the energy-momentum
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

, is not necessarily conserved; the gravitational field can change the energy
 and the momentum of matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For one scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with the Lagrangian\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lagr scalar}

\end_inset

), the conservation of energy-momentum tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}{}^{;\mu}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:scalar field EMT}

\end_inset

), and the equation of motion, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}\phi_{;\mu\nu}+V'(\phi)=0$
\end_inset

, are equivalent:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =T_{\mu\nu}{}^{;\mu}=\left(\phi_{,\mu}\phi_{,\nu}\right)^{;\mu}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\phi_{,\alpha}\phi^{,\alpha}\right)_{;\nu}+V(\phi)\phi_{,\nu}\\
 & =\left(\phi_{;\mu}^{;\mu}+V(\phi)\right)\phi_{,\nu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In a theory of a single scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 coupled to gravity, the conservation law 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}{}^{;\mu}=0$
\end_inset

 is essentially a consequence of the Einstein equation.
 Therefore, one may say that the Einstein equation contains the equation
 of motion for the scalar field.
 However, the same statement will not hold for theories with more than one
 scalar field.
 A single conservation law cannot yield several independent equations of
 motion for all the fields.
\end_layout

