\begin_layout Subsection*
Translational symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A field theory is described by a Lagragian, and a 
\series bold
symmetry
\series default
 of a field theory means a transformation that leaves the Lagrangian invariant.
 For example, consider the theory of a scalar field with the Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset

, for instance, that of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lagr scalar}

\end_inset

) in a flat, Minkowski spacetime, where the metric is 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\eta=\textrm{diag}(1,-1,-1,-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Since this Lagrangian in this spacetime does not depend explicitly on the
 coordinates, it is invariant under a translation of fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\phi(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary constant 4-vector.
 We shall now study the consequences of this symmetry for any Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset

 that depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section only, we denote spacetime points by boldface letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\equiv(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 for brevity.
 This notation is different from the notation in the rest of the text, where
 boldface letters are 
\emph on
vectors
\emph default
 or vector fields.
 In the Minkowski spacetime, one can identify points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 with vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, but in a curved spacetime points are not vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first examine the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\phi(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

 in more detail.
 The transformation is understood as the replacement of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 by a different function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})=\phi(\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a}).\]

\end_inset

Note that the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of the new function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 at a location 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
equal
\emph default
 to the value of the old function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at the location 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

; i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the value of the function is not modified beyond the necessary change
 due to the replacement of the argument, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\tilde{\phi}]$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in the following sense: the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\tilde{\phi}](\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, computed at a fixed location 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, is 
\emph on
equal
\emph default
 to the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi](\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a})$
\end_inset

, i.e., to the value of the same function 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset

, computed for the old field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, at the location 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now express this invariance as a mathematical identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to consider an infinitesimal displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 At a given location 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, the value of any scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{x)}$
\end_inset

 changes under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{x}+\delta\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, to first order, as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta f(\mathbf{x})\equiv\tilde{f}(\mathbf{x})-f(\mathbf{x})=f(\mathbf{x}+\delta\mathbf{a})-f(\mathbf{x})=\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}f+O(\delta\mathbf{a}^{2}).\]

\end_inset

This is the 
\series bold
local variation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{local variation}

\end_inset

of the value of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 (From now on, we shall drop the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\delta\mathbf{a}^{2})$
\end_inset

 since we need to consider only first-order variations.) Because of the assumptio
n of translational invariance, the same argument applies also to the Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi](\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, considered as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x})] & \equiv L[\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})]-L[\phi(\mathbf{x})]\\
 & =L[\phi](\mathbf{x}+\delta\mathbf{a})-L[\phi](\mathbf{x})=\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}L[\phi](\mathbf{x}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The above relation is, essentially, the requirement of translational invariance
 of the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the same variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 can be computed directly, expressing it through the local variation of
 the field,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\phi(\mathbf{x})\equiv\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})-\phi(\mathbf{x})=\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}\phi(\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

We have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x})]=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}\delta\phi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta\phi_{,\mu}.\]

\end_inset

Thus the same quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in two different ways:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x})]=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}\delta\phi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta\phi_{,\mu}=\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}L.\]

\end_inset

This identity expresses the invariance of the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 under translations.
 A conservation law can be now derived, assuming that the Euler-Lagrange
 equation holds for a specific field configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial L[\phi]}{\partial\phi}-\nabla_{\mu}\frac{\partial L[\phi]}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}=0.\]

\end_inset

Namely, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is a constant vector, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 as total divergences, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\phi=\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}\phi=\phi_{,\mu}\delta a^{\mu}=\nabla_{\mu}\left(\phi\delta a^{\mu}\right),\quad\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}L=\nabla_{\mu}\left(L\delta a^{\mu}\right),\]

\end_inset

and then rewrite the above identity as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}\delta\phi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta\phi_{,\mu}-\nabla_{\delta\mathbf{a}}L\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}-\nabla_{\mu}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\right)\delta\phi+\nabla_{\mu}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}-L\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}\right)\delta a^{\nu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the Euler-Lagrange equation is assumed to hold and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, it follows that the following conservation law holds,
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\nabla_{\mu}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}-Lg_{\mu\nu}\right)\equiv\nabla_{\mu}T_{\nu}^{\mu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{\nu}^{\mu}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}-Lg_{\mu\nu}\label{eq:canonical EMT}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the energy-momentum tensor of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 coincides (after lowering the index) with the expression\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:scalar field EMT}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A relation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}j^{\mu}\equiv\textrm{div}\mathbf{j}=0$
\end_inset

 in flat space is called a 
\series bold
conservation law
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conservation law}

\end_inset

and the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{j}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
conserved current
\series default
.
 A simple interpretation can be given in Minkowski coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,\vec{x}\right)$
\end_inset

: The 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is decomposed into the time component 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{0}$
\end_inset

 and a spatial part 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{0}$
\end_inset

 is a density of some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at a point, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{j}$
\end_inset

 is the 3-velocity.
 The conservation law 
\begin_inset Formula $0=j^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}=\partial_{t}j^{0}+\textrm{div}\vec{j}$
\end_inset

 shows that the change in the density 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{0}$
\end_inset

 is always due to the transport of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from neighbor points, which means that the amount of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is conserved.
 Alternatively, we may consider a spacelike 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and compute the total amount 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(t_{1})$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the surface,
\begin_inset Formula \[
Q(t_{1})\equiv\int_{t=t_{1}}j^{0}\textrm{d}^{3}\vec{x}.\]

\end_inset

The conservation law then says that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(t)$
\end_inset

 is constant,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dQ(t)}{dt}=\int\frac{dj^{0}}{dt}\textrm{d}^{3}\vec{x}=-\int\left(\textrm{div}\vec{j}\right)\textrm{d}^{3}\vec{x}=0.\]

\end_inset

The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
conserved charge
\series default
 corresponding to the current 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 with respect to a 3-surface.
 The equations of motion for the field are such that the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is time-independent.
 This is the meaning of the conservation law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, we may consider a one-parametric group of coordinate transformat
ions 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x};\varepsilon),\quad\phi(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is a real parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the identical transformation.
 If a Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi;\mathbf{x}]$
\end_inset

, possibly depending explicitly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, is invariant under this transformation group, in the sense explained above,
 then a similar calculation leads to the conservation law 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}=0$
\end_inset

 for a certain 4-vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
Noether current
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Noether current}

\end_inset

corresponding to the symmetry transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 The Noether current 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is then defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
j^{\mu}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}f^{\nu}-f^{\mu}L,\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula \[
f^{\mu}\equiv\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\mathbf{x}}}{\partial\varepsilon}\right|_{\varepsilon=0}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the above expression for the Noether current 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}})$
\end_inset

, assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int d^{4}\mathbf{x}\, L[\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x});\mathbf{x}]=\int d^{4}\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\, L[\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}});\tilde{\mathbf{x}}].\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 Consider a transformation with an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x})\varepsilon,\quad\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x};\varepsilon)}{\partial\varepsilon}\right|_{\varepsilon=0}.\]

\end_inset

The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 describes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the infinitesimal coordinate transformation.
 The local variation of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\phi\equiv\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})-\phi(\mathbf{x})=\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}})-\phi(\mathbf{x})=\varepsilon f^{\alpha}\phi_{,\alpha}=\varepsilon\mathbf{f}\circ\phi.\]

\end_inset

The local variation of the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{,\mu}$
\end_inset

 is slightly more complicated due to the dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta(\phi_{,\mu})=\frac{\partial\tilde{\phi}(\mathbf{x})}{\partial x^{\mu}}-\frac{\partial\phi(\mathbf{x})}{\partial x^{\mu}}=\frac{\partial\phi(\mathbf{x}+\varepsilon\mathbf{f})}{\partial x^{\mu}}-\frac{\partial\phi(\mathbf{x})}{\partial x^{\mu}}=\left(\varepsilon f^{\alpha}\phi_{,\alpha}\right)_{,\mu}.\]

\end_inset

The local variation of the Lagrangian (at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

) due to the local variation of the field is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x});\mathbf{x}] & =\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}\delta\phi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta(\phi_{,\mu})\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta\phi\right)_{,\mu}=\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}f^{\nu}\varepsilon\right)_{,\mu},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we have used the Euler-Lagrange equation.
 On the other hand, the invariance of the action under the transformation
 means that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\,\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x});\mathbf{x}]=\int\textrm{d}^{4}\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\, L[\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}});\tilde{\mathbf{x}}]-\int\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\, L[\phi(\mathbf{x});\mathbf{x}].\]

\end_inset

The volume element is transformed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{d}^{4}\tilde{\mathbf{x}} & =\left(\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\right)\det\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}=\left(\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\right)\det\left(1+\varepsilon\frac{\partial f^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\right)\left(1+\varepsilon\frac{\partial f^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\mu}}\right)=\left(\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\right)\left(1+\varepsilon\textrm{div}\mathbf{f}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

(Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(1+\varepsilon A\right)=1+\varepsilon\textrm{Tr}A+O(\varepsilon^{2})$
\end_inset

 for a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.) Since
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\phi(\tilde{\mathbf{x}});\tilde{\mathbf{x}}]-L[\phi;\mathbf{x}]=\varepsilon f^{\mu}\frac{\partial L}{\partial x^{\mu}}=\varepsilon\mathbf{f}\circ L,\]

\end_inset

we obtain the identity (up to terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{2}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}f^{\nu}\varepsilon\right)_{,\mu}-\varepsilon f^{\mu}\frac{\partial L}{\partial x^{\mu}}-\varepsilon\frac{\partial f^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\mu}}L\\
 & =\varepsilon\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}f^{\nu}-f^{\mu}L\right)_{,\mu}\equiv\varepsilon j^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a conserved current.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the symmetry group has 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

 parameters then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 conservation laws can be found.
 Let us study this case in some more detail.
 Suppose we are given an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-parametric group of smooth transformations of a spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuous groups of transformations, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
groups that are themselves smooth
 multidimensional manifolds, are called 
\series bold
Lie groups
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie group}

\end_inset

 If the symmetry group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional Lie group then each element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in G$
\end_inset

 acts as a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x};\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
 An 
\emph on
infinitesimal
\emph default
 transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{x}+\delta\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an element of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimally close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the identity transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Such elements can be (heuristically) parametrized as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\exp(\varepsilon\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\mathbf{1}+\varepsilon\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a tangent vector from the (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional) tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathbf{1}}G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is the exponentiation map that produces points along the orbits of a vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a derivation operator acting on functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The transformation of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\varepsilon\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v})\equiv\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x})}{\partial\varepsilon}\right|_{\varepsilon=0}=\mathbf{v}\circ\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x};\gamma),\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{x};\gamma)$
\end_inset

 is a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathbf{1}}G$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathbf{x}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{s}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional and labels the tangent space to the Lie group.
 The calculation leading to the definition of the Noether current yields
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\phi_{,\nu}f_{s}^{\nu}-f_{s}^{\mu}L\right)_{;\mu}v^{s}\equiv j_{s}^{\mu}{}_{;\mu}=0,\]

\end_inset

thus the Noether current 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is also a 1-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathbf{1}}G$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathbf{x}}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 We have seen an example of such a Noether current\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:canonical EMT}

\end_inset

): the group of transformations is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 and thus the index 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 can be identified as a four-dimensional Minkowski index, yielding a (1,1)-tenso
r 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding Noether charge 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Q_{\nu}(t_{0})=\int_{t=t_{0}}T_{\nu}^{0}\textrm{d}^{3}x\]

\end_inset

 represents the total 4-momentum on a spacelike 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The total energy and the total momentum are conserved, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\nu}(t)=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EMT\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:canonical EMT}

\end_inset

) obtained as a Noether current with respect to translation symmetry is
 called the 
\series bold
canonical EMT
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{canonical energy-momentum tensor}

\end_inset

while the tensor defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric EMT}

\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
metric EMT
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{metric energy-momentum tensor}

\end_inset

The canonical and the metric EMT coincide for the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 but not necessarily for other fields; however, this mismatch is merely
 a technical problem with the calculations.
 Both these tensors are conserved in flat space, and therefore the difference
 between them is a divergence-free tensor.
 Indeed, we can always add a divergence of an arbitrary antisymmetric tensor
 to a conserved current without changing the conservation law,
\begin_inset Formula \[
j^{\mu}\rightarrow\tilde{j}^{\mu}=j^{\mu}+\left(B^{\mu\nu}-B^{\nu\mu}\right)_{,\nu};\quad j^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}=\tilde{j}^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}=0.\]

\end_inset

Note that the calculation leading to the definition of the Noether current
 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 only shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}{}_{,\mu}=0$
\end_inset

 and thus does not necessarily determine the physically correct expression
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the metric EMT, not the canonical EMT, that contributes to the Einstein
 equations and plays the role of the source of gravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Internal symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The essense of Noether's theorem is that 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 symmetry of a Lagrangian leads to a conservation law.
 Our first example was a transformation that did not modify the value of
 the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (beyond the necessary change due to the coordinate shift).
 The second example is a field theory with an 
\series bold
internal symmetry
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{internal symmetry}

\end_inset

i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a symmetry transformation that changes the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 but does not involve the coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a complex-valued scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 with the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\psi]=\frac{1}{2}\left(g^{\mu\nu}\partial_{\mu}\psi\partial_{\nu}\psi^{*}-V(|\psi|)\right)\sqrt{-g}.\]

\end_inset

This Lagrangian is manifestly invariant under the group of transformations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\rightarrow\tilde{\psi}=e^{\text{i}\alpha}\psi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary real number; this is an example of an internal symmetry
 of the theory.
 The identity 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\tilde{\psi}]=L[\psi]$
\end_inset

 leads to a conservation law.
 Again, it is convenient to apply an infinitesimal transformation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi\rightarrow\tilde{\psi}=\psi\left(1+\text{i}\alpha\right)+O(\alpha^{2}),\]

\end_inset

and to suppress terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}$
\end_inset

 or higher.
 The local variation of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\psi(\mathbf{x})=\text{i}\alpha\psi(\mathbf{x}),\quad\delta\psi^{*}=-\text{i}\alpha\psi^{*},\]

\end_inset

hence the local variation of the Lagrangian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\delta L[\psi(\mathbf{x}),\mathbf{x}]=L[\tilde{\psi}(\mathbf{x}),\mathbf{x}]-L[\psi(\mathbf{x}),\mathbf{x}]\\
 & =\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi}\delta\psi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi^{*}}\delta\psi^{*}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}}\delta\psi_{,\mu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}^{*}}\delta\psi_{,\mu}^{*}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}}\delta\psi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}^{*}}\delta\psi^{*}\right)_{,\mu}=\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}^{*}}\psi-\frac{\partial L}{\partial\psi_{,\mu}}\psi^{*}\right)_{,\mu}\text{i}\alpha,\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we have used the Euler-Lagrange equations.
 For the above Lagrangian, the Noether current is
\begin_inset Formula \[
j^{\mu}=g^{\mu\nu}\frac{\psi_{,\nu}\psi^{*}-\psi_{,\nu}^{*}\psi}{2i},\]

\end_inset

and the Noether charge is interpreted as the charge density of the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Infinite-dimensional (gauge) symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Noether theorem applies to a more general case: namely, an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional Lie group of transformations that changes both the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and the values of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,...,A$
\end_inset

, according to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\varepsilon\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}),\quad\phi_{a}(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}_{a}(\mathbf{x})=\phi_{a}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}})+\varepsilon q_{a}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}),\]

\end_inset

and adds a total divergence to the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\, L[\tilde{\phi}_{a}(\mathbf{x}),\mathbf{x}]=\int\textrm{d}^{4}\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\, L[\phi_{a}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}),\tilde{\mathbf{x}}]+\int\textrm{d}^{4}\mathbf{x}\left(\partial_{\mu}C^{\mu}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a suitable auxiliary vector field.
 A corresponding Noether current 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 exists also in this case, indicating a conserved quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 that remains constant by virtue of the equations of motion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conservation of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as simply a consequence of the equations of motion, and derived
 by suitable algebraic manipulations from the Euler-Lagrange equations.
 However, in that case one may wonder what other conservation laws may be
 found and how the necessary manipulations are to be guessed.
 On the other hand, the Noether theorem explains that the existence of conserved
 quantities is necessary, as long as the Lagrangian has a continuous symmetry.
 (And, conversely, every conservation law is a consequence of a symmetry.)
 Thus, symmetries and the Noether theorem provide a more natural way to
 obtain conservation laws in a given field theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A qualitatively different situation arises if the theory is invariant under
 symmetry transformations parametrized by an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 
\emph on
function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 of the spacetime.
 (This makes the group of transformations an 
\emph on
infinite
\emph default
-dimensional group.) Such symmetry transformation is called a 
\series bold
gauge symmetry
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{gauge symmetry}

\end_inset

A familiar example of a gauge symmetry is the Maxwell theory with the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{EM}=-\frac{1}{16\pi}F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu},\quad F_{\mu\nu}\equiv\partial_{\mu}A_{\nu}-\partial_{\nu}A_{\mu},\]

\end_inset

which is invariant under the gauge transformation
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\mu}(\mathbf{x})\rightarrow\tilde{A}_{\mu}(\mathbf{x})=A_{\mu}(\mathbf{x})+\partial_{\mu}\alpha(\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now examine the consequences of a gauge symmetry.
 Suppose that a field theory is described by a Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the (infinitesimal) internal symmetry transformations
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}=\phi+\delta\phi(\phi;\alpha),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi(\phi;\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity, let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi(\phi,\alpha)$
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the first derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{,\mu}$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\phi(\phi,\alpha)=p(\phi)\alpha+q^{\mu}(\phi)\alpha_{,\mu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\mu}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 are some known coefficients.
 Then the local variation of the Lagrangian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\delta L[\phi(\mathbf{x}),\mathbf{x}]=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}\delta\phi+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\delta\phi_{,\mu}\\
 & =\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}p\alpha+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}q^{\mu}\alpha_{,\mu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\left(p\alpha\right)_{,\mu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}\left(q^{\nu}\alpha_{,\nu}\right)_{,\mu}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}p+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}p_{,\mu}\right)\alpha+\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}q^{\mu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\nu}}\left(p\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}+q^{\mu}{}_{,\nu}\right)\right)\alpha_{,\mu}\\
 & \;+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}q^{\nu}\alpha_{,\mu\nu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function, the terms involving 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\nabla\alpha$
\end_inset

, etc., must separately vanish.
 Thus we obtain the following three identities,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}p+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}p_{,\mu} & =0,\\
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}q^{\mu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\nu}}\left(p\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}+q^{\mu}{}_{,\nu}\right) & =0,\\
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\mu}}q^{\nu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi_{,\nu}}q^{\mu} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

(The last line follows because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{,\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 tensor.) Note that we did not assume that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Euler-Lagrange equation.
 Hence, the above identities hold simply because of the mathematical properties
 of the Lagrangian and the fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an illustration, let us evaluate the three identities in the Maxwell
 theory.
 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is now the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, and we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L_{EM}}{\partial A_{\mu}} & =0,\quad\frac{\partial L_{EM}}{\partial A_{\mu,\nu}}=-\frac{1}{4\pi}F^{\mu\nu},\\
\delta A_{\mu} & =\alpha_{,\mu}=\delta_{\mu}^{\nu}\alpha_{,\nu}\equiv q_{\mu}^{\nu}\alpha_{,\nu};\quad q_{\mu;\rho}^{\nu}=0;\quad p=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Of the three identities, the first two yield 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0$
\end_inset

 and the last one is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial A_{\lambda,\mu}}q_{\lambda}^{\nu}+\frac{\partial L}{\partial A_{\lambda,\nu}}q_{\lambda}^{\mu}=F^{\nu\mu}+F^{\mu\nu}=0.\]

\end_inset

This is a simple mathematical consequence of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invariance of a field theory under gauge transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}(\phi;\alpha)$
\end_inset

 does not lead to useful conservation laws but has another important consequence
 for the theory.
 Consider a Cauchy problem for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, which consists of specifying the initial values of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{in}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 at an initial spacelike 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the Euler-Lagrange equation for the initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{in}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is a symmetry of the equations of motion, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}(\phi;\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is another solution, for an arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 can be chosen so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\neq0$
\end_inset

 to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}(\phi(\mathbf{x});\alpha)$
\end_inset

 will then have the same initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{in}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 but will differ from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the solution of the Cauchy problem is not unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, this lack of uniqueness was a problem initially encountered by
 A.
 Einstein who came up with the following 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hole argument
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{hole argument}

\end_inset

 when trying to derive the equations for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is a solution for the metric in the spacetime, subject to some boundary
 conditions.
 If the boundary conditions are imposed on some 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 that encircles a domain of spacetime, we can find a small region (a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hole
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) inside the domain.
 Due to the general covariance of the theory, we are free to transform the
 coordinates, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, in such a way that the coordinates are changed only within the hole but
 remain the same everywhere else.
 This would change the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 inside the hole but not elsewhere.
 The new metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 still satisfies the same boundary conditions as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the metric at any given point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is not uniquely specified by the equations of motion and boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resolution of this paradox is that coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary labels assigned to events in spacetime.
 A gauge transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 merely relabels the events but does not influence the observable effects
 of gravitation (e.g.\InsetSpace ~
the distance between some physical events).
 Thus, solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
physically equivalent
\emph default
.
 In any theory with a gauge symmetry, two solutions that differ by a gauge
 transformation are physically equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the freedom to choose an arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 in a gauge transformation means that any one of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 may be set to zero (or to any other function).
 This will reduce the number of unknown functions to solve for.
 Such a reduction is called 
\series bold
gauge fixing
\series default
.
 For example, the gauge symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}\rightarrow A_{\mu}+\partial_{\mu}\alpha$
\end_inset

 in electrodynamics allows one to fix 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and to consider the remaining three components 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},A_{3}$
\end_inset

 as the only physically relevant fields.
 However, the Maxwell equations in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},A_{3}$
\end_inset

 appear much less symmetric and more difficult to solve.
 Alternatively, one may choose the 
\series bold
Lorentz gauge 
\series default
condition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}{}^{;\mu}=0$
\end_inset

, or other suitable condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To conclude: The presence of a gauge symmetry indicates that the description
 of the theory contains 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too many
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fields.
 The freedom can be eliminated by fixing the gauge.
 However, a description in a fixed gauge may be much less convenient than
 the original description.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hamiltonian formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Literature sources: 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Pois04}

\end_inset

, chapter 4; 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

, Appendix.
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this section is to introduce the Hamiltonian formulation
 of general relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point of a classical theory is the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L(q_{i},\dot{q}_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,N_{q}$
\end_inset

, are the generalized coordinates, and the action functional is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[q_{i}(t)]=\int L(q_{i},\dot{q}_{i})\textrm{d}t.\]

\end_inset

 A Hamiltonian formulation of the theory is then obtained through the following
 steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define the 
\series bold
canonical momenta
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{canonical momentum}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\equiv\partial L/\partial\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Express 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 from these equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H(p_{i},q_{i})\equiv\sum_{i}p_{i}\dot{q}_{i}-L(q_{i},\dot{q}_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are expressed as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the right-hand side.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the 
\series bold
Hamilton equations
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hamilton equations}

\end_inset

of motion, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dt}q_{i}=\frac{\partial H}{\partial p_{i}},\quad\frac{d}{dt}p_{i}=-\frac{\partial H}{\partial q_{i}}.\]

\end_inset

These equations can be also considered as Euler-Lagrange equations following
 from the Hamiltonian action principle,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hamiltonian action principle}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta\int_{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}\textrm{d}t\left(\sum_{i}p_{i}\dot{q}_{i}-H(p,q)\right)=0,\label{eq:Hamiltonian action}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 are varied 
\emph on
independently
\emph default
, subject only to the boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q_{i}(t_{1,2})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In field theory, the role of the generalized coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 is played by the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N_{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 now becomes a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

condensed index
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv\{ j,x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in the Hamiltonian formalism the dependence on time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 must be separated from the dependence on spatial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)\equiv x_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 (We shall use Latin indices for three-dimensional components.) In a curved
 spacetime, there is no natural time variable, which means that we need
 to 
\emph on
arbitrarily select
\emph default
 a coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding family of spacelike 3-surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a family of nonintersecting spacelike 3-surfaces, covering the entire
 spacetime, is called a 
\series bold
time foliation 
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{time foliation}

\end_inset

of the spacetime.
 The traditional Hamiltonian approach is 
\emph on
noncovariant
\emph default
: it requires an explicit time foliation of the spacetime and treats the
 time dependence of every variable differently from the spacial dependence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L(q_{i},\dot{q}_{i})$
\end_inset

 is replaced by a Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, which is an integral over a 3-surface,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}[\phi_{i},\dot{\phi}_{i}]=\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\textrm{d}^{3}x_{a}\, L(\phi_{i},\partial_{a}\phi_{i},\dot{\phi}_{i}),\]

\end_inset

where we separated the time derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}_{i}$
\end_inset

 from the spatial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{a}\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is now a 
\emph on
functional
\emph default
 and is denoted by a script letter, in distinction from the Lagrangian density
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which is a 
\emph on
function
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(t,x_{a})$
\end_inset

 is defined as the functional derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}_{i}(t,x_{a})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{i}(t,x_{a})=\frac{\delta\mathcal{L}[\phi_{i},\dot{\phi}_{i}]}{\delta\dot{\phi}_{i}(t,x_{a})}.\]

\end_inset

Finally, the summation over 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the definition of the Hamiltonian must be replaced by a summation over
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and an integration over the 3-surface,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{H}[p_{i},\phi_{i}]=\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\sum_{j}p_{j}(t,x_{a})\dot{\phi}_{j}(t,x_{a})\textrm{d}^{3}x_{a}-\mathcal{L}[\phi_{i},\dot{\phi}_{i}].\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now derive Hamiltonian formulations for the Maxwell theory where
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the 4-potential 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}(x)$
\end_inset

, and for Einstein's General Relativity where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electrodynamics in Hamiltonian formulation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Maxwell Lagrangian}

\end_inset

) of the Maxwell theory is
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{16\pi}F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu}=\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{8\pi}\left(|\vec{E}|^{2}-|\vec{B}|^{2}\right),\]

\end_inset

which (in flat space) is the familiar expression for the pressure of the
 electromagnetic field.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Several field theories, e.g.\InsetSpace ~
the scalar field and the electromagnetic field,
 have the energy-momentum tensor of a 
\series bold
perfect fluid
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{perfect fluid}

\end_inset

form, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}=\rho u_{\mu}u_{\nu}-\left(p+\rho\right)g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, the Lagrangian density 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the Hamiltonian density 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 to the energy density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The spacetime metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is now considered as a known function, so only the electromagnetic potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is to be determined.
 (To express this, one says that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
background field
\series default
.) 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{background field}

\end_inset

To compute the canonical momenta corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, we need to separate the dependence of the Lagrangian on the 
\emph on
time
\emph default
 derivatives of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a time foliation of the spacetime is fixed and some coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 are chosen on equal-time surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 be a normalized, timelike vector field orthogonal to the equal-time surfaces.
 For each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}(p)\subset T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent space to the equal-time surface intersecting the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then we may decompose the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{n}A_{0}+P\mathbf{A},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}\equiv g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{A})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{n}g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is the orthogonal projector onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 The 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is spacelike and tangent to the equal-time surfaces.
 Hence, in local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 on equal-time surfaces, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $P\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is described by a 3-vector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{1},A_{2},A_{3}\right\} \equiv\vec{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we can define the 3-vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Time derivatives appear in the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{E}\equiv E_{a}=\partial_{t}A_{a}-\partial_{a}A_{0}\equiv\partial_{t}\vec{A}-\textrm{grad }A_{0},\]

\end_inset

 while the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{B}\equiv B_{a}=\sum_{b,c=1}^{3}\varepsilon_{abc}\partial_{b}A_{c}=\textrm{rot }\vec{A}\]

\end_inset

 depends only on spatial derivatives.
 It is clear that the Lagrangian does not contain the time derivative of
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we cannot define a canonical momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

, and there are no Hamilton equations of motion for the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{0},p_{0}\right\} $
\end_inset

; in this case, one says that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not a dynamical variable
\emph default
.
 This conclusion agrees with the existence of a gauge symmetry in electrodynamic
s.
 Namely, by performing a gauge transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}\rightarrow A_{\mu}+\partial_{\mu}\alpha$
\end_inset

 one could set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 to an arbitrary fixed function (this is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixing the gauge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 For simplicity, let us set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the variation of the Lagrangian with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{a=1}^{3}\partial_{a}\left(\sqrt{-g}E_{a}\right)\equiv\sqrt{-g}\,\textrm{div }\vec{E}=0,\label{eq:Maxwell constraint}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which does not contain time derivatives and is therefore a 
\series bold
constraint
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{constraint}

\end_inset

of the theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
There might be a sign error here: 
\begin_inset Formula $p=-E$
\end_inset

? See Wald 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

, p.
 461-462.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,2,3$
\end_inset

) for the spatial components of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are easily found,
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{a}(x)=-\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{4\pi}E_{a}=\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{4\pi}\dot{A}_{a}.\]

\end_inset

The time derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{A}_{a}$
\end_inset

 are expressed through the momenta as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{A}_{a}=\frac{4\pi}{\sqrt{-g}}p_{a},\]

\end_inset

hence the Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{H}[p_{a},A_{a},A_{0}] & =\int_{t=\textrm{const}}d^{3}x_{a}\left(\frac{2\pi}{\sqrt{-g}}\sum_{b=1}^{3}p_{b}^{2}(x)+\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{8\pi}\left|\vec{B}\right|^{2}\right)\\
 & =\int_{t=\textrm{const}}d^{3}x_{a}\frac{\sqrt{-g}}{8\pi}\left(|\vec{E}|^{2}-|\vec{B}|^{2}\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

which (in flat space) is the familiar expression for the total energy of
 the electromagnetic field at a fixed time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hamilton equations of motion are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial A_{a}}{\partial t} & =\frac{\delta\mathcal{H}}{\delta p_{a}}=\frac{4\pi}{\sqrt{-g}}p_{a},\\
\frac{\partial p_{a}}{\partial t} & =-\frac{\delta\mathcal{H}}{\delta A_{a}}=\sum_{b,c}\partial_{c}(\sqrt{-g}\varepsilon_{abc}B_{b})\equiv-\sqrt{-g}\,\textrm{rot }\vec{B}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to see that the above equations, together with the
 constraint\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Maxwell constraint}

\end_inset

), are equivalent to the Maxwell equations in vacuum.
 The constraint is merely a restriction on possible initial conditions:
 Once the constraint holds at an initial time, it will hold at any future
 time since 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}\textrm{div }\vec{E}=-\textrm{div}\left(\textrm{rot }\vec{B}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gauge fixing condition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 does not entirely remove the gauge freedom because one can still perform
 a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{a}\rightarrow A_{a}+\partial_{a}\alpha$
\end_inset

 with a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(x_{a})$
\end_inset

 depending only on spatial coordinates.
 An additional gauge fixing condition, such as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{a}\partial_{a}\left(\sqrt{-g}A_{a}\right)=\textrm{div }\vec{A}=0,\]

\end_inset

 will remove the remaining gauge freedom.
 Note that the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div }\vec{E}=0$
\end_inset

 will be an automatic consequence of this gauge condition.
 The resulting gauge is called the 
\series bold
radiation gauge
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{radiation gauge}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{div }\vec{E}=0$
\end_inset

 is the Maxwell equation in vacuum, describing the propagation of pure electroma
gnetic field, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 means, heuristically, the absence of an electrostatic field component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we have fixed the gauge, we had to add the constraint\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Maxwell constraint}

\end_inset

) to the Hamilton equations of motion.
 It is possible instead to keep the nondynamical field 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the Hamiltonian (without introducing the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 The constraint will then be obtained as the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathcal{H}/\delta A_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 To get a better idea of the Hamiltonian treatment of constrained systems,
 in the next subsection we shall consider some simple examples from classical
 mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hamiltonian mechanics of constrained systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See also 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{LeWa90,Jack93}

\end_inset

 for a more detailed and wide-ranging developments.
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hamiltonian formalism involves replacing velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 by momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 through the relations 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\delta L/\delta\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 However, in many cases these relations cannot be solved for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and then the standard rule for finding the Hamiltonian cannot be used.
 For instance, the Lagrangian for electrodynamics is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{A}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and thus the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=\delta L/\delta\dot{A}_{0}$
\end_inset

 cannot be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Another example is when 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 in, say, the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

; in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L/\delta\dot{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and again the same problem arises: namely, we cannot express 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 through the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In these cases, one can use a slightly different but equivalent approach
 to develop a Hamiltonian formulation.
 This approach is known as the 
\series bold
Faddeev-Jackiw formalism
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Faddeev-Jackiw formalism}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea of the Faddeev-Jackiw approach is to recognize that the Hamilton
 equations of motion are first-order in time derivatives and follow, as
 Euler-Lagrange equations, from the action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hamiltonian action}

\end_inset

) that is 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 in all the velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Given the Lagrangian\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hamiltonian action}

\end_inset

), we do not attempt to introduce new canonical momenta for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, because we recognize that these momenta are already present in the Lagrangian
 (they are the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, the transition from a Lagrangian formulation to a Hamiltonian formulation
 can be seen as the replacement of a Lagrangian action 
\begin_inset Formula $L(q,\dot{q})$
\end_inset

, which is generally nonlinear in the velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

, by 
\emph on
another Lagrangian
\emph default
, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}\equiv\sum_{i}p_{i}\dot{q}_{i}-H(p,q)$
\end_inset

, which is 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 in the velocities and thus yields first-order Euler-Lagrange equations
 of motion.
 The replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\tilde{L}$
\end_inset

 comes at the cost of extending the Lagrangian by introducing extra momentum
 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we need to add only as many momentum variables as needed for
 the Lagrangian to become linear in all the velocities.
 If we notice that the Lagrangian is linear in velocities, we conclude that
 all the necessary momentum variables are already introduced, and the Hamilton
 equations will be found as the ordinary Euler-Lagrange equations for an
 ordinary (Lagrangian) system.
 All these Euler-Lagrange equations will be (at most) first-order in time
 derivatives, as expected for Hamilton equations.
 After deriving these equations, one can easily determine whether constraints
 are present in the system.
 Namely, the constraints will be any equations not containing time derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first example, consider the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{0}(x,\dot{x},y,\dot{y},z,\dot{z})=\dot{x}y+\frac{1}{2}m\dot{z}^{2}-\frac{1}{2m}y^{2}-V(x,z).\]

\end_inset

This Lagrangian is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}$
\end_inset

, independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}$
\end_inset

, and quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{z}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to obtain a Hamiltonian formulation for this system.
 Since the Lagrangian is nonlinear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{z}$
\end_inset

, we introduce the canonical momentum for the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{z}\equiv\frac{\partial L_{0}}{\partial\dot{z}}=m\dot{z},\]

\end_inset

express 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{z}=\frac{1}{m}p_{z}$
\end_inset

, and build the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

temporary Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{0}\equiv\left.p_{z}\dot{z}-L_{0}\right|_{\dot{z}=p_{z}/m}=-\dot{x}y+\frac{1}{2m}p_{z}^{2}+\frac{1}{2m}y^{2}+V(x,z).\]

\end_inset

Now we formulate the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

temporary Hamiltonian action principle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the variation of the new, extended Lagrangian, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\tilde{L}_{0}(x,\dot{x},y,z,\dot{z},p_{z}) & \equiv p_{z}\dot{z}-H_{0}\\
 & =p_{z}\dot{z}+\dot{x}y-\frac{1}{2m}p_{z}^{2}-\frac{1}{2m}y^{2}-V(x,z).\end{align*}

\end_inset

The Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is linear in all the velocities.
 Therefore, we do not need to introduce any more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

momentum
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variables; instead, we simply need to relabel some of the existing variables
 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

momenta.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Presently, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 plays the role of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

momentum
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, relabeling 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}\equiv y$
\end_inset

, we obtain the Hamiltonian action,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{L}_{0}(x,\dot{x},p_{x},z,\dot{z},p_{z})=p_{x}\dot{x}+p_{z}\dot{z}-\frac{1}{2m}\left(p_{x}^{2}+p_{z}^{2}\right)-V(x,z),\]

\end_inset

 which describes a particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in a two-dimensional potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x,z)$
\end_inset

.
 The Euler-Lagrange equations of motion are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\dot{x}=\frac{1}{m}p_{x}, & \quad\dot{p}_{x}=-\partial V/\partial x,\\
\dot{z}=\frac{1}{m}p_{z}, & \quad\dot{p}_{z}=-\partial V/\partial z.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Clearly, there are no constraints in this model.
 We conclude that the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}$
\end_inset

 is actually 
\emph on
not constrained
\emph default
, despite the fact that we could not introduce the momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{y}$
\end_inset

 in the conventional manner.
 The reason for the difficulty was purely technical: the initial Lagrangian
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}$
\end_inset

 was already 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

half-way done
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 becoming a Hamiltonian.
 However, the unusual Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}$
\end_inset

 is completely equivalent to the more conventional 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some systems, however, 
\emph on
are
\emph default
 constrained.
 As a further example, consider the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{1}(q_{1},\dot{q}_{1},q_{2},\dot{q}_{2})=\frac{1}{2}\left(\dot{q}_{1}-q_{2}\right)^{2}.\]

\end_inset

This Lagrangian is quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

, so we introduce the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{1}\equiv\frac{\partial L_{1}}{\partial\dot{q}_{1}}=\dot{q}_{1}-q_{2},\]

\end_inset

solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}=p_{1}+q_{2}$
\end_inset

, and obtain the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

temporary Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{1}(q_{1},p_{1},q_{2},p_{2})=\left.p_{1}\dot{q}_{1}-L_{1}\right|_{\dot{q}_{1}=p_{1}+q_{2}}=\frac{1}{2}p_{1}^{2}+p_{1}q_{2}\]

\end_inset

and the extended Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{L}_{1}(q_{1},\dot{q}_{1},q_{2},\dot{q}_{2},p_{1})=p_{1}\dot{q}_{1}-H_{1}=p_{1}\dot{q}_{1}-\frac{1}{2}p_{1}^{2}-p_{1}q_{2}.\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is linear in all the velocities, we now find the Hamilton equations as
 the Euler-Lagrange equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{q}_{1}-p_{1}-q_{2}=0,\quad p_{1}=0,\quad\dot{p}_{1}=0.\]

\end_inset

Clearly, we have one constraint, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, and one dynamical equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system with the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the gauge symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q_{1}\rightarrow q_{1}+\alpha(t),\quad q_{2}\rightarrow q_{2}+\partial_{t}\alpha(t),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(t)$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function.
 Determine the identity that this symmetry generates via Noether's theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practice problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the Hamilton equations of motion for the following Lagrangians:
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{3}=\frac{\dot{x}^{2}}{2}+xy\dot{z};\quad L_{4}=\frac{\dot{x}^{2}}{2}+\frac{\left(x+y\right)^{2}}{2};\quad L_{5}=\dot{x}y+\frac{\dot{y}^{2}}{2}+xy.\]

\end_inset

Determine which of these Lagrangians are constrained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, after determining the Hamilton equations and the constraints,
 one needs to solve these equations.
 Sometimes it is easy to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solve the constraints,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
to express some canonical variables as functions of others, and thus
 to reduce the number of dynamical degrees of freedom.
 In other cases, solving the constraints is a nontrivial task, and instead
 one attempts to solve the dynamical equations and impose the constraints
 afterwards.
 A full consideration of this topic is beyond the scope of these lectures;
 there exists an extensive literature about constrained systems, both classical
 and quantized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauss-Codazzi equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Hamiltonian formalism, time derivatives play a completely different
 role from spatial derivatives.
 To compute the canonical momenta in general relativity, we will need to
 separate the spatial and the temporal derivatives in the Einstein-Hilbert
 Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}R$
\end_inset

.
 Under 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
