\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\delta g$
\end_inset

 must vanish on a boundary surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is different from the usual condition where only the variation of
 a field is constrained to vanish (but not its derivative).
 The formal reason for imposing the extra condition was the presence of
 a total divergence term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\tilde{\mathcal{M}}}\sqrt{-g}d^{4}p\,\textrm{div}\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 is a vector field depending on the 
\emph on
derivatives
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\delta g$
\end_inset

, as defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:variation Ricci}

\end_inset

).
 However, one can cancel this divergence term by subtracting an extra boundary
 term from the Einstein-Hilbert action, thus defining the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corrected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 action 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}[g]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{G}\equiv S_{EH}-\oint_{\partial\tilde{\mathcal{M}}}2K\sqrt{h}\textrm{d}^{3}p,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a suitable function (the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is for later convenience), and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the induced metric on the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\tilde{\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

.
 In this section, we show how to choose the required function 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 so that the variation of the action 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}[g]$
\end_inset

