\begin_layout Subsection
The Hamiltonian for pure gravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall compute the canonical momenta and the Hamiltonian for pure
 gravity (without matter) in general relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, we choose a time foliation such that the (timelike) vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv g^{-1}dt$
\end_inset

 normal to the surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is normalized, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
geodesic
\emph default
 vector field (why?); also, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the proper time along the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This choice of the time foliation, called the 
\series bold
synchronous gauge
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{sunchronous gauge}

\end_inset

 may be impossible to perform globally due to focusing of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this choice is always possible locally, because one can emit timelike
 geodesics normal to an arbitrary initial spacelike surface and use the
 proper time along the geodesics as the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 It is also convenient to choose the local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

 within a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 such that the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 are connecting vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{e}_{a}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This completely removes the coordinate freedom (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixes the gauge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 induced on the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
h_{\mu\nu}=g_{\mu\nu}-n_{\mu}n_{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

 Hence, in a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{n},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has the matrix representation
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & * & * & *\\
0 & * & * & *\\
0 & * & * & *\end{array}\right),\]

\end_inset

where the stars indicate the unknown nonzero components 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 of the partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}=\sqrt{-h}$
\end_inset

, so the covariant 4-volume element is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x=\sqrt{-h}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}^{3}x_{a}$
\end_inset

, while the covariant 3-volume element on a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-h}\textrm{d}^{3}x_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that the Lagrangian depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, therefore we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t,x_{a})$
\end_inset

 to be the set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense of the Hamiltonian formalism.
 The next task is to find the dependence of the Lagrangian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}R$
\end_inset

, on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h_{ab}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 and to compute the corresponding canonical momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}_{ab}\equiv\partial h_{ab}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in a geometric way as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{h}\equiv\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}h,\]

\end_inset

since the basis vectors in the 3-surface commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{e}_{a}=0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial h_{ab}}{\partial t}=\partial_{t}\circ\left(h(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\right)=\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\left(h(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\right)=\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}h\right)\circ(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}).\]

\end_inset

 Hence, for tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}h\right)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\left(h(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\right)-h(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-h(\mathbf{x},\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{y})\nonumber \\
=\nabla_{\mathbf{n}} & h(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-h(\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{x}-\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})-h(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{y}-\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n})\nonumber \\
 & =h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})+h(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{y})=2K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}),\label{eq:Lnh and K}\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\cdot,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is the extrinsic curvature of the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}_{ab}=2K_{ab}$
\end_inset

, and the dependence of the Einstein-Hilbert action on 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 will be found if we express 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{EH}[g]=\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}R$
\end_inset

 through the extrinsic curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

 of the surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We already saw a relation of precisely this sort, namely the Gauss-Codazzi
 equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

) that expresses the 4-curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $R\equiv{}^{(4)}R$
\end_inset

 through the 3-curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

 and the extrinsic curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 The only nontrivial calculation in this section will be to show that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}{}^{(4)}R=\int\textrm{d}^{4}x\sqrt{-g}\left(^{(3)}R+K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right),\label{eq:R4 through R3}\end{equation}

\end_inset

up to total derivative terms that we omit.
 Note that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

) is very similar to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

), except for the different sign at the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 terms.
 We shall derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

) at the end of this section, and now let us assume that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) is valid and determine the canonical momenta.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the Lagrangian density 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}R$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h/\partial t$
\end_inset

 only through the terms containing 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

, the canonical momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ab}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
p^{ab}\equiv\frac{1}{16\pi G}\frac{\partial\left(\sqrt{-g}R\right)}{\partial\dot{h}_{ab}}=\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{32\pi G}\frac{\partial}{\partial K_{ab}}\left(K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right).\]

\end_inset

Rewriting for convenience
\begin_inset Formula \[
K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}=K_{ab}K_{cd}\left(h^{ac}h^{bd}-h^{ab}h^{cd}\right),\]

\end_inset

we find after a simple calculation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p^{ab}=\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left(K^{ab}-K_{c}^{c}h^{ab}\right).\label{eq:pab K}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The inverse relation allows us to express the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}$
\end_inset

 through the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{h}^{ab}=2K^{ab}=\frac{32\pi G}{\sqrt{-h}}\left(p^{ab}-\frac{1}{2}p_{c}^{c}h^{ab}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can write the Hamiltonian for pure gravity:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
 & \mathcal{H}[p_{ab},h_{ab}]\nonumber \\
 & =\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\left[p^{ab}\dot{h}_{ab}-\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left(^{(3)}R+K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left[K^{ab}K_{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}-{}^{(3)}R\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\left[-\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}{}^{(3)}R+\frac{16\pi G}{\sqrt{-h}}\left(p^{ab}p_{ab}-\frac{1}{2}p_{a}^{a}p_{b}^{b}\right)\right].\label{eq:Hamiltonian for GR}\end{align}

\end_inset

The Hamilton equations of motion are cumbersome but follow straightforwardly,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial h_{ab}}{\partial t} & =\frac{\partial H}{\partial p^{ab}}=\frac{32\pi G}{\sqrt{-h}}\left(p_{ab}-\frac{1}{2}h_{ab}p_{c}^{c}\right),\\
\frac{\partial p_{ab}}{\partial t} & =-\frac{\delta H}{\delta h^{ab}}\\
 & =-\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\frac{\delta{}^{(3)}R}{\delta h^{ab}}+\frac{\delta}{\delta h^{ab}}\left(p^{ab}p_{ab}-\frac{1}{2}p_{a}^{a}p_{b}^{b}\right)\frac{16\pi G}{\sqrt{-h}}\\
 & =-\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left(^{(3)}R_{ab}-\frac{1}{2}{}^{(3)}Rh_{ab}\right)\\
 & +\frac{8\pi G}{\sqrt{-h}}\left[\left(p^{ab}p_{ab}-\frac{1}{2}p_{a}^{a}p_{b}^{b}\right)h_{ab}-4\left(p_{ac}p_{b}^{c}-\frac{1}{2}p_{c}^{c}p_{ab}\right)\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that we used the three-dimensional Ricci tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R_{ab}$
\end_inset

 when computing the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion in the Hamiltonian form are equivalent to Einstein's
 equations, but now it is clear that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset

 and the extrinsic curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset

 can be found from initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(t_{0})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}(t_{0})$
\end_inset

 at an initial spacelike 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

, as a solution of an appropriate Cauchy problem.
 This has applications in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

numerical relativity,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a numerical solution of the Einstein equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Derivation of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 3-dimensional curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

 is defined as the 3-dimensional trace of the induced Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the 3-surfaces, the 3-dimensional trace 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}$
\end_inset

 of any tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through its 4-dimensional trace as
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})={}^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})-A(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n}).\]

\end_inset

The Gauss-Codazzi equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gauss-Codazzi 1}

\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}\! R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})={}^{(3)}\! R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})+K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{t})K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}).\]

\end_inset

We begin by evaluating the 3-dimensional trace of the above equation over
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(3)}R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})\,= & ^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})\\
+{}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})} & K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{t})K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})\textrm{Tr }K\\
={}^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})} & ^{(4)}R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})-{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{t})\\
+{}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})} & K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{t})K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})-K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})K_{a}^{a},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{a}^{a}\equiv{}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

.
 Then we evaluate the 3-trace of the result over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t}\right)$
\end_inset

, using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n},\cdot,\cdot)=0$
\end_inset

 and hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})={}^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z}).\]

\end_inset

We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
^{(3)}R\equiv{}{}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{t})}{}^{(3)}R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},\mathbf{t})\,= & ^{(4)}R\\
-2{}^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z}) & +K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

It remains to compute the term 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

.
 I shall present a computation in the index notation and also an index-free
 computation, for comparison.
 Let us first convert this term to the index notation:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}{}^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z}) & \equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}z^{\delta}g_{\gamma\delta}n^{\alpha}x^{\beta}\left[\nabla_{\alpha},\nabla_{\beta}\right]n^{\gamma}\\
=g^{\beta\gamma}g_{\gamma\delta}n^{\alpha} & \left[\nabla_{\alpha},\nabla_{\beta}\right]n^{\gamma}=n^{\alpha}\left[\nabla_{\alpha},\nabla_{\beta}\right]n^{\beta}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The last expression is simplified as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
n^{\alpha}n^{\beta}{}_{;\beta\alpha}-n^{\alpha}n^{\beta}{}_{;\alpha\beta} & =\left(n^{\alpha}n_{;\beta}^{\beta}\right)_{;\alpha}-n_{;\alpha}^{\alpha}n_{;\beta}^{\beta}-\left(n^{\alpha}n_{;\alpha}^{\beta}\right)_{;\beta}+n_{;\beta}^{\alpha}n_{;\alpha}^{\beta}\\
 & =\textrm{div}\left(...\right)+K_{\alpha\beta}K^{\alpha\beta}-K_{\alpha}^{\alpha}K_{\beta}^{\beta},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha\beta}=n_{\alpha;\beta}$
\end_inset

 and omitted the uninteresting total divergence terms.
 Finally, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}R\equiv{}^{(4)}R-K_{ab}K^{ab}+K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}+\textrm{div}\left(...\right),\]

\end_inset

which is equivalent to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the index-free notation, the manipulations with traces are somewhat less
 transparent.
 We need to use the property that mute vectors have vanishing derivatives
 under the trace operation, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})A(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z},...)\]

\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Index-free-trace}

\end_inset

).
 Also, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=K(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})} & ^{(4)}R(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{n},\mathbf{z})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{n}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}+\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{n})\\
= & \textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}\left[g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})+g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{n})\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second term in brackets yields directly 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}g(\mathbf{a},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\mathbf{n})=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}K(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})K(\mathbf{z},\mathbf{b})=K_{ab}K^{ab},\]

\end_inset

 while the first term in brackets is transformed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})=\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\left[g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})\right]-g(\mathbf{b},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n}),\]

\end_inset

which yields a total divergence and the term
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})}g(\mathbf{b},\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{n})g(\mathbf{z},\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n})=-\left[\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}K(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\right]^{2}=-\left(K_{a}^{a}\right)^{2}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore we again recover Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constraints in General Relativity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hamilton equations of motion are incomplete without the constraint equations
 which we neglected to derive earlier.
 These constraints are present because the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{EH}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the time derivatives of the components 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{0\mu}$
\end_inset

 of the metric.
 To see this explicitly, we can repeat the derivation of the Hamiltonian
 formulation without assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the proper time along geodesic lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Standard
***The stuff in this note is too complicated for what it's worth!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constraint equations are found as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta L_{EH}}{\delta g^{0\mu}}=0,\]

\end_inset

or, in covariant form,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\delta L_{EH}}{\delta g^{\mu\nu}}n^{\mu}u^{\nu}=0,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary 4-vector field.
 Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Einstein equ from var}

\end_inset

), we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =\frac{\delta L_{EH}}{\delta g^{\mu\nu}}n^{\mu}u^{\nu}=\left(R_{\mu\nu}-\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}R\right)n^{\mu}u^{\nu}\\
 & \equiv\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u})-\frac{1}{2}Rg(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{u}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let us see just one constraint that follows from this equation when we choose
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Rewriting the curvature scalar as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
^{(4)}R & \equiv{}^{(4)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}{}^{(4)}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & ={}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}{}^{(4)}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+{}^{(4)}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

we use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) and the property (see Exercise below)
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(4)}R={}^{(3)}R+{}^{(4)}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})\]

\end_inset

and derive the following constraint, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & ={}^{(4)}\textrm{Ric}(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})-\frac{^{(4)}R}{2}=\frac{^{(4)}R}{2}-{}^{(3)}R\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(^{(3)}R+K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right)-{}^{(3)}R\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(-{}^{(3)}R+K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

This expression is equal to the Hamiltonian density and is constrained to
 vanish.
 Therefore, we may heuristically say that gravity itself has zero local
 energy density.
 This constraint is called the 
\series bold
Hamiltonian constraint
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative way to derive the Hamiltonian constraint is to relax the
 requirement that the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 be normalized to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, let us consider an arbitrary normalization, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=N^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a function of space and time.
 Since the extrinsic curvature is a function only of the surface, the relation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) remains valid, and the only difference in the Lagrangian will be the replaceme
nt of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $N\sqrt{-h}$
\end_inset

.
 The momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, and finally the Hamiltonian becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{H}=\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace d^{3}x\frac{N\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left[K^{ab}K_{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}-{}^{(3)}R\right].\]

\end_inset

The variation of this Hamiltonian with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 yields the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have computed the Hamiltonian in the syncronous gauge for simplicity,
 but the calculation can be performed in an arbitrary gauge, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
with an arbitrary
 selection of the time foliation.
 Suppose that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given on a spacetime, such that the contravariant gradient vector 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}dt$
\end_inset

 is everywhere timelike (but not necessarily normalized).
 We may use the function 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as the time coordinate and define equal-time 3-surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us define the normal vector to the 3-surfaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}\equiv N\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{n},\mathbf{n})=1$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{-2}=g^{-1}(\textrm{d}t,\textrm{d}t)$
\end_inset

.
 The local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

 on these 3-surfaces may be chosen arbitrarily.
 Given a choice of the local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

, we may define the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 which acts on functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t,x_{a})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\rightarrow\partial f/\partial t$
\end_inset

, the partial derivative at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and by construction we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{n},\partial_{t})=Ng(\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}t,\partial_{t})=N\left(\textrm{d}t\right)\circ\left(\partial_{t}\right)=N,\]

\end_inset

 hence in general we can decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial_{t}=N\mathbf{n}+\mathbf{s},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 is a spacelike vector tangent to the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, which is thus equivalent to a 3-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}=\sum_{a=1}^{3}s^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 in the local basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{a}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
lapse
\series default
 
\series bold
function
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{lapse function}

\end_inset

 and the 
\series bold
shift
\series default
 
\series bold
vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{shift vector}

\end_inset

for a chosen coordinate system.
 The lapse describes how much time 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

elapses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between two consecutive 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 surfaces along the lines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

, and the shift vector shows how much the local coordinate system shifts
 when we pass from one 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 surface to another along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now determine the induced metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 within the 3-surfaces.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}\equiv g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})$
\end_inset

 is related to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{t},\mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 by the following matrix representation (verify this!),
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
N^{2}+h(\mathbf{s},\mathbf{s}) & s_{1} & s_{2} & s_{3}\\
s_{1} & h_{11} & h_{12} & h_{13}\\
s_{2} & h_{21} & h_{22} & h_{23}\\
s_{3} & h_{31} & h_{32} & h_{33}\end{array}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a}\equiv h_{ab}s^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from this representation that the determinants of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are related by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}=N\sqrt{-h}$
\end_inset

.
 (See Calculation below.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det g=N^{2}\det h$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 by the above formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 To compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\det g$
\end_inset

 directly, subtract from the first row of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 the linear combination of the other three rows with coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This does not change the determinant, but the first row of the matrix simplifie
s to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N^{2},0,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\det g_{\mu\nu} & =\det\left|\begin{array}{cc}
N^{2}+s_{a}s^{a} & s_{a}\\
s_{b} & h_{ab}\end{array}\right|\\
 & =\det\left|\begin{array}{cc}
N^{2} & 0\\
s_{b} & h_{ab}\end{array}\right|=N^{2}\det h_{ab}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) involves 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

, which is independent of the choice of gauge, and the extrinsic curvature
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 The relationship between the extrinsic curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{n})$
\end_inset

 and the metric derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h_{ab}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 needs to be derived now.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a connecting vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\partial h_{ab}}{\partial t} & \equiv\partial_{t}\circ\left[h(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\right]=\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{t}}\left[h(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\right]\\
 & =\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{t}}h\right)\circ(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence for arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 tangent to a 3-surface, we find, similarly to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Lnh and K}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathcal{L}_{\partial_{t}}h\right)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\partial_{t},\mathbf{y})+h(\mathbf{x},\nabla_{\mathbf{y}}\partial_{t}).\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\mathbf{n},\cdot)=0$
\end_inset

, we can simplify the above terms, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\partial_{t},\mathbf{y}) & =h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}(N\mathbf{n}+\mathbf{s}),\mathbf{y})\\
 & =Nh(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})+h(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{s},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =NK(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+h({}^{(3)}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{s},\mathbf{y}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the last line, we replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}\nabla$
\end_inset

 since, by definition,
\begin_inset Formula \[
h({}^{(3)}\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\]

\end_inset

 for tangent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial h_{ab}/\partial t=2NK_{ab}+s_{a|b}+s_{b|a},\]

\end_inset

where we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}\nabla_{a}$
\end_inset

 by a vertical bar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It now follows from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R4 through R3}

\end_inset

) that the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{EH}=\sqrt{-g}R$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the time derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we do not need to introduce the canonical momenta for these
 nondynamical variables.
 As before, the only canonical momenta are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ab}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the components 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 of the induced 3-metric, and a simple calculation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is still related to 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

 by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:pab K}

\end_inset

).
 Hence, the Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{H} & =\int d^{3}x_{a}\frac{\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left[\left(K^{ab}K_{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}-{}^{(3)}R\right)N\right.\\
 & \left.-\left(K^{ab}-K_{c}^{c}h^{ab}\right)_{|a}s_{b}\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

A complete derivation of the Hamiltonian in an arbitrary gauge (including
 also a detailed treatment of all the boundary terms) can be found in the
 book [Poisson 2004], chapter\InsetSpace ~
4.
 Here, we shall only determine the constraints of the theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a}$
\end_inset

 enter the Hamiltonian as nondynamical Lagrange multipliers, therefore the
 constraints are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{\delta\mathcal{H}}{\delta N} & =0\;\Rightarrow\; KK_{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}-{}^{(3)}R=0,\\
\frac{\delta\mathcal{H}}{\delta s_{a}} & =0\;\Rightarrow\;\left(K^{ab}-K_{c}^{c}h^{ab}\right)_{|a}=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mathcal{H}/\delta N=0$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
