\begin_layout Standard
The Hamiltonian description of General Relativity was developed to quantize
 that theory.
 We shall now describe the approach to quantization of gravity due to J.
 Wheeler and B.
 DeWitt.
 So far it was impossible to develop a full quantum theory of gravity based
 on the Hamiltonian description presented above.
 Technical difficulties are too great to derive in detail, for example,
 the quantum state that corresponds to a Schwarzschild spacetime.
 Therefore this approach to quantization of gravity remains formal.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, a more promising approach to canonical quantization of General
 Relativity is a Hamiltonian approach based on a different choice of generalized
 coordinates, called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ashtekar variables.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The theory based on these variables is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

loop quantum gravity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and is beyond the scope of this book.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 However, as we shall now see, some interesting qualitative results 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 be obtained in the Wheeler-DeWitt approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Wave function of the universe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the general scheme of canonical quantization, we need to replace
 the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $q,p$
\end_inset

 by operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p},\hat{q}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the standard equal-time commutation relations.
 In the case of gravitation, we shall therefore write
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\hat{p}_{mn}(t,x_{a}),\hat{h}^{cd}(t,x_{b})\right]=\delta_{m}^{c}\delta_{n}^{d}\delta^{(3)}(x_{a}-x_{b}).\]

\end_inset

It is easier to visualize the quantum theory in the Schrdinger picture.
 The quantum state in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordinate representation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
wave function
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(t;q_{i})$
\end_inset

 of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the generalized coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

; the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 acts as multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{i}=-\text{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial q_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 In General Relativity, the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is played by the 3-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(x_{c})$
\end_inset

, stripped of the dependence on time.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wave function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\left[t;h_{ab}(x_{c})\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Heuristically, one might expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi[t;h_{ab}]\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of observing the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(x_{c})$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 (Below, we shall see that the interpretation of this wave function is not
 quite as straightforward as it may appear.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may also consider other matter fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(t,x_{a})$
\end_inset

 coupled to gravity.
 In the Hamiltonian formalism, these fields will be described by generalized
 coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(x_{a})$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding canonical momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}(x_{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the wave function of the full theory will be a functional of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi[t;h_{ab}(x_{c}),\phi_{j}(x_{c})]$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
wave function of the universe
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{wave function of the universe}

\end_inset

because it describes (in principle) all the possible processes anywhere
 in the universe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space consisting of all the possible gravity and matter field configurations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ h_{ab}(x_{c}),\phi_{j}(x_{c})\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
superspace
\series default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Note that a point of superspace is a configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(x_{c}),\phi_{j}(x_{c})$
\end_inset

 which contains functions only of 3-dimensional coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

, not of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This can be visualized as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

instantaneous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field configuration on a 3-surface of constant time.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{superspace}

\end_inset

 Thus, the wave function of the universe is a (complex-valued) function
 on superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the standard rules of quantum mechanics, the wave function
 of the universe satisfies the Schrdinger equation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\text{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}] & =\hat{\mathcal{H}}\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}]\\
 & \equiv\mathcal{H}\left(\hat{p}_{ab},h_{ab};\hat{p}_{j},\phi_{j}\right)\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}]\\
=\mathcal{H} & \left[\frac{\delta}{\delta h_{ab}(x_{c})},h_{ab}(x_{c});\frac{\delta}{\delta\phi_{j}(x_{c})},\phi_{j}(x_{c})\right]\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}].\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 is the total Hamiltonian of the system, which is itself a functional of
 all the canonical variables.
 For instance, the Hamiltonian for pure gravity is given by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hamiltonian for GR}

\end_inset

).
 Note that the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are replaced by 
\emph on
functional
\emph default
 derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Wheeler-DeWitt equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since classical General Relativity is a constrained theory, the constraints
 must be passed on to the quantum theory as well.
 A comprehensive treatment of quantization for constrained systems is beyond
 the scope of these lectures; here we shall adopt the simplistic point of
 view that the constraint equations, which are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $C(q_{i},p_{i})=0$
\end_inset

, should be made operator-valued and imposed as operators on physical states:
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(\hat{q}_{i},\hat{p}_{i})\Psi(q_{i})=0.\]

\end_inset

 In other words, quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 satisfying the constraints are the only valid physical states of the system.
 It follows that the Hamiltonian constraint, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=0$
\end_inset

, is translated to the restriction
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\mathcal{H}}\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}]=0.\label{eq:WdW equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then the Schrdinger equation yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}]=0.\]

\end_inset

Hence, the wave function of the universe is 
\emph on
time-independent
\emph default
 and satisfies the Hamiltonian constraint\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WdW equation}

\end_inset

), which is called in this context the 
\series bold
Wheeler-DeWitt (WD) equation
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Wheeler-DeWitt equation}

\end_inset

The time independence of the wave function may appear to be a puzzling feature
 of the theory.
 However, it is a necessary feature: In a generally covariant theory, the
 time parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary label on events in spacetime, and physically meaningful
 probabilities must be defined in terms of coordinate-independent functionals
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall consider the interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi[t;h_{ab},\phi_{j}]$
\end_inset

 in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although we wrote the equations for quantized General Relativity, it remains
 difficult to extract any tangible results from these equations.
 Quite apart from the problem of solving the highly complicated equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WdW equation}

\end_inset

), the question of the 
\series bold
operator ordering
\series default
:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{operator ordering}

\end_inset

 The Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ab}$
\end_inset

, containing terms such as 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}h_{cd}p^{ac}p^{bd}$
\end_inset

, hence it is unclear how to order these noncommuting operators in the quantum
 Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

.
 The quantum Hamiltonian is thus not a well-defined operator unless we adopt
 a particular prescription for the operator ordering.
 To determine the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator ordering, one needs to compute some predictions of the quantum
 theory with one or another operator ordering and to compare these predictions
 with experiments or with other known results.
 Such computations are generally too difficult, and thus the Wheeler-DeWitt
 equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WdW equation}

\end_inset

) remains, in its full generality, a formula without application.
 (However, below we shall see that the Wheeler-DeWitt equation can be transforme
d into a differential equation and solved, if one restricts gravity and
 matter fields to spatially homogeneous configurations.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interpretation of the wave function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if one somehow computes the wave function of the universe 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

, its interpretation is nontrivial, mainly because the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi[h_{ab},\phi_{j}]$
\end_inset

 is independent from the time parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This fact, however, does not mean that the theory always describes a 
\emph on
static
\emph default
 universe! A physically meaningful 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be defined not as the value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, which can be changed by a coordinate transformation, but through some
 physical process (a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Since the wave function of the universe contains information about all
 the processes through its dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

, the theory can describe an evolving universe if an appropriate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clock process
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could be found.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to realize that the clock process must be realized by an
 
\emph on
essentially classical
\emph default
 rather than by an essentially quantum physical system.
 In the quantum language, the generalized coordinate describing the clock
 process must exhibit very small quantum fluctuations around a large expectation
 value.
 If the universe were in a quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 in which quantum fluctuations of every variable (including the metric)
 are significant, one could not expect to observe anything resembling a
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow of time.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Therefore, even the 
\emph on
possibility
\emph default
 of an interpretation of the wave function of the universe depends on the
 existence of (nearly) classical systems in the universe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that a nearly classical subsystem exists and is described by a variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 According to a standard result of quantum mechanics, the wave function
 of the subsystem is of the semiclassical (WKB) type,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(\phi_{c})\propto\exp\left(-\text{i}S_{cl}(\phi_{c})\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{cl}(\phi_{c})$
\end_inset

 is the value of the classical action on a classical trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

, expressed as a function of the value of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

 at a final time,
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{cl}(\phi_{c})=\int_{t_{0}}^{t}L_{\phi_{c}}(\phi,\dot{\phi})dt,\quad\phi(t)=\phi_{c}.\]

\end_inset

The total wave function of the universe is a product of the semiclassical
 part 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi_{c})$
\end_inset

 and the quantum part 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{q}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Psi[h_{ab},\phi_{j}]=\exp\left(-\text{i}S_{cl}(\phi_{c})\right)\Psi_{q}[\phi_{c};h_{ab},\phi_{j}].\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now see how the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

 can be used as a clock process.
 The trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 of the classical subsystem is, at least locally, a monotonic function of
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

 can be used as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and then the quantum part of the wave function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{q}[\phi_{c};h_{ab},\phi_{j}]$
\end_inset

, becomes a time-dependent wave function for the quantum variables 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab},\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 One can show (see e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Vile89}

\end_inset

) that a Schrdinger-type equation holds for this wave function, the variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

 playing the role of time, if the total wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 satisfies the WD equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Minisuperspace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The WD equation is a functional differential equation for a functional on
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

superspace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and, as such, is too complicated to be solved in general.
 One can obtain specific results from the WD equation if one simplifies
 the problem sufficiently drastically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that one of the main applications of General Relativity is 
\series bold
cosmology
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{cosmology}

\end_inset

where one considers only the gross features of the universe, that is, fields
 averaged over astronomically large scales.
 Astronomical observations offer a strong evidence that the universe around
 us is extremely homogeneous on large scales.
 Therefore, in cosmology one usually assumes that the 3-surfaces of constant
 time are spatially homogeneous.
 In other words, the 3-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}(t)$
\end_inset

 and the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

 depend only on the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and are independent of the spatial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we are motivated to consider the theory of quantized gravity with
 spatially homogeneous metric and fields.
 The corresponding simplification of the WD equation consists of reducing
 the infinite-dimensional superspace to a finite-dimensional space containing
 3-metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and field configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 that are spatially homogeneous, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
independent of the 3-coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 The reduced superspace is called 
\series bold
minisuperspace
\series default
.
 
\series bold

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{minisuperspace}

\end_inset


\series default
The WD equation in minisuperspace becomes a (partial) differential equation
 for a wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(h_{ab},\phi_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 The analysis of this simplified WD equation is the subject of 
\series bold
quantum cosmology
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{quantum cosmology}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be specific, let us consider a model of classical spacetime whose equal-time
 surfaces are homogeneous 3-spheres 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 (hence, a closed universe!) with a fixed 3-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 The spacetime metric is
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=N^{2}(t)\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}t-a^{2}(t)\gamma,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t)$
\end_inset

 is the lapse function and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 is an unknown function of time called the 
\series bold
scale factor
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{scale factor}

\end_inset

 Since the lapse function is nondynamical, the scale factor is the only
 physical variable in the gravitational sector of the model.
 Further, suppose there exists a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 which is, again, independent of the spatial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the minisuperspace is two-dimensional and consists of two variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now quantize this cosmological model using the WD equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to express the classical Hamiltonian\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hamiltonian for GR}

\end_inset

) for gravity through the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

, and add the Hamiltonian for the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{H}_{\phi}=\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x_{c}N\sqrt{-h}\left[\frac{1}{2}p_{\phi}^{2}+h^{ab}\phi_{,a}\phi_{,b}+V(\phi)\right],\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical momentum for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
V(\phi)\equiv\Lambda+\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi^{2}+O(\phi^{3})\]

\end_inset

 is a potential describing the vacuum energy density 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and a possible self-interaction of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The partial metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h=-a^{2}\gamma$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-h}=a^{3}\sqrt{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is spatially homogeneous, we may integrate over 3-spheres, assuming that
 the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is normalized so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x_{c}\sqrt{\gamma}=\sigma_{3}=2\pi^{2},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{n}\equiv\frac{2\pi^{n/2}}{\Gamma(n/2)}\]

\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-volume of a unit 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 (This normalization of the 3-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 means that the radius of the 3-sphere is equal to 1.) Thus we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{H}_{\phi}=Na^{3}\sigma_{3}\left[\frac{1}{2}p_{\phi}^{2}+V(\phi)\right].\]

\end_inset

Returning to the gravitational sector of the model, we need to compute the
 3-curvature scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

 and the extrinsic curvature tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 The 3-curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $^{(3)}R$
\end_inset

 depends only on the intrinsic geometry of the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, which is a 3-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 with the natural metric and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

, and thus a space of constant curvature; the value of the curvature is
 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The 3-dimensional Riemann tensor for a space of constant curvature was
 computed in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Induced-Riemann}

\end_inset

, hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})=a^{-2}\left(h(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c})h(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d})-h(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{d})h(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})\right).\]

\end_inset

Using
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}h(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=3,\]

\end_inset

we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{(3)}R={}^{(3)}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c})(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{d})}{}^{(3)}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})=6a^{-2}.\]

\end_inset

 It remains to compute the extrinsic curvature.
 We may introduce local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

 on a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

; however, the explicit form of these coordinates will not be necessary
 for the present calculation.
 It is sufficient to note that the basis 3-vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}\equiv\partial_{x_{a}}$
\end_inset

 commute with each other and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

) we get
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\partial_{t},\mathbf{e}_{c})=\frac{1}{2}\partial_{t}g(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=\dot{a}a\gamma(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=\frac{\dot{a}}{a}h_{bc}.\]

\end_inset

 Since the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 to the 3-surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}=N^{-1}\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

, the extrinsic curvature tensor is
\begin_inset Formula \[
K\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)\equiv g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{n},\mathbf{y})=N^{-1}g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\partial_{t},\mathbf{y})=N^{-1}\frac{\dot{a}}{a}h(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

Then we determine the relevant combination of the traces of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
K_{bc}K^{bc}-K_{b}^{b}K_{c}^{c}=\left(\frac{\dot{a}}{Na}\right)^{2}\left(h_{bc}h^{bc}-h_{b}^{b}h_{c}^{c}\right)=-6\left(\frac{\dot{a}}{Na}\right)^{2}.\]

\end_inset

The gravitational Lagrangian becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{G} & =\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\frac{N\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left(^{(3)}R+K_{ab}K^{ab}-K_{a}^{a}K_{b}^{b}\right)\\
 & =\negmedspace\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\frac{N\sqrt{-h}}{16\pi G}\left(\frac{6}{a^{2}}-6\left(\frac{\dot{a}}{Na}\right)^{2}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can now integrate over the 3-volume of the 3-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{t=\textrm{const}}\negmedspace\textrm{d}^{3}x\sqrt{-h}=a^{3}\sigma_{3},\]

\end_inset

 because all the terms are spatially homogeneous.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}=\frac{6Na^{3}\sigma_{3}}{16\pi G}\left(\frac{1}{a^{2}}-\frac{\dot{a}^{2}}{N^{2}a^{2}}\right)=\frac{3\pi}{4G}Na\left(1-\frac{1}{N^{2}}\dot{a}^{2}\right).\]

\end_inset

To compute the Hamiltonian, it remains to determine the canonical momentum
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{a}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\dot{a}}=-\frac{3\pi}{2G}\frac{a\dot{a}}{N}.\]

\end_inset

Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{a}=-\frac{2G}{3\pi}\frac{N}{a}p_{a},\]

\end_inset

 and the gravitational Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{H}_{G}(p_{a},a) & =p_{a}\dot{a}-\mathcal{L}_{G}\\
 & =\frac{-3\pi}{4G}Na+\frac{N}{a}p_{a}^{2}\left(-\frac{2G}{3\pi}+\frac{3\pi}{4G}\frac{4G^{2}}{9\pi^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{-3\pi}{4G}Na-\frac{G}{3\pi}\frac{N}{a}p_{a}^{2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we can write the total Hamiltonian for the minisuperspace theory,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \mathcal{H}\left(p_{a},a,p_{\phi},\phi\right)=\mathcal{H}_{G}+\mathcal{H}_{\phi}\\
 & =\frac{N}{a}\left[-\frac{G}{3\pi}p_{a}^{2}-\frac{3\pi}{4G}a^{2}+a^{4}\sigma_{3}\left(\frac{1}{2}p_{\phi}^{2}+V(\phi)\right)\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wave function of the mini-universe,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(a,\phi)$
\end_inset

, satisfies the WD equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \left[-\frac{G}{3\pi}\hat{p}_{a}^{2}-\frac{3\pi}{4G}a^{2}+2\pi^{2}a^{4}\left(\frac{1}{2}\hat{p}_{\phi}^{2}+V(\phi)\right)\right]\Psi\\
 & =\left[\frac{G}{3\pi}\hbar^{2}\partial_{a}^{2}-\frac{3\pi}{4G}a^{2}+\pi^{2}a^{4}\left(-\hbar^{2}\partial_{\phi}^{2}+2V(\phi)\right)\right]\Psi=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

This equation needs to be supplemented by boundary conditions.
 However, the choice of the boundary conditions is a subtle problem and
 we shall not discuss this issue here.
 In the present case, we shall simply choose the solution of the WD equation
 that will have a clear physical interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is reasonable to suppose that the scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has a semiclassical regime where it is the 
\emph on
large
\emph default
 radius of the 3-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

.
 (Our universe is 
\emph on
large
\emph default
.) Therefore, in the semiclassical regime the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be used as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variable.
 We can then express the wave function in the semiclassical form with respect
 to the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Psi(a,\phi)=\exp\left(-\text{i}\hbar^{-1}S(a)\right)\psi(a,\phi),\]

\end_inset

where the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(a,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be a slow-varying function of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 but quickly-varying function of the quantum variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial a}\right|\sim\hbar\left|\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\phi}\right|.\]

\end_inset

 Then we can expand the WD equation in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

, substituting the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
-\frac{G}{3\pi}\left(S^{\prime2}+\frac{9\pi^{2}a^{2}}{4G^{2}}-\frac{6\pi^{3}}{G}a^{4}V_{0}\right)\psi\label{eq:WD S part}\\
-\frac{\text{i}G\hbar}{3\pi}\left(S^{\prime\prime}+2S^{\prime}\partial_{a}\right)\psi+\pi^{2}a^{4}\left(-\hbar^{2}\partial_{\phi}^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right)\psi & =0.\label{eq:WD psi part}\end{align}

\end_inset

The first line\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WD S part}

\end_inset

) above is of zeroth order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 and thus must be satisfied separately.
 This is an equation determining the behavior of the metric variable 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Its solution is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S(a)=\pm\int\textrm{d}a\,\sqrt{\frac{6\pi^{3}}{G}a^{4}V_{0}-\frac{9\pi^{2}a^{2}}{4G^{2}}}.\]

\end_inset

To visualize the physical interpretation of this solution, we note that
 Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WD S part}

\end_inset

) is formally analogous to the semiclassical form of the stationary Schrdinger
 equation for a one-dimensional particle in a potential
\begin_inset Formula \[
U(a)\equiv\frac{9\pi^{2}a^{2}}{8G^{2}}-\frac{3\pi^{3}}{G}a^{4}V_{0}.\]

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can tunnel from the initial state at 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 to the value
\begin_inset Formula \[
a=a_{0}\equiv\sqrt{\frac{3}{8\pi GV_{0}}}.\]

\end_inset

The regime 
\begin_inset Formula $a>a_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a classical motion of the particle with the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $da/d\tau=\sqrt{2U(a)}$
\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<a<a_{0}$
\end_inset

 the motion is classically forbidden since 
\begin_inset Formula $U(a)<0$
\end_inset

.
 The tunneling process is interpreted as the 
\emph on
creation of a closed universe
\emph default
 having the initial size 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the assumed initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a sphere of zero radius or, in other words, to the absence
 of space, this process is also called 
\series bold
creation of a universe from nothing
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the second part\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WD psi part}

\end_inset

) of the WD equation.
 In the semiclassical regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $S(a)$
\end_inset

 is a slow-changing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, so we can disregard 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|S^{\prime\prime}\right|\ll S^{\prime2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined semiclassical variable in the regime 
\begin_inset Formula $a>a_{0}$
\end_inset

, we may define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 according to the heuristic picture of a moving 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to define
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\tau=\frac{3\pi^{3}}{2G}\frac{a^{4}\textrm{d}a}{\sqrt{2U(a)}}=\frac{3\pi^{3}}{2G}\frac{a^{4}\textrm{d}a}{S^{\prime}(a)},\]

\end_inset

and express 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $a>a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WD psi part}

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{i}\hbar\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\tau}=\left(-\hbar^{2}\partial_{\phi}^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right)\psi\equiv\hat{H}_{\psi}\psi.\]

\end_inset

This is a familiar 
\emph on
time-dependent
\emph default
 Schrdinger equation for a quantum system with the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way, we find that the time-independent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wave function of the universe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(a,\phi)$
\end_inset

, when properly interpreted in the regime when one of the variables is classical
, yields a familiar picture of the evolution of quantum systems with time.
 Note that in the classically forbidden regime 
\begin_inset Formula $0<a<a_{0}$
\end_inset

, no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be defined, and a classical interpretation of the wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is impossible.
\end_layout

