\begin_layout Standard
In the standard approach, General Relativity is formulated as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theory of the metric.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In other words, the main variable is the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, while the connection and the curvature are expressed through the metric.
 An alternative formulation is through orthonormal bases of vector fields
 (called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tetrads
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 This formulation is convenient for many calculations, and also serves to
 connect gravity with spinor field theory.
 Some approaches to quantum gravity are based on the tetrad formulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience, I work in a four-dimensional manifold having a metric with
 Lorentzian signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+---\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Generalizations to other dimensions and signatures are straightforward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tetrads
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Tetrads}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is specified, one can always choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{0}(p),\mathbf{e}_{1}(p),\mathbf{e}_{2}(p),\mathbf{e}_{3}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 in each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 One of the tetrad vectors must be timelike and the other three must be
 spacelike (because the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has a Lorentzian signature).
 It is a convention to choose the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{0}$
\end_inset

 timelike and the other three spacelike, so that the scalar product matrix
 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})=\eta_{ab}\equiv\textrm{diag}\left(1,-1,-1,-1\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is understood as a fixed matrix (which is numerically the same as the standard
 metric in Minkowski spacetime).
 Note that the Latin indices label the basis vectors and run (for convenience)
 from 0 to 3.
 In this section I will indicate summations over these indices explicitly.
 I will work in a four-dimensional spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Essentially we have chosen a particular set of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

, defined at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Such an orthonormal set of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
tetrad
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tetrad}

\end_inset

or a 
\series bold
vierbein
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vierbein}

\end_inset

in case of four-dimensional manifolds, and a 
\series bold
frame field
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{frame field}

\end_inset

or 
\series bold
vielbein
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vielbein}

\end_inset

in any number of dimensions.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

