\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a slight strain on the terminology, I call the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orthonormal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 even though 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{a})=-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 as it must be since the metric has Lorentzian signature.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where the metric is specified as a set of components 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

, the components 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\mu}^{a}(p)$
\end_inset

 of the tetrad may be found by the following procedure.
 At a fixed spacetime point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, consider the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 as a bilinear form.
 This bilinear form may be diagonalized by a linear coordinate transformation,
 according to standard procedures of linear algebra.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

 are new coordinates in which the metric is diagonal at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}(p)=\textrm{diag}\left(A,-B,-C,-D\right)\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
A & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & -B & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & -C & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & -D\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C,D>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to write an orthogonal basis in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, for instance 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{0}(p) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{A}}\partial_{t},\quad\mathbf{e}_{1}(p)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{B}}\partial_{x},\\
\mathbf{e}_{2}(p) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{C}}\partial_{y},\quad\mathbf{e}_{3}(p)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{D}}\partial_{z}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this way, obviously generalizable to any number of dimensions, a vielbein
 may be determined at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of the manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, if a tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is given at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 then we may recover the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 explicitly in the following way.
 First we need to compute the four 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

) that comprise the dual basis to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Here and below we denote vectors and forms by boldface symbols.
 (It is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as an upper index in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

, even though we presently do not consider it a tensor index.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Construction of the dual basis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely decomposed as a linear combination
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\sum_{a}\lambda^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{a}$
\end_inset

 are some numbers.
 When the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is fixed, the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{a}$
\end_inset

 are linear functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, and thus are 1-forms which we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

; in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{a}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

.
 These 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 yield the components of a vector in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{a}.\]

\end_inset

This relationship holds for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

; sometimes this is written as a decomposition of the identity operator,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{1}}=\sum_{a}\mathbf{e}_{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}.\label{eq:decomposition of identity in vielbein}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The set of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
dual tetrad
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{dual tetrad}

\end_inset

 and is a basis in the dual tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}\mathcal{M}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes one calls 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 simply the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tetrad
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for brevity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, it is straightforward to pass from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and back.
 In a local coordinate system, the dual basis has components 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mu}^{a}$
\end_inset

 which comprise a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{a}\theta_{\mu}^{a}v^{\mu}e_{a}^{\nu}=v^{\nu}\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{a}\theta_{\mu}^{a}e_{a}^{\nu}=\delta_{\mu}^{\nu},\]

\end_inset

so the matrix of components 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mu}^{a}$
\end_inset

 can be computed as the inverse matrix to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{a}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

, are computed, the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=g\left(\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{e}_{a},\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b}\right)=\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u})\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{v}).\label{eq:metric through dual tetrad}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Rewritten in a more condensed notation, the above formula becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\]

\end_inset

In components,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}=\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\theta_{\mu}^{a}\theta_{\nu}^{b}.\]

\end_inset

This is an explicit formula that expresses the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 through the dual tetrad.
 Analogously, the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is expressed through the tetrad vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}=\sum_{a,b}\eta^{ab}\mathbf{e}_{a}\otimes\mathbf{e}_{b}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in order to define a metric structure on a manifold, one may specify
 a tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 or alternatively a dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 instead of specifying the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remarks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a map from a fixed, four-dimensional spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula \[
v^{a}\equiv\left\{ v^{0},v^{1},v^{2},v^{3}\right\} \in\mathbb{R}^{4}\]

\end_inset

 is mapped to the tangent vector
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\equiv\sum_{a}v^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}.\]

\end_inset

This map 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{a}\rightarrow\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the scalar product in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 defined by the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and the scalar product in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 defined by the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}u^{a}v^{b}=g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\,\textrm{ if }u^{a}\rightarrow\mathbf{u},\; v^{a}\rightarrow\mathbf{v}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore one refers to the abstract space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\series bold
fiducial
\series default
 
\series bold
Minkowski
\series default
 
\series bold
spacetime
\series default
 and metric.
 This fiducial flat spacetime can be interpreted as the instantaneous reference
 frame of a certain observer.
 This observer's four-velocity instantaneously coincides with the timelike
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{0}(p)$
\end_inset

 and the observer's spatial axes are chosen along the directions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are infinitely many possible tetrads corresponding to one and the
 same metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 A given tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be transformed via a Lorentz rotation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\rightarrow\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}(p)\equiv\sum_{b}\Lambda_{a}^{b}(p)\mathbf{e}_{b}(p),\]

\end_inset

without changing the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{a}^{b}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a matrix representing a Lorentz transformation in the fiducial Minkowski
 spacetime.
 This matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{a}^{b}(p)$
\end_inset

 may be chosen arbitrarily at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and thus is called a 
\series bold
local
\series default
 Lorentz transformation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{local Lorentz transformation}

\end_inset

.
 Conversely, 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 two orthonormal bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are connected by a Lorentz transformation.
 Therefore, the local Lorentz transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{a}^{b}(p)$
\end_inset

 represent the entire freedom of choosing the tetrad field for a fixed metric
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A tetrad is essentially a set of four vector fields which must be linearly
 independent at every point.
 Since it is impossible to have globally nonzero vector fields on some manifolds
 (e.g.\InsetSpace ~
on a 2-sphere), the tetrad fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 might have to be defined only locally.
 In other words, different tetrad fields will have to be defined within
 different charts covering the manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is clear that the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and the metric as follows, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v})\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ\mathbf{v}=\eta_{aa}g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{v})=\sum_{b}\eta^{ab}g(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary vector.
 In the notation of Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Correspondence-of-vectors}

\end_inset

, we may rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\eta_{aa}\hat{g}\mathbf{e}_{a}=\sum_{b}\eta^{ab}\hat{g}\mathbf{e}_{b}.\]

\end_inset

(There is no summation over 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{aa}\hat{g}\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 above.) Often it is convenient to raise and lower the Latin (tetrad) indices
 using the fiducial Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, one defines
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\equiv\eta_{aa}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\sum_{b}\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\label{eq:theta lower}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and writes equations such as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{v})=\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\mathbf{v}).\label{eq:theta lower 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, I stress that the dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be calculated from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\emph on
without
\emph default
 using this formula.
 The metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is already fixed once we declare that a given basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is orthonormal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is orthonormal with respect to the 
\emph on
inverse
\emph default
 metric, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{-1}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a},\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b})=\eta^{ab}.\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis in the cotangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}\mathcal{M}(p)$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Holonomic and nonholonomic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes the frame basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 or the dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
nonholonomic
\series default
 bases,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{nonholonomic basis}

\end_inset

 while the coordinate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
holonomic
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{holonomic basis}

\end_inset

 This terminology will not be used in the present text; instead I call 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 an orthonormal frame basis, a tetrad, and a vielbein.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holonomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 seems to come from mechanics textbooks.
 In theoretical mechanics, there is a notion of holonomic and nonholonomic
 constraint equations.
 A 
\series bold
constraint equation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{constraint equation}

\end_inset

is a relation of the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{j}\frac{dq^{j}}{dt}A_{j}(\mathbf{q})=0,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}\equiv\left\{ q^{j}\right\} \in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a time-dependent vector of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

 are some coefficients.
 A constraint equation is called 
\series bold
holonomic
\series default
 if it can be rewritten as a total time derivative of a function, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
if there
 exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

 such that the constraint equation is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $d\alpha(\mathbf{q})/dt=0$
\end_inset

, in other words if
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{j}=\frac{\partial\alpha(\mathbf{q})}{\partial q^{j}},\quad j=1,...n.\]

\end_inset

 One can reformulate these statements more transparently by introducing
 the auxiliary 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\equiv\sum_{j}A_{j}\textrm{d}q^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the constraint equation is rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\circ\dot{\mathbf{q}}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathbf{q}}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent vector to the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The constraint is holonomic if there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}=\textrm{d}\alpha$
\end_inset

; in the standard terminology, the constraint is holonomic when the 1-form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
exact
\series default
 (equal to a differential of some function).
 So one calls a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holonomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if there exist functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{a}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\textrm{d}f^{a}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nonholonomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 These functions could serve as a local coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f^{0},f^{1},f^{2},f^{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 naturally adapted to the given basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to recognize a holonomic basis by checking that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 For example, a basis of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ t^{2}\mbox{d}t,x\mbox{d}x+y\mbox{d}y,x\mbox{d}y+y\mbox{d}x,\mbox{d}z\}$
\end_inset

 is holonomic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, when an 
\emph on
orthonormal
\emph default
 basis is holonomic, it means that there exist coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in which the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{d}x^{a}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal.
 In other words, these are Cartesian coordinates and the metric is simply
 the flat Euclidean (or Minkowski) metric.
 It is impossible to choose an orthonormal holonomic basis of 1-forms in
 a nonflat spacetime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The condition on the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 that indicates a holonomic basis is mutual commutation.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a holonomic basis, then there exist a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\mbox{d}x^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 will consist of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}=\partial_{x^{a}}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

.
 This is the property that indicates a holonomic basis.
 In a nonflat spacetime, an 
\emph on
orthonormal
\emph default
 basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 will be necessarily nonholonomic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is true that in almost all cases we will be working in a nonflat spacetime,
 and hence the vielbein will be nonholonomic.
 However, to me this is not a sufficient motivation to call 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 a nonholonomic basis.
 What is important for our considerations is the 
\emph on
orthonormality
\emph default
 of the chosen frame basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with respect to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Calling 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 merely a nonholonomic basis may create an impression that it is sufficient
 to select 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 nonholonomic basis, whether orthonormal or not.
 However, an arbitrary non-orthonormal, nonholonomic basis is much less
 useful in calculations than an orthonormal basis.
 For this reason, we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orhonormal frame basis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (or a 
\series bold
vielbein
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vielbein}

\end_inset

) rather than a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nonholonomic basis.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the Schwarzschild metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Schwarzschild}

\end_inset

).
 The task is to determine a tetrad basis and a dual tetrad basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the metric is in a diagonal form, a possible choice of the tetrad
 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{0} & =\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1/2}\partial_{t},\quad\mathbf{e}_{1}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{1/2}\partial_{r},\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\frac{1}{r}\partial_{\theta},\quad\mathbf{e}_{3}=\frac{1}{r\sin\theta}\partial_{\phi}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the tetrad is undefined (singular) if 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta=0$
\end_inset

 because at these locations the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r,\theta,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and/or the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are singular.
 This is an example of a tetrad defined only 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
, that is, only within a certain limited coordinate patch, rather than globally
 in the entire spacetime.
 More than one coordinate patch must be used to cover the entire Schwarzschild
 spacetime.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Schwarzschild spacetime}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 corresponding to the tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0} & =\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{1/2}\textrm{d}t,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1/2}\textrm{d}r,\\
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2} & =r\textrm{d}\theta,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}=r\sin\theta\textrm{d}\phi.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose now that we are given a two-dimensional spacetime with local coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the frame fields
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{0}=\partial_{t},\quad\mathbf{e}_{1}=e^{-Ht}\partial_{x}.\]

\end_inset

The task is to determine the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 such that this frame is orthonormal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can recover the metric by first determining the dual frame,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=\textrm{d}t,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{Ht}\textrm{d}x,\]

\end_inset

and then writing
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g & =\sum_{a,b}\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=\textrm{d}t\otimes\textrm{d}t-e^{2Ht}\textrm{d}x\otimes\textrm{d}x\\
 & \equiv dt^{2}-e^{2Ht}dx^{2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

This metric is the two-dimensional version of de Sitter metric\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:de Sitter}

\end_inset

).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hodge duality
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Hodge-duality}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, one determines the Levi-Civita tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

, and then one can establish a one-to-one linear map between 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms and 
\begin_inset Formula $(4-n)$
\end_inset

-forms.
 This map is called the 
\series bold
Hodge duality
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hodge duality}

\end_inset

operation.
 Since this operation is used relatively little in the present text (it
 rarely yields a computational advantage), I only sketch the construction
 on examples and list some basic properties of the Hodge duality.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
I was motivated to make this excursion into the Hodge duality by reading
 the lecture notes\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Hebe07}

\end_inset

, chapter 6, where I learned about Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset

(a).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work with a four-dimensional manifold where the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and the Levi-Civita tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 are known.
 First consider a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The Hodge duality map yields a 3-form 
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}\omega$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
Hodge dual
\series default
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

; this operation is also called the 
\series bold
Hodge star
\series default
.
 The 3-form 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined by its action on arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(^{*}\omega\right)\circ(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\equiv\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\hat{g}^{-1}\omega,\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}).\]

\end_inset

Somewhat more awkwardly, this definition can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
*\omega=\iota_{\hat{g}^{-1}\omega}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}.\]

\end_inset

It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\mapsto*\omega$
\end_inset

 is a linear map in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 (if we regard the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 as fixed).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a four-dimensional Minkowski space with the orthonormal basis of
 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \textrm{d}t,\textrm{d}x,\textrm{d}y,\textrm{d}z\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The Levi-Civita tensor is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z.\]

\end_inset

Let us compute the Hodge star applied to the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset

.
 Using the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}t=\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \[
*(\textrm{d}t)=\iota_{\partial_{t}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z.\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
*(\textrm{d}x)=\iota_{\partial_{x}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=-\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}y\wedge\textrm{d}z.\]

\end_inset

Heuristically, 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 must contain the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\wedge*\omega$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another convenient way to express 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 is to use an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{g}^{-1}\omega=\sum_{a,b}\eta^{ab}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{a},\]

\end_inset

we can write
\begin_inset Formula \[
*\omega=\sum_{a}\eta^{aa}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right).\]

\end_inset

This expression can be also used as a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, this definition is independent of the choice of the basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, as long as this basis is orthonormal with respect to the fixed metric
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and positively oriented with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 (We merely rewrote a basis-free definition in terms of an arbitrary orthonormal
 basis.) The basis independence can be made manifest by expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 through the trace operation as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
*\omega=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{b}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right).\]

\end_inset

It is clear that this can be used as a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 equivalent to the definitions above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 is converted to its Hodge dual 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

, which is also a 2-form.
 This 2-form can be defined using an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
*\omega\equiv\frac{1}{2!}\sum_{a,b}\eta^{aa}\eta^{bb}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right).\label{eq:star 2w ea}\end{equation}

\end_inset

As before, this definition is independent of the choice of the orthonormal
 basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This can also be seen with the following trick.
 Any 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed into a linear combination of exterior products of 1-forms.
 Since the Hodge duality is a linear map, we only need to consider a single
 exterior product 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\phi\wedge\chi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 are 1-forms.
 The 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $*(\phi\wedge\chi)$
\end_inset

 is then expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(*(\phi\wedge\chi)\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)=\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\hat{g}^{-1}\phi,\hat{g}^{-1}\chi,\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

It is straightforward to verify that this expression is equivalent to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:star 2w ea}

\end_inset

).
 When the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 is written in this basis-free manner, it becomes manifest that 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 depends only on the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 but not on the choice of the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 However, calculations using an explicit basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are much more convenient since one does not need to decompose all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms into linear combinations of exterior products of 1-forms.
 Sometimes also the index-free trace notation is convenient,
\begin_inset Formula \[
*\omega\equiv\frac{1}{2!}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a}')(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{b}')}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{b}'}\iota_{\mathbf{a}'}\omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have seen the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $*\omega$
\end_inset

 for 1-forms and 2-forms.
 To express the Hodge dual of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, one can build an expression analogous to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:star 2w ea}

\end_inset

) but with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sets of vectors and the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n!$
\end_inset

 in front:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*\Omega & \equiv\frac{1}{n!}\sum_{a_{1},...,a_{n}}\eta^{a_{1}a_{1}}...\eta^{a_{n}a_{n}}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{n}}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{1}}}\Omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{n}}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{1}}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n!}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1})...(\mathbf{a}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n})}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{a}_{n}}...\iota_{\mathbf{a}_{1}}\Omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{b}_{n}}...\iota_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here we wrote the arguments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a_{j}}$
\end_inset

 in the reverse order for convenience; recall that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{n}}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a_{1}}}\Omega\equiv\Omega(\mathbf{e}_{a_{1}},...,\mathbf{e}_{a_{n}}).\]

\end_inset

As before, this definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $*\Omega$
\end_inset

 depends only on the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 but not on the choice of the orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In four dimensions, the Hodge star establishes a linear map from 0-forms
 (scalars) to 4-forms, from 1-forms to 3-forms, etc.
 In particular, the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is mapped into a scalar.
 The numerical factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n!$
\end_inset

 leads to the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $*\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=-1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} & =\frac{1}{4!}\sum_{a,b,c,d}\eta^{aa}...\eta^{dd}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{d}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{d}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\\
 & =\eta^{00}\eta^{11}\eta^{22}\eta^{33}=\det\eta_{ab}=-1.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hodge dual to a scalar function (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0-form
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $*f=f\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

; taking the Hodge dual again, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $*(f\boldsymbol{\varepsilon})=-f$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $**f=-f$
\end_inset

 for scalar functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

) be an orthonormal basis of 1-forms; then we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0} & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}\right)=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3};\\
*\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3} & =\iota_{-\mathbf{e}_{3}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}\right)=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2};\\
*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}) & =\iota_{-\mathbf{e}_{1}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}\right)=-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3};\\
*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3}) & =\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1};\quad*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{3})=-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0};\quad\textrm{etc.}\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In four dimensions, one can derive a more convenient formula for the Hodge
 dual to a 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}(\mathbf{e}_{a},...,\mathbf{e}_{d})\neq0$
\end_inset

 only when all the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d$
\end_inset

 are different:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*\Omega & =\frac{1}{4!}\sum_{a,b,c,d}\eta^{aa}...\eta^{dd}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{d}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\Omega\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{d}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\\
 & =\left(\det\eta_{ab}\right)\Omega(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3},\mathbf{e}_{4})=-\Omega(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3},\mathbf{e}_{4}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is clear that this formula extends from four-dimensional to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
*\Omega=\left(\det\eta_{ab}\right)\Omega(\mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{N}),\label{eq:Hodge star of N-form}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical form of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional metric (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the form where the metric is diagonal and has only
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 on the diagonal).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of the Hodge star on basis 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, as illustrated by the examples above, can be summarized by the following
 formulas:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*1\equiv\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} & =\frac{1}{4!}\sum_{a,b,c,d}\varepsilon^{abcd}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d},\\
*\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a} & =\frac{1}{3!}\sum_{b,c,d}\varepsilon^{abcd}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d},\\
*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}) & =\frac{1}{2!}\sum_{c,d}\varepsilon^{abcd}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d},\\
*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}) & =\sum_{d}\varepsilon^{abcd}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{abcd}$
\end_inset

 is not a tensor but a totally antisymmetric array of numbers (the Levi-Civita
 symbol) defined such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{0123}=1$
\end_inset

.
 (It is important to note that the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}$
\end_inset

 differ from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 by the sign factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{aa}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The example above shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $**f=-f$
\end_inset

 for a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=*1$
\end_inset

, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $**\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=-\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 A similar property holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-hodge-hodge}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-hodge-hodge}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold with canonical metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
**\omega=(\det\eta_{ab})\left(-1\right)^{(N-n)n}\omega.\]

\end_inset

 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-hodge-hodge}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not particularly easy to perform calculations with the Hodge star
 operation.
 For instance, there are no general identities relating the Hodge star to
 other operations, such as the exterior differential or the Lie derivative;
 so in general 
\begin_inset Formula $*(\omega\wedge\psi)\neq*\omega\wedge*\psi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}*\omega\neq*\textrm{d}\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{x}}*\omega\neq*\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{x}}\omega$
\end_inset

, etc.
 When doing calculations with the Hodge star, one needs to use either an
 explicit basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, or the index-free trace formalism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from the example above that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge*\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=-\boldsymbol{\varepsilon};\quad(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1})\wedge*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1})=-\boldsymbol{\varepsilon};\quad\textrm{etc.}\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, it is easy to see that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge*\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=0;\quad(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1})\wedge*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2})=0;\quad\textrm{etc.}\]

\end_inset

It seems that the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero on basis 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms only when the two forms are equal.
 This combination is indeed a useful function of two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
 The following statement lists some properties of this function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms in an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, one can compute the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge(*\omega_{2})$
\end_inset

 that is symmetric under interchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}=\omega_{2}\wedge*\omega_{1}.\]

\end_inset

Thus the scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $*(\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2})$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric bilinear function in the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
 This bilinear function can be viewed as a natural scalar product in the
 space of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis of 1-forms, then an orthonormal basis in the space
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms is the set of exterior products
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a_{n}}\right\} ,\]

\end_inset

with all possible sets of indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{1},...,a_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for which these exterior products are nonzero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(b)
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the volume element with the following coefficient,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
 & \omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\textrm{Vol}}{n!}\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1})...(\mathbf{a}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n})}\omega_{1}(\mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n})\omega_{2}(\mathbf{b}_{1},...,\mathbf{b}_{n}).\label{eq:omega wedge star omega Tr}\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(c)
\series default
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are 1-forms corresponding to vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=\hat{g}\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}=\hat{g}\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

.Then the scalar product defined in part 
\series bold
(a)
\series default
 coincides with the natural scalar product of 1-forms given by the inverse
 metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}=g^{-1}(\omega_{1},\omega_{2})\,\textrm{Vol}=g(\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2})\,\textrm{Vol}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(d)
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 are 1-forms corresponding to vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

, one has
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Omega\wedge*(\omega_{1}\wedge\omega_{2})=\Omega(\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2})\,\textrm{Vol}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to note what happens if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

-form and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

-form with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}\neq n_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n_{1}+N-n_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

-form while 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}\wedge*\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n_{2}+N-n_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

-form.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}\neq n_{2}$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}+N-n_{2}>N$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}+N-n_{1}>N$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, one of the expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\wedge*\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}\wedge*\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 is identically zero as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with 
\begin_inset Formula $n>N$
\end_inset

, while the other expression is not necessarily zero.
 It is clear that Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset

 cannot be extended to this case.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Practice-calculation:omega-Omega}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Practice-calculation:omega-Omega}

\end_inset


