\begin_layout Subsection
Levi-Civita connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, one may determine the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 explicitly (see Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

) in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Levi-Civita-connection}

\end_inset

).
 It turns out that the Levi-Civita connection can be expressed directly
 through the tetrad.
 We begin by assuming that the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 are known, and then derive the formula for the covariant derivative of
 the tetrad field.
 Subsequently, it will be clear how to recover the connection from the tetrad
 without explicitly involving the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, we would like to be able to compute the covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis, every vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}=\sum_{a}v^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{a}\equiv v^{a}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a set of four 
\emph on
scalar
\emph default
 functions (the Latin index is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a tensor index).
 Therefore it is sufficient to be able to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 According to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

), we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}) & =\frac{1}{2}\big(\mathbf{x}\circ g(\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})+\mathbf{y}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z})-\mathbf{z}\circ g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & -g(\mathbf{x},[\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z}])-g(\mathbf{y},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z}])+g(\mathbf{z},[\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}])\big).\end{align*}

\end_inset

 This formula enables us to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})$
\end_inset

 if we can evaluate terms such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ g(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{e}_{a},[\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c}])$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=\eta_{bc}$
\end_inset

 is (by construction) a fixed numerical matrix, the directional derivatives
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 are zero, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ g(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=\frac{g(\mathbf{e}_{c},[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}])-g(\mathbf{e}_{a},[\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c}])-g(\mathbf{e}_{b},[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{c}])}{2}.\]

\end_inset

We may rewrite this formula using the
\emph on
 lower-index
\emph default
 version of the dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}$
\end_inset

 [see Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:theta lower}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:theta lower 1}

\end_inset

)] as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}=\frac{\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\circ[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}]-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\circ[\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c}]-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\circ[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{c}]}{2}.\label{eq:Levi-Civita tetrad}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

-th component of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita tetrad}

\end_inset

) completely determines the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 if the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and their commutators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]$
\end_inset

 are known.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We point out that the essential information required for computing the covariant
 derivative is the commutators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 In general, these commutators can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]=\sum_{c}C^{c}{}_{ab}\mathbf{e}_{c},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}=-C^{c}{}_{ba}$
\end_inset

 are some scalar coefficients (which are, of course, functions of the spacetime
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

).
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 can be explicitly computed from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 without need to involve the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

; recall that the commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a geometric operation defined independently of the metric.
 Then one has complete information about the Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 through Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita tetrad}

\end_inset

).
 The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita tetrad}

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\eta_{cc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}=\frac{1}{2}\left(C_{c\, ab}-C_{b\, ac}-C_{a\, bc}\right),\label{eq:Levi-Civita C0}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c\, ab}$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 by lowering the first index through 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ac}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, we may write
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{c}\left(C_{c\, ab}-C_{b\, ac}-C_{a\, bc}\right)\eta_{cc}\mathbf{e}_{c}.\label{eq:Levi-Civita C}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 At this point, one can compute covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 of arbitrary vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 by expressing them through the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and using the Leibnitz rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a two-dimensional spacetime with local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the given orthonormal frame
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{0}=\partial_{t},\quad\mathbf{e}_{1}=e^{-Ht}\partial_{x}.\]

\end_inset

The task is to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by calculating the commutators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The only nontrivial commutator is
\begin_inset Formula \[
[\mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{1}]=-H\mathbf{e}_{1}.\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}{}_{01}=-C^{1}{}_{10}=-H$
\end_inset

 are the only nonzero coefficients among 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Lowering the first index of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1\,01}=-C_{1\,10}=H$
\end_inset

.
 Then we use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita C}

\end_inset

) and compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{e}_{0} & =0,\quad(\textrm{no nonzero }C_{c\, ab})\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(C_{1\,01}-C_{1\,01}\right)\eta_{11}\mathbf{e}_{1}=0,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{1}}\mathbf{e}_{0} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(C_{1\,10}-C_{1\,01}\right)\eta_{11}\mathbf{e}_{1}=H\mathbf{e}_{1},\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{1}}\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(-C_{1\,10}-C_{1\,10}\right)\eta_{00}\mathbf{e}_{0}=H\mathbf{e}_{0}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Finally, we use the Leibnitz rule:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\partial_{t}}\partial_{x} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\left(e^{Ht}\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=\left(\mathbf{e}_{0}\circ e^{Ht}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+e^{Ht}\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{0}}\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
 & =\left(\partial_{t}e^{Ht}\right)e^{-Ht}\partial_{x}=H\partial_{x}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{t}}\partial_{t}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x}=He^{2Ht}\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Koszul formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

), terms with scalar products vanish for an orthonormal basis; however,
 terms with commutators remain.
 If we choose the basis vectors as coordinate derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 (this is the choice usually made in calculations using index notation),
 the terms with commutators will vanish but terms with scalar products will
 remain.
 At first glance, it is not obvious which choice of basis has more advantages
 in calculations.
 However, it turns out that in many cases calculations are shorter in an
 orthonormal basis.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connection as a set of 1-forms
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Connection-as-a-set-of-1-forms}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section we have seen that the information about Levi-Civita
 connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is carried entirely by the commutators 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]$
\end_inset

 and can thus be recovered without explicitly involving the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 A more elegant (and practically more useful) description of the Levi-Civita
 connection is obtained by considering the dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as the commutator of vector fields is defined geometrically without
 involving the metric, the exterior differential
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{exterior differential}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 is a 2-form defined geometrically by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})=\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v})-\mathbf{v}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u})-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}([\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]).\]

\end_inset

Substituting the tetrad vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{c}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}([\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c}])\equiv-C^{a}{}_{bc}.\]

\end_inset

So the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 carry essentially the same information as the commutators of the tetrad
 vectors.
 Hence, we expect to be able to express the Levi-Civita connection through
 the dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and its differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, one uses some clever tricks, which we will now show.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis in the dual space, the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 can be always decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{b,c}X^{a}{}_{bc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\]

\end_inset

with some coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{a}{}_{bc}=-X^{a}{}_{cb}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that these coefficients are directly related to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{a}{}_{bc}$
\end_inset

 (see the following Calculation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{a}{}_{bc}=-C^{a}{}_{bc}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 applied to arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 through the tetrad and compute 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right)\circ(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}) & =\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right)\circ\left(\sum_{b}u^{b}\mathbf{e}_{b},\sum_{c}v^{c}\mathbf{e}_{c}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{b,c}u^{b}v^{c}\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right)\circ(\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})=-\sum_{b,c}C^{a}{}_{bc}u^{b}v^{c}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{b}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\circ\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{c}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\sum_{b,c}X^{a}{}_{bc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\right) & =\sum_{b,c}X^{a}{}_{bc}\left(u^{b}v^{c}-u^{c}v^{b}\right)\\
 & =2\sum_{b,c}X^{a}{}_{bc}u^{b}v^{c}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary vectors, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{a}{}_{bc}=-C^{a}{}_{bc}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now see how to recover the Levi-Civita connection.
 So far we have the property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}=-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a,b}C_{\: ab}^{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b},\label{eq:dtheta X}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which shows that the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 can be easily computed by decomposing 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}$
\end_inset

 into the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 However, according to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita C0}

\end_inset

), covariant derivatives of vectors involve a certain combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}=\frac{1}{2}\left(C_{c\, ab}-C_{b\, ac}-C_{a\, bc}\right),\]

\end_inset

rather than simply 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 (Here and below we freely lower and raise all Latin indices by implicitly
 using the fiducial Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.) Now we note that the scalar expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 linearly depends on the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and is thus equal to some 1-form applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us 
\emph on
denote
\emph default
 that 1-form by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

; in other words, by definition, we set
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{b}.\]

\end_inset

 Another way to restate the definition is to say that the 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{b}=\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{e}_{c}\label{eq:cov diff thru omega}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
 The 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
connection 1-forms
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{connection 1-forms}

\end_inset

 or the 
\series bold
spin connection
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spin connection}

\end_inset

corresponding to the dual tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Levi-Civita C0}

\end_inset

) that the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}$
\end_inset

 (that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 with the first index lowered) satisfy
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a}\left(C_{c\, ab}-C_{b\, ac}-C_{a\, bc}\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}.\label{eq:omega def 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Thus, the connection forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}$
\end_inset

 may be computed straightforwardly from the commutator coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}{}_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 After computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}$
\end_inset

, covariant derivatives of arbitrary vector fields can be expressed as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{b} & =\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{e}_{c},\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v} & =\sum_{b}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(v^{b}\mathbf{e}_{b}\right)=\sum_{b}\left(\mathbf{u}\circ v^{b}\right)\mathbf{e}_{b}+\sum_{b,c}v^{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{e}_{c}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In terms of the components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{c}$
\end_inset

 of a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, we find the formula
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{c}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{u}\circ v^{c}+\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})v^{b}.\label{eq:cov der vec omega}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 play the role of the Christoffel symbols in the formula for the covariant
 derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

) is not necessarily the quickest way to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing it with Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dtheta X}

\end_inset

), we notice that it might help to compute the following expression,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b} & =\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a,b}\left(C_{c\, ab}-C_{b\, ac}-C_{a\, bc}\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a,b}C_{c\, ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

(The simplification in the second line happens because the terms symmetric
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 cancel).
 Then we can raise the index 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dtheta X}

\end_inset

), and obtain the following relationship,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}=-\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\label{eq:Cartan 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The relationship\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
first
\series default
 
\series bold
Cartan structure equation
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Cartan structure equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An immediate practical importance of this equation is that it can be used,
 instead of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

), to 
\emph on
determine
\emph default
 the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

) alone does not specify 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 uniquely.
 For instance, the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a}C^{c}{}_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 are also a solution of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

), although these 1-forms do not coincide with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 is any solution of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

), one may add the following term, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}+\sum_{a}B^{c}{}_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{c}{}_{ab}=B^{c}{}_{ba}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary array of coefficients symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The new 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 will still be a solution of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

).
 However, in addition to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

) the connection 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the antisymmetry requirement,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}=-\boldsymbol{\omega}_{b\, c},\label{eq:omega antisymmetry}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be easily read from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

).
 It turns out
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
See Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Solving-equations-for}

\end_inset

 for a general proof of this statement.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the two requirements\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) are sufficient to specify 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 uniquely, so that one does not need to use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

).
 In practice, it is often quicker to guess the solution of Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) than to follow the straightforward but longer formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a two-dimensional spacetime with local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t,x\right\} $
\end_inset

 and a frame field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{0},\mathbf{e}_{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{0}=e^{-f(t)}\partial_{t},\quad\mathbf{e}_{1}=e^{-h(t)}\partial_{x},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t),h(t)$
\end_inset

 are scalar functions depending only on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (but not on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 The task is to compute the connection 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c\, b}$
\end_inset

 and the covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{t}}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The metric corresponding to the given frame field is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=e^{2f(t)}dt^{2}-e^{2h(t)}dx^{2}.\]

\end_inset

 We begin by defining the dual frame,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=e^{f(t)}\textrm{d}t,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{h(t)}\textrm{d}x,\]

\end_inset

and the differentials,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=0,\quad\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=\dot{h}e^{h(t)}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x=-\dot{h}e^{h(t)-f(t)}\textrm{d}x\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}\equiv\partial_{t}h(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we intentionally wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(...\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(...\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}$
\end_inset

, trying to satisfy the antisymmetry property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) which entails 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{0}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{1}{}_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can 
\emph on
try to guess
\emph default
 a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

) as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{0}{}_{0}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{0}{}_{1}=0,\quad\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{1}{}_{0}=\dot{h}e^{h(t)-f(t)}\textrm{d}x,\quad\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{1}{}_{1}=0.\]

\end_inset

Despite our efforts, the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 are not yet the correct connection forms because they do not satisfy the
 antisymmetry property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega antisymmetry}

\end_inset

).
 To correct this, we may add a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{1}{}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{0}{}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Presently, it is clear that we only need to add 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{h}e^{h(t)-f(t)}\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{0}{}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So the correct set of the connection 1-forms is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}=\boldsymbol{\omega}_{0\,1}=-\boldsymbol{\omega}_{1\,0}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{1}{}_{0}=\dot{h}e^{h(t)-f(t)}\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariant derivatives are now computed using the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:cov der vec omega}

\end_inset

).
 Consider the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\partial_{x}=e^{h(t)}\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 has a single nonzero component, 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{1}=e^{h(t)}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:cov der vec omega}

\end_inset

) is rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{c}=\mathbf{u}\circ v^{c}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{1}(\mathbf{u})v^{1}.\]

\end_inset

A direct evaluation of components yields
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{0} & =\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}(\mathbf{u})e^{h(t)}=\dot{h}e^{2h(t)-f(t)}\mathbf{u}\circ x,\\
\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}\right)^{1} & =\mathbf{u}\circ e^{h(t)}=\dot{h}e^{h(t)}\mathbf{u}\circ t.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{v}=\dot{h}e^{h(t)}\left\{ e^{h(t)-f(t)}\left(\mathbf{u}\circ x\right)\mathbf{e}_{0}+\left(\mathbf{u}\circ t\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}\right\} .\]

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\partial_{t}}\partial_{x} & =\dot{h}e^{h(t)}\mathbf{e}_{1}=\dot{h}\partial_{x};\\
\nabla_{\partial_{x}}\partial_{x} & =\dot{h}e^{2h(t)-f(t)}\mathbf{e}_{0}=\dot{h}e^{2h(t)-2f(t)}\partial_{t}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
*Solving equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Solving-equations-for}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Connection-as-a-set-of-1-forms}

\end_inset

 we found that the connection 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 can be found by solving the Cartan structure equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

).
 In general, there are several tricks for finding general solutions of linear
 equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms in the frame basis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following statement shows how to solve the equations such as the Cartan
 structure equation in a more general case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:solution-for-Cartan}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:solution-for-Cartan}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If any set of 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is given (where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a frame index) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a dual frame basis then there exists a unique set of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{A}_{a}+\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=0;\quad\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}=-\boldsymbol{\chi}_{b\, a}.\]

\end_inset

The 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed by the formula
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}=\sum_{c}\chi_{a\, bc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c},\quad\chi_{a\, bc}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(A_{a\, bc}-A_{b\, ac}-A_{c\, ab}\right),\label{eq:formula for omega in components}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c\, ab}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients in the decomposition
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{A}_{c}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{a,b}A_{c\, ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b},\quad A_{c\, ab}=-A_{c\, ba}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Idea of proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Guess the formula for a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 and then show that the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{a\, b}-\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 of two possible solutions is zero.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{sub:Proof-of-Statement-Solution-for-Cartan}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consequence of Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:solution-for-Cartan}

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}=\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\equiv\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 is that the system of equations\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega antisymmetry}

\end_inset

) has the unique solution\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega def 1}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega in components}

\end_inset

) can be also rewritten in a component-free manner, using the frame bases
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 instead:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}-\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right).\label{eq:formula for omega without components}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is clear that this expression is antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding solution for the connection 1-forms can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}=\frac{1}{2}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\frac{1}{2}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{c}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}.\label{eq:formula for omega a b with i}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is instructive to check directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{a}+\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=0$
\end_inset

 holds with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega without components}

\end_inset

).
 We compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
2\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b} & =\sum_{b}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}-\sum_{b}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\sum_{b,c}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\label{eq:omega a b theta b 1}\end{align}

\end_inset

To proceed, we note that expressions such as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{b}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\]

\end_inset

are reminiscent of the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:decomposition of identity in vielbein}

\end_inset

).
 The following statement shows how such expressions can be simplified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 is any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis and a dual basis for which the decomposition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:decomposition of identity in vielbein}

\end_inset

) holds.
 (These bases must be dual to each other but do not actually have to be
 orthonormal.) Then one has the decomposition
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right).\label{eq:decomposition of n-form in frame basis}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In other words,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{n}\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\]

\end_inset

 is the identity operator on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us apply the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form at the right-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:decomposition of n-form in frame basis}

\end_inset

) to a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 arbitrary vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 By definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:definition of exterior product of n-forms}

\end_inset

) of the exterior product, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \left(\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)\\
 & \quad=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(-1\right)^{j-1}\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v}_{j})\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{j},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the hat over 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{j}$
\end_inset

 means that the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th vector is absent from the list of arguments.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is linear in each argument, we may substitute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v}_{j})\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{v}_{1},...\right) & =\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{v}_{j})\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{v}_{1},...\right)\\
 & =\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{v}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{1},...\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \left(\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)\circ\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)\\
 & \quad=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(-1\right)^{j-1}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{v}_{j},\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\hat{\mathbf{v}}_{j},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)\\
 & \quad=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right)=n\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\mathbf{v}_{1},...,\mathbf{v}_{n}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

This shows that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:decomposition of n-form in frame basis}

\end_inset

) holds.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, we can transform Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega a b theta b 1}

\end_inset

) as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
2\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b} & =-2\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\sum_{b}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\\
 & \quad+\sum_{c}\left(\sum_{b}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\\
 & =-2\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\sum_{c}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}+\sum_{c}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\\
 & =-2\boldsymbol{A}_{a}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{a}+\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A useful alternative way of writing the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega without components}

\end_inset

) is shown in the following calculation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Calculation-formula-for-omega}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Calculation-formula-for-omega}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega without components}

\end_inset

) can be rewritten equivalently as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}-\frac{1}{2}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{A}_{c}.\label{eq:formula for chi without components 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Details:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may interchange the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega without components}

\end_inset

) by using the property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)=\left(\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right)\boldsymbol{\Omega}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\boldsymbol{\Omega},\]

\end_inset

which holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 and for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}=\delta_{a}^{c}$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{A}_{c} & =\sum_{c}\delta_{a}^{c}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}-\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\\
 & =\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{A}_{c} & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}+\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}.\label{eq:i i A identity}\end{align}

\end_inset

Since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\equiv\boldsymbol{A}_{c}(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}),\]

\end_inset

 the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega without components}

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for chi without components 2}

\end_inset

).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spin connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 can be found from the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for chi without components 2}

\end_inset

) by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\equiv\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the Frobenius theorem, the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{A}_{c}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero if the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}$
\end_inset

 correspond to hypersurface-orthogonal vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

 frequently consists of hypersurface-orthogonal vectors, calculations are
 simplified when the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for chi without components 2}

\end_inset

) is used.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an aside, we note that the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for chi without components 2}

\end_inset

) cannot hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}$
\end_inset

 (any 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is decomposed uniquely as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a}A_{ac}\theta^{a}$
\end_inset

 and the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ac}$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily antisymmetric), but it can be generalized from 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{a}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-formula-for-Omega-n}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-formula-for-Omega-n}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{c}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a vielbein index and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq3$
\end_inset

), there exists a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\sum_{b}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a}=0;\quad\boldsymbol{B}_{a\, b}=-\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a}.\label{eq:required equation for A and B}\end{equation}

\end_inset

A suitable set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a}$
\end_inset

 is determined by the equivalent expressions 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a} & =\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}\right)-\frac{1}{n\left(n-1\right)}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\label{eq:formula for B 1}\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\boldsymbol{A}_{a}-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{b}\right)-\frac{1}{n\left(n-1\right)}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\boldsymbol{A}_{c}\right).\label{eq:formula for B 2}\end{align}

\end_inset

Unlike the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{b\, a}$
\end_inset

 satisfying Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:required equation for A and B}

\end_inset

) is not unique.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-for-Omega-n}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Applications of tetrad formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After developing powerful techniques for manipulating the orthonormal frames,
 let us see what calculations are possible in this formalism.
 To make the notation more concise, I will now adopt the Einstein summation
 convention for the frame indices; for instance, I will now write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a}\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

.
 (In Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Tetrad-formalism}

\end_inset

 I did not use the Einstein summation convention but wrote all summations
 explicitly, to make the presentation more clear.) The frame indices are
 raised and lowered using the fiducial Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

