\begin_layout Subsection
Computing geodesic equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geodesic equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u}=0$
\end_inset

 is used to find trajectories of particles in GR.
 We now show how to use the vielbein formalism to derive the required differenti
al equations for the particle worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

 in a local coordinate system.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
The idea to explore geodesic equations in tetrad formalism came to me after
 reading the section entitled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Computing with adapted frames and examples
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the book\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Mich06}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a given local coordinate system in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold, we are interested in determining a trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\equiv\left\{ x^{\mu}(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that an orthonormal frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the dual frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and the corresponding connection 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 are already known.
 We would like to determine the unknown functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=u^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a},\quad u^{a}\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}.\]

\end_inset

The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 will be particular expressions involving 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}^{\mu}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:cov diff thru omega}

\end_inset

) and compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}} & =\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}\left(u^{a}\mathbf{e}_{a}\right)\\
 & =\left(\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}u^{a}\right)\mathbf{e}_{a}+u^{b}\mathbf{e}_{c}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}u^{a}+u^{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\right)\mathbf{e}_{a}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equations
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}u^{a}+\sum_{b}u^{b}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}\circ\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}=0,\quad a=1,...,n.\]

\end_inset

These equations are second-order in derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, while the derivative along the curve, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}}u^{a}$
\end_inset

, produces 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{x}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 when it acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geodesic equations can be further simplified, so that precomputing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 is not required.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-simplify-geodesic-in-tetrad}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-simplify-geodesic-in-tetrad}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geodesic equation for a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}\circ\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\mathbf{u})\right)+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\iota_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right)=0,\quad a=1,...,n.\label{eq:geodesic in pure tetrad}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
(Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-simplify-geodesic-in-tetrad}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Paragraph
Details for Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-simplify-geodesic-in-tetrad}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-simplify-geodesic-in-tetrad}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can derive the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic in pure tetrad}

\end_inset

) by using the explicit relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

, for instance, in the form\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for omega a b with i}

\end_inset

).
 However, it is faster to use the Koszul formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:LC connection ans}

\end_inset

) for computing the scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a})$
\end_inset

, which must vanish for every 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,...,n$
\end_inset

.
 We find (without assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a}) & =\frac{1}{2}\big(2\mathbf{u}\circ g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a})-\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})-2g(\mathbf{u},[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a}])\big)\\
 & \lyxbuildrel1\above=\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\mathbf{u})-\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\frac{g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})}{2}+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}([\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{u}])\\
 & \lyxbuildrel2\above=\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\mathbf{u})+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a})+\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\right)\\
 & \quad-\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\frac{g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})}{2}\\
 & \lyxbuildrel3\above=\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\mathbf{u})+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel1\above=$
\end_inset

 is due to Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:metric through dual tetrad}

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:theta lower 1}

\end_inset

); 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel2\above=$
\end_inset

 is due to the definition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dw 12}

\end_inset

) and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{e}_{a})=\mathbf{u}\circ\eta_{ab}=0$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lyxbuildrel3\above=$
\end_inset

 is due to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{u})\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}(\mathbf{u})\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u}).\]

\end_inset

Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 for a geodesic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, but we did not use that fact in the present derivation.
 As a result, the left-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic in pure tetrad}

\end_inset

) is strictly equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{u},\mathbf{e}_{a})$
\end_inset

 even for non-geodesic vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practical calculations, it is frequently convenient to use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conservation law
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 in place of one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 geodesic equations.
 (The first-order equation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 is always a consequence of the second-order geodesic equations.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us determine the geodesic curves in the two-dimensional metric 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=e^{2f(x)}dt^{2}-e^{2h(x)}dx^{2}.\]

\end_inset

The obvious orthonormal frame consists of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{0}=e^{-f}\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}=e^{-h}\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=e^{f}\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{h}\textrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
 According to the geodesic equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:geodesic in pure tetrad}

\end_inset

), a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)\equiv\left\{ t(\tau),x(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}(\tau)\equiv\left\{ \frac{dt(\tau)}{d\tau},\frac{dx(\tau)}{d\tau}\right\} \equiv\dot{t}(\tau)\partial_{t}+\dot{x}(\tau)\partial_{x}\]

\end_inset

 is geodesic if the following two equations hold,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\right)+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right)\circ\left(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\mathbf{e}_{a}\right)=0,\quad a=0,1.\]

\end_inset

(The overdot denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d\tau$
\end_inset

 everywhere.) Presently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=f'e^{f}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=0$
\end_inset

, while
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=\boldsymbol{\theta}_{0}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=e^{f}\dot{t},\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{1}(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=e^{h}\dot{x},\]

\end_inset

so the two geodesic equations are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ\left(e^{f}\dot{t}\right)+e^{f}\dot{t}\left(f'e^{f}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}t\right)\circ\left(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},e^{-f}\partial_{t}\right) & =0,\qquad[a=0]\\
\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}\circ\left(-e^{h}\dot{x}\right)+e^{f}\dot{t}\left(f'e^{f}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}t\right)\circ\left(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},e^{-h}\partial_{x}\right) & =0.\qquad[a=1]\end{align*}

\end_inset

Simplifying these equations, while keeping in mind that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}$
\end_inset

 simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $d/d\tau$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\ddot{t}+2f'\dot{x}\dot{t} & =0,\qquad[a=0]\\
\ddot{x}+h'\dot{x}^{2}+f'e^{2f-2h}\dot{t}^{2} & =0.\qquad[a=1]\end{align*}

\end_inset

These are second-order equations for a general geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t(\tau),x(\tau)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now use the property 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

 to simplify further calculations.
 To be definite, let us look for timelike geodesics normalized by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}},\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}})=e^{2f}\dot{t}^{2}-e^{2h}\dot{x}^{2}=1.\]

\end_inset

 Presently it is clear that the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\tau)$
\end_inset

 contains only 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, let us substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 into that equation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\ddot{x}+h'\dot{x}^{2}+f'e^{-2h}\left(1+e^{2h}\dot{x}^{2}\right)\\
=\ddot{x}+\left(h'+f'\right)\dot{x}^{2}+f'e^{-2h} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

We obtained a closed second-order equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\tau)$
\end_inset

, and we can proceed to solve this equation by standard methods.
 Reducing to the first-order equation by a substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}=v(x)$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
vv'+\left(h'+f'\right)v^{2}+f'e^{-2h}=0,\]

\end_inset

where the prime stands for 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset

.
 The last equation can be integrated to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{2}v^{2}e^{2(h+f)}=\frac{1}{2}C^{2}-\frac{1}{2}e^{2f},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 is an integration constant.
 Finally, the solution of the geodesic equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is expressed in the form of an indefinite integral,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int^{x(\tau)}\frac{dx}{v(x)}=\int^{x(\tau)}\frac{e^{h+f}dx}{\sqrt{C^{2}-e^{2f}}}=\tau-\tau_{0}.\]

\end_inset

Then the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $t(\tau)$
\end_inset

 can be found by integrating the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{t}=e^{-f}\sqrt{1+e^{2h}\dot{x}^{2}}=Ce^{-2f(x(\tau))}.\]

\end_inset

In some cases (for some functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

), these equations can be integrated analytically and the geodesics obtained
 in closed form.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Determining Killing vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Killing vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=0$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Killing-vectors}

\end_inset

); a conformal Killing vector satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=2\lambda g$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Conformal-Killing-vectors}

\end_inset

).
 Sometimes one would like to determine whether a Killing vector or a conformal
 Killing vector exists for a given metric.
 One can perform the necessary calculations in the vielbein formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through the vielbein (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tetrads}

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=\eta_{ab}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b},\]

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is a constant numeric matrix, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=\eta_{ab}\left[\left(\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right)\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\right].\]

\end_inset

The Lie derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 can be computed easily through the Cartan homotopy formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan homotopy formula}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}=\textrm{d}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ\mathbf{k}\right)+\iota_{\mathbf{k}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}.\]

\end_inset

Then one can derive the Killing equation easily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a metric 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g=e^{2f(t)}dt^{2}-e^{2h(t)}dx^{2}.\]

\end_inset

Let us determine whether 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{k}\equiv a(t,x)\partial_{t}+b(t,x)\partial_{x}\]

\end_inset

can be a Killing vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t,x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b(t,x)$
\end_inset

 are unknown functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dual frame is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=e^{f(t)}\textrm{d}t,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{h(t)}\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset

The differentials are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=0,\quad\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{h}\dot{h}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset

So we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0} & =\textrm{d}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\circ\mathbf{k}\right)+\iota_{\mathbf{k}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=\textrm{d}\left(e^{f}a\right),\\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1} & =\textrm{d}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\circ\mathbf{k}\right)+\iota_{\mathbf{k}}\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=\textrm{d}\left(e^{h}b\right)+e^{h}\dot{h}\left(a\textrm{d}x-b\textrm{d}t\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}(e^{f}a)=\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,t}\textrm{d}t+\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,x}\textrm{d}x,\]

\end_inset

and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}(e^{h}b)$
\end_inset

.
 So the Killing equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}g=0$
\end_inset

, becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}+\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}\otimes\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}-\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\otimes\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=0.\]

\end_inset

This is rewritten (with implied symmetric tensor products) as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \left[\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,t}dt+\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,x}dx\right]e^{f}dt\\
 & \;-\left[\left(e^{h}b\right)_{,t}dt+\left(e^{h}b\right)_{,x}dx+e^{h}\dot{h}\left(adx-bdt\right)\right]e^{h}dx\\
 & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Gathering terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $dt^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dt\, dx$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{2}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the equations
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,t} & =0,\\
\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,x}e^{f}-\left(e^{h}b\right)_{,t}e^{h}+b\dot{h}e^{2h} & =0,\\
\left(e^{h}b\right)_{,x}+a\dot{h}e^{h} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

These equations can be simplified to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(e^{f}a\right)_{,t} & =0,\\
a_{,x} & =b_{,t}e^{2h-2f},\\
b_{,x} & =-a\dot{h}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

One solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0,b=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, which is the obvious Killing vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, we may solve the first equation as 
\begin_inset Formula $a=q(x)e^{-f}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0$
\end_inset

, differentiate the second equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the third equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{q_{,xx}}{q}=-e^{2h-2f}\left(\ddot{h}-\dot{h}\dot{f}\right).\]

\end_inset

Since the right-hand side is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 while the left-hand side is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, solutions exist only if both sides are equal to a constant.
 Unless the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t),h(t)$
\end_inset

 are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2h-2f}\left(\ddot{h}-\dot{h}\dot{f}\right)=K=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset

, no other Killing vectors exist besides 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=\partial_{x}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Curvature as a set of 2-forms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 contain first derivatives of the metric and are analogous to Christoffel
 symbols.
 The Riemann tensor also can be conveniently represented as a set of 2-forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the definition of the Riemann tensor,
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{w}\equiv\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{w}-\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{w}-\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\mathbf{w},\]

\end_inset

and recall that this is a transformation-valued antisymmetric bilinear form,
 if viewed as a function of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the object 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation that can be described, as usual, by a matrix
 of coefficients in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let us denote this matrix by 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

; so we set, by definition,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\equiv\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b}.\label{eq:Riemann tetrad def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 acts on the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b}=\mathbf{e}_{a}\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

 The 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 completely describe the curvature tensor and are called the 
\series bold
curvature 2-forms
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{curvature 2-forms}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often convenient to lower the index of the curvature 2-forms and to
 consider the array
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}\equiv\eta_{ac}\boldsymbol{R}^{c}{}_{b}.\]

\end_inset

The relationship between the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 and the covariant Riemann tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d})$
\end_inset

 can then be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b})=\boldsymbol{R}_{b\, a}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\iota_{\mathbf{y}}\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\boldsymbol{R}_{b\, a}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an obvious arbitrariness in the definition of the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

: one could interchange the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{b\, a}$
\end_inset

 above.
 This is the freedom of choosing the overall sign of the Riemann tensor.
 While not essential, this freedom leads to annoying sign discrepancies
 between different textbooks.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The curvature 2-forms can be computed directly and efficiently from the
 connection 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 using the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 2}

\end_inset

) below.
 To derive that formula, let us begin by expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 with help of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:cov diff thru omega}

\end_inset

).
 We find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\mathbf{e}_{b} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{a}\right)\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\right)\mathbf{e}_{a}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{e}_{a}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\right)\mathbf{e}_{a}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{a}(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{e}_{c};\\
\nabla_{[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]}\mathbf{e}_{b} & =\mathbf{e}_{a}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}([\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}]).\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can now compute the coefficient at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 (while doing that, we need to relabel the index 
\begin_inset Formula $a\rightarrow c$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\circ R(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})\mathbf{e}_{b} & =\mathbf{u}\circ\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})-\mathbf{v}\circ\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{u})-\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}([\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}])\\
 & +\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{c}(\mathbf{u})-\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{v})\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{c}(\mathbf{u})\\
 & =\left(\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}\right)\circ(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})+\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\right)\circ(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}),\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the standard definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

 for 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The result is called the 
\series bold
second
\series default
 
\series bold
Cartan structure equation
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Cartan structure equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}=\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{b}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}{}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}.\label{eq:Cartan 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remarks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The curvature 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 (with the first index lowered through 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ac}$
\end_inset

) are obviously antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 are.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cartan structure equations make computations of the curvature tensor
 significantly shorter.
 The simplification is due to several factors: firstly, the connection forms
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

, being antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, have fewer nonzero coefficients than the Christoffel symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, which are symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Secondly, many terms are cancelled automatically during the calculation
 of exterior differential and exterior product in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 2}

\end_inset

).
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compute the connection and the curvature forms for the two-dimensional metric
 
\begin_inset Formula $g=e^{2f}dt^{2}-e^{2h}dx^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t,x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t,x)$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the curvature 2-form of the two-dimensional de Sitter metric by
 setting 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t,x)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t,x)=Ht$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dual frame is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=e^{f}\textrm{d}t,\quad\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=e^{h}\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset

The differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{0}=\textrm{d}f\wedge e^{f}\textrm{d}t=f_{,x}e^{f}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}t,\quad d\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}=h_{,t}e^{h}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset

The only nonzero connection forms are 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{1}{}_{0}$
\end_inset

, so after some tries we get
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}=\boldsymbol{\omega}_{0\,1}=-\boldsymbol{\omega}_{1\,0}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{1}{}_{0}=f_{,x}e^{f-h}\textrm{d}t+h_{,t}e^{h-f}\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset

The only nonzero curvature 2-forms are 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}^{0}{}_{1}=\boldsymbol{R}^{1}{}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and are found as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{R}^{0}{}_{1}=\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}+\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{1};\]

\end_inset

however, the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 falls out because 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{0}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{1}{}_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the only nontrivial component of the curvature 2-forms is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{R}^{0}{}_{1} & =\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{0}{}_{1}=\left(f_{,x}e^{f-h}\right)_{,x}\textrm{d}x\wedge\textrm{d}t+\left(h_{,t}e^{h-f}\right)_{,t}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x\\
 & =\left[\left(h_{,t}e^{h-f}\right)_{,t}-\left(f_{,x}e^{f-h}\right)_{,x}\right]\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the calculation is significantly simplified due to the use of
 forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the de Sitter case, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{R}^{0}{}_{1}=H^{2}e^{Ht}\textrm{d}t\wedge\textrm{d}x.\]

\end_inset


\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ricci tensor and Ricci scalar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ricci tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Ric}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the trace of the Riemann tensor,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Ric}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)\equiv\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y}).\]

\end_inset

In the tetrad formulation, the first two arguments of 
\begin_inset Formula $R()$
\end_inset

 are the implicit arguments of the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}$
\end_inset

, so by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann tetrad def}

\end_inset

) we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{y})\equiv g(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{y})=g(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{y})\boldsymbol{R}^{a}{}_{b}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

We can use the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 to compute the trace:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Ric}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right) & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{e}^{c},\mathbf{e}_{b},\mathbf{e}_{c})\\
 & =\boldsymbol{R}^{c}{}_{b}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{e}_{c}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, the Ricci tensor is adequately described by the set of 1-forms
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{Ric}_{b} & \equiv-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{c}}\boldsymbol{R}^{c}{}_{b}=\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{c}}\boldsymbol{R}_{b\, c};\\
\textrm{Ric}\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right) & =\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}(\mathbf{y})\iota_{\mathbf{x}}\textrm{Ric}_{b}=\iota_{\mathbf{x}}g(\mathbf{e}^{b},\mathbf{y})\textrm{Ric}_{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here it is important to recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}^{b}$
\end_inset

 differs from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 and is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}^{b}\equiv\eta^{ab}\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the Ricci scalar is computed as the trace
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R=\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})}\textrm{Ric}\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}\right)=\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{b}}\textrm{Ric}_{b}=R_{a\, b}\left(\mathbf{e}^{b},\mathbf{e}^{a}\right).\label{eq:R as trace of Rab}\end{equation}

\end_inset

These equations offer an efficient method for practical calculations with
 the Ricci tensor and scalar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Calculation-Conformal-curvature-through-tetrads}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Calculation-Conformal-curvature-through-tetrads}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the tetrad formalism, we will now compute the change in the Ricci
 tensor and Ricci scalar due to a conformal transformation of the metric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the dual basis in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding dual basis in the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}\equiv e^{2\lambda}g$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e^{\lambda}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 are the connection 1-forms for the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We now need to compute the modified connection forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

.
 After that, the modified Riemann and Ricci tensors will be determined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 are found using the first Cartan structure equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 1}

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c} & =-\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b},\\
\textrm{d}\left(e^{\lambda}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right) & =-\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}^{c}{}_{b}\wedge e^{\lambda}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}=-\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}_{c\, b}-\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}.\]

\end_inset

We can now use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formula for chi without components 2}

\end_inset

) to express the 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}_{c\, b}\equiv\tilde{\boldsymbol{\omega}}_{c\, b}-\boldsymbol{\omega}_{c\, b}\]

\end_inset

 explicitly through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\right)-\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\right).\]

\end_inset

The last term vanishes since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}=0$
\end_inset

, and after a simplification,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\right)=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\eta_{ab}=\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\eta_{ab}\textrm{d}\lambda,\]

\end_inset

 we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}=\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\label{eq:delta omega tetrads}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Riemann tensor is expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 via the second Cartan structure equation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cartan 2}

\end_inset

).
 Hence, the curvature 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 are related to the 2-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 for the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{a\, b} & =\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}+\textrm{d}\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}\\
 & +\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}+\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, c}\wedge\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}+\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, c}\wedge\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now we need to substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta omega tetrads}

\end_inset

).
 The individual terms can be rewritten as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}=\left(\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left[_{a\leftrightarrow b}\right],\]

\end_inset

where I indicated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[_{a\leftrightarrow b}\right]$
\end_inset

 the repetition of previous terms with the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 interchanged.
 Further, we use the first Cartan structure equation to simplify
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b} & =\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\textrm{d}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using the identities
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c} & =\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{c}}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)=\textrm{d}\lambda,\\
\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\left(\mathbf{e}^{c}\circ\lambda\right) & =\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\left(\iota_{\mathbf{b}}\textrm{d}\lambda\right)=g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right),\\
\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c} & =0,\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (the first line above follows from Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-decomposition of form}

\end_inset

), we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
 & \delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, c}\wedge\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\\
 & =\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\right)\wedge\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}-\left(\mathbf{e}^{c}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right)\\
 & =\left[\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right]\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\\
 & =\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Putting the terms together and simplifying, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{a\, b} & =\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}+\left(\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\nonumber \\
 & +\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)\left[\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{a}\right]\nonumber \\
 & +\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\label{eq:Riemann tetrad tilde pre}\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point we note that the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 involve second derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 It is useful to introduce explicitly the tensor consisting of the second
 
\emph on
covariant
\emph default
 derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This tensor is called the 
\series bold
Hessian
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hessian}

\end_inset

 of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The Hessian is a symmetric bilinear form defined by the equivalent formulas
\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{\lambda}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\iota_{\mathbf{a}}\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\textrm{d}\lambda\right)=\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\nabla_{\mathbf{b}}\lambda-\nabla_{\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}}\lambda.\]

\end_inset

It follows from the definition that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 contains only derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and of the metric, but no derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a given function, we may assume that the Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a known tensor.
 We can now express the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 through the Hessian.
 First, we use the Leibnitz rule for the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

 of a 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\lambda$
\end_inset

 applied to a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\left[\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\circ\mathbf{b}\right] & =\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\circ\mathbf{b}+\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\circ\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}\\
 & =H_{\lambda}\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)+\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{a}}\mathbf{b}\right)\circ\lambda.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\left[\left(\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\circ\mathbf{e}_{b}\right]=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)=H_{\lambda}\left(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}_{b}\right)+\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}\right)\circ\lambda.\]

\end_inset

Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:cov diff thru omega}

\end_inset

), we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

 through the connection 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 and obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}H_{\lambda}+\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\sum_{c}\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right).\]

\end_inset

By dropping the insertion 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}$
\end_inset

 of the arbitrary basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{a}$
\end_inset

, we can rewrite the above as an equality of 1-forms,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{d}\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)=\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}H_{\lambda}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{c}{}_{b}\left(\mathbf{e}_{c}\circ\lambda\right).\]

\end_inset

This relationship is now used to simplify Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann tetrad tilde pre}

\end_inset

) further,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{a\, b} & =\boldsymbol{R}_{a\, b}+\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}H_{\lambda}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}H_{\lambda}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\nonumber \\
 & +\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b}\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\label{eq:Riemann tetrad tilde 1}\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Riemann tetrad tilde 1}

\end_inset

), we can now compute the Ricci tensor,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}_{b}=\iota_{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}^{a}}\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{b\, a}=e^{-\lambda}\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{b\, a}.\]

\end_inset

The following auxiliary calculations are helpful,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right) & =\left(N-1\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b};\\
\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b} & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\left[\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right]\\
 & =\left(N-1\right)\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right);\\
\left(\mathbf{e}^{a}\circ\lambda\right)\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{a\, b} & =\left(\mathbf{e}^{a}\circ\lambda\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}-\left(\mathbf{e}_{a}\circ\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\right)\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b};\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the spacetime,
\begin_inset Formula \[
N=\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}.\]

\end_inset

 Then we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
e^{\lambda}\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}_{b} & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\tilde{\boldsymbol{R}}_{b\, a}=\textrm{Ric}_{b}\\
 & \quad+\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\left[\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}H_{\lambda}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}-\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}H_{\lambda}\right)\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\right]\\
 & \quad+\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{a}}\left[\delta\boldsymbol{\omega}_{b\, a}\wedge\textrm{d}\lambda-g^{-1}\left(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda\right)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}\right]\\
 & =\textrm{Ric}_{b}+\left(N-2\right)\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}H_{\lambda}+H_{\lambda}(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}^{a})\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}\\
 & \quad-\left(N-2\right)\left(\mathbf{e}_{b}\circ\lambda\right)\textrm{d}\lambda+\left(N-2\right)g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda)\boldsymbol{\theta}_{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The trace of the Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 appearing in the last expression is traditionally called the (covariant)
 
\series bold
D'Alembertian
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{D'Alembertian}

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\square\lambda$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Tr}_{(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})}H_{\lambda}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=H_{\lambda}(\mathbf{e}_{a},\mathbf{e}^{a})\equiv\square\lambda.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ricci scalar is given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{R}=\iota_{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}^{b}}\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}_{b}=e^{-\lambda}\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{b}}\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}_{b},\]

\end_inset

so we finally obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
e^{2\lambda}\tilde{R} & =\iota_{\mathbf{e}^{b}}e^{\lambda}\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}_{b}\\
 & =R+2\left(N-1\right)\square\lambda+\left(N-1\right)\left(N-2\right)g^{-1}(\textrm{d}\lambda,\textrm{d}\lambda).\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulas for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\textrm{Ric}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 coincide with those obtained in Calculation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:Riemann-conformal}

\end_inset

.
 The calculation in the tetrad formalism is somewhat shorter and less tedious
 than the calculation in vector notation (see details\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-Statement-:Riemann-conformal}

\end_inset

).
 The trade-off is that one needs to introduce and use new techniques, such
 as connection 1-forms, the exterior product, and the insertion operator.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Einstein-Hilbert action in tetrads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamics of General Relativity is described by Einstein equations, which
 are derived from the action principle.
 In Section\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Einstein-Hilbert-action}

\end_inset

 the action was defined as a functional of the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The metric was treated as a dynamical variable that satisfies certain equations
 of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach is to regard the tetrad of 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as the primary dynamical variable.
 The metric tensor can be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\sum_{a}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\otimes\boldsymbol{\theta}_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 However, it is also useful to work directly with the tetrad, without using
 the metric tensor.
 In this section I will explain how the Einstein-Hilbert action is expressed
 and the Einstein equations are derived in the tetrad formalism.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
I learned some relevant details regarding this derivation from the course
 notes\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Kemp05}

\end_inset

, lecture 15.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard way of expressing the Einstein-Hilbert action in local coordinates
 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{\text{EH}}=\frac{1}{16\pi G}\int R\sqrt{-g}\textrm{d}^{4}x,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the Ricci scalar and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is Newton's constant.
 This formula can be rewritten with help of the volume 4-form,
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{\text{EH}}=\frac{1}{16\pi G}\int_{\mathcal{M}}R\,\textrm{Vol}.\]

\end_inset

Now we would like to express the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $R\,\textrm{Vol}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This can be done using the following trick.
 We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a double trace of the Riemann tensor, and that a multiple trace can
 be seen in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega wedge star omega Tr}

\end_inset

).
 Therefore, it will be possible to express the 4-form 
\begin_inset Formula $R\,\textrm{Vol}$
\end_inset

 directly through the curvature 2-forms.
 Using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:R as trace of Rab}

\end_inset

) and Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-hodge-symmetric}

\end_inset

(d), we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
R\,\textrm{Vol}=R_{a\, b}(\mathbf{e}^{b},\mathbf{e}^{a})\,\textrm{Vol}=R_{a\, b}\wedge*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}).\]

\end_inset

Using the relationship (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Hodge-duality}

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula \[
*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b})=\frac{1}{2!}\varepsilon^{abcd}\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d},\]

\end_inset

we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
R\,\textrm{Vol}=-\frac{1}{2}\varepsilon^{abcd}R_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d}.\]

\end_inset

Hence, the Einstein-Hilbert action can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
S_{\text{EH}} & =\frac{1}{16\pi G}\int_{\mathcal{M}}R_{a\, b}\wedge*\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right)\\
 & =-\frac{1}{32\pi G}\int_{\mathcal{M}}\varepsilon^{abcd}R_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{c}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}_{d}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Connections on vector bundles
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Connections-on-bundles}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector bundles as generalization of tangent bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tangent bundle 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tangent bundle}

\end_inset

to a manifold can be viewed as a collection of vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 attached to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 These vector spaces are attached to points in a special way, so that the
 relation between tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p'}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for neighbor points 
\begin_inset Formula $p,p'$
\end_inset

 can be nontrivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This construction is generalized by replacing the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by a different, perhaps more complicated, vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The result is the concept of a 
\series bold
vector bundle
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector bundle}

\end_inset

which is the union of copies of vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)$
\end_inset

 attached to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 All the vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)$
\end_inset

 should have the same dimension.
 The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is then called the 
\series bold
base manifold
\series default
 and the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
fiber
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector bundle!fiber}

\end_inset

of the bundle at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:p\rightarrow V(p)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 with values in the fibers 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
section
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector bundle!section of}

\end_inset

of the bundle.
 For example, sections of the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
vector fields
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 since the value of a vector field at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a vector from the space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Sections of more general vector bundles can be visualized as 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 on the manifold, such that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 belongs to the fiber space 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason we need to consider more general vector bundles than 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is that it is convenient to represent physical fields in (classical) field
 theory as sections of vector bundles.
 Fields are usually vector-valued (or tensor-valued) functions of spacetime,
 e.g.\InsetSpace ~
a Dirac spinor 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Dirac spinor}

\end_inset

field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 represents particles of spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and has values in a four-dimensional complex vector space.
 When we represent a field by a section of a vector bundle, the spacetime
 is the base manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and the value of the field at a point belongs to some vector space which
 is the fiber at that point.
 For example, spinor fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as sections of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spinor bundle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with fibers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{4}$
\end_inset

; tensor fields 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\mu\nu}(p)$
\end_inset

 are sections of a vector bundle with the fibers 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}\otimes T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Vector bundles give us a mathematical construction that describes all the
 physical fields in a unified language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of bundles
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Examples of bundles}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A direct product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\times V$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is any manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is any vector space, is obviously a vector bundle; such bundles are called
 
\series bold
trivial
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector bundle!trivial}

\end_inset

Many of the vector bundles used in physics are trivial, but sometimes the
 bundles turn out to be nontrivial, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
not isomorphic to a direct product
 of a base and a fiber.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{2}$
\end_inset

 to a sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This bundle has the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the base 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{2}$
\end_inset

 were trivial, one would be able to find a 
\series bold
trivialization
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{vector bundle!trivialization}

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
a smooth, one-to-one map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:S^{2}\times\mathbb{R}^{2}\rightarrow TS^{2}$
\end_inset

 which preserves the linear structure in the fibers.
 The existence of such a map would imply that the image of a fixed nonzero
 vector from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, say the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 with components 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)$
\end_inset

, is a smooth and everywhere nonzero vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(p;\mathbf{e}_{1})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 However, such a vector field does not exist, as shown by the following
 statement, which is a standard theorem of topology (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one cannot comb a sphere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{combing a sphere}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no smooth, everywhere nonzero tangent vector field to a sphere
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 (Proof 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vpageref{par:Proof-of-Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset

.)
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-combing-sphere}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2n}$
\end_inset

 of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 embedded in an (
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

)-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2n+1}$
\end_inset

, so that every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{2n}$
\end_inset

 is represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left\{ x_{1},...,x_{2n+1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{2n+1}x_{j}^{2}=R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The parity symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow-\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2n+1}$
\end_inset

, generates a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}:S^{2n}\rightarrow S^{2n}$
\end_inset

, bringing every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to the opposite point 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}p$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is an everywhere nonzero, smooth tangent vector field; we shall obtain
 a contradiction from this assumption.
 From each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{2n}$
\end_inset

, we can emit a geodesic in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{2n}$
\end_inset

 we have a geodesic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau;p)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the proper length along the curve, measured from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0;p)=p$
\end_inset

.
 Note that every geodesic on a sphere is an arc of great circle, and the
 circumference of every great circle is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau;p)$
\end_inset

 reaches the opposite point 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}p$
\end_inset

 when we extend it until 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\pi R$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\pi R;p)=\hat{P}p$
\end_inset

.
 Since by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth field, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow\gamma(\tau;p)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2n}\rightarrow S^{2n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow\gamma(\tau;p)$
\end_inset

 smoothly interpolates between the identity map and the parity inversion
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 changes between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi R$
\end_inset

.
 However, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2n+1}$
\end_inset

 is odd-dimensional, so the parity inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

 changes the orientation of the sphere; more precisely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{2n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(TS^{2n}\right)_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the radial vector representing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{x},\mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{2n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2n+1}$
\end_inset

 whose orientation is reversed under 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

.
 It is impossible to smoothly deform the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow p$
\end_inset

, which does not change the orientation, into the parity inversion map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

, which reverses the orientation.
 Therefore the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
 // This is taken from Husemoller, Fiber bundles.
 However, I don't really understand how to make this proof watertight.
 Why doesn't it work for just one neighborhood of one point? But surely
 we have vector fields in a neighborhood of a point.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider a stereographic projection of the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 onto a plane.
 The sphere is realized as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(x,y,z\right):x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=R^{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, and the projection is described explicitly by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(x,y,z\right)\rightarrow\frac{x+iy}{R-z}\equiv\zeta,\]

\end_inset

where the plane is parametrized by a single complex coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that the north pole 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,R\right)$
\end_inset

 is mapped onto infinity,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{x,y\rightarrow0}\frac{x+iy}{R-\sqrt{R^{2}-x^{2}-y^{2}}}=\infty,\]

\end_inset

while the south pole 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,-R\right)$
\end_inset

 is mapped onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0$
\end_inset

 (the center of the plane).
 Suppose we have a smooth and everywhere nonzero vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 on the sphere; then the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 under the projection is a smooth, everywhere nonzero vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 on the plane.
 By the smoothness assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is almost constant and nonzero in a sufficiently small neighborhood of
 the north pole.
 We may trace the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 around a small closed contour 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 surrounding the pole, and compute the accumulated angle swept by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 This accumulated angle will be zero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is almost constant.
 However, after the stereographic projection the small contour 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will become a large closed contour 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 on the plane.
 Since the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 on the sphere will be mapped to the exterior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 on the plane, the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is mirrored and the angle swept by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 when traced around 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset

.
 However, the contour 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be continuously deformed into a small contour 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 surrounding the center 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0$
\end_inset

 of the plane.
 The angle swept by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 is zero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 must be approximately constant in a sufficiently small neighborhood of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, the angle swept by a vector field around a closed contour is always
 an integer multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

