\begin_layout Subsection
Covariant derivatives on vector bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A covariant derivative on a vector bundle is a generalization of directional
 derivative, so that for a section 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\phi$
\end_inset

 is another section.
 We have seen that the covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 acts on various tensors in different ways (the covariant derivatives of
 a vector and a tensor are given by different formulae).
 Using the picture of bundles, we say that tensors of different ranks are
 sections of different bundles, and it is natural that different bundles
 have different covariant derivatives.
 (Up to now, we have been using the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 to mean different connections, depending on the rank of tensor it acts
 on.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general way to write the covariant derivative on a vector bundle is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}=\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\mathbf{t}+\Gamma(\mathbf{u})\mathbf{t},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial derivative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connection defined using a particular local coordinate system on the base
 manifold, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mathbf{u}}\equiv u^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is a transformation-valued 1-form.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation within a fiber and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
connection 1-form
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{connection 1-form}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauge theories and associated bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gauge field theories (such as electrodynamics, electroweak theory, and chromodyn
amics) use vector bundles with an additional structure.
 Namely, a certain Lie group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is acting in each fiber, such that the equations of the theory are invariant
 under local transformations of the group.
 For example, the gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)$
\end_inset

 for electromagnetism, 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 for the electroweak theory, and 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(3)$
\end_inset

 for chromodynamics.
 The group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is then called the 
\series bold
gauge group
\series default
 and the vector bundle is called 
\series bold
associated
\series default
 to this group (this is not a rigorous definition but is intended only as
 a qualitative hint).
 For an associated bundle, the connection 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 has values in a representation of the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 This of course limits the possible connections 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, leaving only the physically relevant ones.
 
\series bold
Why not give a more rigorous definition?
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent bundle as associated bundle
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Tangent-bundle-as}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us try to see if the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 can be also viewed as a bundle of which a gauge group acts.
 The gauge group in that case would be the orthogonal group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(n)$
\end_inset

 that acts fiber-wise, preserving the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in each fiber.
 (For a metric with the Lorentzian signature, the group will be 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

, called also the 
\series bold
Lorentz group
\series default
.) The connection 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is then required to give a transformation which is one of the transformations
 from the representation of the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{so}(n)$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 must be an antisymmetric linear transformation such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g(\Gamma(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})+g(\mathbf{x},\Gamma(\mathbf{v})\mathbf{y})=0.\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that this condition coincides with the condition\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:compatibility with the metric}

\end_inset

) expressing the compatibility of the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla=\partial+\Gamma$
\end_inset

 with the metric.
 Therefore the statement that the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 on the tangent bundle comes from the orthogonal gauge group is the same
 as the assumption of the compatibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 with the metric.
 This is just one example of how physical assumptions can be expressed in
 the language of gauge groups.
 
