\begin_layout Chapter
Spinors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional literature: 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{PeRi88a,Stew91}

\end_inset

.
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this chapter is to explain the definition of spinors and
 spinor fields, and to show some basic uses of spinors in general relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introducing spinors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
spinor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinor}

\end_inset

is a two-dimensional complex-valued vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in S$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S\equiv\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary space (the space of spinors).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
These two-dimensional objects are also called 
\series bold
Weyl spinors
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Weyl spinors}

\end_inset

 in distinction from 
\series bold
Dirac spinors
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Dirac spinors}

\end_inset

that have four complex components and are defined using Weyl spinors.
 The connection between the two will be explained below, and we say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spinor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Weyl spinor.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 The necessity to introduce spinors became apparent only after the development
 of quantum mechanics: It turned out that particles such as electrons or
 quarks must be described by spinor-valued fields, rather than by vector
 or tensor-valued fields.
 Below I shall explain the motivation for introducing spinors in more detail.
 Right now, I only give a rough heuristic picture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors can be visualized as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitudes,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which literally means a direction along a curve leading from a point of
 the manifold to a neighbor point.
 Tensors are defined algebraically through vectors.
 Every tensor remains unchanged under a rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 because every point returns to its original place, and tensors are defined
 through directions between points.
 Now, it turns out that one can define a special kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitude
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 called a spinor that remains unchanged only under a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset

 rotation but 
\emph on
changes
\emph default
 
\emph on
sign
\emph default
 under a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 rotation.
 Clearly, such an object cannot be a vector or a tensor, or any other object
 defined through points of a manifold, because every point in the neighborhood
 of a given center of rotation will return to its initial position after
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 rotation.
 Thus, a spinor cannot be defined through vectors of the tangent space.
 Spinors belong to some auxiliary vector space in which the rotation group
 acts in a special way.
 To understand how a rotation can act in such an unusual way, we need to
 study the rotation group in some more detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
The Lorentz group, 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

, does not directly act on the space of spinors; instead, its covering group
 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

, consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 complex matrices with unit determinant, acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The transformations from 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 differing by sign correspond to the same transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quaternions describe 3-rotations.
 However, they are from 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 and not from 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)/\mathbb{Z}_{2}=SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of quaternions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider rotations in a three-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all orthogonal transformations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the set of all linear transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\hat{R}^{T}=\hat{1}$
\end_inset

, is a group denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $O(3)$
\end_inset

.
 The subgroup denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

 contains 
\series bold
proper rotations
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{proper rotation}

\end_inset

 i.e.\InsetSpace ~
orthogonal transformations preserving the orientation (
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}=1$
\end_inset

).
 This way of describing rotations is tedious: one needs to specify 9 components
 of a matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 in a certain basis, while the group 
\begin_inset Formula $O(3)$
\end_inset

 is merely three-dimensional.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more concise way of representing rotations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is through quaternions.
 Quaternions are a generalization of complex numbers where one introduces
 three 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary units
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of one.
 I will now show how quaternions describe rotations, and I will also use
 quaternions to define spinors.
 (In brief: The four-dimensional space of quaternions is equivalent to the
 complex two-dimensional spinor space).
 Let us now briefly explore the properties of quaternions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of
\series bold
 quaternions
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{quaternion}

\end_inset

is a four-dimensional real space spanned by the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1},\mathbf{h}_{1},\mathbf{h}_{2},\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 is the set of linear combinations of the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}=x_{0}\mathbf{1}+x_{1}\mathbf{h}_{1}+x_{2}\mathbf{h}_{2}+x_{3}\mathbf{h}_{3},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are real coefficients.
 The special elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
quaternionic units
\series default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
A more traditional notation for quaternionic units is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{i},\mathbf{j},\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1},\mathbf{h}_{2},\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

, but I would like to avoid using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{i}$
\end_inset

 because I will later need to mix quaternions with complex numbers with
 their own imaginary unit, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multiplication of quaternions will be defined once we define the multiplicat
ion of the quaternionic units.
 The quaternionic units obey, by definition, the multiplication rules that
 can be written concisely as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{1}=\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{2}=\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{1}.\label{eq:Hamilton rule}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 It can be derived from these multiplication rules that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{h}_{j}*\mathbf{h}_{k}=-\delta_{jk}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{l=1}^{3}\varepsilon_{jkl}\mathbf{h}_{l},\label{eq:hj hk rule}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker symbol and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{jkl}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate representation of the three-dimensional Levi-Civita symbol,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{123}=1$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}=\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{1}.\]

\end_inset

With these definitions, the quaternionic space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 becomes a non-commutative algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming Hamilton's quaternionic multiplication rule\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hamilton rule}

\end_inset

), the associativity and distributivity of quaternionic multiplication,
 and the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}*\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{1}=\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 for any quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, one can derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:hj hk rule}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}=-\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=\mathbf{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

; after multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

 on the right, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{1}=-\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{2}=-\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}=-\mathbf{h}_{3}.\]

\end_inset

Consider the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{1}*\mathbf{h}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

; it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{1}=\mathbf{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 All other required relations are obtained in a similar way.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is sometimes useful to visualize a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\equiv x_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}x_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 as a formal sum 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}+\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 of a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a 3-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\equiv(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the quaternionic multiplication law\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:hj hk rule}

\end_inset

) is equivalent to the rule 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(x_{0}+\vec{x})*(y_{0}+\vec{y})=(x_{0}y_{0}-\vec{x}\cdot\vec{y})+(x_{0}\vec{y}+y_{0}\vec{x}+\vec{x}\times\vec{y}).\label{eq:quaternionic multiplication vector rule}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
conjugate
\series default
 quaternion
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{conjugate quaternion}

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{\mathbf{x}}\equiv x_{0}\mathbf{1}-\sum_{j=1}^{3}x_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}.\]

\end_inset

It is straightforward to verify that the conjugation operation interacts
 with quaternionic multiplication as
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
In mathematical language, the conjugation operator is an anti-automorphism
 of the algebra of quaternions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\overline{\left(\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}\right)}=\overline{\mathbf{y}}*\overline{\mathbf{x}}.\]

\end_inset

A quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
purely imaginary
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{x}}=-\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, which means that the first coefficient vanishes, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
magnitude
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|$
\end_inset

 of a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\equiv\left(x_{0}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}\right)^{1/2}.\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{x}}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}\right|=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\left|\mathbf{y}\right|$
\end_inset

, similarly to the properties of complex numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To verify these properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 We use the multiplication rule (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternionic multiplication vector rule}

\end_inset

) in the vector notation.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{x}}=x_{0}\mathbf{1}-\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{x}}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The property 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}\right|^{2}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\left|\mathbf{y}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is straightforward to derive, recalling that the vector product 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\times\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, and using the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{x}\times\vec{y}\right|^{2}=\left|\vec{x}\right|^{2}\left|\vec{y}\right|^{2}-\left|\vec{x}\cdot\vec{y}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important property is that every nonzero quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 has an inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}^{-1}=\mathbf{x}^{-1}*\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to a general quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=x_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}x_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Show that the inverse would not necessarily exist if we admitted complex
 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{x}}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}^{-1}=\frac{\bar{\mathbf{x}}}{\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}}=\frac{1}{\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}}\left(x_{0}\mathbf{1}-x_{1}\mathbf{h}_{1}-x_{2}\mathbf{h}_{2}-x_{3}\mathbf{h}_{3}\right).\]

\end_inset

The inverse exists when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}=\sum_{j=0}^{4}x_{j}^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

, which is guaranteed for quaternions with real coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quaternionic multiplication law also admits a representation in terms
 of complex 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 We may guess the required representation if we note that the multiplication
 rule of the 
\series bold
Pauli matrices
\series default
,
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Pauli matrices}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\sigma_{1} & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0\end{array}\right),\quad\sigma_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -\text{i}\\
\text{i} & 0\end{array}\right),\quad\sigma_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1\end{array}\right),\\
\sigma_{j} & \sigma_{k}=\delta_{jk}+\text{i}\sum_{l=1}^{3}\varepsilon_{jkl}\sigma_{l},\end{align*}

\end_inset

is very similar to the multiplication rule of the quaternionic units 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

, except for the extra factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore a representation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 complex matrices may be found as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{h}}_{j}=-\text{i}\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

, assuming (naturally) that the identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}$
\end_inset

 is used for the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The general quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=a_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 will be represented by the matrix
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{a}}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a_{0}-\text{i}a_{3} & -\text{i}a_{1}-a_{2}\\
-\text{i}a_{1}+a_{2} & a_{0}+\text{i}a_{3}\end{array}\right).\label{eq:quaternions by Pauli}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the determinant of this matrix is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, and that the Hermitian conjugate matrix corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det\hat{\mathbf{a}}=\left|\mathbf{a}\right|^{2}=a_{0}^{2}+a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2};\quad\hat{\mathbf{a}}^{\dagger}=\hat{\bar{\mathbf{a}}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an additional motivation, it is helpful to derive a matrix representation
 of quaternions without guessing the Pauli matrices.
 The four-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 of quaternions can be interpreted as a two-dimensional 
\emph on
complex
\emph default
 vector space if we somehow define what it means to multiply a quaternion
 by a complex number,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\lambda+\text{i}\mu\right)\mathbf{a}=???\]

\end_inset

 Clearly, it is sufficient to define the multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}$
\end_inset

, and we need to imitate the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{i}^{2}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Since any of the unit quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}^{2}=-\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

, we may choose for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

 as the representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{i}$
\end_inset

, so then we define
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\lambda+\text{i}\mu\right)\mathbf{a}\equiv\lambda\mathbf{a}+\mu\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{h}_{1}.\]

\end_inset

This is clearly a linear map in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 (note that we multiply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

 from the 
\emph on
right
\emph default
).
 We expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

, considered as a complex vector space, will be two-dimensional, so any
 quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\in\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a linear combination of two basis quaternions with
 complex coefficients.
 We may choose, for instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{1},\mathbf{h}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as the basis, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is already chosen as the representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{i}$
\end_inset

.
 (Different such choices will yield different but algebraically equivalent
 representations.) Then an arbitrary quaternion will be decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}\equiv a_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}=\left(a_{0}+\text{i}a_{1}\right)\mathbf{1}+\left(a_{2}-\text{i}a_{3}\right)\mathbf{h}_{2}\]

\end_inset

and so can be represented by an array of two complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{0}+\text{i}a_{1},a_{2}-\text{i}a_{3}\right)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the multiplication by a fixed quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation of the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it is natural to represent that transformation by a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 complex matrix.
 For example, the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\rightarrow\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 will be equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{h}_{3}*\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{0}+\text{i}a_{1}\\
a_{2}-\text{i}a_{3}\end{array}\right) & =\mathbf{h}_{3}*\left(a_{0}\mathbf{1}+a_{1}\mathbf{h}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{h}_{2}+a_{3}\mathbf{h}_{3}\right)\\
 & =-a_{3}\mathbf{1}-a_{2}\mathbf{h}_{1}+a_{1}\mathbf{h}_{2}+a_{0}\mathbf{h}_{3}\\
 & =\left(\begin{array}{c}
-a_{3}-\text{i}a_{2}\\
a_{1}-\text{i}a_{0}\end{array}\right)\\
 & =\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -\text{i}\\
-\text{i} & 0\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{0}+\text{i}a_{1}\\
a_{2}-\text{i}a_{3}\end{array}\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is represented by the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $-\text{i}\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}\rightarrow i\sigma_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{2}\rightarrow-\text{i}\sigma_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way we find a possible representation of quaternions through Pauli
 matrices.
 (This representation is equivalent to the standard one, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{j}\rightarrow-\text{i}\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

, after a permutation of the unit quaternions.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quaternions and rotations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection between quaternions and rotations is found by using the following
 method: We first consider an infinitesimal rotation, represent it through
 quaternionic multiplication, and then exponentiate the infinitesimal rotation
 to obtain a finite rotation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
rotation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{rotation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator that preserves the scalar product:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\forall\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\,:\, g(\hat{R}\mathbf{v},\hat{R}\mathbf{u})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}).\label{eq:orthogonal rotation def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

To define a rotation, it is actually sufficient to demand that a linear
 operator preserves the norm of each single vector,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\forall\mathbf{x}\,:\, g(\hat{R}\mathbf{x},\hat{R}\mathbf{x})=g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset

because the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 allows us to derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:orthogonal rotation def}

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
infinitesimal rotation
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{infinitesimal rotation}

\end_inset

 is a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{v},\hat{S}\mathbf{v})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (that is to say, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 must be antisymmetric with respect to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

).
 The picture behind this is that of transforming a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}_{0}\mapsto\mathbf{v}_{0}+\lambda\hat{S}\mathbf{v}_{0},\]

\end_inset

where the formal parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is, heuristically, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and describes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 angle of the rotation.
 Given an infinitesimal rotation operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

, one can obtain the corresponding finite rotation with angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This is done by considering the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 rotated by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as a vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(0)=\mathbf{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

, and then writing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal rotation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}(\lambda+\delta\lambda)=\mathbf{v}(\lambda)+\delta\lambda\,\hat{S}\mathbf{v}(\lambda)\]

\end_inset

 in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, as the differential equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\lambda}\mathbf{v}(\lambda)=\hat{S}\mathbf{v}(\lambda),\quad\mathbf{v}(0)=\mathbf{v}_{0}.\]

\end_inset

The solution is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}(\lambda)=\exp(\lambda\hat{S})\mathbf{v}_{0}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Infinitesimal rotations can be represented by quaternionic multiplication
 through the following trick: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=q_{0}+\vec{q}$
\end_inset

 is a quaternion and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 3-dimensional vector, understood also as a (purely imaginary) quaternion,
 then the quaternionic commutator
\begin_inset Formula \[
[\mathbf{q},\vec{v}]\equiv\mathbf{q}*\vec{v}-\vec{v}*\mathbf{q}=2\vec{q}\times\vec{v}\]

\end_inset

yields a vector that is always orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the quaternionic commutator with a fixed quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 is an infinitesimal rotation.
 Geometrically, this is a rotation around the axis given by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

, since the infinitesimal change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}\times\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The factor 2 means that an infinitesimal rotation with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a physical rotation by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $2\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The scalar part 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 of the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 does not play any role in the commutator; therefore, let us suppose that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 is purely imaginary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=\vec{q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to exponentiate this infinitesimal rotation to a finite rotation.
 This is accomplished with the standard technique for computing the exponential
 of a commutator: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}\vec{v}=[\mathbf{q},\vec{v}]$
\end_inset

, where the commutator is computed according to the multiplication rules
 of the quaternion algebra, then
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\exp(\lambda\hat{S})\vec{v}=\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\vec{v}*\exp(-\lambda\mathbf{q}),\label{eq:exponential of quaternion commutator}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where now the exponential 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(\lambda\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is also to be computed according to the rules of the quaternion algebra.
 (The exponential of a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined by the Taylor series,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp\mathbf{x}=1+\mathbf{x}+\frac{1}{2!}\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}+\frac{1}{3!}\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}+...,\]

\end_inset

and it can be shown that this series converges for any quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, just like in the case of a matrix exponential.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Derivation of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:exponential of quaternion commutator}

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We introduce the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-dependent function 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $0)=\vec{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and such that the differential equation holds, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\lambda}\vec{v}(\lambda)=[\mathbf{q},\vec{v}(\lambda)].\]

\end_inset

We can verify that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:exponential of quaternion commutator}

\end_inset

) is a solution of this differential equation.
 First, we note that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\lambda}\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})=\mathbf{q}*\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})=\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\mathbf{q};\]

\end_inset

here it is essential that the quaternionic multiplication should be used
 in defining the exponential.
 Then we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\frac{d}{d\lambda} & \left(\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\vec{v}_{0}*\exp(-\lambda\mathbf{q})\right)\\
 & =\mathbf{q}*\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\vec{v}_{0}*\exp(-\lambda\mathbf{q})\\
 & \;+\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\vec{v}_{0}*\exp(-\lambda\mathbf{q})*(-\mathbf{q})\\
 & =[\mathbf{q},\exp(\lambda\mathbf{q})*\vec{v}_{0}*\exp(-\lambda\mathbf{q})]\\
 & =[\mathbf{q},\vec{v}(\lambda)].\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the solution of the differential equation with a given initial condition
 is unique, we find that the formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:exponential of quaternion commutator}

\end_inset

) is indeed the solution.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation did not essentially use the fact that we are computing in
 the algebra of quaternions.
 Therefore, the same derivation will hold in the matrix algebra or in any
 other algebra.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we now need quaternionic exponentiation, let us derive an explicit
 formula for it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit formula for the exponential of a purely imaginary quaternion
 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp(\vec{a})=\mathbf{1}\cos\left|\vec{a}\right|+\frac{\vec{a}}{\left|\vec{a}\right|}\sin\left|\vec{a}\right|,\]

\end_inset

and for the exponential of an arbitrary quaternion is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp\left(a_{0}\mathbf{1}+\vec{a}\right)=\mathbf{1}e^{a_{0}}\cos\left|\vec{a}\right|+e^{a_{0}}\frac{\vec{a}}{\left|\vec{a}\right|}\sin\left|\vec{a}\right|.\]

\end_inset

 It follows that every nonzero quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is an exponential of some other quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\equiv\ln\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is purely imaginary if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}*\vec{a}=-\left|\vec{a}\right|^{2}\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

, so we find the same algebraic law as with the complex number 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{i}\left|\vec{a}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the same derivation as for the Euler formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp\left(\text{i}a\right)=\cos a+\text{i}\sin a\]

\end_inset

goes through.
 We obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\exp\vec{a} & =\mathbf{1}\cos\left|\vec{a}\right|+\frac{\vec{a}}{\left|\vec{a}\right|}\sin\left|\vec{a}\right|,\\
\exp\left(a_{0}\mathbf{1}+\vec{a}\right) & =e^{a_{0}}\exp\vec{a}=\mathbf{1}e^{a_{0}}\cos\left|\vec{a}\right|+e^{a_{0}}\frac{\vec{a}}{\left|\vec{a}\right|}\sin\left|\vec{a}\right|.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 For an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=x_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}x_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\exp(a_{0}\mathbf{1}+\vec{a})$
\end_inset

 and find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
a_{0} & =\ln\left|\mathbf{x}\right|,\\
\vec{a} & =\frac{x_{1}\mathbf{h}_{1}+x_{2}\mathbf{h}_{2}+x_{3}\mathbf{h}_{3}}{\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}}}\arccos\frac{x_{0}}{\left|\mathbf{x}\right|}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the vector notation,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln\,(x_{0}+\vec{x})=\ln\sqrt{x_{0}^{2}+\left|\vec{x}\right|^{2}}+\frac{\vec{x}}{\left|\vec{x}\right|}\arccos\frac{x_{0}}{\sqrt{x_{0}^{2}+\left|\vec{x}\right|^{2}}}.\]

\end_inset

We note that the direction of the vector part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the same as that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have found that the exponential of an infinitesimal rotation is expressed
 by the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{v}\mapsto\mathbf{c}*\vec{v}*\mathbf{c}^{-1},\]

\end_inset

where the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}=\exp(\lambda\vec{q}),\quad\mathbf{c}^{-1}=\exp(-\lambda\vec{q}).\]

\end_inset

 The axis of rotation is given by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

, and the angle of rotation is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider the linear transformation in the space of quaternions, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}:\mathbf{x}\mapsto\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{c}^{-1},\]

\end_inset

for an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 fixed quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We may normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 without changing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}(\mathbf{x})=\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}\label{eq:quaternionic SO3}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}(\bar{\mathbf{x}})=\overline{\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}(\mathbf{x})}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the three-dimensional subspace of purely imaginary quaternions is
 invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 preserves the magnitude of quaternions,
\begin_inset Formula \[
|\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}(\mathbf{x})|=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|.\]

\end_inset

A purely imaginary quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=-\bar{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, interpreted as a 3-vector, is transformed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 without changing its Euclidean length; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 acts as an 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 transformation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\in O(3)$
\end_inset

.
 Since every quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 is an exponential of some purely imaginary quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=\ln\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}(\mathbf{x})=\exp\left(\mathbf{b}\right)*\mathbf{x}*\exp\left(-\mathbf{b}\right),\]

\end_inset

and thus we can smoothly deform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 into the identity map by decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 to zero.
 Since the determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}=\pm1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\in O(3)$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 In this way, normalized quaternions represent three-dimensional rotations,
 and multiplication of quaternions corresponds to composition of rotations:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{a}}\hat{R}_{\mathbf{b}}=\hat{R}_{\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 is quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, heuristically one may say that the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

square root
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, we have shown that quaternions describe rotations, but we have not
 yet shown that 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 can be described through some quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 as the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 This also turns out to be true.
 The following theorem summarizes the precise relationship between quaternions
 and rotations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{par:Statement-:magnitude-quaternion}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Statement-:magnitude-quaternion}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(The Euler theorem and the Cayley parametrization of rotations.) An arbitrary
 proper rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 can be represented through the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}=\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}\equiv\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}},\]

\end_inset

with some quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|=1$
\end_inset

.
 (Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as a purely imaginary quaternion.) For a given rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

, the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is unique up to sign; the same rotation is generated also by 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\mathbf{c})$
\end_inset

.
 The magnitude of the (pure imaginary) quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=\ln\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a 
\emph on
half
\emph default
 of the angle of the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, and the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is the axis of rotation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\neq0$
\end_inset

 generates a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\,:\,\mathbf{x}\mapsto\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{c}^{-1}\]

\end_inset

 which is a rotation because it is linear and preserves the norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\mathbf{1}=\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{c}^{-1}*\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{c}^{-1}=(\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x})*(\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 remains the same when we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 by a number.
 Thus, it is possible to restrict to quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 without loss of generality.
 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}^{-1}=\bar{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector.
 Let us define the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}=\exp(\lambda\vec{u})=\cos\lambda+\vec{u}\sin\lambda\]

\end_inset

and write the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 on a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 explicitly as follows: Either 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}=x_{1}\vec{u}$
\end_inset

, and then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\vec{x}=\mathbf{c}*x_{1}\vec{u}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}=\vec{x}\]

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

; or else we can choose a right-handed orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \vec{u},\vec{v},\vec{w}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{x}=x_{1}\vec{u}+x_{2}\vec{v},\]

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 but does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}=\vec{u}\times\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we compute
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\vec{x} & =\mathbf{c}*\vec{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}\\
 & =x_{1}\vec{u}+\left(\cos\lambda+\vec{u}\sin\lambda\right)*\left(x_{2}\vec{v}\right)*\left(\cos\lambda-\vec{u}\sin\lambda\right)\\
 & =x_{1}\vec{u}+(\cos2\lambda)x_{2}\vec{v}+(\sin2\lambda)x_{2}\vec{w}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 rotates the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 around the axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $2\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, a rotation around an axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{u}\right|=1$
\end_inset

) by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is represented by the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}=\exp\left(\frac{1}{2}\alpha\vec{u}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also need to show that for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 given proper rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

, a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 exists such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}=\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is not a trivial statement since we have to be able to analyze an
 arbitrary rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We start with the representation of the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 as a proper orthogonal transformation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 (that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}^{T}\hat{R}=\hat{1}$
\end_inset

) and will now compute the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we note that any linear operator in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 has a cubic characteristic polynomial and therefore has at least one real
 eigenvalue.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}^{T}\hat{R}=\hat{1}$
\end_inset

, all eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Any complex eigenvalues must come in complex conjugate pairs; therefore,
 there is at most one such pair, 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\pm\text{i}\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 If there is such a pair, the remaining eigenvalue must be 1 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}=1$
\end_inset

.
 If there are no complex eigenvalues then all eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

 and there are only two possibilities: the eigenvalues of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 are either 
\begin_inset Formula $1,-1,-1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1,1,1$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is either equal to the identity operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}$
\end_inset

 or else must have a nondegenerate eigenvalue 1 (with algebraic multiplicity
 1) and two other eigenvalues of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\pm\text{i}\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with a real 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in any case there exists an eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\vec{v}=\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, we may suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{v}\right|=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 preserves the scalar product, the 2-dimensional subspace orthogonal to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In that subspace, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 acts as a proper orthogonal transformation.
 In two dimensions, all proper orthogonal transformations are rotations
 by some angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is a rotation around the axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quaternion representing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 can now be easily found as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=\exp(\frac{1}{2}\alpha\vec{v})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}=\exp\left(\frac{1}{2}\alpha\vec{v}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now show that, for a given rotation, the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is unique up to a sign.
 If two different quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 generate the same rotation, then
\begin_inset Formula \[
\forall\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\::\:\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}=\mathbf{b}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{b}}.\]

\end_inset

Multiply on the left by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 and on the right by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\forall\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\::\:\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{x},\qquad\mathbf{a}\equiv\bar{\mathbf{c}}*\mathbf{b}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 commutes with all quaternions.
 This is possible only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is a number.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{a}\right|^{2}=\left|\mathbf{c}\right|^{2}\left|\mathbf{b}\right|^{2}=1.\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\pm\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=\pm\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

