\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is a given orthogonal transformation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 By the Euler theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is a rotation around some axis by some angle.
 Show that the trace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2\cos\alpha$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the angle of rotation.
 Show that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{S}\equiv\hat{R}-\hat{R}^{T}\]

\end_inset

is antisymmetric and, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}\neq0$
\end_inset

, can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{S}\vec{x}=\vec{v}\times\vec{x},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 1 (i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the axis of rotation).
 In this way, the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 can be easily read off the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 (however, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}\neq0$
\end_inset

 then the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 cannot be determined in this way).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the Euler theorem, there exists an axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 and the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 is a rotation around 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 in an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \vec{v},\vec{w}_{1},\vec{w}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\alpha & -\sin\alpha\\
0 & \sin\alpha & \cos\alpha\end{array}\right).\]

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tr}\,\hat{R}=1+2\cos\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 defined above.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric, there exists a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}\vec{x}=\vec{a}\times\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{S}\vec{v}=(\hat{R}-\hat{R}^{T})\vec{v}=(\hat{R}-\hat{R}^{-1})\vec{v}=0.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}\times\vec{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that a quaternion contains only the information
 about the half-angle of rotation, so a rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 may be represented by a nontrivial quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=-\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 as well as by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Imagine that we use a quaternion to keep track of the orientation of a
 rigid body; then the quaternion will 
\emph on
change
\emph default
 
\emph on
sign
\emph default
 after a rotation of the rigid body by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 and return to the original value only after another rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 in the same direction.
 This unusual behavior is the main reason quaternions are useful in the
 construction of spinors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}=\hat{R}_{-\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, every two opposite quaternions correspond to the same three-dimensional
 rotation.
 The set of all normalized quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{c}:\left|\mathbf{c}\right|=1\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 in the four-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to a sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 with identified opposite points.
 We have thus defined a projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}\rightarrow SO(3)$
\end_inset

 acting as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\rightarrow\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, and this map is everywhere 2-to-1.
 Such maps between manifolds are called 
\series bold
coverings
\series default
, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{covering}

\end_inset

so in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}\rightarrow SO(3)$
\end_inset

 is a twofold covering.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 is represented as the set of 
\emph on
unitary
\emph default
 complex matrices with unit determinant via Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternions by Pauli}

\end_inset

); the group of these matrices is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie group!$SU(2)$}

\end_inset

Note that this group is at the same time a manifold (
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

), and also the multiplication by a fixed matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in SU(2)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}\rightarrow S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Groups that are smooth manifolds are called 
\series bold
Lie groups
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie group}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the multiplication of quaternions corresponds, on the one hand,
 to the multiplication of matrices, and on the other hand, to multiplication
 of rotations.
 Thus the covering 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)\rightarrow SO(3)$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no canonical way to define a smooth inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)\rightarrow SU(2)$
\end_inset

 because we would need to choose the sign of a quaternion according to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how many 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 rotations were made,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and this information cannot be derived from one element of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 If one were given not only an element 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 but also a continuous path leading from the identity transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

, then one would be able to choose a unique element of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

.
 (Paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to an odd and an even number of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 rotations are topologically inequivalent and cannot be continuously deformed
 into each other.) On the other hand, we have seen that 
\emph on
infinitesimal
\emph default
 transformations can be uniquely mapped 1-to-1 between 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that a quaternion can be equivalently viewed as a two-dimensional
 complex vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 on which quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 act as unitary matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}\in SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 Although the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 does not belong to the real three-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can be transformed by a rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 performed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 because we can find a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}=\hat{R}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

and transform the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 with the unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that unitary matrices preserve the Hermitian scalar product in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.) Transformed in this manner, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 represents an unusual kind of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directed magnitude
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that rotates only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

half-way.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the two-dimensional complex vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is in fact a 
\series bold
spinor
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinor}

\end_inset

and the auxiliary space 
\begin_inset Formula $S\equiv\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the spinor space.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinor space}

\end_inset

 To summarize, spinors are quaternions viewed as elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A non-proper rotation is an orthogonal transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{R}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Such transformations can be represented through quaternions as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}\mapsto-\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Lorentz group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, we worked in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and ignored the time dimension of the spacetime.
 We shall now extend the considerations to the 3+1-dimensional case.
 We have seen that proper rotations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\in SO(3)$
\end_inset

 are represented by matrices acting in a two-dimensional complex space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of spinors, such that a spinor changes sign under a rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now extend the considerations to the 3+1-dimensional case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our goal for now is to define spinors at a point.
 We shall be working in the Minkowski spacetime, which we interpret as a
 tangent plane to a point of a 3+1-dimensional spacetime manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lorentz transformations are linear transformations of the Minkowski spacetime
 that preserve the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 preserving the metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\hat{L}\mathbf{x},\hat{L}\mathbf{y})=g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

, must be a linear transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Hint:
\emph default
 Consider an image of an orthogonal basis under 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 An orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{e}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 must be transformed into another orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{L}\mathbf{e}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\hat{L}(\mathbf{x}+\lambda\mathbf{y}),\hat{L}\mathbf{z}) & =g(\mathbf{x}+\lambda\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})\\
 & =g(\hat{L}\mathbf{x},\hat{L}\mathbf{z})+\lambda g(\hat{L}\mathbf{y},\hat{L}\mathbf{z}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}=\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0...3$
\end_inset

, we obtain the required linearity property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the Lorentz transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 form a group 
\begin_inset Formula $O(3,1)$
\end_inset

, with a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 of orientation-preserving transformations (
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{L}=1$
\end_inset

).
 Below we shall always consider only the group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 which we shall call the 
\series bold
Lorentz group
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lorentz group}

\end_inset

 Lorentz transformations include proper rotations, 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)\subset SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

, and we already know how spinors transform under 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 Now we need to investigate how spinors may transform under other elements
 the Lorentz group that are not purely rotations.
 These other elements are the 
