\begin_layout Standard
Show by deriving an explicit formula that there exists a boost 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}\in SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 transforming a timelike vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 into another timelike vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\neq\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, and leaving invariant two spacelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{1,2}$
\end_inset

, orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution:
\emph default
 The required Lorentz transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 should act in the 2-plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a transformation will leave invariant every spacelike vector orthogonal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is two-dimensional, therefore there exist two spacelike vectors orthogonal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 which will be left invariant.
 An explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 can be derived e.g.\InsetSpace ~
by determining the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{ij}$
\end_inset

 in the general expression for a linear transformation in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\}$
\end_inset

 plane, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}\mathbf{x}=\lambda_{11}\mathbf{u}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u})+\lambda_{12}\mathbf{u}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v})+\lambda_{21}\mathbf{v}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u})+\lambda_{22}\mathbf{v}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v}).\]

\end_inset

Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{u})=g(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})=1$
\end_inset

, the result is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{v}g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{u})+\frac{\gamma\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{u}}{\gamma^{2}-1}g(\mathbf{x},\gamma\mathbf{u}-\mathbf{v}),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\equiv g(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v})>1$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

boost factor.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\rightarrow\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 the result is well-behaved.
\end_layout

