\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is brought into the 3-plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we look for the remaining transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{2}\in SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}=\hat{L}_{2}\hat{L}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

 should leave 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 invariant, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{2}(\mathbf{v}^{\perp})\subset\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a proper rotation.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This statement allows us to understand the topological structure of the
