\begin_layout Subsection
Lorentz transformations of spinors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine how spinors transform under a boost, we need to extend the
 quaternionic picture of proper rotations to boosts.
 Once each Lorentz transformation is mapped to a quaternion, the representation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternions by Pauli}

\end_inset

) will yield the corresponding spinor transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can arrive at a quaternionic representation of Lorentz transformations
 by analogy with Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternionic SO3}

\end_inset

) if we consider quaternions with 
\emph on
complex
\emph default
 coefficients.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{quaternion!with complex coefficients}

\end_inset

Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}\otimes\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 the space of linear combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=c_{0}\mathbf{1}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

 are complex coefficients.
 By analogy with Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternionic SO3}

\end_inset

), let us consider the quaternionic transformation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{c}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 does not generate Lorentz transformations!
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}:\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}},\label{eq:quaternion SO31}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a quaternion satisfying
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{c}\right|^{2}\equiv c_{0}^{2}+c_{1}^{2}+c_{2}^{2}+c_{3}^{2}=1,\]

\end_inset

and the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 is at once the quaternionic and the complex conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{\mathbf{c}}\equiv\bar{c}_{0}\mathbf{1}-\sum_{j=1}^{3}\bar{c}_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}.\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Complex-valued quaternions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 do not necessarily satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|^{2}\geq0$
\end_inset

, but it is easy to check that the algebraic property 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}\right|^{2}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\left|\mathbf{y}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 still holds (its derivation is independent of the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

 are real-valued).
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
|\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}|^{2}=\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}\]

\end_inset

as before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}}=\bar{\mathbf{y}}*\bar{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, and so the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 acting in the complex quaternionic space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{H}\otimes\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 preserves the subspace of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

self-adjoint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hermitian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\overline{\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}}\equiv\overline{\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}}=\mathbf{c}*\bar{\mathbf{x}}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}=\mathbf{c}*\mathbf{x}*\bar{\mathbf{c}}.\]

\end_inset

 Note that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hermitian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quaternion must have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=x_{0}\mathbf{1}+i\sum_{j=1}^{3}x_{j}\mathbf{h}_{j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
real
\emph default
.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a real 4-vector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we immediately find that the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}=x_{0}^{2}-x_{1}^{2}-x_{2}^{2}-x_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is conserved by transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 act as Lorentz transformations in the 4-dimensional space of Hermitian
 quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 (The same result holds for anti-Hermitian quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{x}}=-\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we have found a correspondence between quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and Lorentz transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 The following simple considerations show that the inverse map, 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)\rightarrow\mathbb{H}\otimes\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, also exists.
 It follows from previous calculations that every 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 is equal to an exponential of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

purely imaginary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quaternion, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{c}=\exp\mathbf{b},\quad\mathbf{b}=b_{1}\mathbf{h}_{1}+b_{2}\mathbf{h}_{2}+b_{3}\mathbf{h}_{3},\]

\end_inset

where now 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 are also complex-valued.
 As before, only orientation-preserving transformations are generated by
 quaternions.
 Transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\exp\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

 with all real 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 correspond to proper rotations that preserve the 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\equiv\left(1,0,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These rotations form the subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 Transformations with imaginary 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 are boosts that preserve two spacelike vectors orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 (see Calculation below).
 Since every Lorentz transformation is a product of a proper rotation and
 a boost, and since the product of quaternions corresponds to the product
 of transformations, it follows that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}\in SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 there exists a complex-valued quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}=\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the explicit formula for the transformation of the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 of the 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}=\exp\left(\text{i}\alpha\mathbf{h}_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

, and show that this is a boost in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us use the matrix representation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternions by Pauli}

\end_inset

) which maps quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 complex matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 acting in 
\begin_inset Formula $S\equiv\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{c}\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{\mathbf{c}}=1$
\end_inset

, therefore the set of all the admissible quaternions is the same as the
 set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 complex matrices with unit determinant.
 This set is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
special linear group
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lie group!$SL(2,\mathbb C)$}

\end_inset

in two complex dimensions.
 It is clear that we have built a group homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})\rightarrow SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

.
 As before, quaternions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 generate the same Lorentz transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})\rightarrow SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 is a 2-to-1 covering.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to see that the quaternionic conjugation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\rightarrow\bar{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the Hermitian conjugation of matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}\rightarrow\hat{\mathbf{c}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the matrix formula describing the transformation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:quaternion SO31}

\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}\mathbf{x}=\hat{\mathbf{c}}\hat{\mathbf{x}}\hat{\mathbf{c}}^{\dagger},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}\in SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 and the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 describing the 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{x}}\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cc}
x_{0}+x_{3} & x_{1}-\text{i}x_{2}\\
x_{1}+\text{i}x_{2} & x_{0}-x_{3}\end{array}\right).\label{eq:real 4vector Pauli}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that this matrix is Hermitian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{x}}^{\dagger}=\hat{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

; thus the subspace of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hermitian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quaternions is equivalent to the subspace of Hermitian 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 A concise expression for the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\mathbf{x}}=\sum_{j=0}^{3}\sigma_{j}x_{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli matrices, and we have set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}\equiv\hat{1}$
\end_inset

.
 As before, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det\hat{\mathbf{x}}=g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=x_{0}^{2}-x_{1}^{2}-x_{2}^{2}-x_{3}^{2}.\]

\end_inset

 In this way, the Pauli matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

 provide a 1-to-1 map between the Minkowski spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 and the space of all 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 Hermitian matrices.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
This map is called the 
\series bold
Infeld-van der Waerden map
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Infeld-van der Waerden map}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Below we shall denote this map by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have built the 
\series bold
spinor representation
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Lorentz group!spinor representation}

\end_inset

of the Lorentz group in the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The procedure can be summarized like this: Every Lorentz transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}\in SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 yields a quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}=\hat{L}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, and then we compute the corresponding matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 acting in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The product of Lorentz transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the product of matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a Lorentz transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}\in SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

, the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 (and thus the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

) is defined only up to a sign.
 Hence, it is necessary to consider spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as quantities that are defined only up to a sign.
 (In quantum mechanics, this would be a natural conclusion if the spinor
 were considered as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wave function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is defined only up to a phase.) As before, a spinor changes sign after
 a rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 However, now we know how to rotate the spinor in 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 reference frame since we derived the action of an arbitrary Lorentz transformat
ion on a spinor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
* Rotations in higher dimensions
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Rotations-in-higher-dimensions}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction of spinors depends on the description of rotations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 through quaternions.
 Quaternions work well for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and even for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 if one considers complex-valued quaternions; however, quaternions cannot
 be straightforwardly generalized to describe higher-dimensional rotations.
 Instead, one can use the construction based on Clifford algebras.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, an 
\series bold
algebra
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{algebra}

\end_inset

 is a vector space with a bilinear multiplication (any two vectors can be
 multiplied to yield another vector in the same space).
 So, to define an algebra, we need to specify a vector space and define
 the multiplication rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A formal definition of a Clifford algebra will be given in the next subsection.
 A motivation for introducing the Clifford algebra is found by recalling
 the construction of rotations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 through quaternions.
 We started with infinitesimal rotations and then exponentiated them to
 obtain finite rotations.
 An arbitrary infinitesimal rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 can be represented by the cross product 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}\vec{x}=\vec{v}\times\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, which is then replaced by a commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\vec{v},\vec{x}\right]$
\end_inset

 computed in the quaternion algebra.
 A finite rotation is found by exponentiating the commutator, which yields
 the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\vec{v}}*\vec{x}*e^{-\vec{v}}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to obtain a similar description for vectors from an arbitrary
 vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 where, for instance, the vector 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cross
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 product is not defined.
 Thus, our goal is to find an algebra where the commutator corresponds to
 infinitesimal rotations in the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 An arbitrary infinitesimal rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 is an antisymmetric tensor and can be identified with an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge^{2}V$
\end_inset

, the space of bivectors, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
of linear combinations of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}\wedge\mathbf{d}+...$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d},...\in V$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wedge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 represents the antisymmetric (exterior) tensor product.
 Thus it appears that we can obtain the required algebra only if the vector
 space of the algebra includes not only the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 but also, at least, the space of bivectors.
 The enlargement of the vector space did not appear in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 because the space of bivectors over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is three-dimen\SpecialChar \-
sional and could be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 itself.
 In higher dimensions, this identification is not possible any more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to guess the new multiplication law, let us replace quaternions
 by bivectors in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 We can choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and note that the ordinary right-hand rule identifies the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 with the cross product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

; for instance, the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is identified with the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 At this point, we would like to avoid performing this identification.
 So we are motivated to replace the quaternionic units 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

 by bivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and also to replace cross products by bivectors where appropriate.
 In order to make contact with the standard definition of the Clifford algebra,
 we will choose the signs as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}_{1}\mapsto-\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{3},\quad\mathbf{h}_{2}\mapsto-\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{h}_{3}\mapsto-\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}.\]

\end_inset

 The rules of quaternionic multiplication can now be written as rules for
 multiplication of vectors and bivectors: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We distinguish vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 from quaternionic units such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{1}\equiv\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\in\wedge^{2}\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication of two quaternions: Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}*\mathbf{h}_{3}=-\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)*\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=-1$
\end_inset

, and similarly for other quaternionic units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication of a vector and a quaternion: Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{h}_{1}*\vec{e}_{2}=-\vec{e}_{2}*\mathbf{h}_{1}=\vec{e}_{3}\]

\end_inset

 we write
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)*\mathbf{e}_{2}=-\mathbf{e}_{2}*\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)=\mathbf{e}_{3}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These rules of multiplication can be summarized as follows: if vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 are unit vectors such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=0$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y} & =\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y},\quad\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{1},\\
\mathbf{x}*(\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}) & =\mathbf{y},\quad(\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y})*\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{x}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that the algebra of quaternions is equivalent to a larger algebra
 containing numbers, vectors, and bivectors.
 We have not yet completely defined the multiplication in the larger algebra;
 for instance, we have not yet defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)*\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the quaternion algebra, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{h}_{3}*\vec{e}_{3}=\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

, so it is natural to define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)*\mathbf{e}_{1}=\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}=-\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{3}.\]

\end_inset

Note that this is not a number but an antisymmetric tensor of rank 3.
 Since the space of antisymmetric 3-tensors over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional, we again find a natural correspondence with the quaternion
 algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are interested in representing rotations through an algebra, the
 rule for multiplication of a vector and a bivector must be such that all
 infinitesimal rotations are represented by commutators of vectors with
 some bivectors.
 For instance, an infinitesimal rotation around the axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

 by an (infinitesimal) angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 was previously represented by the commutator
\begin_inset Formula \[
\vec{x}\mapsto\vec{x}+\lambda\vec{e}_{3}\times\vec{x}=\vec{x}+\frac{\lambda}{2}\left(\mathbf{h}_{3}*\vec{x}-\vec{x}*\mathbf{h}_{3}\right).\]

\end_inset

 We can easily check that this holds with the above multiplication rules
 if we use the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 instead of the quaternion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multiplication operator 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 applied to orthonormal unit vectors can be summarized as follows.
 When all vectors in a product term are different, the term yields the exterior
 multiplication, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{y}*\mathbf{z}=\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}\wedge\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

.
 When not all vectors are different, any equal unit vectors can be brought
 together using antisymmetry, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
...*\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{b}*\mathbf{x}*...=-...*\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}*...\]

\end_inset

and then the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 can be omitted, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula \[
...*\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{b}*...=...*\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}*...\]

\end_inset

This multiplication rule is associative but not commutative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Clifford algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This construction can be now generalized from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
Clifford
\series default
 
\series bold
algebra
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Clifford algebra}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

 based on a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector space of the Clifford algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

 is the same as the vector space of the exterior algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

 consists of a direct sum of the spaces of all the possible antisymmetric
 tensors built out of vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

 could be of the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha_{0}\mathbf{1}+\mathbf{x}_{1}+\mathbf{x}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{x}_{3}+\mathbf{x}_{4}\wedge\mathbf{x}_{5}\wedge\mathbf{x}_{6}+...,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a number.
 The above is just an example; there could be of course more terms of each
 tensorial rank.
 (The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

 denotes the scalar unit.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the exterior algebra, the multiplication is denoted by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wedge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

.
 In the Clifford algebra, a different multiplication rule is defined, which
 we will denote by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 like the quaternion multiplication.
 The Clifford multiplication can be defined most concisely as follows.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
This definition follows Rashevskij P.K.
 Teorija spinorov, URSS, 2006 (in Russian).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Scalars are multiplied with other terms in the natural way: for example,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sqrt{2}\mathbf{1}*(\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y})=\sqrt{2}\mathbf{x}\wedge\mathbf{y}.\]

\end_inset

Scalars commute with all other terms.
 In order to define the Clifford multiplication of arbitrary tensor terms,
 it is sufficient to define the multiplication of the form, say,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)*\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{4}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{5}\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are vectors from an 
\emph on
orthonormal
\emph default
 basis in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multiplication of basis tensors is defined as follows.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}=\mathbf{e}_{i_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{i_{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}=\mathbf{e}_{j_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j_{n}}$
\end_inset

 are two antisymmetric tensors built out of the vectors of this basis.
 We would like to define the Clifford product 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}*\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We first compute the exterior product 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

, and we must find that either 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the first case, we define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi_{1}*\psi_{2}\equiv\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}\quad\text{if}\:\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}\neq0.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the exterior multiplication can be replaced by Clifford multiplicatio
n as long as all vectors are orthogonal to each other,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi_{1}=\mathbf{e}_{i_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{i_{m}}=\mathbf{e}_{i_{1}}*...*\mathbf{e}_{i_{m}},\]

\end_inset

and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It also follows that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}=-\mathbf{b}*\mathbf{a}\quad\text{if}\; g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=0.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second case (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}\wedge\psi_{2}=0$
\end_inset

), the resulting product 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}*\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 will be a tensor of a lower rank.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
The two cases of the Clifford product rule unite the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exterior
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interior
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 multiplication as first defined by H.
 Grassmann.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There must exist at least one basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{s}$
\end_inset

 that enters both 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now there are two further cases: either 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}=\psi_{2}=\mathbf{e}_{s}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 have a higher rank.
 In the first case, we define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{s}*\mathbf{e}_{s}\equiv\mathbf{1}.\]

\end_inset

In the second case, we use the antisymmetry of the exterior product to reorder
 the vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that these tensors have the form
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi_{1}=\pm\mathbf{e}_{i_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{i_{m-1}}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{s},\quad\psi_{2}=\pm\mathbf{e}_{s}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j_{2}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j_{n}}.\]

\end_inset


\series default
Then we define (with the appropriate sign)
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi_{1}*\psi_{2}=\pm\left(\mathbf{e}_{i_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{i_{m-1}}\right)*\left(\mathbf{e}_{j_{2}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{j_{n}}\right).\]

\end_inset

Now we have a Clifford product of two tensors of a lower rank; we use again
 the same rule until all Clifford products are simplified.
 Since the multiplication is defined by moving vectors together towards
 the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

, the rule is automatically associative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the multiplication of basis tensors is defined, we use linearity to
 define the Clifford multiplication of arbitrary terms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Exercise 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 are any vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, show that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}=g\left(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right)\mathbf{1}+\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}.\]

\end_inset

In particular,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}=g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{1}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may choose a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},...,\mathbf{e}_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that (for simplicity) 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}=a\mathbf{e}_{1},\quad\mathbf{b}=b_{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}.\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b} & =ab_{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}*\mathbf{e}_{1}+ab_{2}\mathbf{e}_{1}*\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =ab_{1}\mathbf{1}+ab_{2}\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{1}+\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Exercise 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 are vectors orthogonal to each other and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is any vector, show that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left[\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\right] & =(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b})*\mathbf{c}-\mathbf{c}*(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b})\\
 & =2\mathbf{a}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c})-2\mathbf{b}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{c}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the final formula resembles the double cross product in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\vec{a}\times\vec{b})\times\vec{c}=\vec{b}g(\vec{a},\vec{c})-\vec{a}g(\vec{b},\vec{c}),\]

\end_inset

up to a constant factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Hint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Clifford multiplication rule can be summarized more concisely (but less
 transparently) by the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}*\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{b}*\mathbf{a}=2g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\mathbf{1}.\]

\end_inset

Starting with this formula, one can (after some work) derive the more explicit
 rules that we have presented earlier.
 We will not use this formula directly.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Representing rotations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now use the Clifford algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

 in the manner quite analogous to the use of quaternions, for representing
 rotations in an arbitrary vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with a given metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, an arbitrary infinitesimal rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 is an antisymmetric operator.
 The space of antisymmetric operators is isomorphic to the space of bivectors.
 Explicitly, a bivector such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the antisymmetric operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}_{\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

 that acts on vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{S}_{\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\mathbf{a}g(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x})-\mathbf{b}g(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x}).\]

\end_inset

As shown in Exercise\InsetSpace ~
2, this is equivalent to the Clifford commutator 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{S}_{\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}}(\mathbf{x})=\frac{1}{2}[\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}].\]

\end_inset

A general antisymmetric operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 may require more than one exterior product term, e.g.\InsetSpace ~
for a certain given
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 we may need more vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, etc., so that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{S}(\mathbf{x}) & =\hat{S}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\left[\boldsymbol{\psi},\mathbf{x}\right],\\
\boldsymbol{\psi} & \equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{1}+\mathbf{a}_{2}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{2}+...+\mathbf{a}_{n}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, this representation is always possible with just one term.
 One can show
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
Statement 2 and Exercise 7 in Section 5.7 of S.
 Winitzki, 
\emph on
Linear Algebra via Exterior Products
\emph default
, lulu.com, 2010.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that no more than 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

 terms suffice in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

, and that all the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be chosen mutually orthogonal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A finite rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}$
\end_inset

 is now obtained by exponentiating an infinitesimal rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}(\mathbf{x})\equiv\exp\left(\boldsymbol{\psi}\right)*\mathbf{x}*\exp\left(-\boldsymbol{\psi}\right).\]

\end_inset

As in the case of quaternions, one can easily show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}$
\end_inset

 is an orthogonal transformation in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}}=\mathbf{1},\]

\end_inset

we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g(\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\mathbf{x},\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\mathbf{x})\mathbf{1} & =(\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\mathbf{x})*(\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\mathbf{x})\\
 & =e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}*\mathbf{x}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}}*e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}*\mathbf{x}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}}\\
 & =e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}*\mathbf{x}*\mathbf{x}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}}\\
 & =e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}*g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{1}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}}\\
 & =g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})\mathbf{1}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Given an explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}$
\end_inset

, one can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 Assume, without loss of generality, that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\psi}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i},\]

\end_inset

where all the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{i},\mathbf{b}_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are mutually orthogonal unit vectors, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 are some numbers.
 We first note that a term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 commutes with any other term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{j}$
\end_inset

 in the Clifford algebra: If 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 then the Clifford product coincides with the exterior product, so
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}\right)*\left(\mathbf{a}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{j}\right) & =\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{a}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{j}\\
 & =\mathbf{a}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}=\left(\mathbf{a}_{j}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{j}\right)*\left(\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Therefore the exponential 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}}$
\end_inset

 can be factorized as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp\boldsymbol{\psi}=e^{\lambda_{1}\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{1}}*...*e^{\lambda_{n}\mathbf{a}_{n}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}}.\]

\end_inset

Each single-term exponential is computed just as in the case of quaternions:
 since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\right)*\left(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\right)=-\left(\mathbf{b}\wedge\mathbf{a}\right)*\left(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\right)=-\mathbf{1},\]

\end_inset

we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp\left(\lambda\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\right)=\mathbf{1}\cos\lambda+\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}\sin\lambda.\]

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\exp\boldsymbol{\psi} & =\left(\mathbf{1}\cos\lambda_{1}+\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{1}\sin\lambda_{1}\right)*...\\
 & \qquad*(\mathbf{1}\cos\lambda_{n}+\mathbf{a}_{n}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}\sin\lambda_{n}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Expanding the brackets, we would obtain an expression of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\exp\boldsymbol{\psi} & =\cos\lambda_{1}...\cos\lambda_{n}\left(\mathbf{1}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}\tan\lambda_{i}+...\right)\\
 & \qquad+\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}\sin\lambda_{1}...\sin\lambda_{n}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can consider all elements of the Clifford algebra that are generated
 as exponentials of some bivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}$
\end_inset

, or Clifford products of such exponentials.
 It is clear that a Clifford product 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}*e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}$
\end_inset

 generates the composition of two consecutive rotations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}$
\end_inset

, even though generally 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}*e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}\neq e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}+\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}.\]

\end_inset

The set of all such elements (allowing products of arbitrary many single
 exponentials) is called the 
\series bold
Clifford
\series default
 
\series bold
group
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Clifford group}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have shown that every element of the Clifford group generates a rotation
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 proper rotation in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 can be represented by a certain element of the Clifford group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any proper orthogonal transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

, there exists a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq N-1$
\end_inset

 bivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}_{i}\equiv\mathbf{a}_{i}\wedge\mathbf{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,n$
\end_inset

) from the Clifford algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Cl}(V)$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{R}\mathbf{x} & =\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}\circ...\circ\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{n}}\mathbf{x}\\
 & =e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}*...*e^{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{n}}*\mathbf{x}*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}_{n}}*...*e^{-\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show this by induction in the number of dimensions.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

, the statement is true because every proper rotation is an identity transformat
ion.
 Now we suppose that the statement is proved in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N-1}$
\end_inset

, and we will prove it for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 An arbitrary rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

 brings an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 into another orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{f}_{1},...,\mathbf{f}_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{i}\equiv\hat{R}\mathbf{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We can now compute a bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}=\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\neq\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}=\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\neq\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

, we choose 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}=\lambda\mathbf{f}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\]

\end_inset

 with an appropriate value of the number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 To compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mathbf{f}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{1})\equiv\cos\phi$
\end_inset

 and write
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{f}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{f}_{1}-\mathbf{e}_{1}g(\mathbf{f}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{1})\right)\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}=\left(\mathbf{f}_{1}-\mathbf{e}_{1}\cos\phi\right)*\mathbf{e}_{1};\\
\left(\mathbf{f}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)*\left(\mathbf{f}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & =-\left|\mathbf{f}_{1}-\mathbf{e}_{1}\cos\phi\right|^{2}=-\sin^{2}\phi;\\
\mathbf{f}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\sin\phi,\quad\mathbf{b}_{1}\equiv\frac{1}{\sin\phi}\left(\mathbf{f}_{1}-\mathbf{e}_{1}\cos\phi\right);\\
\exp\left(\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}\right) & =\mathbf{1}\cos\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right)+\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\sin\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right),\end{align*}

\end_inset

and then obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\exp\left(\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}\right)*\mathbf{e}_{1}*\exp\left(-\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}\right)\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{1}\cos\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right)+\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\sin\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right)\right)*\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
 & \quad*\left(\mathbf{1}\cos\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right)-\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge\mathbf{e}_{1}\sin\left(\lambda\sin\phi\right)\right)\\
 & =\mathbf{e}_{1}\cos\left(2\lambda\sin\phi\right)+\mathbf{b}_{1}\sin\left(2\lambda\sin\phi\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

This expression will be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula \[
\cos\left(2\lambda\sin\phi\right)=g(\mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{f}_{1})=\cos\phi.\]

\end_inset

This determines the required value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\phi}{\sin\phi}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the required rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 The rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 brings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and all other basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{N}$
\end_inset

 to some vectors that all belong to the orthogonal complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The original rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 can be then represented as a composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and an auxiliary rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 that does not change 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

 but operates only within the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N-1\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspace orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}=\hat{R}^{\prime}\circ\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}.\]

\end_inset

By the inductive hypothesis, the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a product of not more than 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N-2\right)$
\end_inset

 rotations of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{n}}$
\end_inset

, where now 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq N-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it is possible to express 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}=\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2}}\circ...\circ\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{n}}\circ\hat{R}_{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{1}}\]

\end_inset

 as required.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that an arbitrary rotation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by up to 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

axes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of rotation and the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

 angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

, where each 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

axis of rotation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a bivector of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 with unit vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and can be visualized as a rotation in the plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $2\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we apply this description to Lorentz transformations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, we find that an arbitrary Lorentz transformation can be characterized
 by two bivectors, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\wedge\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis, and the corresponding two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

angles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, we may suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 is time-like while 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c},\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

 are spacelike.
 In this way, we can describe an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 Lorentz transformation as a boost in the spacelike direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 with boost parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 combined with a spatial rotation around the 
\emph on
same
\emph default
 axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Once the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 are fixed, the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\wedge\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

 can be determined as 
\begin_inset Formula $*(\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a Lorentz transformation is fully characterized by two numbers, a
 time-like unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, and a spacelike unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 (The choice of unit vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary as long as the bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\wedge\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 remains constant.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spinor algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role of quaternions in the construction of spinors is illustrative but
 purely auxiliary.
 Quaternions provide a visual derivation of the concept of spinor spaces
 adapted to 3+1-dimensional spacetimes, as well as a convenient tools for
 computations with rotations and Lorentz transformations.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
A definition of spinors for higher-dimensional spacetimes can be formulated
 using a suitable generalization of quaternions, called 
\series bold
Clifford algebras
\series default
.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Clifford algebra}

\end_inset

 A primer on Clifford algebras is found in Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Rotations-in-higher-dimensions}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 From now on, we may forget quaternions and simply assume that spinors are
 elements of a complex vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in which two structures are defined:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A representation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

up to a sign
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the Lorentz group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rotates by half-angle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (the spinor representation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A fixed 1-to-1 correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 Hermitian matrices and vectors from the Minkowski spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these properties as building blocks, we shall now study the tensor
 algebra generated by the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and its relation to the usual tensor algebra in the Minkowski spacetime.
 Since quaternions will not be used any more, we shall denote the spinorial
 form of Lorentz transformations simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{s}$
\end_inset

 rather than by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we shall not distinguish between 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 since this distinction will play no role in our calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a real vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, tensors of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)$
\end_inset

 are defined as tensor products of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 copies of the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To build tensors from the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, we need to consider the dual space to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 We define the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}$
\end_inset

 as the space of linear functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(\mathbf{b}+\lambda\mathbf{c})=f(\mathbf{b})+\lambda f(\mathbf{c}),\quad\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\in S,\;\lambda\in\mathbb{C}.\]

\end_inset

 Additionally, we can define the 
\emph on
complex conjugate
\emph default
 dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

 as the space of 
\series bold
anti-linear
\series default
 
\series bold
functions
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{anti-linear function}

\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(\mathbf{b}+\lambda\mathbf{c})=f(\mathbf{b})+\bar{\lambda}f(\mathbf{c}),\quad\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}\in S,\;\lambda\in\mathbb{C}.\]

\end_inset

 Finally, we define the space dual to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

 as the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complex conjugate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spinors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
This needs to be illustrated by explicit examples with calculations and
 bases!
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the four spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are two-dimensional, and a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 naturally generates a dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}^{*},\mathbf{b}^{*}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}$
\end_inset

, a conjugate dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{a}}^{*},\bar{\mathbf{b}}^{*}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

, and a conjugate basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{a}},\bar{\mathbf{b}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural antilinear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

: a linear function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 generates an anti-linear function whose values are 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{f}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding map 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow\bar{S}$
\end_inset

 is also denoted by the overbar, so for instance
\begin_inset Formula \[
\overline{\mathbf{a}+\lambda\mathbf{b}}=\bar{\mathbf{a}}+\bar{\lambda}\bar{\mathbf{b}}\in\bar{S}\quad\textrm{if }\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\in S,\;\lambda\in\mathbb{C}.\]

\end_inset

Lorentz transformations act on dual spinors by inverse matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{s}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and on conjugate spinors by Hermitian conjugate matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{s}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Spinorial tensors
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinorial tensor}

\end_inset

can be built by taking tensor products of the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and its three conjugates.
 The rank of a spinorial tensor contains four numbers, for instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\bar{1},2\bar{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, showing how many copies of each of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}^{*}$
\end_inset

 participate in the tensor product.
 For instance, Hermitian bilinear forms are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\bar{1}\right)$
\end_inset

-tensors on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Complex conjugation is then a naturally defined map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j\bar{k},l\bar{m}\right)$
\end_inset

-tensors to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k\bar{j},m\bar{l}\right)$
\end_inset

-tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we have many different types of tensors, it is inevitable that we
 must eventually use the (abstract) index notation.
 It is traditional to denote indices in spinor spaces by capital letters,
 and indices in conjugate spaces by a prime, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{AB'}$
\end_inset

 denotes a rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\bar{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 spinorial tensor.
 Note that the order of primed and unprimed indices is insignificant: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{AB'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{B'A}$
\end_inset

 is the same object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The fundamental 2-form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is two-dimensional, every 2-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is proportional to an arbitrarily selected one.
 There is in fact a naturally selected 2-form, which we shall call the 
\series bold
fundamental 2-form
\series default
 and denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 We shall now define the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 by using the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and the Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 transforms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hermitian matrices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into 4-vectors, and we need to be more specific about the space of such
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matrices.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a Hermitian matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}h\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding 4-vector.
 Since the formula for the Lorentz transformation is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}\left(\hat{\sigma}h\right)=\hat{\sigma}\left(\hat{L}_{s}h\hat{L}_{s}^{\dagger}\right),\]

\end_inset

it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a spinorial tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\bar{1},0\right)$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $h\in S\otimes\bar{S}$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, we may write the application of the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 to such a tensor as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\hat{\sigma}h\right)^{\mu}=\sigma_{AA'}^{\mu}h^{AA'}.\]

\end_inset

Moreover, the property of being Hermitian means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{h}=h$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 defines a bilinear form in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes\bar{S}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall temporarily denote this bilinear form by angular brackets,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle h_{1},h_{2}\right\rangle \equiv g\left(\hat{\sigma}h_{1},\hat{\sigma}h_{2}\right).\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, we have (
\emph on
with some choice of basis
\emph default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) the explicit formula\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:real 4vector Pauli}

\end_inset

), from which it follows that the determinant of a Hermitian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\hat{\sigma}h,\hat{\sigma}h)$
\end_inset

.
 The determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a quadratic form in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes\bar{S}$
\end_inset

, and it is clear from the above equation that this quadratic form generates
 the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle h_{1},h_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 However, the determinant can be expressed through the Levi-Civita symbol
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det h=\frac{1}{2}\varepsilon_{AB}\varepsilon_{A'B'}h^{AA'}h^{BB'}.\]

\end_inset

It follows that, 
\emph on
in the same basis 
\emph default
where Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:real 4vector Pauli}

\end_inset

) holds,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{\mu\nu}\sigma_{AA'}^{\mu}\sigma_{BB'}^{\nu}=\frac{1}{2}\varepsilon_{AB}\varepsilon_{A'B'}.\label{eq:g sigma sigma e e}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Although the above formula is written in a specific basis, it can be reinterpret
ed as the definition of the fundamental 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is chosen as follows: First we take any nonzero 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in S^{*}\wedge S^{*}$
\end_inset

; then we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 by a suitable constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\lambda\omega$
\end_inset

 satisfies Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g sigma sigma e e}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $S\wedge S$
\end_inset

, we naturally define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\varepsilon}:S\rightarrow S^{*}$
\end_inset

 and the inverse form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{-1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}\wedge S^{*}$
\end_inset

, as well as the corresponding conjugate forms.
 Note, however, that the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric and hence there is a choice of sign in defining the inverse.
 For instance, we might debate whether the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{-1}\mathbf{a}^{*}$
\end_inset

 should be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\varepsilon(\varepsilon^{-1}\mathbf{a}^{*},\mathbf{b})\equiv\mathbf{a}^{*}\circ\mathbf{b}\]

\end_inset

or by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\varepsilon^{-1}\mathbf{a}^{*},\mathbf{b})\equiv\mathbf{a}^{*}\circ\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

? The convention is to use the 
\emph on
first
\emph default
 argument of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 (as shown above) but the 
\emph on
second
\emph default
 argument of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the index notation, this corresponds to the following definitions,
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{A}\varepsilon^{BA}=a^{B},\quad b^{B}\varepsilon_{BA}=b_{A},\quad\varepsilon^{AB}\varepsilon_{BC}=-\delta^{A}{}_{C}\equiv\varepsilon_{C}^{A}.\]

\end_inset

In the index notation, additional trouble arises because 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{A}{}_{C}=-\delta_{C}{}^{A}$
\end_inset

 if we raise and lower indices using 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

, so one uses the unambiguous notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{A}{}_{C}=\varepsilon_{C}{}^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The same conventions apply to the conjugate forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

