\begin_layout Subsection
Relationship of spinors and vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the fundamental 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, we may choose a preferred basis adapted to the form.
 The traditional notation for the basis is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ o,\iota\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $o,\iota\in S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(o,\iota)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is as close as possible to an orthogonal basis, given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric.
 The basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ o,\iota\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
spin basis
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spin basis}

\end_inset

or the 
\series bold
spin frame
\series default
.
 The basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $o,\iota$
\end_inset

 naturally induce to spin frames in the dual, conjugate, and dual conjugate
 spaces.
 It follows that the fundamental 2-form is written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\varepsilon_{AB}=o_{A}\iota_{B}-\iota_{A}o_{B};\quad\varepsilon^{-1}=\iota\wedge o=\iota\otimes o-o\otimes\iota.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the spin frame, we obtain a natural basis in the (four-dimensional)
 space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\bar{1},0\right)$
\end_inset

-tensors:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left\{ l^{AA'},m^{AA'},\bar{m}^{AA'},n^{AA'}\right\}  & \equiv\left\{ o^{A}\bar{o}^{A'},o^{A}\bar{\iota}^{A'},\iota^{A}\bar{o}^{A'},\iota^{A}\bar{\iota}^{A'}\right\} \\
 & \equiv\left\{ o\otimes\bar{o},o\otimes\bar{\iota},\iota\otimes\bar{o},\iota\otimes\bar{\iota}\right\} .\end{align*}

\end_inset

Transforming these basis tensors by the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the 4-vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are real-valued but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{m}}$
\end_inset

 are complex-valued, because the corresponding basis elements are not Hermitian.
 It is easy to see, however, that each of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{l},\mathbf{m},\bar{\mathbf{m}},\mathbf{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is null.
 In fact, these vectors are a 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{null tetrad!from spin basis}

\end_inset

Newman-Penrose null tetrad (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Null-tetrad-formalism}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

