 Let us now consider how we could construct some tensor objects out of spinors
 and in this way obtain a geometric interpretation for spinors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firstly, a spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}\in S$
\end_inset

 defines a null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}=\hat{\sigma}(\mathbf{c}\otimes\bar{\mathbf{c}})$
\end_inset

.
 In components, this is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\mu}=\sigma_{AA'}^{\mu}c^{A}\bar{c}^{A'}$
\end_inset

 or more concisely 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{AA'}=c^{A}\bar{c}^{A'}$
\end_inset

.
 (The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is usually omitted for brevity since it is a fixed structure relating the
 spinor and the vector spaces.) One may say figuratively that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a spinor is a square root of a null vector.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The null direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 is the principal geometric information contained in a spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 However, spinors differing by a phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}e^{i\alpha}$
\end_inset

, define the same null vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 The phase information can be extracted if we define the 
\series bold
flag bivector
\series default

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{flag bivector}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
F_{(\mathbf{c})} & \equiv\mathbf{c}\otimes\mathbf{c}\otimes\bar{\varepsilon}+\varepsilon\otimes\bar{\mathbf{c}}\otimes\bar{\mathbf{c}},\nonumber \\
F^{AA'BB'} & \equiv c^{A}c^{B}\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}+\varepsilon^{AB}\bar{c}^{A'}\bar{c}^{B'}.\label{eq:flag through c}\end{align}

\end_inset

The spinorial tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{AA'BB'}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to an antisymmetric bivector 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F^{\mu\nu}n_{\nu}=0,\quad F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu}=0.\label{eq:flag property 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that there exists a (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

-dependent) vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{\mathbf{c}}=\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}\wedge\mathbf{k},\quad F^{\mu\nu}=n^{\mu}k^{\nu}-n^{\nu}k^{\mu},\quad g(\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}},\mathbf{k}_{\mathbf{c}})=0.\]

\end_inset

The choice of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 is up to a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

, so the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}},F_{\mathbf{c}})$
\end_inset

 only defines a null 
\emph on
plane
\emph default
 containing the null direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 This geometric configuration is similar to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flag
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flagpole
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flag plane
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{k}_{\mathbf{c}},\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}}\}$
\end_inset

; so we call a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{c}},F_{\mathbf{c}}\right)$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
flag
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{flag of a spinor}

\end_inset

corresponding to a spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}'$
\end_inset

 differing by sign give the same flag, and conversely, a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n},F\right)$
\end_inset

 determines a spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 up to a sign.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
This can be shown following 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wald84}

\end_inset

, Eqs.\InsetSpace ~
(13.1.47)-(13.1.50), and deriving an explicit formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 given a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n},F\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

