\begin_layout Standard
These properties offer a possible geometric interpretation of spinors and
 illustrate the fact that spinors are related to null directions.
 Since the flag bivector carries the entire physical information in a spinor
 (the sign of a spinor is not observable), one could in principle forego
 spinors and reformulate every spinor equation in terms of unambiguously
 defined flag bivectors.
 However, flags are quadratic in spinors, and thus linear equations of motion
 for spinor fields will become nonlinear tensor equations if written in
 terms of flags.
 Spinors provide a simpler formulation of many equations, especially those
 with massless fields for which null directions are especially important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simplification of spinorial tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is two-dimensional, its properties are significantly simpler than those
 of a higher-dimensional space.
 For instance, every antisymmetric tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, an arbitrary rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,2\right)$
\end_inset

 spinorial tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{AB}$
\end_inset

 can be simplified into a symmetric tensor and a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
T_{AB} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(T_{AB}+T_{BA}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\left(T_{AB}-T_{BA}\right)\\
 & =T_{(AB)}+\frac{1}{2}\left(T_{CD}\varepsilon^{CD}\right)\varepsilon_{AB}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Moreover, every spinorial tensor can be reduced to a combination of products
 of the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and some totally symmetric tensors.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{PeRi88a}

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Stew91}

\end_inset

 for a complete proof.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For example, a rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,2\bar{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 tensor can be decomposed as
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{ABA'B'}=T_{(AB)A'B'}+\frac{1}{2}T_{CDA'B'}\varepsilon^{CD}\varepsilon_{AB}.\]

\end_inset

The same decomposition can be applied to the primed indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us consider two special cases.
 Suppose the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ABA'B'}$
\end_inset

 comes from an 
\emph on
antisymmetric
\emph default
 4-tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ABA'B'}=-T_{BAB'A'}$
\end_inset

, and then
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{ABA'B'}=\phi_{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}+\varepsilon_{AB}\bar{\phi}_{A'B'},\]

\end_inset

where the symmetric spinorial tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{AB}$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi_{AB}\equiv\frac{1}{2}T_{ABA'B'}\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}.\]

\end_inset

If, on the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ABA'B'}$
\end_inset

 comes from a 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 4-tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{ABA'B'}=T_{(AB)(A'B')}+\frac{1}{4}\varepsilon_{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}\left(T_{CDC'D'}\varepsilon^{CD}\bar{\varepsilon}^{C'D'}\right).\label{eq:symmetric TABAB decomp}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the only nontrivial spinorial tensors we need to consider are totally
 symmetric ones.
 For those, the following decomposition property holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every totally symmetric spinorial tensor can be decomposed into a symmetric
 product of spinors:
\begin_inset Formula \[
T_{(AB)}=a_{(A}b_{B)},\quad T_{(ABC)}=a_{(A}b_{B}c_{C)},\]

\end_inset

etc.
 The null flagpoles 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

, etc., corresponding to the spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, etc., are called the 
\series bold
principal null directions
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{principal null direction}

\end_inset

of the spinorial tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A totally symmetric tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by its values on a single vector; e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{z})$
\end_inset

 can be restored if we know 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=o+\iota z$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $o$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 are two spinors building a spin frame, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is a cubic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 A cubic polynomial can be factorized as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x})=\left(a_{0}+a_{1}z\right)\left(b_{0}+b_{1}z\right)\left(c_{0}+c_{1}z\right),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0},a_{1},...,c_{1}$
\end_inset

 are suitable complex numbers (not uniquely determined).
 We can interpret these numbers as the spin frame components 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{A}$
\end_inset

 of three spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ABC}$
\end_inset

 is totally symmetric, we have obtained a decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{(ABC)}=a_{(A}b_{B}c_{C)}$
\end_inset

.
 The general case of a spinorial tensor of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is treated analogously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: Classification of 4-tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since every Minkowski 4-tensor can be mapped into a spinorial tensor, we
 may reduce every 4-tensor first to totally symmetric spinorial tensors,
 and then to products of individual spinors.
 In this way, every 4-tensor gives rise to a set of principal null directions.
 This construction provides a classification of 4-tensors based on how many
 of their principal null directions coincide.
\end_layout

