\begin_layout Section
Equations for spinor fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have worked in the Minkowski spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, interpreted as the tangent space at a single point of a spacetime manifold.
 Now we shall consider a (curved) spacetime where a spinor field should
 be defined at every point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spinors in curved spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
spinor field
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinor field}

\end_inset

is, roughly speaking, a spinor-valued function on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

; thus we would like to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\in S$
\end_inset

 to denote the value of the spinor field at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 However, spinors are tied to the Lorentz transformations in a tangent space
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and tangent spaces differ at different points of the manifold.
 Therefore, we cannot directly compare the values of spinors at different
 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A precise picture of a spinor field is provided by the construction of a
 vector bundle (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Connections-on-bundles}

\end_inset

).
 We consider a 
\series bold
spinor bundle
\series default
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{spinor bundle}

\end_inset

with the spacetime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as the base and the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as the fiber.
 Thus, we would like to have a separate copy of the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 A spinor field is defined
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Standard
We ignore possible topological difficulties with the construction of a spinor
 bundle for a given base manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The spinor bundle exists for all physically relevant spacetimes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a (smooth) section of the spinor bundle; thus, the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a spinor belonging to the copy 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p)$
\end_inset

 of the spinor space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we constructed the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 through the Minkowski metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\equiv\textrm{diag}(1,-1,-1,-1)$
\end_inset

.
 However, we now need to assign a spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p)$
\end_inset

 to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a curved spacetime where the Minkowski metric is replaced by a general
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-dependent metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we need to modify the construction of the spinor space, so that
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and the antisymmetric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

 are compatible with the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)$
\end_inset

 at each point.
 This is achieved by the following construction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set of four vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(\mathbf{e}_{j},\mathbf{e}_{k})\equiv g_{\mu\nu}e_{j}^{\mu}e_{k}^{\nu}=\eta_{jk},\label{eq:tetrad ortho}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is defined above as a standard, fixed matrix representing the ``fiducial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Minkowski metric.
 These four vectors obviously form a basis in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, and such a basis is called an 
\series bold
orthonormal tetrad
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{tetrad}

\end_inset

We can always choose such a tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 in some neighborhood of any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can also be viewed as a map from an auxiliary Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 to the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, whereby a 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 is mapped into the spacetime vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\equiv\sum_{j=0}^{3}\mathbf{e}_{j}x_{j}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 To contrast 4-vectors and 4-tensors in the fiducial Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 with vectors and tensors defined through tangent spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 in the actual curved spacetime, the latter are sometimes called 
\series bold
world vectors
\series default
 and 
\series bold
world tensors
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{world tensor}

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a basis, we obtain a 1-to-1 correspondence between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

; it is easy to see that the inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\rightarrow\left(x_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\equiv g(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{e}_{j}(p))$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction of spinors at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a curved spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 uses the fixed, Minkowski-space matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{(M)}\equiv\sigma_{AB'}^{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 We define the modified map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}(p):S\otimes\bar{S}\rightarrow T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 by using a tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 which maps the result of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{(M)}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\tilde{\sigma}}(h^{AB'})=\sum_{j=0}^{3}\sigma_{AB'}^{j}h^{AB'}\mathbf{e}_{j}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}.\]

\end_inset

This defines the curved-spacetime map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}}(p)$
\end_inset

 which can be thought of a world-vector-valued spinorial 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\bar{1}\right)$
\end_inset

-tensor,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}_{AB'}(p)\equiv\sum_{j=0}^{3}\sigma_{AB'}^{j}\mathbf{e}_{j}(p);\quad\tilde{\sigma}_{AB'}^{\mu}\equiv\sum_{j=0}^{3}\sigma_{AB'}^{j}e_{j}^{\mu}.\]

\end_inset

Due to the defining property\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:tetrad ortho}

\end_inset

) of a tetrad, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
g_{\mu\nu}(p)\tilde{\sigma}_{AA'}^{\mu}(p)\tilde{\sigma}_{BB'}^{\nu}(p) & =\sum_{j,k=0}^{3}g_{\mu\nu}(p)e_{j}^{\mu}(p)\sigma_{AA'}^{j}e_{k}^{\mu}(p)\sigma_{BB'}^{k}\\
 & =\sum_{j,k=0}^{3}\eta_{jk}\sigma_{AA'}^{j}\sigma_{BB'}^{k}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, the spinorial 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

 automatically satisfies the property analogous to Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:g sigma sigma e e}

\end_inset

) at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}(p)\tilde{\sigma}_{AA'}^{\mu}(p)\tilde{\sigma}_{BB'}^{\nu}(p)=\frac{1}{2}\varepsilon_{AB}\varepsilon_{A'B'}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the definition of the spinor spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p)$
\end_inset

 involves an arbitrary choice of an orthonormal tetrad 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Different choices of the tetrad are related to teach other with Lorentz
 transformations.
 (For any two orthonormal tetrads 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{j}^{\prime}\right\} $
\end_inset

, there exists a unique Lorentz transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}\mathbf{e}_{j}=\mathbf{e}_{j}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.) The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

 and the 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

 are invariant under Lorentz transformations.
 Thus, any Lorentz-invariant spinorial expression, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}g^{AA'BB'}$
\end_inset

, will be mapped into a world scalar, independently of the choice of the
 tetrad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remark: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since spinors are not defined directly through points of the manifold, there
 is no concept of arbitrary pointwise transformations (diffeomorphisms)
 directly applied to spinor fields! The only transformations that apply
 to spinors are Lorentz transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{s}$
\end_inset

 within the spinor space.
 Thus one cannot define the change in a spinor field due to the flow of
 an arbitrary vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

; in other words, the Lie derivative ``
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{v}}\psi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a spinor with respect to a vector is undefined.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
Unless the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a conformal Killing vector for the metric.
 See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{PeRi88a}

\end_inset

, vol.\InsetSpace ~
2, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
S 
\end_layout

\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
6.6.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 However, this does not mean that the presence of spinors in a theory violates
 general covariance.
 General point transformations 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 be applied to the tetrad vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and thus effectively change the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

, which is the only connection between the spinor space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Field theories involving spinors can be formulated in terms of Lorentz
 invariants in the spinor space, and invariants involving the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

 and the world metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and then these theories are generally covariant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Covariant derivative on spinors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 (but not any other connection, see below!) can be uniquely extended to
 a covariant derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\psi$
\end_inset

 on spinor fields.
 In addition to the usual properties (linearity, Leibnitz rule, torsion-freeness
), the Levi-Civita connection satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\bar{\psi} & =\overline{\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\psi},\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\varepsilon_{AB} & =\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\varepsilon^{AB}=0,\\
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\hat{\sigma} & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Naturally, the gradient operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is also equivalent to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\bar{1}\right)$
\end_inset

-tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{AA'}$
\end_inset

 in the spinor space,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\equiv v^{\mu}\nabla_{\mu}\equiv v^{\mu}\sigma_{\mu}^{AA'}\nabla_{AA'}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps, it appears strange that such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operations as the coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 cannot be defined on spinor fields.
 One way to explain the fact that only the Levi-Civita connection is defined
 on spinors is to consider the flag field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n}_{\psi},F_{\psi}\right)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to a spinor field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we attempt to define a parallelly transported spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 using some connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parallelly transported along a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\mathbf{v}}\psi^{A}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we expect that the flag 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n}_{\psi},F_{\psi}\right)$
\end_inset

 should also be parallelly transported along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the basic properties (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:flag property 1}

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:flag property 2}

\end_inset

) of a flag (the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 should be null, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 should be transverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\psi}$
\end_inset

, etc.) involve the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Unless the connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, a parallelly transported flag will fail to remain a valid flag; for instance,
 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 may fail to remain null, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 may fail to remain transverse to
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}_{\psi}$
\end_inset


\series default
, etc.
 Only the metric-compatible (Levi-Civita) connection guarantees that the
 pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{n}_{\psi},F_{\psi}\right)$
\end_inset

 will remain a valid flag after an arbitrary parallel transport.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another argument is based on the concept of associated bundles.
 The spinor bundle is associated to the gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

, which is essentially equivalent to the Lorentz group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3,1)$
\end_inset

.
 The Levi-Civita connection 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is the gauge-invariant connection with respect to the gauge group, because
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the metric (see Sec.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Tangent-bundle-as}

\end_inset

).
 No other connection is admissible in the associated bundle.
 Thus, no other connection can be defined on spinors.
\end_layout

