\begin_layout Subsection
Maxwell equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electromagnetic field corresponds to a particle of spin 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and is described by a 2-form 
\begin_inset Formula $F=dA$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 1-form representing the electromagnetic potential.
 In the index notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the antisymmetric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 We have seen that such a tensor can be reduced to a symmetric spinorial
 tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{AB}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\phi^{AB} & =\frac{1}{2}\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}F^{AA'BB'},\\
F^{AA'BB'} & =\phi^{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}+\varepsilon^{AB}\bar{\phi}^{A'B'}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now we shall show that the Maxwell equations can be written concisely in
 terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{AB}$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla_{AA'}\phi^{AB}=\frac{1}{2}\bar{\varepsilon}_{A'B'}j^{BB'},\label{eq:maxwell phi}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{BB'}\equiv j^{\mu}\sigma_{\mu}^{BB'}$
\end_inset

 is the spinorial version of the familiar charge 4-current 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mu}\equiv\left(\rho,\vec{j}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to define the Hodge dual
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Hodge star}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}F$
\end_inset

 which is again a 2-form, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
^{*}F^{\mu\nu}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\varepsilon^{\kappa\lambda\mu\nu}F_{\kappa\lambda},\]

\end_inset

and to rewrite the Maxwell equations equivalently as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\nabla_{\mu}F^{\mu\nu} & =j^{\nu},\\
\nabla_{\mu}\left(^{*}F^{\mu\nu}\right) & =0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

(The last equation is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{[\lambda}F^{\mu\nu]}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $dF=0$
\end_inset

, which is a consequence of the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $ddA=0$
\end_inset

, which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $F=dA$
\end_inset

