\begin_inset Formula \[
F^{AA'BB'}+i\left(*F\right)^{AA'BB'}=2\phi^{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}.\]

\end_inset

Then, the Maxwell equations are equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
j^{\nu} & =\nabla_{\mu}(F^{\mu\nu}+i*F^{\mu\nu})=2\nabla_{AA'}\left(\phi^{AB}\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'}\right)\\
 & =2\left(\nabla_{AA'}\phi^{AB}\right)\bar{\varepsilon}^{A'B'},\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varepsilon}_{B'C'}$
\end_inset

, we find that Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:maxwell phi}

\end_inset

) is equivalent to the Maxwell equations.
\end_layout

