How 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 to learn tensor calculus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This brief chapter is intended as a consolation to those students who have
 difficulty learning tensor calculus from some GR textbooks.
 Almost every explanation here (except for trivial statements) is flawed
 in one way or another, even though all the equations are formally correct.
 Because of this, a beginning student might become thoroughly confused and
 frustrated when trying to understand this material.
 However, the fault is with the explanations and not with the student! Better
 explanations are given elsewhere in this book.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tensor algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letters with Greek indices, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, denote arrays of numbers, and indices run over 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of space.
 For brevity, we shall always use the 
\series bold
Einstein summation convention
\series default
: we omit the sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

 but 
\emph on
always
\emph default
 imply summation when an index is repeated in an expression, which must
 occur once as an upper index and once as a lower index.
 For example, we write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\alpha}B^{\alpha}C_{\beta\gamma}D^{\beta}\equiv\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N}\sum_{\beta=1}^{N}A_{\alpha}B^{\alpha}C_{\beta\gamma}D^{\beta}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Levi-Civita symbol
\series default
 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{123...N}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\alpha...\lambda\mu....\rho}=-\varepsilon_{\alpha...\mu\lambda....\rho}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\alpha...\rho}$
\end_inset

 is totally antisymmetric in all the indices.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{123}=\varepsilon_{231}=\varepsilon_{321}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{132}=\varepsilon_{213}=\varepsilon_{312}=-1$
\end_inset

, and all the other components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\alpha\beta\gamma}$
\end_inset

 are equal to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Kronecker symbol
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\alpha\beta}=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\alpha\beta}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\neq\beta$
\end_inset

.
 This symbol represents an identity matrix of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes, the Kronecker symbol is also written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to see that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\varepsilon_{\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{N}}\varepsilon^{\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{N}} & =N!,\\
\varepsilon_{\lambda\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{N-1}}\varepsilon^{\mu\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{N-1}} & =\left(N-1\right)!\delta_{\lambda}^{\mu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
determinant
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 of a square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the number defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\det A^{\alpha\beta}=\frac{1}{N!}\varepsilon_{\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{N}}\varepsilon_{\beta_{N}...\beta_{N}}A^{\alpha_{1}\beta_{1}}...A^{\alpha_{N}\beta_{N}},\]

\end_inset

where the right-hand side contains 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that the determinant of the product of two matrices is
 equal to the product of their determinants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\series bold
contravariant vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is an array of quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v^{1},...,v^{N}\right)$
\end_inset

 called 
\series bold
components
\series default
 that transform under a change of basis according to the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{v}^{\mu}=v^{\nu}\left(S^{-1}\right)_{\nu}^{\mu},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix describing the change of basis,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
e_{j}^{\mu}\rightarrow\tilde{e}_{j}^{\mu}=S_{j}^{k}e_{k}^{\mu},\label{eq:basis change}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse matrix.
 Here, a 
\series bold
basis
\series default
 is a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 contravariant vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{1}^{\mu},...,e_{N}^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that the determinant of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 Such a matrix is called 
\series bold
nondegenerate
\series default
.
 Since the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate, any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 can be uniquely decomposed as a linear combination of basis vectors:
\begin_inset Formula \[
v^{\mu}=v^{j}e_{j}^{\mu}.\]

\end_inset

This is why the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1,...,N$
\end_inset

) are called the 
\series bold
components
\series default
 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 By convention, a 
\emph on
superscript
\emph default
 index is used for contravariant vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
metric
\series default
 is a nondegenerate symmetric matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}=g_{\nu\mu}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det g_{\mu\nu}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The scalar product of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}u^{\mu}v^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and can be written for brevity as
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}u^{\mu}v^{\nu}\equiv u^{\mu}v_{\mu},\]

\end_inset

where the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
covariant components
\series default
 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Covariant components transform under a change of basis as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{v}_{\mu}=S_{\mu}^{\nu}v_{\mu};\]

\end_inset

that is, they transform in the same way as the basis vectors do [Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:basis change}

\end_inset

)].
 Such vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
covariant
\series default
 
\series bold
vectors
\series default
 or 
\series bold
covectors
\series default
 and are written with a 
\emph on
subscript
\emph default
 index 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Then, in every expression there can be only one pair of repeated indices,
 one subscript and one superscript, in agreement with the Einstein summation
 convention.
 An expression violating this rule, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mu}b_{\mu}c^{\nu}$
\end_inset

, is written incorrectly, while 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mu}b^{\mu}c^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be used to transform contravariant components into covariant ones,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mu}=g_{\mu\nu}v^{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 This operation is called 
\series bold
lowering the index
\series default
.
 Likewise, the inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be used to 
\series bold
raise the index
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}=g^{\mu\nu}v_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Since raising an index after that index has been lowered should result
 in the same vector, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\mu\nu}g^{\lambda\nu}=\delta_{\mu}^{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
tensor
\series default
 is a set of components with several indices, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

, that transforms under a change of basis\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:basis change}

\end_inset

) as a suitable product of components of covariant and contravariant vectors.
 For example, a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 transforms as the product 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}v^{\beta}w_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
according to the formula
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{A}_{\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}=S_{\gamma}^{\nu}\left(S^{-1}\right)_{\lambda}^{\alpha}\left(S^{-1}\right)_{\mu}^{\beta}A_{\nu}^{\lambda\mu}.\]

\end_inset

This tensor is said to have 
\series bold
rank
\series default
 (2,1).
 Tensors of any rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m,n\right)$
\end_inset

 are defined in this way; contravariant and covariant vectors are tensors
 of rank (1,0) and (0,1) respectively.
 It is clear that only tensors of equal rank can be added; for example,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}+u_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 does not transform as a vector and is therefore incorrect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}v^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is not the same tensor as 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\beta}v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, but of course 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\alpha}v^{\beta}=v^{\beta}v^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\alpha}v^{\beta}=v^{\beta}u^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tensor calculus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we considered vectors and tensors in Euclidean coordinates, but now
 we need to consider arbitrary, curvilinear coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 itself is not a vector any more because the coordinates are not rectangular.
 However, an infinitesimal displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
 To verify this, we consider an arbitrary change of coordinates described
 by arbitrary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{\mu}(x^{\nu})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
x^{\mu}\rightarrow\tilde{x}^{\mu}=\tilde{x}^{\mu}(x^{\nu}).\]

\end_inset

Then the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 transforms as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\tilde{x}^{\mu}=\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}\delta x^{\nu},\]

\end_inset

which is the correct transformation law for a vector under a change of basis\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:basis change}

\end_inset

) with the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}^{\mu}=\partial x^{\mu}/\partial\tilde{x}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is an example of a 
\series bold
contravariant vector field
\series default
, that is, a set of components 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}(x^{\nu})$
\end_inset

 depending on the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 that transform under an arbitrary change of coordinates as components of
 a contravariant vector,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{v}^{\mu}=\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}v^{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
covariant vector field
\series default
 transforms as components of a covariant vector.
 Analogously, a 
\series bold
tensor field of rank
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined as a set of components 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{p}}{}_{\beta_{1}...\beta_{q}}$
\end_inset

 that transform under a change of coordinates as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{T}^{\alpha_{1}...\alpha_{p}}{}_{\beta_{1}...\beta_{q}}=\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\alpha_{1}}}{\partial x^{\lambda_{1}}}...\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\alpha_{p}}}{\partial x^{\lambda_{p}}}\frac{\partial x^{\mu_{1}}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{\beta_{1}}}...\frac{\partial x^{\mu_{q}}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{\beta_{q}}}T^{\lambda_{1}...\lambda_{p}}{}_{\mu_{1}...\mu_{q}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important operation of tensor calculus is the covariant derivative.
 First, observe that a partial derivative of a contravariant vector field,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}{}_{,\nu}\equiv\partial v^{\mu}/\partial x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 does not transform as a tensor of rank (1,1).
 To get a derivative that transforms correctly, one adds a suitable 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term and thus defines the 
\series bold
covariant derivative
\series default

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v^{\mu}{}_{;\nu}\equiv\frac{\partial v^{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}+\Gamma_{\alpha\nu}^{\mu}v^{\alpha},\label{eq:covariant der gamma}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the set of quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
Christoffel symbol
\series default
.
 It can be verified by a direct calculation that the covariant derivative
 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}{}_{;\nu}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:covariant der gamma}

\end_inset

) transforms as a tensor of rank (1,1) as long as the Christoffel symbol
 transforms as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}=\tilde{\Gamma}_{\nu\rho}^{\mu}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\nu}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\rho}}{\partial x^{\beta}}\frac{\partial x^{\lambda}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{\mu}}+\frac{\partial^{2}x^{\lambda}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{\nu}\partial\tilde{x}^{\rho}}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\nu}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{\rho}}{\partial x^{\beta}}.\label{eq:Christoffel transform}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, we require that the transformation law\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Christoffel transform}

\end_inset

) holds for the Christoffel symbol.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is not a tensor, and a suitable change of coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} \rightarrow\left\{ \tilde{x}^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can make 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

 at any point.
 Such coordinates are called an 
\series bold
inertial coordinate system
\series default
 at that point.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}-\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor because the second term in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Christoffel transform}

\end_inset

) drops out when we write the transformation law for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}-\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}-\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 vanishes in a locally inertial coordinate system, it vanishes in all coordinate
 systems, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha,\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As shown in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:covariant der gamma}

\end_inset

), the covariant derivative is denoted by a semicolon and an index.
 The covariant derivative of a 
\emph on
covariant
\emph default
 vector is defined similarly by
\begin_inset Formula \[
v_{\mu;\nu}=\frac{\partial v_{\mu}}{\partial x^{\nu}}-\Gamma_{\mu\nu}^{\lambda}v_{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset

Then it can be shown that the covariant derivative of the scalar product
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mu}b^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the ordinary derivative, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(a_{\mu}b^{\mu}\right)_{;\alpha}=a_{\mu;\alpha}b^{\mu}+a_{\mu}b^{\mu}{}_{;\alpha}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\left(a_{\mu}b^{\mu}\right).\]

\end_inset

This is, of course, to be expected for a scalar quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mu}b^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since tensors are quantities that transform as products of vectors and covectors
, the covariant derivative can be defined on arbitrary tensors in a similar
 way.
 For each upper index there is a term with 
\begin_inset Formula $+\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, and for each lower index a term with 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
\begin_inset Formula \[
A_{\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}{}_{;\mu}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}A_{\gamma}^{\alpha\beta}+\Gamma_{\mu\nu}^{\alpha}A_{\gamma}^{\nu\beta}+\Gamma_{\mu\nu}^{\beta}A_{\gamma}^{\alpha\nu}-\Gamma_{\gamma\mu}^{\nu}A_{\nu}^{\alpha\beta}.\]

\end_inset

Then one can prove that the Leibnitz rule holds for arbitrary tensors,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(A^{\alpha\beta...}B^{\gamma\delta...}\right)_{;\mu}=A^{\alpha\beta...}{}_{;\mu}B^{\gamma\delta...}+A^{\alpha\beta...}B^{\gamma\delta...}{}_{;\mu}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In General Relativity, one uses the Christoffel symbol of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\alpha\nu}^{\mu}=\frac{1}{2}g^{\mu\beta}\left(g_{\alpha\beta,\nu}+g_{\nu\beta,\alpha}-g_{\alpha\nu,\beta}\right).\label{eq:Gamma def 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression can be derived from the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}=\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 To derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gamma def 2}

\end_inset

), let us first prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu;\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

.
 For any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}X^{\beta}=X_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, hence
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{\alpha\beta}\left(A^{\beta}\right)_{;\lambda}=\left(A_{\alpha}\right)_{;\lambda}\label{eq:derivative g sneaky}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and therefore
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left(g_{\alpha\beta}A^{\beta}\right)_{;\lambda} & =g_{\alpha\beta;\lambda}A^{\beta}+g_{\alpha\beta}\left(A^{\beta}\right)_{;\lambda}\\
\Rightarrow & \quad g_{\alpha\beta;\lambda}A^{\beta}=0.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The required property 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta;\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

 follows since 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary vector.
 Then it is a matter of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

juggling the indices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to derive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gamma def 2}

\end_inset

).
 Namely, we write
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=g_{\alpha\beta;\lambda}=g_{\alpha\beta,\lambda}-\Gamma_{\alpha\lambda}^{\mu}g_{\beta\mu}-\Gamma_{\beta\lambda}^{\mu}g_{\alpha\mu},\]

\end_inset

then exchange indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\lambda$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
0 & =g_{\alpha\lambda,\beta}-\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\mu}g_{\lambda\mu}-\Gamma_{\beta\lambda}^{\mu}g_{\alpha\mu},\\
0 & =g_{\lambda\beta,\alpha}-\Gamma_{\alpha\lambda}^{\mu}g_{\beta\mu}-\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\mu}g_{\lambda\mu}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

Adding the above two equations and subtracting the initial one, we obtain
 Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Gamma def 2}

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Riemann tensor
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\lambda\rho\sigma}^{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covariant derivative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the Christoffel symbol as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{\lambda\rho\sigma}^{\kappa}=\partial_{\rho}\Gamma_{\lambda\sigma}^{\kappa}-\partial_{\sigma}\Gamma_{\rho\lambda}^{\kappa}+\Gamma_{\nu\rho}^{\kappa}\Gamma_{\sigma\lambda}^{\nu}-\Gamma_{\nu\sigma}^{\kappa}\Gamma_{\lambda\rho}^{\nu}.\]

\end_inset

It is easy to check that this formula defines a tensor (despite 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 not being a tensor), because one can notice that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R_{\lambda\rho\sigma}^{\kappa}u^{\sigma}=\nabla_{\rho}\nabla_{\lambda}u^{\kappa}-\nabla_{\lambda}\nabla_{\rho}u^{\kappa},\label{eq:Riemann nabla nabla 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\lambda\rho\sigma}^{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 is manifestly a tensor.
 In flat space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\lambda}\equiv\partial_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\lambda\rho\sigma}^{\kappa}=0$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\lambda}\partial_{\mu}=\partial_{\mu}\partial_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, I give you some hints as to why the preceding explanations
 are flawed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levi-Civita symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is not merely a collection of numbers 0, 1, and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, arranged in a special way, but is interpreted as an antisymmetric tensor
 or a volume 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-form.
 The Kronecker symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix representing an identity transformation (in any basis), while
 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 represents (in an orthogonal basis) a bilinear form that may represent
 a scalar product in a Euclidean space.
 Determinants of matrices are not simply some complicated combinations of
 matrix elements.
 Determinants have a direct geometric meaning; for instance, the oriented
 volume of the image of the unit cube under a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\det T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors are most clearly seen as geometric quantities --- elements of vector
 spaces, rather than collections of components that mysteriously 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transform themselves under a change of basis.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Bases are maximal sets of linearly independent vectors, and the components
 of a vector are coefficients relative to a chosen basis.
 It is easier to regard the transformation formulas for components as consequenc
es of the geometric picture rather than as definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Covariant vectors are better seen as vectors from a 
\emph on
different
\emph default
 vector space (the dual space), rather than as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

different kind of components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the same vector.
 There is no natural map between contravariant and covariant vectors unless
 a metric is given; and when several metrics are given, there are several
 such maps.
 The idea that there exist 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covariant components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of vectors can be justified only if a metric is fixed once and for all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is either 
\emph on
defined
\emph default
 as the inverse matrix to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

, or is derived through the dual basis (in the dual space).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A tensor is an element of a tensor space (the space of tensor products and
 their linear combinations).
 As in the case of vectors, the components of a tensor with respect to a
 basis can be defined after the tensor space is defined.
 Then the complicated transformation law for the components will be a natural
 consequence of the construction, rather than a definition of a tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitesimal displacement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a heuristic representation of a tangent vector: one imagines that a
