\begin_layout Standard
A covariant derivative is not simply an old derivative with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 added to it, but rather the only type of directional derivative that can
 be meaningfully considered as a geometric object in a curved space.
 (The coordinate derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial v^{\mu}/\partial x^{\nu}\equiv v^{\mu}{}_{,\nu}$
\end_inset

 does not exist as a geometric object since it depends on the coordinate
 system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset

.) However, there exist infinitely many possible covariant derivatives since
 there are infinitely many possible 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Christoffel symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 cannot be set to zero by a change of coordinates unless 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}\equiv\Gamma_{\alpha\beta}^{\lambda}-\Gamma_{\beta\alpha}^{\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

