\begin_layout Standard
Suppose such a smooth map exists and maps the north pole 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 into a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a very small circle around the north pole.
 Since the chart provides a smooth one-to-one map, this circle will be mapped
 into a small 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

image
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 circle around 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The circle around the north pole can be smoothly contracted into a point
 in two essentially different ways: either by contracting it to the north
 pole, or by shifting it around the sphere towards the south pole and contractin
g to the south pole, without ever crossing the north pole.
 These deformations of the circle are, by assumption, smoothly mapped into
 corresponding deformations of the image circle in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 During the second deformation, the image circle around 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is supposedly contracted into a point without ever crossing 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 But such a deformation is obviously impossible within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the assumption that a smooth one-to-one map 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 exists.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{par:Exercise:chain rule}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-chain-rule}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A smooth function can be approximated arbitrarily precisely by a polynomial,
 and it is technically convenient to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial,
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(z)=\sum_{m=0}^{m_{\max}}\frac{1}{m!}z^{m}\left.\frac{d^{(m)}f}{dz^{m}}\right|_{z=0}.\]

\end_inset

Since derivations are linear maps by Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:linearity}

\end_inset

), it is sufficient to prove the statement for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0,1,2,..$
\end_inset

.
 By Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:derivative of const}

\end_inset

), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\circ1=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is trivial to check the statement for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z$
\end_inset

.
 Now use induction in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z$
\end_inset

.
 Once the statement is proved for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{m-1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{v}\circ\left(g^{m-1}\right)=\left(m-1\right)g^{m-2}\mathbf{v}\circ g.\]

\end_inset

Now we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{m}$
\end_inset

 and use Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Leibnitz rule}

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}\circ f(g) & =\mathbf{v}\circ\left(gg^{m-1}\right)=\left(\mathbf{v}\circ g\right)g^{m-1}+g\mathbf{v}\circ(g^{m-1})\\
 & =mg^{m-1}\mathbf{v}\circ g,\end{align*}

\end_inset

 thus the statement is proved for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{m}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Proof of Statement\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{par:Statement-:commutator-func}

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Proof-of-Statement:commutator-func}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 necessary to introduce a local coordinate system around 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Introduce the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 as in Fig.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Vector-commutator}

\end_inset

.
 By definition of a tangent vector and its orbits, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\left(\mathbf{a}\circ f\right)\right|_{p_{0}}=\lim_{\delta\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{f(p_{1})-f(p_{0})}{\delta\tau},\label{eq:a circ f 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

because the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by following the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 for an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau$
\end_inset

, while the right-hand side of Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a circ f 1}

\end_inset

) is the definition of the directional derivative along the orbit.
 The relation\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a circ f 1}

\end_inset

) holds for every function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, so let us apply it to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\circ f$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\left(\mathbf{a}\circ\left(\mathbf{b}\circ f\right)\right)\right|_{p_{0}}=\lim_{\delta\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{\delta\tau}\left(\mathbf{b}\circ f(p_{1})-\mathbf{b}\circ f(p_{0})\right).\label{eq:a circ b circ f 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We now need to express the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\circ f$
\end_inset

 similarly,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left.\left(\mathbf{b}\circ f\right)\right|_{p_{1}} & =\lim_{\delta\tau'\rightarrow0}\frac{f(p)-f(p_{1})}{\delta\tau'},\\
\left.\left(\mathbf{b}\circ f\right)\right|_{p_{0}} & =\lim_{\delta\tau'\rightarrow0}\frac{f(p_{2})-f(p_{0})}{\delta\tau'},\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we introduced a different variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\tau'$
\end_inset

 for convenience.
 Substituting this into Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a circ b circ f 1}

\end_inset

), we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\left(\mathbf{a}\circ\left(\mathbf{b}\circ f\right)\right)\right|_{p_{0}}=\lim_{\begin{array}{c}
\delta\tau\rightarrow0\\
\delta\tau'\rightarrow0\end{array}}\frac{f(p)-f(p_{1})-f(p_{2})+f(p_{0})}{\delta\tau\,\delta\tau'}.\]

\end_inset

Similarly, using the analogous relation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\left(\mathbf{a}\circ f\right)\right|_{p_{2}}=\lim_{\delta\tau\rightarrow0}\frac{f(p')-f(p_{2})}{\delta\tau},\]

\end_inset

we find 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\left(\mathbf{b}\circ\left(\mathbf{a}\circ f\right)\right)\right|_{p_{0}}=\lim_{\begin{array}{c}
\delta\tau\rightarrow0\\
\delta\tau'\rightarrow0\end{array}}\frac{f(p')-f(p_{2})-f(p_{1})+f(p_{0})}{\delta\tau\,\delta\tau'}.\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\left(\left[\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\right]\circ f\right)\right|_{p_{0}}=\lim_{\begin{array}{c}
\delta\tau\rightarrow0\\
\delta\tau'\rightarrow0\end{array}}\frac{f(p)-f(p')}{\delta\tau\,\delta\tau'},\]

\end_inset

as required.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

