\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{par:Statement-exist-connecting-basis}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Proof-of-Statement-exist-connecting-basis}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may complete the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}(p_{0})\neq0$
\end_inset

 to an arbitrary basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}(p_{0}),\mathbf{c}_{1}(p_{0}),\mathbf{c}_{2}(p_{0}),...\right\} $
\end_inset

 at the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v},\mathbf{c}_{j}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 is a first-order differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}$
\end_inset

 that has a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

 along one orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 starting from the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, at least in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this explicitly, consider the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 in a local coordinate system, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{\alpha}c^{\alpha}\frac{\partial v^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}-\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial c^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}=0.\]

\end_inset

Consider one orbit 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\equiv\dot{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}$
\end_inset

 is the tangent vector to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 For points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 on the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, the second term above is equal to the derivative of the component 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 along this orbit,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\sum_{\alpha}v^{\alpha}\frac{\partial c^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}}\right|_{p}=\frac{d}{d\tau}c^{\beta}(\tau),\]

\end_inset

assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(\tau)=p$
\end_inset

.
 So the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{c},\mathbf{v}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{d\tau}c^{\beta}=\sum_{\alpha}c^{\alpha}\frac{\partial v^{\beta}}{\partial x^{\alpha}},\]

\end_inset

which is an ordinary differential equation for the unknown components 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\beta}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, to be solved with an initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\beta}(\tau_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 This differential equation has a unique solution (by assumption, the vector
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is smooth everywhere).
 Thus we can in principle compute the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is any point along one orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 The set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v}(p),\mathbf{c}_{1}(p),...,\mathbf{c}_{n-1}(p)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly independent at the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 and will remain linearly independent along the orbit at least in some neighborh
ood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We can prove this by noting that linear independence of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{v},\mathbf{c}_{1},...,\mathbf{c}_{n-1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be verified by computing the determinant of their components in a local
 coordinate system.
 The vectors form a basis iff the determinant is nonzero.
 By assumption, the determinant is nonzero at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the determinant is a smooth function along the orbit.
 Thus the determinant remains nonzero along the orbit at least in some neighborh
ood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 (perhaps in a very small neighborhood, but that is all we need presently).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we obtained a basis of connecting vectors along one orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

