\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have obtained a basis of connecting fields 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
, in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Proof of Statement 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{sub:Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset

:
\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-multivectors}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(a)
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},...,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be a basis in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

; we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is either equal to zero, or proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 with a nonzero coefficient.
 It will follow that any two 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-vectors are proportional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent.
 This follows from the antisymmetry of the exterior product: suppose
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}_{n}=\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}\lambda_{j}\mathbf{a}_{j},\]

\end_inset

where some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 are nonzero.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n-1}\wedge\mathbf{a}_{j}=0\quad\textrm{for}\, j=1,...,n-1,\]

\end_inset

we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}=\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n-1}\wedge\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}\lambda_{j}\mathbf{a}_{j}=0.\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 Then every basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with some coefficients,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{e}_{k}=\sum_{j}A_{kj}\mathbf{a}_{j}.\]

\end_inset

Let us now substitute these linear combinations into the nonzero multivector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

, and simplify the resulting expression using the linearity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

.
 The result will be a sum of terms of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j_{1}}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{j_{n}}$
\end_inset

 with some coefficients.
 Only the terms with all different 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{k}$
\end_inset

 will survive.
 Finally, we can reorder the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 at will (and if necessary change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

), so eventually we will obtain simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 with a nonzero coefficient.
 Therefore, the multivectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are proportional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(b)
\series default
 We need to show that the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional volumes,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{a}_{1},...,\mathbf{a}_{n}\right)=\textrm{Vol}\left(\mathbf{b}_{1},...,\mathbf{b}_{n}\right),\]

\end_inset

 is equivalent to the relation between multivectors
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}=\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}.\]

\end_inset

It is sufficient to consider the case when all the volumes involved are
 nonzero.
 By part 
\series bold
(a)
\series default
, the two multivectors are always proportional with 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 nonzero coefficient; denote that coefficient by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that the volumes are related by the same factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show this, we will transform the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 into the parallelepiped spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{b}_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The transformation will be performed through a sequence of steps which
 preserve the relationship between the volume of the parallelepiped and
 the multivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Each step will either multiply both the volume and the multivector by the
 same number, or leave them both unchanged.
 At the end, the multivector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 will be transformed into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}\wedge...\wedge\mathbf{b}_{n}$
\end_inset

; hence, the volumes are related by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, which will prove the statement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allowed steps of the transformation are of three kinds: (i) adding a
 multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{a}_{i}\rightarrow\mathbf{a}_{i}+\alpha\mathbf{a}_{j},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\neq0$
\end_inset

 is some number; (ii) stretching a vector 
