\emph on
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{par:Proof-of-Statement-measure-Riemann}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to lift the restrictions on the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric bilinear form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 This bilinear form can be determined for spacelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 by a finite number of values (say, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 being vectors of a spacelike basis).
 The requirement that vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 be spacelike and orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is then easily lifted since 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},...)$
\end_inset

 is linear and antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x}+\lambda\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y}+\mu\mathbf{v})\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can deduce 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequently, we can regard 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 as a quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})\equiv R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y}).\label{eq:Q x y def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 A standard trick in linear algebra is to recover a symmetric bilinear form
 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 if the quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is known:
\begin_inset Formula \[
A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\frac{A(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b},\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b})-A(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{a})-A(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{b})}{2}.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, we can try to recover a symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 from the quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\equiv & \frac{1}{2}\left(R(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})-R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})\right).\label{eq:finding Q x y a b}\end{align}

\end_inset

To recover 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 completely, it suffices to know the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

; in total, we need 10 different values (for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

).
 However, we are allowed to measure only 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 for future-directed and timelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 We note that the sum of two such vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}+\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

, is again future-directed and timelike.
 So we may deduce 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 for any two future-directed, timelike 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:finding Q x y a b}

\end_inset

).
 We also note that a basis in the four-dimensional space can be found as
 a linearly independent set of 4 future-directed, timelike vectors.
 Such a basis will not be orthogonal, but one does not need an orthogonal
 basis to determine a bilinear form.
 Hence, for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 can be determined by finitely many measurements.
 This process needs to be repeated for 10 different combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We are thus able to deduce the values 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 for 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 if we measure 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for sufficiently many future-directed timelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and spacelike vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 (each time orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we recovered the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

, which is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and also in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Despite the suggestive Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Q x y def}

\end_inset

), we must note that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})\neq R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 as a bilinear form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 This bilinear form is not necessarily symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 In general, this bilinear form has a symmetric part,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{2}\left(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})+R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})\right),\]

\end_inset

and an antisymmetric part, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{2}\left(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})-R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})\right).\]

\end_inset

 The quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 is defined through Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Q x y def}

\end_inset

) and knows only about the symmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(...)$
\end_inset

 as shown above.
 Therefore, we recover precisely the symmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(...)$
\end_inset

 when we determine the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

 is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 through symmetrization in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\frac{1}{2}\left(R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})+R(\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})\right).\label{eq:Qxy Raxby}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 To recover the full Riemann tensor, it remains to extract the antisymmetric
 part.
 A property of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 not yet used is the first Bianchi identity\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bianchi 1}

\end_inset

), which we apply to the last term in Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Qxy Raxby}

\end_inset

) and obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
2Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})-R(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y})-R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\\
 & =-2R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{b})+R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x}).\end{align*}

\end_inset

We now need to express this somehow through 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Note that a suitable combination is
\begin_inset Formula \[
2Q_{\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})=R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{x})+R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{b}).\]

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
2Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) & =-3R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y},\mathbf{b})+2Q_{\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y});\\
R(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{x},\mathbf{b},\mathbf{y}) & =\frac{2}{3}\left(Q_{\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})-Q_{\mathbf{b},\mathbf{x}}(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{y})\right).\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus all the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(...)$
\end_inset

 can be deduced from the given experimental data.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

