\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be an orthonormal basis and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the corresponding dual basis.
 Since the Hodge duality map 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\mapsto*\omega$
\end_inset

 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, it suffices to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\chi_{1}\wedge...\wedge\chi_{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{j}$
\end_inset

 are some 1-forms.
 Moreover, it is sufficient to consider the case when all 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{j}$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
basis
\emph default
 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Further, it is sufficient to treat the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{n}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we only need to consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and the fact that
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{n}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{1}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n}\right)=1\]

\end_inset

is (up to permutations) the only nonzero expression of the type 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{a}}\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{b}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{c}}\left(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n}\right),\]

\end_inset

 we can compute 
\begin_inset Formula $**\omega$
\end_inset

 explicitly:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
*\omega & =*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n})=\eta^{11}...\eta^{nn}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{n}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{1}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)\\
 & =\eta^{11}...\eta^{nn}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n+1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{N};\\
**\omega & =*(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{n+1}\wedge...\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{N})\eta^{11}...\eta^{nn}\\
 & =\eta^{11}...\eta^{NN}\left(\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{N}}...\iota_{\mathbf{e}_{n+1}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\right)=(\det\eta_{ab})\left(-1\right)^{\left(N-n\right)n}\omega.\end{align*}

\end_inset

The sign factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1\right)^{(N-n)n}$
\end_inset

 appears in the identity
