\begin_layout Standard
The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

 can be guessed in the following way.
 One notes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

 should be a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

, with some indices permuted.
 Due to the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

, there are only three possible permutations (namely with either 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 as the first index).
 Moreover, the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 means that the only possibility is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\chi_{a\, bc}=\left(A_{a\, bc}-A_{b\, ac}\right)\lambda+A_{c\, ab}\mu,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\mu$
\end_inset

 are unknown constants.
 A direct substitution then yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-\mu=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to show that this solution is unique.
 Suppose there exist two different solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

.
 The difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}\equiv\tilde{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{a\, b}-\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the homogeneous equations
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{b}\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=0,\quad\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}=-\mathbf{X}_{b\, a}.\]

\end_inset

The 1-forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 can be expanded in the dual frame basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}=\sum_{c}X_{a\, bc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c},\quad X_{a\, bc}=-X_{b\, ac}.\]

\end_inset

Then we can write
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{b}\mathbf{X}_{a\, b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}=\sum_{b,c}X_{a\, bc}\boldsymbol{\theta}^{b}\wedge\boldsymbol{\theta}^{c}=0.\]

\end_inset

 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a\, bc}=X_{a\, cb}$
\end_inset

, i.e.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset Formula $X_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c$
\end_inset

.
 However, it is impossible that a nonzero quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a\, bc}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c$
\end_inset

 and at the same time antisymmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
X_{a\, bc}=-X_{b\, ac}=-X_{b\, ca}=X_{c\, ba}=X_{c\, ab}=-X_{a\, cb}=-X_{a\, bc},\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a\, bc}=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 equals zero, i.e.\InsetSpace ~
the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{a\, b}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
\hfill

\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

