\begin_layout Section
Comments on Ludvigsen's 
\emph on
General Relativity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The book is M.
 Ludvigsen,
\emph on
 General relativity: a geometric aproach
\emph default
 (Cambridge University Press, 1999).
 Many explanations in that book are outstandingly clear, and I benefited
 greatly by reading it.
 Nevertheless, there are some minor gaffes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) On p.
 91, eq.\InsetSpace ~
9.27 is supposedly the same as eq.\InsetSpace ~
9.20 when 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

written in full.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 However, these equations actually differ by the choice of the permuted
 indices.
 The relation 9.27 can be obtained from 9.20 only if one assumes the identity
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{abcd}=R_{cdab}$
\end_inset

, which Ludvigsen actually never mentions in the book.
 This well-known standard identity is a consequence of 9.19 and 9.20.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) On p.
 103, eq.\InsetSpace ~
10.14 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{a}\nabla^{a}\phi=R...$
\end_inset

, while the preceding (unnumbered) equation on p.102 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla_{e}\nabla^{a}\phi=R...$
\end_inset

.
 A minus sign has materialized from nowhere! The answer (10.17) is correct,
 and the extra minus sign is actually needed to compensate for an error
 made earlier.
 In the last paragraph on p.
 101, Ludvigsen writes (in 3-dimensional notation) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 whereas in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=-\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 in Newtonian gravity.
 (The acceleration points down, the potential grows upwards.) So the correct
 calculation starts by introducing 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{a}=\nabla_{a}\phi$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla_{a}\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) On p.
 108, top line, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{a}n^{a}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{a}l_{b}=\nabla_{b}l_{a}$
\end_inset

, we have...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 --- actually, the same result follows with merely the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{a}$
\end_inset

 is a null geodesic.
 It is not necessary to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{a}$
\end_inset

 is integrable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4) On p.
 109, top line, --- one cannot actually derive Eq.
 (11.10) as claimed.
 By contracting the top equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $l^{a}m^{b}m^{c}$
\end_inset

 and using Eq.\InsetSpace ~
(11.8), which already assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is integrable, one gets
\begin_inset Formula \[
D\sigma=R(l,m,l,m)+2l^{a}\bar{m}_{b}(\nabla_{a}m^{b}).\]

\end_inset

Now it is unclear how to show that the last term is equal to 2
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 There is a significant freedom in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla m$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is chosen simply to be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n,l$
\end_inset

 and this is not sufficient to fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla m$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, the null tetrad can be changed by the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $m\rightarrow e^{i\lambda}m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\rightarrow e^{2i\lambda}\sigma$
\end_inset

, as shown at top of page 110.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a function of position then the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $D\sigma=...$
\end_inset

 will be changed after the transformation! Thus this equation really depends
 on the choice of the tetrad, and some choices are better than others.
 The equation (11.10) is perhaps obtained with a suitable choice of the tetrad,
 but this is not discussed in the book.
\newline

\end_layout

